DEFINITION: alpha; the first letter of the Greek alphabet.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin; the first letter of the alphabet; figuratively, only (from its use as a numeral) the first.
USAGE: Alpha. Often used (usually an, before a vowel) also in composition (as a contraction from aneu) in the sense of privation; so, in many words, beginning with this letter; occasionally in the sense of union (as a contraction of hama).

DEFINITION: Aaron, son of Amram and Jochebed, brother of Moses.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Aharown); Aaron, the brother of Moses.

DEFINITION: Abaddon, Destroyer (i.e. Destroying Angel) or place of destruction (personified).
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('abaddown); a destroying angel.

DEFINITION: not burdensome, bringing no weight or oppression upon.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and baros; weightless, i.e. (figuratively) not burdensome.

DEFINITION: Abba, father.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin ('ab); father as a vocative.

DEFINITION: Abel, second son of Adam and Eve, brother of Cain.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Hebel); Abel, the son of Adam.

DEFINITION: Abijah, (a) a king, son of Rehoboam, (b) founder of the eighth class of priests.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Abiyah); Abijah, the name of two Israelites.

DEFINITION: Abiathar, a priest in King David's time.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Ebyathar); Abiathar, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: the Abilenian territory, the territory of Abila (in Syria), a small principality in the mountains of Damascus.
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin (compare 'abel); Abilene, a region of Syria.

DEFINITION: Abiud, son of Zerubbabel and father of Eliakim.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Abiyhuwd); Abihud, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Abraham, progenitor of the Hebrew race.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Abraham); Abraham, the Hebrew patriarch.
USAGE: Abraham. (In Acts 7:16 the text should probably read Jacob.)

DEFINITION: the abyss, unfathomable depth, an especially Jewish conception, the home of the dead and of evil spirits.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a variation of buthos; depthless, i.e. (specially) (infernal) "abyss".

DEFINITION: Agabus, a Christian prophet.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (compare Chagab); Agabus, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: to work that which is good, perform good deeds.
ORIGIN: From agathos and ergon; to work good.

DEFINITION: to do that which is good.
ORIGIN: From agathopoios; to be a well-doer (as a favor or a duty).

DEFINITION: the doing of that which is good, well-doing.
ORIGIN: From agathopoios; well-doing, i.e. Virtue.

DEFINITION: a doer of that which is good.
ORIGIN: From agathos and poieo; a well-doer, i.e. Virtuous.

DEFINITION: intrinsically good, good in nature, good whether it be seen to be so or not, the widest and most colorless of all words with this meaning.
ORIGIN: A primary word; "good" (in any sense, often as noun).
USAGE: benefit, good(-s, things), well. Compare kalos.

DEFINITION: intrinsic goodness, especially as a personal quality, with stress on the kindly (rather than the righteous) side of goodness.
ORIGIN: From agathos; goodness, i.e. Virtue or beneficence.

DEFINITION: wild joy, ecstatic delight, exultation, exhilaration.
ORIGIN: From agalliao; exultation; specially, welcome.

DEFINITION: to exult, rejoice greatly.
ORIGIN: From agan (much) and hallomai; properly, to jump for joy, i.e. Exult.
USAGE: be (exceeding) glad, with exceeding joy, rejoice (greatly).

DEFINITION: unmarried, of a person not in a state of wedlock, whether he or she has formerly been married or not.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and gamos; unmarried.

DEFINITION: to grieve much, to be indignant.
ORIGIN: From agan (much) and achthos (grief; akin to the base of agkale); to be greatly afflicted, i.e. (figuratively) indignant.
USAGE: be much (sore) displeased, have (be moved with, with) indignation.

DEFINITION: feeling of anger, indignation, vexation.
ORIGIN: From aganakteo; indignation.

DEFINITION: to love, wish well to, take pleasure in, long for; denotes the love of reason, esteem.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from agan (much); to love (in a social or moral sense).

DEFINITION: love, benevolence, good will, esteem; plur: love-feasts.
ORIGIN: From agapao; love, i.e. Affection or benevolence; specially (plural) a love-feast.

DEFINITION: loved, beloved, with two special applications: the Beloved, a title of the Messiah (Christ), as beloved beyond all others by the God who sent Him; of Christians, as beloved by God, Christ, and one another.
ORIGIN: From agapao; beloved.

DEFINITION: Hagar, the servant of Sarah, concubine of Abraham.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Hagar); Hagar, the concubine of Abraham.

DEFINITION: to impress (into service), send (on an errand).
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin (compare 'iggra'); properly, to be a courier, i.e. (by implication) to press into public service.

DEFINITION: a vessel, flask.
ORIGIN: From aggos (a pail, perhaps as bent; compare the base of agkale); a receptacle.

DEFINITION: a message.
ORIGIN: From aggelos; an announcement, i.e. (by implication) precept.

DEFINITION: a messenger, generally a (supernatural) messenger from God, an angel, conveying news or behests from God to men.
ORIGIN: From aggello (probably derived from ago; compare agele) (to bring tidings); a messenger; especially an "angel"; by implication, a pastor.

DEFINITION: come!.
ORIGIN: Imperative of ago; properly, lead, i.e. Come on.

DEFINITION: a flock, herd.
ORIGIN: From ago (compare aggelos); a drove.

DEFINITION: of unrecorded genealogy, whose descent cannot be traced.
ORIGIN: From a (as negative particle) and genealogeo; unregistered as to birth.

DEFINITION: lit: without family, hence: ignoble, base.
ORIGIN: From a (as negative particle) and genos; properly, without kin, i.e. (of unknown descent, and by implication) ignoble.

DEFINITION: to make holy, treat as holy, set apart as holy, sanctify, hallow, purify.
ORIGIN: From hagios; to make holy, i.e. (ceremonially) purify or consecrate; (mentally) to venerate.

DEFINITION: the process of making or becoming holy, set apart, sanctification, holiness, consecration.
ORIGIN: From hagiazo; properly, purification, i.e. (the state) purity; concretely (by Hebraism) a purifier.

DEFINITION: holy place, sanctuary.
ORIGIN: Neuter of hagios; a sacred thing (i.e. Spot).

DEFINITION: set apart by (or for) God, holy, sacred.
ORIGIN: From hagos (an awful thing) (compare hagnos, thalpo); sacred (physically, pure, morally blameless or religious, ceremonially, consecrated).

DEFINITION: holiness, sanctity, as an abstract quality.
ORIGIN: From hagios; sanctity (i.e. Properly, the state).

DEFINITION: a holy or sanctified state.
ORIGIN: From hagios; sacredness (i.e. Properly, the quality).

DEFINITION: an arm, especially as bent to receive a burden.
ORIGIN: From agkos (a bend, "ache"); an arm (as curved).

DEFINITION: a fish-hook.
ORIGIN: From the same as agkale; a hook (as bent).

DEFINITION: an anchor.
ORIGIN: From the same as agkale; an "anchor" (as crooked).

DEFINITION: uncarded, undressed.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and the same as gnapheus; properly, unfulled, i.e. (by implication) new (cloth).

DEFINITION: purity, chastity.
ORIGIN: From hagnos; cleanliness (the quality), i.e. (specially) chastity.

DEFINITION: to cleanse, purify, either ceremonially, actually, or morally.
ORIGIN: From hagnos; to make clean, i.e. (figuratively) sanctify (ceremonially or morally).

DEFINITION: (ceremonial) purification.
ORIGIN: From hagnizo; a cleansing (the act), i.e. (ceremonially) lustration.

DEFINITION: to not know, be ignorant of (a person, thing, or fact), sometimes with the idea of willful ignorance.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and noieo; not to know (through lack of information or intelligence); by implication, to ignore (through disinclination).
USAGE: (be) ignorant(-ly), not know, not understand, unknown.

DEFINITION: an offence committed through ignorance, an error due to (willful or culpable) ignorance.
ORIGIN: From agnoeo; a thing ignored, i.e. Shortcoming.

DEFINITION: ignorance, inadvertence, sometimes with the idea of willful blindness.
ORIGIN: From agnoeo; ignorance (properly, the quality).

DEFINITION: (originally, in a condition prepared for worship), pure (either ethically, or ritually, ceremonially), chaste.
ORIGIN: From the same as hagios; properly, clean, i.e. (figuratively) innocent, modest, perfect.

DEFINITION: purity, chastity.
ORIGIN: From hagnos; cleanness (the state), i.e. (figuratively) blamelessness.

DEFINITION: purely, sincerely, with pure motives, honestly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from hagnos; purely, i.e. Honestly.

DEFINITION: ignorance; specifically: willful ignorance.
ORIGIN: From a (as negative particle) and gnosis; ignorance (properly, the state).

DEFINITION: unknown, unknowable.
ORIGIN: From a (as negative particle) and gnostos; unknown.

DEFINITION: market-place, forum, public place of assembly.
ORIGIN: From ageiro (to gather; probably akin to egeiro); properly, the town-square (as a place of public resort); by implication, a market or thoroughfare.

DEFINITION: to buy in the marketplace, purchase.
ORIGIN: From agora; properly, to go to market, i.e. (by implication) to purchase; specially, to redeem.

DEFINITION: a lounger in the market-place, perhaps with the idea of agitator.
ORIGIN: From agora; relating to the market-place, i.e. Forensic (times); by implication, vulgar.

DEFINITION: catching, a catch.
ORIGIN: From ago; (abstractly) a catching (of fish); also (concretely) a haul (of fish).

DEFINITION: unlettered, illiterate, uneducated, perhaps with the narrower idea: unacquainted with Rabbinic teaching.
ORIGIN: From a (as negative particle) and gramma; unlettered, i.e. Illiterate.

DEFINITION: to spend the night in the open, bivouac.
ORIGIN: From agros and auleo (in the sense of aule); to camp out.

DEFINITION: to catch, take by hunting.
ORIGIN: From agra; to hunt, i.e. (figuratively) to entrap.

DEFINITION: a wild olive tree, oleaster.
ORIGIN: From agrios and elaia; an oleaster.

DEFINITION: living in the fields, wild, savage, fierce.
ORIGIN: From agros; wild (as pertaining to the country), literally (natural) or figuratively (fierce).

DEFINITION: Agrippa, the name of two descendant of Herod the Great.
ORIGIN: Apparently from agrios and hippos; wild-horse tamer; Agrippas, one of the Herods.

DEFINITION: a field, especially as bearing a crop; the country, lands, property in land, a country estate.
ORIGIN: From ago; a field (as a drive for cattle); genitive case, the country; specially, a farm, i.e. Hamlet.
USAGE: country, farm, piece of ground, land.

DEFINITION: to be not asleep, be awake; especially: to be watchful, careful.
ORIGIN: Ultimately from a (as negative particle) and hupnos; to be sleepless, i.e. Keep awake.

DEFINITION: the state of being awake (at night), sleeplessness, watching.
ORIGIN: From agrupneo; sleeplessness, i.e. A keeping awake.

DEFINITION: to lead, lead away, bring (a person, or animal), guide, spend a day, go.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; properly, to lead; by implication, to bring, drive, (reflexively) go, (specially) pass (time), or (figuratively) induce.
USAGE: be, bring (forth), carry, (let) go, keep, lead away, be open.

DEFINITION: a leading, guiding; hence: mode of life, conduct.
ORIGIN: Reduplicated from ago; a bringing up, i.e. Mode of living.

DEFINITION: an (athletic) contest; hence, a struggle (in the soul).
ORIGIN: From ago; properly, a place of assembly (as if led), i.e. (by implication) a contest (held there); figuratively, an effort or anxiety.

DEFINITION: (properly the feeling of the athlete before a contest), great fear, terror, of death; anxiety, agony.
ORIGIN: From agon; a struggle (properly, the state), i.e. (figuratively) anguish.

DEFINITION: to be struggling, striving (as in an athletic contest or warfare); to contend, as with an adversary.
ORIGIN: From agon; to struggle, literally (to compete for a prize), figuratively (to contend with an adversary), or genitive case (to endeavor to accomplish something).

DEFINITION: Adam, the first man, the first parent of the human race.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Adam); Adam, the first man; typically (of Jesus) man (as his representative).

DEFINITION: without expense, for which nothing has to be paid.
ORIGIN: From a (as negative particle); and dapane; costless, i.e. Gratuitous.

DEFINITION: Addi, son of Cosam, and father of Melchi, one of the ancestors of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Probably of Hebrew origin (compare adiy); Addi, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: a sister, a woman (fellow-)member of a church, a Christian woman.
ORIGIN: Fem of adephos; a sister (naturally or ecclesiastically).

DEFINITION: a brother, member of the same religious community, especially a fellow-Christian.
ORIGIN: From a (as a connective particle) and delphus (the womb); a brother (literally or figuratively) near or remote (much like a).

DEFINITION: brotherhood (in the collective sense), the members of the Christian Church, Christendom.
ORIGIN: From adephos; brotherhood (properly, the feeling of brotherliness), i.e. The (Christian) fraternity.

DEFINITION: unseen, not obvious, inconspicuous, indistinct.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and delos; hidden, figuratively, indistinct.

DEFINITION: the quality of being unseen (of disappearing), indefiniteness, uncertainty.
ORIGIN: From adelos; uncertainty.

DEFINITION: out of sight, obscurely, inconspicuously, uncertainly, without certain aim.
ORIGIN: Adverb from adelos; uncertainly.

DEFINITION: to feel fear, lack courage, be distressed, troubled.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of adeo (to be sated to loathing); to be in distress (of mind).
USAGE: be full of heaviness, be very heavy.

DEFINITION: Hades, the abode of departed spirits.
ORIGIN: From a (as negative particle) and eido; properly, unseen, i.e. "Hades" or the place (state) of departed souls.

DEFINITION: without uncertainty, unambiguous, undivided, whole-hearted.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of diakrino; properly, undistinguished, i.e. (actively) impartial.

DEFINITION: unceasing, unremitting.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of a compound of dia and leipo; unintermitted, i.e. Permanent.

DEFINITION: unceasingly, without remission.
ORIGIN: Adverb from adialeiptos; uninterruptedly, i.e. Without omission (on an appropriate occasion).

DEFINITION: incorruptibility, soundness, integrity, purity.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of a compound of a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of diaphtheiro; incorruptibleness, i.e. (figuratively) purity (of doctrine).

DEFINITION: to act unjustly towards, injure, harm.
ORIGIN: From adikos; to be unjust, i.e. (actively) do wrong (morally, socially or physically).
USAGE: hurt, injure, be an offender, be unjust, (do, suffer, take) wrong.

DEFINITION: a legal wrong, crime (with which one is charged), misdeed, crime against God, a sin.
ORIGIN: From adikeo; a wrong done.
USAGE: evil doing, iniquity, matter of wrong.

DEFINITION: injustice, unrighteousness, hurt.
ORIGIN: From adikos; (legal) injustice (properly, the quality, by implication, the act); morally, wrongfulness (of character, life or act).

DEFINITION: unjust, unrighteous, wicked.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and dike; unjust; by extension wicked; by implication, treacherous; specially, heathen.

DEFINITION: unjustly, undeservedly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from adikos; unjustly.

DEFINITION: failing to pass the test, unapproved, counterfeit.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and dokimos; unapproved, i.e. Rejected; by implication, worthless (literally or morally).

DEFINITION: unadulterated, pure, guileless.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle}; and dolos; undeceitful, i.e. (figuratively) unadulterated.

DEFINITION: belonging to Adramyttium, a port in Mysia, in Asia Minor.
ORIGIN: From Adramutteion (a place in Asia Minor); Adramyttene or belonging to Adramyttium.

DEFINITION: the Hadria, a name given by sailors not merely to the Adriatic Sea, to which it properly belonged, but also to the open Mediterranean to the south-east of Italy, to the sea that lay between Malta, Italy, Greece, and Crete.
ORIGIN: From Adria (a place near its shore); the Adriatic sea (including the Ionian).

DEFINITION: lavishness, lavish generosity, abundance, bounty.
ORIGIN: From hadros (stout); plumpness, i.e. (figuratively) liberality.

DEFINITION: to be impossible; to be unable.
ORIGIN: From adunatos; to be unable, i.e. (passively) impossible.

DEFINITION: of persons: incapable; of things: impossible; either the inability, or that which is impossible.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and dunatos; unable, i.e. Weak (literally or figuratively); passively, impossible.
USAGE: could not do, impossible, impotent, not possible, weak.

DEFINITION: to sing.
ORIGIN: To sing.

DEFINITION: always, unceasingly, perpetually; on every occasion.
ORIGIN: From an obsolete primary noun (apparently meaning continued duration); "ever,"by qualification regularly; by implication, earnestly.

DEFINITION: an eagle, bird of prey.
ORIGIN: From the same as aer; an eagle (from its wind-like flight).

DEFINITION: unleavened, the paschal feast (a feast of the Hebrews); fig: uncorrupted, sincere.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and zume; unleavened, i.e. (figuratively) uncorrupted; (in the neutral plural) specially (by implication) the Passover week.

DEFINITION: Azor, son of Eliakim and father of Zadok, an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (compare Azzuwr); Azor, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Azotus, Ashdod, a coast town of Palestine belonging to the ancient Philistia, and part of Herod's kingdom.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Ashdowd); Azotus (i.e. Ashdod), a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: air, the lower air we breathe.
ORIGIN: From aemi (to breathe unconsciously, i.e. Respire; by analogy, to blow); "air" (as naturally circumambient).

DEFINITION: immortality, imperishability, freedom from death.
ORIGIN: From a compound of a (as a negative particle) and thanatos; deathlessness.

DEFINITION: illegal, unlawful, criminal, lawless.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of themis (statute; from the base of tithemi); illegal; by implication, flagitious.

DEFINITION: without god, without (the only true) God, godless.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and theos; godless.

DEFINITION: lawless, unrestrained, licentious.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of tithemi (in the sense of enacting); lawless, i.e. (by implication) criminal.

DEFINITION: to annul, make of no effect, set aside, ignore, slight; to break faith with.
ORIGIN: From a compound of a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of tithemi; to set aside, i.e. (by implication) to disesteem, neutralize or violate.
USAGE: cast off, despise, disannul, frustrate, bring to nought, reject.

DEFINITION: annulment, nullification, abrogation.
ORIGIN: From atheteo; cancellation (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: Athens, the intellectual capital of Greece.
ORIGIN: Plural of Athene (the goddess of wisdom, who was reputed to have founded the city); Athenoe, the capitol of Greece.

DEFINITION: Athenian, belonging to Athens.
ORIGIN: From Athenai; an Athenoean or inhabitant of Athenae.

DEFINITION: to engage, compete, in an (athletic) contest.
ORIGIN: From athlos (a contest in the public lists); to contend in the competitive games.

DEFINITION: a struggling (as in an athletic contest).
ORIGIN: From athleo; a struggle (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to lose heart, be despondent, be disheartened.
ORIGIN: From a compound of a (as a negative particle) and thumos; to be spiritless, i.e. Disheartened.

DEFINITION: (sometimes: unpunished), guiltless, innocent.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and probably a derivative of tithemi (meaning a penalty); not guilty.

DEFINITION: of a goat.
ORIGIN: From aix (a goat); belonging to a goat.

DEFINITION: sea-coast, (sandy) beach; shore (of sea or lake), land.
ORIGIN: From aisso (to rush) and hals (in the sense of the sea; a beach (on which the waves dash).

DEFINITION: Egyptian.
ORIGIN: From Aiguptos; an Ægyptian or inhabitant of Ægyptus.

DEFINITION: Egypt, the land of the Nile.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation.
USAGE: ÆGyptus, the land of the Nile

DEFINITION: eternal, everlasting.
ORIGIN: From aei; everduring (forward and backward, or forward only).

DEFINITION: a sense of shame.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from a (as a negative particle) and eido (through the idea of downcast eyes); bashfulness, i.e. (towards men), modesty or (towards God) awe.

DEFINITION: an Ethiopian, Abyssinian.
ORIGIN: From aitho (to scorch) and ops (the face, from optanomai); an Æthiopian (as a blackamoor).

DEFINITION: blood (especially as shed).
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; blood, literally (of men or animals), figuratively (the juice of grapes) or specially (the atoning blood of Christ); by implication, bloodshed, also kindred.

DEFINITION: a shedding or pouring forth of blood (in sacrifice).
ORIGIN: From haima and a derivative of ekcheo; an effusion of blood.

DEFINITION: to suffer from a continual flow (oozing) of blood.
ORIGIN: From haima and rheo; to flow blood, i.e. Have a hoemorrhage.
USAGE: diseased with an issue of blood.

DEFINITION: Aeneas, a paralytic cured by Peter.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; Aeneas, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: praise, commendation.
ORIGIN: From aineo; a praising (the act), i.e. (specially) a thank(-offering).

DEFINITION: to praise.
ORIGIN: From ainos; to praise (God).

DEFINITION: a riddle, an enigma.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of ainos (in its primary sense); an obscure saying ("enigma"), i.e. (abstractly) obscureness.

DEFINITION: praise (noun).
ORIGIN: Apparently a prime word; properly, a story, but used in the sense of epainos; praise (of God).

DEFINITION: Aenon; Eusebius and Jerome place this site 8 (Roman) miles south of Scythopolis near the Jordan.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (a derivative of ayin, place of springs); ænon, a place in Palestine.
USAGE: Aenon; Eusebius and Jerome place this site 8 (Roman) miles south of Scythopolis near the Jordan.

DEFINITION: to choose, prefer.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to airo; to take for oneself, i.e. To prefer.
USAGE: choose. Some of the forms are borrowed from a cognate hellomai hel'-lom-ahee; which is otherwise obsolete.

DEFINITION: a self-chosen opinion, a religious or philosophical sect, discord or contention.
ORIGIN: From haireomai; properly, a choice, i.e. (specially) a party or (abstractly) disunion.
USAGE: heresy (which is the Greek word itself), sect.

DEFINITION: to choose.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of haireomai; to make a choice.

DEFINITION: disposed to form sects, sectarian, heretical, factious.
ORIGIN: From the same as hairetizo; a schismatic.

DEFINITION: to raise, lift up, take away, remove.
ORIGIN: A primary root; to lift up; by implication, to take up or away; figuratively, to raise (the voice), keep in suspense (the mind), specially, to sail away (i.e. Weigh anchor); by Hebraism (compare nasa') to expiate sin.
USAGE: away with, bear (up), carry, lift up, loose, make to doubt, put away, remove, take (away, up).

DEFINITION: to perceive, understand.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; to apprehend (properly, by the senses).

DEFINITION: perception, understanding, discernment.
ORIGIN: From aisthanomai; perception, i.e. (figuratively) discernment.

DEFINITION: organ of perception.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of aisthanomai; properly, an organ of perception, i.e. (figuratively) judgment.

DEFINITION: greedy, fond of base gain.
ORIGIN: From aischros and kerdos (gain); sordid.

DEFINITION: greedily, in a spirit of eagerness for base gain.
ORIGIN: Adverb from aischrokerdes; sordidly.

DEFINITION: filthy speech, foul language.
ORIGIN: From aischros and logos; vile conversation.

DEFINITION: shame.
ORIGIN: Neuter of aischros; a shameful thing, i.e. Indecorum.

DEFINITION: base, disgraceful.
ORIGIN: From the same as aischunomai; shameful, i.e. Base (specially, venal).

DEFINITION: obscenity, indecency, baseness.
ORIGIN: From aischros; shamefulness, i.e. Obscenity.

DEFINITION: shame, shamefacedness, shameful deeds.
ORIGIN: From aischunomai; shame or disgrace (abstractly or concretely).

DEFINITION: to be ashamed, be put to shame.
ORIGIN: From aischos (disfigurement, i.e. Disgrace); to feel shame (for oneself).

DEFINITION: to ask, request, petition, demand.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; to ask (in genitive case).
USAGE: ask, beg, call for, crave, desire, require. Compare punthanomai.

DEFINITION: a petition, request.
ORIGIN: From aiteo; a thing asked or (abstractly) an asking.

DEFINITION: a cause, reason, excuse; a charge, accusation; guilt; circumstances, case.
ORIGIN: From the same as aiteo; a cause (as if asked for), i.e. (logical) reason (motive, matter), (legal) crime (alleged or proved).

DEFINITION: a charge, accusation.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of aitia; a thing charged.

DEFINITION: cause, crime, guilt, criminality.
ORIGIN: Neuter of aitios; a reason or crime (like aitia).

DEFINITION: the cause, author; the culprit, the accused; the crime.
ORIGIN: From the same as aiteo; causative, i.e. (concretely) a causer.

DEFINITION: unexpected, sudden.
ORIGIN: From a compound of a (as a negative particle) and phaino (compare exaiphnes) (meaning non-apparent); unexpected, i.e. (adverbially) suddenly.

DEFINITION: captivity; a captive multitude.
ORIGIN: From aichmalotos; captivity.

DEFINITION: to take captive, captivate.
ORIGIN: From aichmalotos; to capture (like aichmalotizo).

DEFINITION: to take captive (in war); to subdue, ensnare.
ORIGIN: From aichmalotos; to make captive.
USAGE: lead away captive, bring into captivity.

DEFINITION: a captive (in war), a prisoner.
ORIGIN: From aichme (a spear) and a derivative of the same as halosis; properly, a prisoner of war, i.e. (genitive case) a captive.

DEFINITION: an age, a cycle (of time), especially of the present age as contrasted with the future age, and of one of a series of ages stretching to infinity.
ORIGIN: From the same as aei; properly, an age; by extension, perpetuity (also past); by implication, the world; specially (Jewish) a Messianic period (present or future).
USAGE: age, course, eternal, (for) ever(-more), (n-)ever, (beginning of the, while the) world (began, without end). Compare chronos.

DEFINITION: age-long, and therefore: practically eternal, unending; partaking of the character of that which lasts for an age, as contrasted with that which is brief and fleeting.
ORIGIN: From aion; perpetual (also used of past time, or past and future as well).

DEFINITION: uncleanness, impurity.
ORIGIN: From akathartos; impurity (the quality), physically or morally.

DEFINITION: filthiness.
ORIGIN: From akathartos; impurity (the state), morally.

DEFINITION: unclean, impure.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of kathairo (meaning cleansed); impure (ceremonially, morally (lewd) or specially, (demonic)).

DEFINITION: to be without a suitable opportunity.
ORIGIN: From a compound of a (as a negative particle) and kairos (meaning unseasonable); to be inopportune (for oneself), i.e. To fail of a proper occasion.

DEFINITION: unseasonably, out of due season, inopportunely.
ORIGIN: Adverb from the same as akaireomai; inopportunely.

DEFINITION: innocent, guileless, simple.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and kakos; not bad, i.e. (objectively) innocent or (subjectively) unsuspecting.

DEFINITION: a thorn-bush, prickly plant; a thorn.
ORIGIN: Probably from the same as akmen; a thorn.

DEFINITION: made of thorns.
ORIGIN: From akantha; thorny.

DEFINITION: unfruitful, barren, profitless.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and karpos; barren (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: not open to just rebuke; irreprehensible.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of kataginosko; unblamable.

DEFINITION: unveiled, uncovered.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of a compound of kata and kalupto; unveiled.

DEFINITION: uncondemned, not yet tried.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of katakrino; without (legal) trial.

DEFINITION: indissoluble, that cannot be broken up.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of kataluo; indissoluble, i.e. (figuratively) permanent.

DEFINITION: not ceasing from, not abandoning (giving up).
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of katapauo; unrefraining.

DEFINITION: disturbance, upheaval, revolution, almost anarchy, first in the political, and thence in the moral sphere.
ORIGIN: From akatastatos; instability, i.e. Disorder.

DEFINITION: unsettled, unstable (though these are hardly strong enough equivalents), almost anarchic.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of kathistemi; inconstant.

DEFINITION: unrestrainable, unruly, untamable.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of katecho; unrestrainable.

DEFINITION: Hakeldama, a field apparantly located south of the valley of Hinnom.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (meaning field of blood; corresponding to kathairesis and exapatao); Akeldama, a place near Jerusalem.

DEFINITION: (lit: unmixed) simple, unsophisticated, sincere, blameless.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of kerannumi; unmixed, i.e. (figuratively) innocent.

DEFINITION: unbent, unyielding, resolute, firm.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and klino; not leaning, i.e. (figuratively) firm.

DEFINITION: to reach maturity, become ripe, be in full vigor.
ORIGIN: From the same as akmen; to make a point, i.e. (figuratively) mature.

DEFINITION: at the present point of time.
ORIGIN: Accusative case of a noun ("acme") akin to ake (a point) and meaning the same; adverbially, just now, i.e. Still.

DEFINITION: hearing, faculty of hearing, ear; report, rumor.
ORIGIN: From akouo; hearing (the act, the sense or the thing heard).
USAGE: audience, ear, fame, which ye heard, hearing, preached, report, rumor.

DEFINITION: to accompany, attend, follow.
ORIGIN: From a (as a particle of union) and keleuthos (a road); properly, to be in the same way with, i.e. To accompany (specially, as a disciple).

DEFINITION: to hear, listen, comprehend by hearing; pass: is heard, reported.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to hear (in various senses).
USAGE: give (in the) audience (of), come (to the ears), (shall) hear(-er, -ken), be noised, be reported, understand.

DEFINITION: incontinence, intemperance (in wide sense), lack of restraint.
ORIGIN: From akrates; want of self-restraint.

DEFINITION: lacking self-control, powerless, inclined to excess.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and kratos; powerless, i.e. Without self-control.

DEFINITION: unmixed, undiluted, pure.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of kerannumi; undiluted.

DEFINITION: strictness, accuracy, exactness, attention to detail, scrupulousness.
ORIGIN: From the same as akribestatos; exactness.

DEFINITION: most exact, strict.
ORIGIN: Superlative of akribes (a derivative of the same as akron); most exact.

DEFINITION: more perfectly.
ORIGIN: Neuter of the comparative of the same as akribestatos; (adverbially) more exactly.

DEFINITION: to learn carefully, inquire with exactness.
ORIGIN: From the same as akribestatos; to be exact, i.e. Ascertain.

DEFINITION: carefully, exactly, strictly, distinctly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from the same as akribestatos; exactly.

DEFINITION: a locust.
ORIGIN: Apparently from the same as akron; a locust (as pointed, or as lighting on the top of vegetation).

DEFINITION: auditorium, recitation hall, court room (for hearing cases).
ORIGIN: From akroates; an audience-room.

DEFINITION: a hearer of, a listener to.
ORIGIN: From akroaomai (to listen; apparently an intensive of akouo); a hearer (merely).

DEFINITION: (a technical word of Jewish use) foreskin, prepuce: used sometimes as a slang term by Jews, of Gentiles.
ORIGIN: From akron and probably a modified form of posthe (the penis or male sexual organ); the prepuce; by implication, an uncircumcised (i.e. Gentile, figuratively, unregenerate) state or person.

DEFINITION: in the corner (of a building); subst: corner-(stone).
ORIGIN: From akron and gonia; belonging to the extreme corner.

DEFINITION: (lit: top of a heap), first-fruits, spoil, treasure (taken in war).
ORIGIN: From akron and this (a heap); properly (in the plural) the top of the heap, i.e. (by implication) best of the booty.

DEFINITION: the end, extremity.
ORIGIN: Neuter of an adjective probably akin to the base of akmen; the extremity.
USAGE: one end... Other, tip, top, uttermost participle.

DEFINITION: the Greek way of writing the Latin Aquila, a male proper name; the husband of Priscilla (Prisca), and a Jew, of a family belonging to (Sinope in ?) Pontus.
ORIGIN: Probably for Latin aquila (an eagle); Akulas, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: to annul, make of no effect, cancel.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and kuroo; to invalidate.

DEFINITION: (characteristic of legal documents), without hindrance, freely.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of koluo; in an unhindered manner, i.e. Freely.

DEFINITION: unwilling, generally used where English would express by an adverb: unwillingly.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and hekon; unwilling.

DEFINITION: a phial or bottle of perfumed ointment, usually of alabaster.
ORIGIN: Neuter of alabastros (of uncertain derivation), the name of a stone; properly, an "alabaster" box, i.e. (by extension) a perfume vase (of any material).

DEFINITION: boasting, show, arrogant display, ostentation; plur: occasions of ostentation.
ORIGIN: From alazon; braggadocio, i.e. (by implication) self-confidence.

DEFINITION: a boaster, one who gives one's self airs in a loud and flaunting way.
ORIGIN: From ale (vagrancy); braggart.

DEFINITION: to cry aloud, raise a war-cry; a clanging or clashing cymbal.
ORIGIN: From alale (a shout, "halloo"); to vociferate, i.e. (by implication) to wail; figuratively, to clang.

DEFINITION: unutterable, that baffles words, unexpressed.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of laleo; unspeakable.

DEFINITION: unable to speak or articulate; speechless.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and laleo; mute.

DEFINITION: salt.
ORIGIN: From hals; salt; figuratively, prudence.

DEFINITION: to anoint: festivally, in homage, medicinally, or in anointing the dead.
ORIGIN: From a (as particle of union) and the base of liparos; to oil (with perfume).

DEFINITION: the cockcrow, as a period of time, between midnight and 3 a.m.
ORIGIN: From alektor and phone; cock-crow, i.e. The third night-watch.

DEFINITION: a cock, rooster.
ORIGIN: From aleko (to ward off); a cock or male fowl.

DEFINITION: an Alexandrian, a native (or resident) of Alexandria in Egypt.
ORIGIN: From Alexandreia (the city so called); an Alexandreian or inhabitant of Alexandria.

DEFINITION: Alexandrian, belonging to Alexandria in Egypt.
ORIGIN: From the same as Alexandreus; Alexandrine, or belonging to Alexandria.

DEFINITION: Alexander, a name of Greek origin, (a) son of Simon of Cyrene, (b) the High Priest's kinsman, (c) an Ephesian Jew, (d) the coppersmith.
ORIGIN: From the same as (the first part of) alektor and aner; man-defender; Alexander, the name of three Israelites and one other man.

DEFINITION: meal, flour.
ORIGIN: From aleo (to grind); flour.

DEFINITION: truth, but not merely truth as spoken; truth of idea, reality, sincerity, truth in the moral sphere, divine truth revealed to man, straightforwardness.
ORIGIN: From alethes; truth.

DEFINITION: to say (speak) truth, do truth, maintain truth (the truth).
ORIGIN: From alethes; to be true (in doctrine and profession).

DEFINITION: unconcealed, true, true in fact, worthy of credit, truthful.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and lanthano; true (as not concealing).

DEFINITION: true (lit: made of truth), real, genuine.
ORIGIN: From alethes; truthful.

DEFINITION: to grind.
ORIGIN: From the same as aleuron; to grind.

DEFINITION: truly, really, certainly, surely.
ORIGIN: Adverb from alethes; truly.
USAGE: indeed, surely, of a surety, truly, of a (in) truth, verily, very.

DEFINITION: a fisherman.
ORIGIN: From hals; a sailor (as engaged on the salt water), i.e. (by implication) a fisher.

DEFINITION: to fish.
ORIGIN: From halieus; to be a fisher, i.e. (by implication) to fish.

DEFINITION: to salt, sprinkle with salt (of sacrifices or of those who offer sacrifice), keep fresh and sound, and so acceptable to God.
ORIGIN: From hals; to salt.

DEFINITION: pollution, perhaps a polluted thing (especially of food).
ORIGIN: From alisgeo (to soil); (ceremonially) defilement.

DEFINITION: otherwise, on the other hand, but.
ORIGIN: Neuter plural of allos; properly, other things, i.e. (adverbially) contrariwise (in many relations).
USAGE: and, but (even), howbeit, indeed, nay, nevertheless, no, notwithstanding, save, therefore, yea, yet.

DEFINITION: to change, alter, exchange, transform.
ORIGIN: From allos; to make different.

DEFINITION: from another place, by another way.
ORIGIN: From allos; from elsewhere.

DEFINITION: to speak allegorically.
ORIGIN: From allos and agoreo (to harangue (compare agora)); to allegorize.
USAGE: be an allegory (the Greek word itself).

DEFINITION: hallelujah, alleluia (an adoring exclamation).
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (imperative of halal and Yahh); praise ye Jah!, an adoring exclamation.

DEFINITION: one another, each other.
ORIGIN: Genitive plural from allos reduplicated; one another.
USAGE: each other, mutual, one another, (the other), (them-, your-)selves, (selves) together (sometimes with meta or pros).

DEFINITION: of another nation, a foreigner.
ORIGIN: From allos and genos; foreign, i.e. Not a Jew.

DEFINITION: to leap, leap up; of water: to spring up, bubble up.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of apparently a primary verb; to jump; figuratively, to gush.

DEFINITION: other, another (of more than two), different.
ORIGIN: A primary word; "else," i.e. Different (in many applications).

DEFINITION: one who meddles in things alien to his calling or in matters belonging to others; factious.
ORIGIN: From allotrios and episkopos; overseeing others' affairs, i.e. A meddler (specially, in Gentile customs).

DEFINITION: belonging to another person, belonging to others, foreign, strange.
ORIGIN: From allos; another's, i.e. Not one's own; by extension foreign, not akin, hostile.

DEFINITION: foreign, of another tribe or race.
ORIGIN: From allos and phule; foreign, i.e. (specially) Gentile.

DEFINITION: otherwise, things that are otherwise.
ORIGIN: Adverb from allos; differently.

DEFINITION: to thresh (wheat).
ORIGIN: From the same as halon; to tread out grain.

DEFINITION: without reason, irrational; contrary to reason, absurd.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and logos; irrational.

DEFINITION: aloes, the powdered fragrant aloe wood.
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin (compare akanthinos); aloes (the gum).

DEFINITION: salt.
ORIGIN: A primary word; "salt".

DEFINITION: salty, saltine, bitter.
ORIGIN: From hals; briny.

DEFINITION: free from pain (grief, trouble).
ORIGIN: Comparative of a compound of a (as a negative particle) and lupe; more without grief.

DEFINITION: a (light) chain, bond.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a fetter or manacle.

DEFINITION: profitless, unprofitable, ruinous, detrimental.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and the base of lusitelei; gainless, i.e. (by implication) pernicious.

DEFINITION: Alphaeus; apparently two persons, (a) father of Levi, and (b) father of James.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (compare Cheleph); Alphoeus, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: a threshing floor.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of heilisso; a threshing-floor (as rolled hard), i.e. (figuratively) the grain (and chaff, as just threshed).

DEFINITION: a fox; a fox-like, crafty person.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a fox, i.e. (figuratively) a cunning person.

DEFINITION: capture, capturing.
ORIGIN: From a collateral form of haireomai.

DEFINITION: at the same time, therewith, along with, together with.
ORIGIN: A primary particle; properly, at the "same" time, but freely used as a preposition or adverb denoting close association.

DEFINITION: unlearned, ignorant.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and manthano; ignorant.

DEFINITION: unfading, fadeless, enduring.
ORIGIN: From amarantos; "amaranthine", i.e. (by implication) fadeless.

DEFINITION: unfading, enduring.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of maraino; unfading, i.e. (by implication) perpetual.

DEFINITION: originally: to miss the mark, hence (a) to make a mistake, (b) to sin, commit a sin (against God); sometimes the idea of sinning against a fellow-creature is present.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from a (as a negative particle) and the base of meros; properly, to miss the mark (and so not share in the prize), i.e. (figuratively) to err, especially (morally) to sin.
USAGE: for your faults, offend, sin, trespass.

DEFINITION: a fault, sin, evil deed.
ORIGIN: From hamartano; a sin (properly concrete).

DEFINITION: prop: missing the mark; hence: (a) guilt, sin, (b) a fault, failure (in an ethical sense), sinful deed.
ORIGIN: From hamartano; a sin (properly abstract).

DEFINITION: without witness, untestified to.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a form of martus; unattested.

DEFINITION: sinning, sinful, depraved, detestable.
ORIGIN: From hamartano; sinful, i.e. A sinner.

DEFINITION: peaceable, abstaining from fighting, not contentious.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and mache; peaceable.

DEFINITION: to mow, reap, collect.
ORIGIN: From hama; properly, to collect, i.e. (by implication) reap.

DEFINITION: amethyst (a kind of rock crystal: the best specimens are the color of unmixed wine, whence perhaps the name), believed to stave off drunkenness.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of methuo; the "amethyst" (supposed to prevent intoxication).

DEFINITION: to neglect, be careless of, disregard.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and melo; to be careless of.
USAGE: make light of, neglect, be negligent, no regard.

DEFINITION: blameless, free from fault or defect.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of memphomai; irreproachable.

DEFINITION: blamelessly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from amemptos; faultlessly.

DEFINITION: free from anxiety (though anxiety is rather too strong a word) or care.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and merimna; not anxious.

DEFINITION: immutable, unchangeable.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of metatithemi; unchangeable, or (neuter as abstract) unchangeability.

DEFINITION: immovable, firm.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of metakineo; immovable.

DEFINITION: not to be repented of, about which no change of mind can take place, not affected by change of mind.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of metamellomai; irrevocable.
USAGE: without repentance, not to be repented of.

DEFINITION: impenitent, unrepentant.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of metanoeo; unrepentant.

DEFINITION: not measurable, immeasurable, to a limitless degree.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and metron; immoderate.

DEFINITION: verily, truly, amen; at the end of sentences may be paraphrased by: So let it be.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('amen); properly, firm, i.e. (figuratively) trustworthy; adverbially, surely (often as interjection, so be it).

DEFINITION: (lit: motherless), whose mother's name is not recorded (or known).
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and meter; motherless, i.e. Of unknown maternity.

DEFINITION: undefiled, untainted, free from contamination.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of miaino; unsoiled, i.e. (figuratively) pure.

DEFINITION: Amminadab, son of Ram and father of Nahshon, one of the ancestors of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Ammiynadab); Aminadab, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: sand, sandy ground.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from hama; sand (as heaped on the beach).

DEFINITION: a lamb (as a type of innocence, and with sacrificial connotation).
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a lamb.

DEFINITION: a change, an exchange; hence plur: reciprocal good deeds (services), a fitting requital.
ORIGIN: From ameibo (to exchange); requital.

DEFINITION: a vine, grape-vine.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of amphoteros and that of halon; a vine (as coiling about a support).

DEFINITION: a vine-dresser, gardener.
ORIGIN: From ampelos and ergon; a vine-worker, i.e. Pruner.

DEFINITION: a vineyard.
ORIGIN: From ampelos; a vineyard.

DEFINITION: Ampliatus (Amplias), a male member of the church at Rome, probably of the imperial household.
ORIGIN: Contracted for Latin ampliatus (enlarged); Amplias, a Roman Christian.

DEFINITION: to ward off, defend myself against, resist, defend, assist.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of a primary verb; to ward off (for oneself), i.e. Protect.

DEFINITION: prop: something thrown around; a fishing-net, drag-net.
ORIGIN: From a compound of the base of amphoteros and ballo; a (fishing) net (as thrown about the fish).

DEFINITION: to put on, clothe.
ORIGIN: From the base of amphoteros and hennumi (to invest); to enrobe.

DEFINITION: Amphipolis, a leading city of Macedonia.
ORIGIN: From the base of amphoteros and polis; a city surrounded by a river; Amphipolis, a place in Macedonia.

DEFINITION: prop: a road around anything; the street of a village.
ORIGIN: From the base of amphoteros and hodos; a fork in the road.

DEFINITION: both (of two).
ORIGIN: Comparative of amphi (around); (in plural) both.

DEFINITION: without blame or fault, unblemished.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of momaomai; unblamable.

DEFINITION: blameless, without blemish, unblemished, faultless.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and momos; unblemished (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: without blame (blemish, fault, spot), faultless, unblamable.

DEFINITION: Amon (Amos), son of Manasseh and father of Josiah, an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Amown); Amon, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Amos, son of Manasseh and father of Josiah, an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Amowts); Amos, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: an untranslatable word (under the circumstances, in that case, anyhow), the general effect of which is to make a statement contingent, which would otherwise be definite: it is thus regularly used with the subjunctive mood.
ORIGIN: A primary particle, denoting a supposition, wish, possibility or uncertainty.
USAGE: (what-, where-, wither-, who-)soever. Usually unexpressed except by the subjunctive or potential mood. Also contracted for ean.

DEFINITION: prep. Rare in NT; prop: upwards, up; among, between; in turn; apiece, by; as a prefix: up, to, anew, back.
ORIGIN: A primary preposition and adverb; properly, up; but (by extension) used (distributively) severally, or (locally) at (etc.).
USAGE: and, apiece, by, each, every (man), in, through. In compounds (as a prefix) it often means (by implication) repetition, intensity, reversal, etc.

DEFINITION: a step, a flight of steps; the well-known stairs leading up from the temple to the tower of Antonia at Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: From anabaino (compare bathmos); a stairway.

DEFINITION: to go up, mount, ascend; of things: to rise, spring up, come up.
ORIGIN: From ana and the base of basis; to go up (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: arise, ascend (up), climb (go, grow, rise, spring) up, come (up).

DEFINITION: to postpone, defer, especially: to postpone the trial of.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from ana and ballo; to put off (for oneself).

DEFINITION: to draw up, as a net to shore.
ORIGIN: From ana and a derivative of the base of basis; to cause to go up, i.e. Haul (a net).

DEFINITION: to look up, recover sight.
ORIGIN: From ana and blepo; to look up; by implication, to recover sight.

DEFINITION: recovery of sight.
ORIGIN: From anablepo; restoration of sight.

DEFINITION: to shout upwards, cry out, raise voice.
ORIGIN: From ana and boao; to halloo.

DEFINITION: postponement, delay, putting off.
ORIGIN: From anaballomai; a putting off.

DEFINITION: to bring back word, report; to announce, declare.
ORIGIN: From ana and the base of aggelos; to announce (in detail).
USAGE: declare, rehearse, report, show, speak, tell.

DEFINITION: to beget again, beget into a new life.
ORIGIN: From ana and gennao; to beget or (by extension) bear (again).

DEFINITION: to read, know again, know certainly, recognize, discern.
ORIGIN: From ana and ginosko; to know again, i.e. (by extension) to read.

DEFINITION: to force, compel, constrain, urge.
ORIGIN: From anagke; to necessitate.

DEFINITION: necessary, essential, intimate, right, proper.
ORIGIN: From anagke; necessary; by implication, close (of kin).

DEFINITION: by way of compulsion, unwillingly, by force, necessarily.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a derivative of anagkazo; compulsorily.

DEFINITION: necessity, constraint, compulsion; there is need to; force, violence.
ORIGIN: From ana and the base of agkale; constraint (literally or figuratively); by implication, distress.
USAGE: distress, must needs, (of) necessity(-sary), needeth, needful.

DEFINITION: to recognize; pass: to be made known, cause myself to be recognized.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from ana and gnorizo; to make (oneself) known.

DEFINITION: recognition, reading; public reading (of the law and prophets in synagogue or church).
ORIGIN: From anaginosko; (the act of) reading.

DEFINITION: to lead up, bring up, offer, produce, put to sea, set sail.
ORIGIN: From ana and ago; to lead up; by extension to bring out; specially, to sail away.
USAGE: bring (again, forth, up again), depart, launch (forth), lead (up), loose, offer, sail, set forth, take up.

DEFINITION: to show forth, show clearly; hence: to proclaim (a person's appointment to an office), appoint.
ORIGIN: From ana and deiknuo; to exhibit, i.e. (by implication) to indicate, appoint.

DEFINITION: the proclamation of an appointment (to an office); perhaps rather admission to membership of a society.
ORIGIN: From anadeiknumi; (the act of) exhibition.

DEFINITION: to welcome, receive kindly; to undertake, assume the responsibility of.
ORIGIN: From ana and dechomai; to entertain (as a guest).

DEFINITION: to send up, deliver, hand over, yield.
ORIGIN: From ana and didomi; to hand over.

DEFINITION: to come to life again, revive, regain life.
ORIGIN: To recover life (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to seek out, search for (implying the difficulty of the task).
ORIGIN: From ana and zeteo; to search out.

DEFINITION: to gird up, brace up (with a view to active exertion); a metaphor from the girding of the flowing tunic, to prevent its hampering one in active work.
ORIGIN: From ana and zonnumi; to gird afresh.

DEFINITION: to stir up the fire, fan the flame of.
ORIGIN: From ana and a compound of the base of zoon and pur; to re-enkindle.

DEFINITION: to thrive or flourish again, revive.
ORIGIN: From ana and thallo (to flourish); to revive.

DEFINITION: a votive offering, a thing devoted to God; a curse, the thing cursed.
ORIGIN: From anatithemai; a (religious) ban or (concretely) excommunicated (thing or person).

DEFINITION: to curse, invoke curses, devote to destruction.
ORIGIN: From anathema; to declare or vow under penalty of execration.
USAGE: (bind under a) curse, bind with an oath.

DEFINITION: to look at attentively, gaze at, consider.
ORIGIN: From ana and theoreo; to look again (i.e. Attentively) at (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: an offering dedicated (hung up in a temple) by a worshipper; a gift or offering consecrated to God.
ORIGIN: From anatithemai (like anathema, but in a good sense); a votive offering.

DEFINITION: shamelessness, shameless persistence (e.g. in greed).
ORIGIN: From a compound of a (as a negative particle (compare aneu)) and aidos; impudence, i.e. (by implication) importunity.

DEFINITION: taking away (of life), killing, slaying, murder.
ORIGIN: From anaireo; (the act of) killing.

DEFINITION: to take up, take away the life of, make an end of, murder.
ORIGIN: From ana and (the active of) haireomai; to take up, i.e. Adopt; by implication, to take away (violently), i.e. Abolish, murder.
USAGE: put to death, kill, slay, take away, take up.

DEFINITION: guiltless, innocent.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and aitios (in the sense of aitia); innocent.

DEFINITION: to set up, to sit up.
ORIGIN: From ana and kathizo; properly, to set up, i.e. (reflexively) to sit up.

DEFINITION: to make fresh again, renew, restore.
ORIGIN: From ana and a derivative of kainos; to restore.

DEFINITION: to renew, make new again.
ORIGIN: From ana and a derivative of kainos; to renovate.

DEFINITION: renewing; a renewal or change of heart and life.
ORIGIN: From anakainoo; renovation.

DEFINITION: to unveil, uncover.
ORIGIN: From ana (in the sense of reversal) and kalupto; to unveil.

DEFINITION: to bend or turn back; to return.
ORIGIN: From ana and kampto; to turn back.

DEFINITION: to recline, especially at a dinner-table.
ORIGIN: From ana and keimai; to recline (as a corpse or at a meal).
USAGE: guest, lean, lie, sit (down, at meat), at the table.

DEFINITION: to sum up, summarize, recapitulate, gather up in one.
ORIGIN: From ana and kephalaioo (in its original sense); to sum up.
USAGE: briefly comprehend, gather together in one.

DEFINITION: to lay upon, lean against, lay down, make to recline; pass: to lie back, recline.
ORIGIN: From ana and klino; to lean back.

DEFINITION: hinder.
ORIGIN: From ana and kopto; to beat back, i.e. Check.

DEFINITION: to shout aloud, cry out.
ORIGIN: From ana and krazo; to scream up (aloud).

DEFINITION: to examine, inquire into, investigate, question.
ORIGIN: From ana and krino; properly, to scrutinize, i.e. (by implication) investigate, interrogate, determine.
USAGE: ask, question, discern, examine, judge, search.

DEFINITION: judicial examination, preliminary inquiry.
ORIGIN: From anakrino; a (judicial) investigation.

DEFINITION: to raise myself, look up, be elated.
ORIGIN: From ana (in the sense of reversal) and kupto; to unbend, i.e. Rise; figuratively, be elated.

DEFINITION: to take up, raise; to pick up, take on board; to carry off, lead away.
ORIGIN: From ana and lambano; to take up.

DEFINITION: a taking up, lifting up.
ORIGIN: From analambano; ascension.

DEFINITION: to destroy, annihilate, expend, consume.
ORIGIN: From ana and a form of the alternate of haireomai; properly, to use up, i.e. Destroy.

DEFINITION: proportion, measure, analogy.
ORIGIN: From a compound of ana and logos; proportion.

DEFINITION: to think upon, consider attentively.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from analogia; to estimate, i.e. (figuratively) contemplate.

DEFINITION: saltless, tasteless, flat.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and hals; saltless, i.e. Insipid.

DEFINITION: a loosing, departing, departure (from this life); (Probably a metaphor from the yoking and unyoking of transport animals).
ORIGIN: From analuo; departure.

DEFINITION: to unloose, unloose for departure, depart, return.
ORIGIN: From ana and luo; to break up, i.e. Depart (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: without blame, faultless, unerring.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of hamartano; sinless.

DEFINITION: to await (one whose coming is expected).
ORIGIN: From ana and meno; to await.

DEFINITION: to remind, admonish, be reminded, remind myself; pass: to remember, recall.
ORIGIN: From ana and mimnesko; to remind; (reflexively) to recollect.
USAGE: call to mind, (bring to, call to, put in), remember(-brance).

DEFINITION: a recalling, remembrance, memory.
ORIGIN: From anamimnesko; recollection.

DEFINITION: to renew; mid: to renew myself, be renewed.
ORIGIN: From ana and a derivative of neos; to renovate, i.e. Reform.

DEFINITION: to return to soberness, regain one's senses.
ORIGIN: From ana and nepho; to become sober again, i.e. (figuratively) regain (one's) senses.

DEFINITION: Ananias, (a) husband of Sapphira, a member of the early church at Jerusalem, (b) a member of the church at Damascus, (c) the high priest at Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Chananyah); Ananias, the name of three Israelites.

DEFINITION: indisputable, undeniable, not to be contradicted.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of a compound of anti and rheo; indisputable.

DEFINITION: without contradiction, without hesitation, promptly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from anantirrhetos; promptly.

DEFINITION: unworthy, inadequate.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and axios; unfit.

DEFINITION: unworthily, in an unworthy manner.
ORIGIN: Adverb from anaxios; irreverently.

DEFINITION: rest, cessation from labor, refreshment.
ORIGIN: From anapano; intermission; by implication, recreation.

DEFINITION: to give rest, give intermission from labor, by implication refresh.
ORIGIN: From ana and pauo; (reflexively) to repose (literally or figuratively (be exempt), remain); by implication, to refresh.

DEFINITION: to persuade, incite, seduce, tempt.
ORIGIN: From ana and peitho; to incite.

DEFINITION: to send up (to a higher tribunal), send back.
ORIGIN: From ana and pempo; to send up or back.

DEFINITION: crippled, maimed.
ORIGIN: From ana (in the sense of intensity) and peros (maimed); crippled.

DEFINITION: to lie down, recline (at a dinner-table), fall back upon (the breast of another person reclining at dinner).
ORIGIN: From ana and pipto; to fall back, i.e. Lie down, lean back.

DEFINITION: to fill up, make up, complete the measure of, fulfill, carry out the commands (provisions, etc.) of.
ORIGIN: From ana and pleroo; to complete; by implication, to occupy, supply; figuratively, to accomplish (by coincidence ot obedience).

DEFINITION: without (ground of) defense, indefensible, inexcusable.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of apologeomai; indefensible.

DEFINITION: to unroll, roll back, unfold.
ORIGIN: From ana (in the sense of reversal) and ptusso; to unroll (a scroll or volume).

DEFINITION: to kindle, set on fire, light.
ORIGIN: From ana and hapto; to enkindle.

DEFINITION: uncountable, innumerable, that cannot be numbered.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of arithmeo; unnumbered, i.e. Without number.

DEFINITION: to shake up, stir up, excite.
ORIGIN: From ana and seio; figuratively, to excite.

DEFINITION: to pervert, subvert, dismantle, unsettle, overthrow, destroy.
ORIGIN: From ana (in the sense of reversal) and a derivative of skeuos; properly, to pack up (baggage), i.e. (by implication, and figuratively) to upset.

DEFINITION: to drag up, pull up, draw up, draw out.
ORIGIN: From ana and spao; to take up or extricate.

DEFINITION: a standing up, a resurrection, a raising up, rising.
ORIGIN: From anistemi; a standing up again, i.e. (literally) a resurrection from death (individual, genitive case or by implication, (its author)), or (figuratively) a (moral) recovery (of spiritual truth).
USAGE: raised to life again, resurrection, rise from the dead, that should rise, rising again.

DEFINITION: (perhaps a political metaphor), to turn upside down, upset, unsettle.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of anistemi (in the sense of removal); properly, to drive out of home, i.e. (by implication) to disturb (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: trouble, turn upside down, make an uproar.

DEFINITION: to impede, crucify (again).
ORIGIN: From ana and stauroo; to recrucify (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to groan or sigh deeply.
ORIGIN: From ana and stenazo; to sigh deeply.

DEFINITION: to overturn; to turn back, return; to turn hither and thither; pass: to turn myself about; to sojourn, dwell; to conduct myself, behave, live.
ORIGIN: From ana and strepho; to overturn; also to return; by implication, to busy oneself, i.e. Remain, live.
USAGE: abide, behave self, have conversation, live, overthrow, pass, return, be used.

DEFINITION: dealing with other men, conduct, life, behavior, manner of life.
ORIGIN: From anastrepho; behavior.

DEFINITION: to arrange, draw up, compose, but perhaps: to set down from memory, restore from memory.
ORIGIN: From ana and the middle voice of tasso; to arrange.

DEFINITION: to make to rise, to rise, shine (generally of the sun, and hence met.).
ORIGIN: From ana and the base of telos; to (cause to) arise.
USAGE: (a-, make to) rise, at the rising of, spring (up), be up.

DEFINITION: to lay (a case) before, impart, communicate, declare, relate (with a view to consulting).
ORIGIN: From ana and the middle voice of tithemi; to set forth (for oneself), i.e propound.

DEFINITION: (a) rising of the sun, hence (b) (sing. and plur.) the quarter whence the sun rises, the East.
ORIGIN: From anatello; a rising of light, i.e. Dawn (figuratively); by implication, the east (also in plural).

DEFINITION: to overturn (lit. or met.), subvert, overthrow, corrupt.
ORIGIN: From ana and the base of trope; to overturn (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to rear, bring up, nourish, educate.
ORIGIN: From ana and trepho; to rear (physically or mentally).

DEFINITION: (a) a nautical term: to sight (a place), (b) mid: to appear (as it were, out of the unseen), (c) to bring to light, make to appear.
ORIGIN: From ana and phaino; to show, i.e. (reflexively) appear, or (passively) to have pointed out.

DEFINITION: (a) to carry up, lead up, (b) to offer up (on a high altar) as a sacrifice, offer up to God on high.
ORIGIN: From ana and phero; to take up (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to call out, shout, exclaim.
ORIGIN: From ana and phoneo; to exclaim.

DEFINITION: outpouring, excess, overflow, a pouring out.
ORIGIN: From a comparative of ana and cheo (to pour); properly, effusion, i.e. (figuratively) license.

DEFINITION: to return, retire, withdraw, depart (underlying idea perhaps of taking refuge from danger or of going into retirement).
ORIGIN: From ana and choreo; to retire.
USAGE: depart, give place, go (turn) aside, withdraw self.

DEFINITION: a recovery of breath, a refreshing.
ORIGIN: From anapsucho; properly, a recovery of breath, i.e. (figuratively) revival.

DEFINITION: to refresh, revive, comfort.
ORIGIN: From ana and psucho; properly, to cool off, i.e. (figuratively) relieve.

DEFINITION: an enslaver, one who forcibly enslaves, a kidnapper.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of a compound of aner and pous; an enslaver (as bringing men to his feet).

DEFINITION: Andrew, brother of Simon Peter, and one of the apostles of Jesus, belonging to Bethsaida.
ORIGIN: From aner; manly; Andreas, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: to behave like a man, to play the man.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from aner; to act manly.

DEFINITION: Andronicus, a member of the Roman church, and a kinsman or fellow-tribesman of Paul.
ORIGIN: From aner and nikos; man of victory; Andronicos, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: a murderer, man-slayer.
ORIGIN: From aner and phonos; a murderer.

DEFINITION: not to be called to account, unreprovable.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of egkaleo; unaccused, i.e. (by implication) irreproachable.

DEFINITION: indescribable, that cannot be thoroughly related, inexpressible.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of ekdiegeomai; not expounded in full, i.e. Indescribable.

DEFINITION: unspeakable.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of eklaleo; not spoken out, i.e. (by implication) unutterable.

DEFINITION: unfailing.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of ekleipo; not left out, i.e. (by implication) inexhaustible.

DEFINITION: endurable, tolerable.
ORIGIN: Comparative of a derivative of anechomai; more endurable.

DEFINITION: unpitying, unmerciful, without compassion, cruel.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and eleemon; merciless.

DEFINITION: to be blown with the wind (referring to the gentler motions of the air).
ORIGIN: From anemos; to toss with the wind.

DEFINITION: the wind; fig: applied to empty doctrines.
ORIGIN: From the base of aer; wind; (plural) by implication, (the four) quarters (of the earth).

DEFINITION: impossible, inadmissible.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of the same as endechetai; unadmitted, i.e. (by implication) not supposable.

DEFINITION: that cannot be searched into, inscrutable, unfathomable.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of exereunao; not searched out, i.e. (by implication) inscrutable.

DEFINITION: enduring evil, patient of evil, patiently forbearing.
ORIGIN: From anechomai and kakos; enduring of ill, i.e. Forbearing.

DEFINITION: that cannot be explored, incomprehensible.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of a compound of ek and a derivative of ichnos; not tracked out, i.e. (by implication) untraceable.

DEFINITION: having no cause to be ashamed.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of a compound of epi and aischunomai; not ashamed, i.e. Irreprehensible.
USAGE: that needeth not to be ashamed.

DEFINITION: irreproachable, never caught doing wrong.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of epilambanomai; not arrested, i.e. (by implication) inculpable.

DEFINITION: to come up, go up, ascend.
ORIGIN: From ana and erchomai; to ascend.

DEFINITION: relief, remission, indulgence, freedom, rest.
ORIGIN: From aniemi; relaxation or (figuratively) relief.

DEFINITION: to examine (a person on trial, a witness) judicially (frequently by the aid of torture).
ORIGIN: From ana and etazo (to test); to investigate (judicially).

DEFINITION: without, without the cooperation (or knowledge) of.
ORIGIN: A primary particle; without.

DEFINITION: unfitted, unsuitable, inconvenient, not well placed.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and euthetos; not well set, i.e. Inconvenient.

DEFINITION: to find by seeking out, discover.
ORIGIN: From ana and heurisko; to find out.

DEFINITION: to endure, bear with, have patience with, suffer, admit, persist.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from ana and echo; to hold oneself up against, i.e. (figuratively) put up with.

DEFINITION: a cousin, nephew.
ORIGIN: From a (as a particle of union) and an obsolete nepos (a brood); properly, akin, i.e. (specially) a cousin.

DEFINITION: anise, dill.
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin; dill.

DEFINITION: is due, becoming, suitable, proper.
ORIGIN: From ana and heko; to attain to, i.e. (figuratively) be proper.

DEFINITION: not tame, fierce, savage.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and hemeros (lame); savage.

DEFINITION: a male human being; a man, husband.
ORIGIN: A primary word (compare anthropos); a man (properly as an individual male).

DEFINITION: to set against; to withstand, resist, oppose.
ORIGIN: From anti and histemi; to stand against, i.e. Oppose.

DEFINITION: to make a mutual agreement; to confess, acknowledge, formally admit, give thanks to.
ORIGIN: From anti and the middle voice of homologeo; to confess in turn, i.e. Respond in praise.

DEFINITION: bloom, possibly a reference to the bright flowers, such as poppies (among the grass).
ORIGIN: A primary word; a blossom.

DEFINITION: a coal-fire, a heap of burning coals.
ORIGIN: From anthrax; a bed of burning coals.

DEFINITION: coal, charcoal, a burning coal.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a live coal.

DEFINITION: desirous of pleasing men, a renderer of service to human beings (as opposed to God).
ORIGIN: From anthropos and aresko; man-courting, i.e. Fawning.

DEFINITION: belonging to human beings (especially as contrasted with God), human (as contrasted with divine).
ORIGIN: From anthropos; human.
USAGE: human, common to man, man(-kind), (man-)kind, men's, after the manner of men.

DEFINITION: a murderer, man-slayer.
ORIGIN: From anthropos and kteino (to kill); a manslayer.

DEFINITION: a man, one of the human race.
ORIGIN: From aner and ops (the countenance; from optanomai); man-faced, i.e. A human being.

DEFINITION: to act as proconsul, be a deputy.
ORIGIN: From anthupatos; to act as proconsul.

DEFINITION: a consul, proconsul.
ORIGIN: From anti and a superlative of huper; instead of the highest officer, i.e. (specially) a Roman proconsul.

DEFINITION: to send up, produce, send back; to let go; to relax, loosen, hence met: to give up, desist from.
ORIGIN: From ana and hiemi (to send); to let up, i.e. (literally) slacken or (figuratively) desert, desist from.

DEFINITION: without mercy, merciless.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and hileos; inexorable.

DEFINITION: unwashed, ceremonially unclean.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of nipto; without ablution.

DEFINITION: to raise up, set up; to rise from among (the) dead; to arise, appear.
ORIGIN: From ana and histemi; to stand up (literal or figurative, transitive or intransitive).
USAGE: arise, lift up, raise up (again), rise (again), stand up(-right).

DEFINITION: Anna, a prophetess, who visited the infant Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Channah); Anna, an Israelitess.

DEFINITION: Annas, high priest at Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Chananyah); Annas (i.e. Ananias), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: foolish, thoughtless.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of noieo; unintelligent; by implication, sensual.

DEFINITION: folly, madness, foolishness.
ORIGIN: From a compound of a (as a negative particle) and nous; stupidity; by implication, rage.

DEFINITION: to open.
ORIGIN: From ana and oigo (to open); to open up (literally or figuratively, in various applications).

DEFINITION: to rebuild, build up (what has fallen or been razed to the ground), sometimes merely: to build.
ORIGIN: From ana and oikodomeo; to rebuild.

DEFINITION: the act of opening.
ORIGIN: From anoigo; opening (throat).

DEFINITION: lawlessness, iniquity, disobedience, sin.
ORIGIN: From anomos; illegality, i.e. Violation of law or (genitive case) wickedness.
USAGE: iniquity, X transgress(-ion of) the law, unrighteousness.

DEFINITION: lawless, wicked, without law.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and nomos; lawless, i.e. (negatively) not subject to (the Jewish) law; (by implication, a Gentile), or (positively) wicked.
USAGE: without law, lawless, transgressor, unlawful, wicked.

DEFINITION: without law, lawlessly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from anomos; lawlessly, i.e. (specially) not amenable to (the Jewish) law.

DEFINITION: to make upright (straight) again, rear again, restore.
ORIGIN: From ana and a derivative of the base of orthos; to straighten up.

DEFINITION: unholy, profane.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and hosios; wicked.

DEFINITION: forbearance, suspense or delay (of punishment), patience.
ORIGIN: From anechomai; self-restraint, i.e. Tolerance.

DEFINITION: to resist, strive against, contend.
ORIGIN: From anti and agonizomai; to struggle against (figuratively) ("antagonize").

DEFINITION: an exchange, purchasing price.
ORIGIN: From a compound of anti and allasso; an equivalent or ransom.

DEFINITION: to fill up in place of someone else, complete, supply.
ORIGIN: From anti and anapleroo; to supplement.

DEFINITION: to give back as an equivalent, recompense.
ORIGIN: From anti and apodidomi; to requite (good or evil).

DEFINITION: a gift in return (for another), a return, recompense, requital.
ORIGIN: From antapodidomi; a requital (properly, the thing).

DEFINITION: a reward, recompense.
ORIGIN: From antapodidomi; requital (properly, the act).

DEFINITION: to contradict, reply against, give a hostile answer.
ORIGIN: From anti and apokrinomai; to contradict or dispute.

DEFINITION: to speak or say in opposition, contradict (oppose, resist).
ORIGIN: From anti and epo; to refute or deny.

DEFINITION: trans: to hold against; intrans: to withstand; mid: to hold out against, hold firmly to, cleave to.
ORIGIN: From anti and the middle voice of echo; to hold oneself opposite to, i.e. (by implication) adhere to; by extension to care for.

DEFINITION: (a) instead of, in return for, over against, opposite, in exchange for, as a substitute for, (b) on behalf, (c) wherefore, because.
ORIGIN: A primary particle; opposite, i.e. Instead or because of (rarely in addition to).
USAGE: for, in the room of. Often used in composition to denote contrast, requital, substitution, correspondence, etc.

DEFINITION: to throw at in opposition, exchange (words) with, perhaps: to compare.
ORIGIN: From anti and ballo; to bandy.

DEFINITION: to oppose, set oneself in opposition.
ORIGIN: From anti and diatithemai; to set oneself opposite, i.e. Be disputatious.

DEFINITION: an opponent (at law), an adversary.
ORIGIN: From anti and dike; an opponent (in a lawsuit); specially, Satan (as the arch-enemy).

DEFINITION: a proposition, tenet, opinion advanced by one party against another; opposition.
ORIGIN: From a compound of anti and tithemi; opposition, i.e. A conflict (of theories).

DEFINITION: to set down against, to replace, oppose.
ORIGIN: From anti and kathistemi; to set down (troops) against, i.e. Withstand.

DEFINITION: to invite in return.
ORIGIN: From anti and kaleo; to invite in return.

DEFINITION: to resist, oppose, withstand, lie opposite to.
ORIGIN: From anti and keimai; to lie opposite, i.e. Be adverse (figuratively, repugnant) to.

DEFINITION: right opposite, off (nautical sense), over against.
ORIGIN: Prolonged from anti; opposite.

DEFINITION: to take hold of, help, share in, partake of, enjoy.
ORIGIN: From anti and the middle voice of lambano; to take hold of in turn, i.e. Succor; also to participate.

DEFINITION: to speak or say in opposition, contradict (oppose, resist).
ORIGIN: From anti and lego; to dispute, refuse.
USAGE: answer again, contradict, deny, gainsay(-er), speak against.

DEFINITION: help, ministration; one who aids.
ORIGIN: From antilambanomai; relief.

DEFINITION: contradiction, contention, rebellion.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of antilego; dispute, disobedience.

DEFINITION: to abuse in return, give abuse for abuse.
ORIGIN: From anti and loidoreo; to rail in reply.

DEFINITION: a ransom.
ORIGIN: From anti and lutron; a redemption-price.

DEFINITION: to measure in return, give equivalent measure.
ORIGIN: From anti and metreo; to mete in return.

DEFINITION: a reward, recompense, retribution.
ORIGIN: From a compound of anti and misthos; requital, correspondence.

DEFINITION: Antioch, (a) Antioch on the river Orontes, capital of the Province Syria, (b) Pisidian Antioch, not in Pisidia, but near Pisidia, in the Roman Province Galatia.
ORIGIN: From Antiochus (a Syrian king); Antiochia, a place in Syria.

DEFINITION: an Antiochian, an inhabitant of Antioch.
ORIGIN: From Antiocheia; an Antiochian or inhabitant of Antiochia.

DEFINITION: to pass opposite, on the opposite side of the road.
ORIGIN: From anti and parerchomai; to go along opposite.
USAGE: pass by on the other side.

DEFINITION: Antipas, a Christian martyr of Pergamum.
ORIGIN: Contracted for a compound of anti and a derivative of pater; Antipas, a Christian.

DEFINITION: Antipatris, a town, where was a Roman colony, on the road between Caesarea and Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: From the same as Antipas; Antipatris, a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: on the opposite side or shore.
ORIGIN: From anti and peran; on the opposite side.

DEFINITION: to resist, oppose, fall against or upon.
ORIGIN: From anti and pipto (including its alternate); to oppose.

DEFINITION: to campaign against, war against.
ORIGIN: From anti and strateuomai; (figuratively) to attack, i.e. (by implication) destroy.

DEFINITION: to range in battle against, to set oneself against.
ORIGIN: From anti and the middle voice of tasso; to range oneself against, i.e. Oppose.

DEFINITION: typical of, representing by type (or pattern), corresponding to, an image.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a compound of anti and tupos; corresponding ("antitype"), i.e. A representative, counterpart.

DEFINITION: antichrist, either one who puts himself in the place of, or the enemy (opponent) of the Messiah.
ORIGIN: From anti and Christos; an opponent of the Messiah.

DEFINITION: to draw (generally water from a deep well in the ground); perhaps: to draw out.
ORIGIN: From antlos (the hold of a ship); to bale up (properly, bilge water), i.e. Dip water (with a bucket, pitcher, etc.).

DEFINITION: what is drawn; a vessel or bucket to draw with.
ORIGIN: From antleo; a baling-vessel.

DEFINITION: to face (lit: to present eye to), resist, withstand; as nautical term: to bear up against the wind.
ORIGIN: From a compound of anti and ophthalmos; to face.

DEFINITION: without water, dry; subst: dry places, desert.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and hudor; waterless, i.e. Dry.

DEFINITION: unfeigned, without hypocrisy, sincere.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of hupokrinomai; undissembled, i.e. Sincere.

DEFINITION: not subject to rule, unruly.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of hupotasso; unsubdued, i.e. Insubordinate (in fact or temper).
USAGE: disobedient, that is not put under, unruly.

DEFINITION: up, above, up to the top, up to the brim, things above, heaven, the heavenly region.
ORIGIN: Adverb from anti; upward or on the top.

DEFINITION: an upper room.
ORIGIN: From ano and ge; above the ground, i.e. (properly) the second floor of a building; used for a dome or a balcony on the upper story.

DEFINITION: (a) from above, from heaven, (b) from the beginning, from their origin (source), from of old, (c) again, anew.
ORIGIN: From ano; from above; by analogy, from the first; by implication, anew.
USAGE: from above, again, from the beginning (very first), the top.

DEFINITION: upper, higher-lying, inland.
ORIGIN: From anoteros; superior, i.e. (locally) more remote.

DEFINITION: higher, to a more honorable place (at the dinner table); previously, in an earlier passage (or a book), above.
ORIGIN: Comparative degree of ano; upper, i.e. (neuter as adverb) to a more conspicuous place, in a former part of the book.

DEFINITION: useless, unprofitable.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and the base of ophelimos; useless or (neuter) inutility.

DEFINITION: an axe.
ORIGIN: Probably from agnumi (to break; compare rhegnumi); an axe.

DEFINITION: worthy, worthy of, deserving, comparable, suitable.
ORIGIN: Probably from ago; deserving, comparable or suitable (as if drawing praise).

DEFINITION: to account or treat as worthy.
ORIGIN: From axios; to deem entitled or fit.

DEFINITION: worthily, in a manner worthy of.
ORIGIN: Adverb from axios; appropriately.
USAGE: as becometh, after a godly sort, worthily(-thy).

DEFINITION: unseen, invisible.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and horatos; invisible.

DEFINITION: to report (from one place to another), bring a report, announce, declare.
ORIGIN: From apo and the base of aggelos; to announce.
USAGE: bring word (again), declare, report, shew (again), tell.

DEFINITION: to choke, strangle; mid: to strangle or hang myself.
ORIGIN: From apo and agcho (to choke; akin to the base of agkale); to strangle oneself off (i.e. To death).

DEFINITION: to lead, carry, take away; met: to be led astray, seduced.
ORIGIN: From apo and ago; to take off (in various senses).
USAGE: bring, carry away, lead (away), put to death, take away.

DEFINITION: untrained, uneducated, showing a want of training or education, ignorant.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of paideuo; uninstructed, i.e. (figuratively) stupid.

DEFINITION: to take away, remove; pass: to be taken away, withdrawn.
ORIGIN: From apo and airo; to lift off, i.e. Remove.

DEFINITION: to ask back, ask what is due, demand back.
ORIGIN: From apo and aiteo; to demand back.
