DEFINITION: (lit: to cease to feel [my] pain), be past feeling, cease to care (suggesting sometimes despair, sometimes recklessness), become callous, reckless.
ORIGIN: From apo and algeo (to smart); to grieve out, i.e. Become apathetic.

DEFINITION: to free (a person) from (anything), oftener in the middle voice: to be released from, be rid of (a person or thing), depart.
ORIGIN: From apo and allasso; to change away, i.e. Release, (reflexively) remove.

DEFINITION: to estrange, alienate; pass: to be alienated from.
ORIGIN: From apo and a derivative of allotrios; to estrange away, i.e. (passively and figuratively) to be non-participant.

DEFINITION: soft, tender, as a shoot of a tree.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; soft.

DEFINITION: to go to meet, meet, encounter.
ORIGIN: From apo and a derivative of anti; to meet away, i.e. Encounter.

DEFINITION: the act of meeting, to meet (a phrase seemingly almost technical for the reception of a newly arrived official).
ORIGIN: From apantao; a (friendly) encounter.

DEFINITION: once, once for all.
ORIGIN: Probably from hapas; one (or a single) time (numerically or conclusively).

DEFINITION: inviolable, unchangeable.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of parabaino; not passing away, i.e. Untransferable (perpetual).

DEFINITION: unprepared.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of paraskeuazo; unready.

DEFINITION: to deny, disown, repudiate (either another person or myself), disregard.
ORIGIN: From apo and arneomai; to deny utterly, i.e. Disown, abstain.

DEFINITION: from henceforth.
ORIGIN: From apo and arti; from now, i.e. Henceforth (already).

DEFINITION: completion, perfection.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of aparti; completion.

DEFINITION: the first-fruits, the earliest crop of the year, hence also met., for example, of the earliest converts in a district; there is evidence in favor of rendering in some passages merely by: sacrifice, gift.
ORIGIN: From a compound of apo and archomai; a beginning of sacrifice, i.e. The (Jewish) first-fruit (figuratively).

DEFINITION: all, the whole, altogether.
ORIGIN: From a (as a particle of union) and pas; absolutely all or (singular) every one.

DEFINITION: to deceive, cheat, lead into error.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; to cheat, i.e. Delude.

DEFINITION: deceit, deception, deceitfulness, delusion.
ORIGIN: From apatao; delusion.

DEFINITION: without (recorded) father, of unknown father.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and pater; fatherless, i.e. Of unrecorded paternity.

DEFINITION: a light flashing forth (from), radiation, gleam.
ORIGIN: From a compound of apo and augazo; an off-flash, i.e. Effulgence.

DEFINITION: see.
ORIGIN: From apo and the same as eido; to see fully.

DEFINITION: willful unbelief, obstinacy, disobedience.
ORIGIN: From apeithes; disbelief (obstinate and rebellious).

DEFINITION: to disobey, rebel, be disloyal, refuse conformity.
ORIGIN: From apeithes; to disbelieve (wilfully and perversely).
USAGE: not believe, disobedient, obey not, unbelieving.

DEFINITION: unbelieving, disobedient, who will not be persuaded.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and peitho; unpersuadable, i.e. Contumacious.

DEFINITION: to threaten, forbid by threatening.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; to menace; by implication, to forbid.

DEFINITION: a threatening, threat.
ORIGIN: From apeileo; a menace.

DEFINITION: to be away, to be absent.
ORIGIN: From apo and eimi; to be away.

DEFINITION: to go away, depart.
ORIGIN: From apo and eimi (to go); to go away.

DEFINITION: to renounce, disown, forbid, refuse.
ORIGIN: Reflexive past of a compound of apo and epo; to say off for oneself, i.e. Disown.

DEFINITION: untried, inexperienced, untempted, incapable of being tempted.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of peirao; untried, i.e. Not temptable.

DEFINITION: inexperienced, unskillful, ignorant.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and peira; inexperienced, i.e. Ignorant.

DEFINITION: to expect eagerly, wait for eagerly, look for.
ORIGIN: From apo and ekdechomai; to expect fully.

DEFINITION: to strip, divest, renounce.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from apo and ekduo; to divest wholly oneself, or (for oneself) despoil.

DEFINITION: a putting off (as of a garment), a casting off.
ORIGIN: From apekduomai; divestment.

DEFINITION: to drive away.
ORIGIN: From apo and elauno; to dismiss.

DEFINITION: refutation, rejection, hence: disrepute, contempt.
ORIGIN: From a compound of apo and elegcho; refutation, i.e. (by implication) contempt.

DEFINITION: a freedman, one who has been a slave but has been manumitted by his master.
ORIGIN: From apo and eleutheros; one freed away, i.e. A freedman.

DEFINITION: Apelles, a Christian (man) in Rome.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; Apelles, a Christian.

DEFINITION: to give up in despair, despair of; to hope to receive from or in return.
ORIGIN: From apo and elpizo; to hope out, i.e. Fully expect.

DEFINITION: against, over against, opposite, in view of, in the presence of.
ORIGIN: From apo and enanti; from in front, i.e. Opposite, before or against.
USAGE: before, contrary, over against, in the presence of.

DEFINITION: unaccomplished, unending, endless.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a secondary derivative of peran; unfinished, i.e. (by implication) interminable.

DEFINITION: without distraction, without being distracted.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a compound of a (as a negative participle) and a presumed derivative of perispao; undistractedly, i.e. Free from (domestic) solicitude.

DEFINITION: uncircumcised.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of peritemno; uncircumcised (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to come or go away from, depart, return, arrive, go after, follow.
ORIGIN: From apo and erchomai; to go off (i.e. Depart), aside (i.e. Apart) or behind (i.e. Follow), literally or figuratively.
USAGE: come, depart, go (aside, away, back, out,... Ways), pass away, be past.

DEFINITION: it is enough.
ORIGIN: Third person singular present indicative active of apecho used impersonally; it is sufficient.

DEFINITION: to abstain from, keep myself away from.
ORIGIN: Middle voice (reflexively) of apecho; to hold oneself off, i.e. Refrain.

DEFINITION: to hold back, keep off, to be away, be distant.
ORIGIN: From apo and echo; (actively) to have out, i.e. Receive in full; (intransitively) to keep (oneself) away, i.e. Be distant (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to be unfaithful, disbelieve, refuse belief, prove false.
ORIGIN: From apistos; to be unbelieving, i.e. (transitively) disbelieve, or (by implication) disobey.

DEFINITION: unbelief, unfaithfulness, distrust.
ORIGIN: From apistos; faithlessness, i.e. (negatively) disbelief (lack of Christian faith), or (positively) unfaithfulness (disobedience).

DEFINITION: unbelieving, incredulous, unchristian; sometimes subst: unbeliever.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and pistos; (actively) disbelieving, i.e. Without Christian faith (specially, a heathen); (passively) untrustworthy (person), or incredible (thing).
USAGE: that believeth not, faithless, incredible thing, infidel, unbeliever(-ing).

DEFINITION: simplicity, sincerity, purity, graciousness.
ORIGIN: From haplous; singleness, i.e. (subjectively) sincerity (without dissimulation or self-seeking), or (objectively) generosity (copious bestowal).

DEFINITION: single, simple, sound, perfect.
ORIGIN: Probably from a (as a particle of union) and the base of pleko; properly, folded together, i.e. Single (figuratively, clear).

DEFINITION: simply, sincerely, graciously, bountifully.
ORIGIN: Adverb from haplous (in the objective sense of haplotes); bountifully.

DEFINITION: from, away from.
ORIGIN: A primary particle; "off," i.e. Away (from something near), in various senses (of place, time, or relation; literal or figurative).
USAGE: (X here-)after, ago, at, because of, before, by (the space of), for(-th), from, in, (out) of, off, (up-)on(-ce), since, with. In composition (as a prefix) it usually denotes separation, departure, cessation, completion, reversal, etc.

DEFINITION: to go or come out of, disembark, turn out, result, become, happen.
ORIGIN: From apo and the base of basis; literally, to disembark; figuratively, to eventuate.

DEFINITION: to throw away from, throw overboard, cast aside.
ORIGIN: From apo and ballo; to throw off; figuratively, to lose.

DEFINITION: to look away from all else at one object, look steadfastly.
ORIGIN: From apo and blepo; to look away from everything else, i.e. (figuratively) intently regard.

DEFINITION: worthy to be cast away, worthless, regarded as vile.
ORIGIN: From apoballo; cast off, i.e. (figuratively) such as to be rejected.

DEFINITION: a casting away, rejection, a loss.
ORIGIN: From apoballo; rejection; figuratively, loss.

DEFINITION: to be away, be removed from, depart life, die.
ORIGIN: Past participle of a compound of apo and ginomai; absent, i.e. Deceased (figuratively, renounced).

DEFINITION: an enrollment, census-taking, record.
ORIGIN: From apographo; an enrollment; by implication, an assessment.

DEFINITION: to enroll, inscribe in a register; mid: to give name for registration (or census-taking).
ORIGIN: From apo and grapho; to write off (a copy or list), i.e. Enrol.

DEFINITION: to show by proof, demonstrate, set forth, proclaim to an officer.
ORIGIN: From apo and deiknuo; to show off, i.e. Exhibit; figuratively, to demonstrate, i.e. Accredit.

DEFINITION: demonstration, proof; a showing off.
ORIGIN: From apodeiknumi; manifestation.

DEFINITION: to take off (deduct) a tenth part (of property) (and give it away), pay tithe.
ORIGIN: From apo and dekatoo; to tithe (as debtor or creditor).

DEFINITION: worthy to be received (welcomed), acceptable, welcome, pleasant.
ORIGIN: From apodechomai; accepted, i.e. Agreeable.

DEFINITION: to receive, welcome, entertain (with hospitality), embrace.
ORIGIN: From apo and dechomai; to take fully, i.e. Welcome (persons), approve (things).

DEFINITION: to be away from home, go into another country, be away, be abroad.
ORIGIN: From apodemos; to go abroad, i.e. Visit a foreign land.
USAGE: go (travel) into a far country, journey.

DEFINITION: away from home, sojourning in another country.
ORIGIN: From apo and demos; absent from one's own people, i.e. A foreign traveller.

DEFINITION: (a) to give back, return, restore, (b) to give, render, as due, (c) mid: to sell.
ORIGIN: From apo and didomi; to give away, i.e. Up, over, back, etc. (in various applications).
USAGE: deliver (again), give (again), (re-)pay(-ment be made), perform, recompense, render, requite, restore, reward, sell, yield.

DEFINITION: to make a logical distinction, make an invidious distinction.
ORIGIN: From apo and a compound of Alexandros and horizo; to disjoin (by a boundary, figuratively, a party).

DEFINITION: to reject after testing (examination), disqualify.
ORIGIN: From apo and dokimazo; to disapprove, i.e. (by implication) to repudiate.

DEFINITION: (properly: reception, welcome, of guests), acceptance, appreciation, approbation.
ORIGIN: From apodechomai; acceptance.

DEFINITION: a putting off, a laying down.
ORIGIN: From apotithemi; a laying aside (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a repository, granary, barn, storehouse.
ORIGIN: From apotithemi; a repository, i.e. Granary.

DEFINITION: to treasure up, store away.
ORIGIN: From apo and thesaurizo; to treasure away.

DEFINITION: (lit: to rub), jostle, press hard, crowd.
ORIGIN: From apo and thlibo; to crowd (from every side).

DEFINITION: to be dying, be about to die, wither, decay.
ORIGIN: From apo and thnesko; to die off (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: be dead, death, die, lie a-dying, be slain (X with).

DEFINITION: to set up again, restore to its original position or condition; hence: to restore, give back.
ORIGIN: From apo and kathistemi; to reconstitute (in health, home or organization).

DEFINITION: to uncover, bring to light, reveal.
ORIGIN: From apo and kalupto; to take off the cover, i.e. Disclose.

DEFINITION: an unveiling, uncovering, revealing, revelation.
ORIGIN: From apokalupto; disclosure.
USAGE: appearing, coming, lighten, manifestation, be revealed, revelation.

DEFINITION: strained expectancy.
ORIGIN: From a comparative of apo and a compound of kara (the head) and dokeo (in the sense of watching); intense anticipation.

DEFINITION: to reconcile, change from one state of feeling to another.
ORIGIN: From apo and katallasso; to reconcile fully.

DEFINITION: restitution, reestablishment, restoration.
ORIGIN: From apokathistemi; reconstitution.

DEFINITION: to have been put away, be stored, be reserved for.
ORIGIN: From apo and keimai; to be reserved; figuratively, to await.

DEFINITION: to behead.
ORIGIN: From apo and kephale; to decapitate.

DEFINITION: to shut fast, close, shut up.
ORIGIN: From apo and kleio; to close fully.

DEFINITION: to smite, cut off, cut loose; mid: to emasculate, castrate, mutilate myself.
ORIGIN: From apo and kopto; to amputate; reflexively (by irony) to mutilate (the privy parts).

DEFINITION: a judicial sentence, an answer.
ORIGIN: From apokrinomai (in its original sense of judging); a judicial decision.

DEFINITION: to answer, reply, take up the conversation.
ORIGIN: From apo and krino; to conclude for oneself, i.e. (by implication) to respond; by Hebraism (compare anah) to begin to speak (where an address is expected).

DEFINITION: an answer, reply.
ORIGIN: From apokrinomai; a response.

DEFINITION: to hide away, conceal, keep secret.
ORIGIN: From apo and krupto; to conceal away (i.e. Fully); figuratively, to keep secret.

DEFINITION: hidden away, secret, stored up.
ORIGIN: From apokrupto; secret; by implication, treasured.

DEFINITION: to put to death, kill; fig: to abolish.
ORIGIN: From apo and kteino (to slay); to kill outright; figuratively, to destroy.

DEFINITION: to bring forth, give birth to (a child), a medical or physical word, marking the close of pregnancy.
ORIGIN: From apo and the base of kuma; to breed forth, i.e. (by transference) to generate (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to roll away.
ORIGIN: From apo and kulioo; to roll away.

DEFINITION: (a) to get back, receive back, (b) to get (receive) as due (deserved), (c) mid: to draw aside, separate.
ORIGIN: From apo and lambano; to receive (specially, in full, or as a host); also to take aside.

DEFINITION: the faculty or experience of enjoyment.
ORIGIN: From a comparative of apo and lauo (to enjoy); full enjoyment.

DEFINITION: to leave, leave behind; pass: to be reserved, remain; to desert, abandon.
ORIGIN: From apo and leipo; to leave behind (passively, remain); by implication, to forsake.

DEFINITION: to lick off, lick clean, lick up.
ORIGIN: From apo and leicho (to "lick"); to lick clean.

DEFINITION: (a) to kill, destroy, (b) to lose, mid: to be perishing (the resultant death being viewed as certain).
ORIGIN: From apo and the base of olethros; to destroy fully (reflexively, to perish, or lose), literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: Apollyon, The Destroying One, a Greek translation of the Hebrew: Abaddon.
ORIGIN: Active participle of apollumi; a destroyer (i.e. Satan).

DEFINITION: Apollonia, a city in Macedonia.
ORIGIN: From the pagan deity Apollon (i.e. The sun; from apollumi); Apollonia, a place in Macedonia.

DEFINITION: Apollos, an Alexandrian Jewish Christian.
ORIGIN: Probably from the same as Apollonia; Apollos, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: to give a defense, defend myself (especially in a law court): it can take an object of what is said in defense.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from a compound of apo and logos; to give an account (legal plea) of oneself, i.e. Exculpate (self).
USAGE: answer (for self), make defence, excuse (self), speak for self.

DEFINITION: a verbal defense (particularly in a law court).
ORIGIN: From the same as apologeomai; a plea ("apology").
USAGE: answer (for self), clearing of self, defence.

DEFINITION: to wash off, mid: to wash away (sins, in baptism).
ORIGIN: From apo and louo; to wash fully, i.e. (figuratively) have remitted (reflexively).

DEFINITION: release effected by payment of ransom; redemption, deliverance.
ORIGIN: From a compound of apo and lutron; (the act) ransom in full, i.e. (figuratively) riddance, or (specially) Christian salvation.

DEFINITION: to release, let go, send away, divorce, be rid; mid: to depart.
ORIGIN: From apo and luo; to free fully, i.e. (literally) relieve, release, dismiss (reflexively, depart), or (figuratively) let die, pardon or (specially) divorce.
USAGE: (let) depart, dismiss, divorce, forgive, let go, loose, put (send) away, release, set at liberty.

DEFINITION: to wipe off, wipe clean; mid: to wipe myself off.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from apo and masso (to squeeze, knead, smear); to scrape away.

DEFINITION: to assign, apportion, render (as due).
ORIGIN: From apo and the base of nomos; to apportion, i.e. Bestow.

DEFINITION: to wash dirt off.
ORIGIN: From apo and nipto; to wash off (reflexively, one's own hands symbolically).

DEFINITION: to fall away (from), fall off.
ORIGIN: From apo and pipto; to fall off.

DEFINITION: to cause to go astray; pass: to be led astray.
ORIGIN: From apo and planao; to lead astray (figuratively); passively, to stray (from truth).

DEFINITION: to sail away.
ORIGIN: From apo and pleo; to set sail.

DEFINITION: to wash, rinse.
ORIGIN: From apo and pluno; to rinse off.

DEFINITION: (a) to suffocate, choke, drown, (b) to stop the growth of.
ORIGIN: From apo and pnigo; to stifle (by drowning or overgrowth).

DEFINITION: to be at a loss, be perplexed; mid: to be in doubt.
ORIGIN: From a compound of a (as a negative particle) and the base of poreuomai; to have no way out, i.e. Be at a loss (mentally).

DEFINITION: perplexity, anxiety, doubt.
ORIGIN: From the same as aporeo; a (state of) quandary.

DEFINITION: to throw away from, throw overboard.
ORIGIN: From apo and rhipto; to hurl off, i.e. Precipitate (oneself).

DEFINITION: to separate from some one, be bereaved.
ORIGIN: From apo and a derivative of orphanos; to bereave wholly, i.e. (figuratively) separate (from intercourse).

DEFINITION: to prepare for a journey, depart.
ORIGIN: From apo and a derivative of skeuos; to pack up (one's) baggage.

DEFINITION: either a shadow cast by an object, or a faint image or copy of an object.
ORIGIN: From a compound of apo and a derivative of skia; a shading off, i.e. Obscuration.

DEFINITION: lit: to wrench away from, drag away, but perhaps sometimes in the well-attested weakened sense: to be parted or withdrawn.
ORIGIN: From apo and spao; to drag forth, i.e. (literally) unsheathe (a sword), or relatively (with a degree of force implied) retire (personally or factiously).

DEFINITION: defection, apostasy, revolt.
ORIGIN: Feminine of the same as apostasion; defection from truth (properly, the state) ("apostasy").

DEFINITION: repudiation, divorce; met: bill of divorce.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a (presumed) adjective from a derivative of aphistemi; properly, something separative, i.e. (specially) divorce.

DEFINITION: to unroof, take the roof off.
ORIGIN: From apo and a derivative of stege; to unroof.

DEFINITION: to send forth, send (as a messenger, commission, etc.), send away, dismiss.
ORIGIN: From apo and stello; set apart, i.e. (by implication) to send out (properly, on a mission) literally or figuratively.
USAGE: put in, send (away, forth, out), set (at liberty).

DEFINITION: to defraud, deprive of, despoil; mid: to endure deprivation; pass: to be bereft of.
ORIGIN: From apo and stereo (to deprive); to despoil.
USAGE: defraud, destitute, kept back by fraud.

DEFINITION: commission, duty of apostle, apostleship.
ORIGIN: From apostello; commission, i.e. (specially) apostolate.

DEFINITION: a messenger, envoy, delegate, one commissioned by another to represent him in some way, especially a man sent out by Jesus Christ Himself to preach the Gospel; an apostle.
ORIGIN: From apostello; a delegate; specially, an ambassador of the Gospel; officially a commissioner of Christ ("apostle") (with miraculous powers).
USAGE: apostle, messenger, he that is sent.

DEFINITION: to draw out by questioning.
ORIGIN: From apo and a (presumed) derivative of stoma; to speak off-hand (properly, dictate), i.e. To catechize (in an invidious manner).

DEFINITION: to turn away, pervert, remove; to restore, replace; mid: to desert, reject.
ORIGIN: From apo and strepho; to turn away or back (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to detest, abhor.
ORIGIN: From apo and the base of stugnetos; to detest utterly.

DEFINITION: away from the synagogue, expelled from the synagogue, excommunicated.
ORIGIN: From apo and sunagoge; excommunicated.

DEFINITION: to withdraw from, take leave of, renounce, send away.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from apo and tasso; literally, to say adieu (by departing or dismissing); figuratively, to renounce.
USAGE: bid farewell, forsake, take leave, send away.

DEFINITION: to complete, accomplish, form fully, perfect, bring to maturity.
ORIGIN: From apo and teleo; to complete entirely, i.e. Consummate.

DEFINITION: to lay off or aside, renounce, stow away, put.
ORIGIN: From apo and tithemi; to put away (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: cast off, lay apart (aside, down), put away (off).

DEFINITION: to shake off.
ORIGIN: From apo and tinasso (to jostle); to brush off.

DEFINITION: to repay, pay what is due (by way of punishment or fine), make good.
ORIGIN: From apo and tino; to pay in full.

DEFINITION: to assume boldness.
ORIGIN: From apo and tolmao; to venture plainly.

DEFINITION: (lit: sheerness, of a rock), abruptness, harshness, severity, rigor.
ORIGIN: From the base of apotomos; (figuratively) decisiveness, i.e. Rigor.

DEFINITION: sharply, severely.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a derivative of a comparative of apo and temno (to cut); abruptly, i.e. Peremptorily.

DEFINITION: to turn away from, shun.
ORIGIN: From apo and the base of trope; to deflect, i.e. (reflexively) avoid.

DEFINITION: absence, deficiency, waste.
ORIGIN: From the participle of apeimi; a being away.

DEFINITION: to carry, bear away (sometimes with violence).
ORIGIN: From apo and phero; to bear off (literally or relatively).

DEFINITION: to flee from, escape.
ORIGIN: From apo and pheugo; (figuratively) to escape.

DEFINITION: to speak out, declare.
ORIGIN: From apo and phtheggomai; to enunciate plainly, i.e. Declare.

DEFINITION: to discharge a cargo.
ORIGIN: From apo and the middle voice of phortizo; to unload.

DEFINITION: using up, abuse, misuse.
ORIGIN: From a compound of apo and chraomai; the act of using up, i.e. Consumption.

DEFINITION: to go away, depart, withdraw.
ORIGIN: From apo and choreo; to go away.

DEFINITION: to separate from; mid: to part; pass: to be swept aside.
ORIGIN: From apo and chorizo; to rend apart; reflexively, to separate.

DEFINITION: to faint, breathe out life, die, be dismayed.
ORIGIN: From apo and psucho; to breathe out, i.e. Faint.

DEFINITION: the township Appi Forum on the Appian Way, 43 Roman miles from Rome, was named.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; (in the genitive, i.e. Possessive case) of Appius, the name of a Roman.

DEFINITION: unapproachable.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of a comparative of pros and eimi (to go); inaccessible.

DEFINITION: (free from hurt or harm, hence) not offending, not causing offence, blameless.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of proskopto; actively, inoffensive, i.e. Not leading into sin; passively, faultless, i.e. Not led into sin.

DEFINITION: (literary and Jewish), without any preference (undue favor, partiality) for a person.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of a presumed compound of prosopon and lambano (compare prosopoleptes); in a way not accepting the person, i.e. Impartially.

DEFINITION: without stumbling or falling, sure-footed.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of ptaio; not stumbling, i.e. (figuratively) without sin.

DEFINITION: prop: to fasten to; to lay hold of, touch, know carnally.
ORIGIN: Reflexive of hapto; properly, to attach oneself to, i.e. To touch (in many implied relations).

DEFINITION: to fasten to, lay hold of.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; properly, to fasten to, i.e. (specially) to set on fire.

DEFINITION: Apphia, a Christian lady of Colossae, either wife or sister of Philemon.
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin; Apphia, a woman of Collosae.

DEFINITION: to push (thrust) away, repulse, reject, refuse.
ORIGIN: Or apothomai ap-o'-thom-ahee from apo and the middle voice of otheo or otho (to shove); to push off, figuratively, to reject.
USAGE: cast away, put away (from), thrust away (from).

DEFINITION: destruction, ruin, loss, perishing; eternal ruin.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of apollumi; ruin or loss (physical, spiritual or eternal).
USAGE: damnable(-nation), destruction, die, perdition, X perish, pernicious ways, waste.

DEFINITION: a prayer; more commonly: a prayer for evil, a curse, imprecation.
ORIGIN: Probably from airo; properly, prayer (as lifted to Heaven), i.e. (by implication) imprecation.

DEFINITION: therefore (an illative particle).
ORIGIN: Probably from airo (through the idea of drawing a conclusion); a particle denoting an inference more or less decisive (as follows).
USAGE: haply, (what) manner (of man), no doubt, perhaps, so be, then, therefore, truly, wherefore. Often used in connection with other particles, especially ge or oun (after) or ei (before). Compare also ara.

DEFINITION: an untranslatable interrogative particle implying anxiety or impatience.
ORIGIN: A form of ara, denoting an interrogation to which a negative answer is presumed.

DEFINITION: Arabia, a peninsula of Asia near Africa.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ( Arab); Arabia, a region of Asia.

DEFINITION: Ram, son of Hezron and father of Amminadab.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Ram); Aram (i.e. Ram), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: unsewn, without seam.
ORIGIN: From Arabia; an Arab or native of Arabia.

DEFINITION: to linger, delay, be idle.
ORIGIN: From argos; to be idle, i.e. (figuratively) to delay.

DEFINITION: idle, lazy, thoughtless, unprofitable, injurious.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and ergon; inactive, i.e. Unemployed; (by implication) lazy, useless.

DEFINITION: made of silver.
ORIGIN: From arguros; made of silver.

DEFINITION: silver, a piece of silver, a shekel, money in general.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of arguros; silvery, i.e. (by implication) cash; specially, a silverling (i.e. Drachma or shekel).

DEFINITION: (lit: silver-cutter), a silversmith.
ORIGIN: From arguros and kopto; a beater (i.e. Worker) of silver.

DEFINITION: silver as a metal.
ORIGIN: From argos (shining); silver (the metal, in the articles or coin).

DEFINITION: Areopagus, or Mar's Hill, an open space on a hill in Athens where the supreme court was held.
ORIGIN: From Ares (the name of the Greek deity of war) and a derivative of pegnumi; rock of Ares, a place in Athens.

DEFINITION: member of the Council of the Areopagus, an Areopagite.
ORIGIN: From Areios Pagos; an Areopagite or member of the court held on Mars' Hill.

DEFINITION: a desire to please, pleasing.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of aresko; complaisance.

DEFINITION: to please, with the idea of willing service rendered to others; hence almost: to serve.
ORIGIN: Probably from airo (through the idea of exciting emotion); to be agreeable (or by implication, to seek to be so).

DEFINITION: pleasing, satisfactory, acceptable.
ORIGIN: From aresko; agreeable; by implication, fit.

DEFINITION: Aretas IV, King of the Nabataeans.
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin; Aretas, an Arabian.

DEFINITION: goodness, a gracious act, virtue, uprightness.
ORIGIN: From the same as arrhen; properly, manliness (valor), i.e. Excellence (intrinsic or attributed).

DEFINITION: a lamb, sheep.
ORIGIN: Perhaps the same as arrhen; a lamb (as a male).

DEFINITION: to number, count.
ORIGIN: From arithmos; to enumerate or count.

DEFINITION: a number, total.
ORIGIN: From airo; a number (as reckoned up).

DEFINITION: Arimathea, probably a city near Jer.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Ramah); Arimathaea (or Ramah), a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: Aristarchus, a Christian, belonging to Thessalonica in Macedonia.
ORIGIN: From the same as ariston and archo; best ruling; Aristarchus, a Macedonian.

DEFINITION: to breakfast, to take a meal.
ORIGIN: From ariston; to take the principle meal.

DEFINITION: better, left, on the left.
ORIGIN: Apparently a comparative of the same as ariston; the left hand (as second-best).

DEFINITION: "best-counseling", Aristobulus, a Christian at Rome.
ORIGIN: From the same as ariston and boule; best counselling; Aristoboulus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: breakfast or a mid-day meal.
ORIGIN: Apparently neuter of a superlative from the same as arrhen; the best meal (or breakfast; perhaps from eri ("early")), i.e. Luncheon.

DEFINITION: sufficient, enough.
ORIGIN: From arkeo; satisfactory.

DEFINITION: to keep off, assist; to suffice; pass: to be satisfied.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb (but probably akin to airo through the idea of raising a barrier); properly, to ward off, i.e. (by implication) to avail (figuratively, be satisfactory).
USAGE: be content, be enough, suffice, be sufficient.

DEFINITION: a bear.
ORIGIN: Probably from arkeo; a bear (as obstructing by ferocity).

DEFINITION: a chariot, vehicle.
ORIGIN: Probably from airo (perhaps with a (as a particle of union) prefixed); a chariot (as raised or fitted together (compare harmos)).

DEFINITION: Har-Magedon.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (har and Mgiddown); Armageddon (or Har-Meggiddon), a symbolic name.

DEFINITION: to fit, join; mid: (the middle indicating deep personal interest) to espouse, betroth; mid: to take a wife, give in marriage.
ORIGIN: From harmos; to joint, i.e. (figuratively) to woo (reflexively, to betroth).

DEFINITION: a joint of the body.
ORIGIN: From the same as harma; an articulation (of the body).

DEFINITION: (a) to deny (a statement), (b) to repudiate (a person, or belief).
ORIGIN: Perhaps from a (as a negative particle) and the middle voice of rheo; to contradict, i.e. Disavow, reject, abnegate.

DEFINITION: (originally: a little lamb, but diminutive force was lost), a lamb.
ORIGIN: Diminutive from aren; a lambkin.

DEFINITION: to plow.
ORIGIN: From arotron; to plow.

DEFINITION: a plow.
ORIGIN: From aroo (to till); a plow.

DEFINITION: the act of plundering; plunder, spoil, robbery.
ORIGIN: From harpazo; pillage (properly abstract).

DEFINITION: spoil, an object of eager desire, a prize.
ORIGIN: From harpazo; plunder (properly concrete).

DEFINITION: to seize, snatch, obtain by robbery.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of haireomai; to seize (in various applications).
USAGE: catch (away, up), pluck, pull, take (by force).

DEFINITION: rapacious, ravenous; a robber, an extortioner.
ORIGIN: From harpazo; rapacious.

DEFINITION: an earnest, earnest-money, a large part of the payment, given in advance as a security that the whole will be paid afterwards.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (arabown); a pledge, i.e. Part of the purchase-money or property given in advance as security for the rest.

DEFINITION: without seam, of a single piece.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of the same as rhaphis; unsewed, i.e. Of a single piece.

DEFINITION: male, man.
ORIGIN: Arsen (ar'-sane) probably from airo; male (as stronger for lifting).

DEFINITION: not to be uttered (because too sacred), secret, unspeakable, unspoken.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and the same as rhetos; unsaid, i.e. (by implication) inexpressible.

DEFINITION: infirm, sick, ill, feeble, sickly.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of rhonnumi; infirm.

DEFINITION: a male engaging in same-gender sexual activity; a sodomite, pederast.
ORIGIN: From arrhen and koite; a sodomite.
USAGE: abuser of (that defile) self with mankind.

DEFINITION: "gift of Artemis", Artemas, a friend of the apostle Paul.
ORIGIN: Contracted from a compound of Artemis and doron; gift of Artemis; Artemas (or Artemidorus), a Christian.

DEFINITION: Artemis, a goddess, worshipped principally at Ephesus, typifying fertility (she had no relation with the other Artemis, the maiden huntress, to whom corresponded the Latin Diana).
ORIGIN: Probably from the same as artemon; prompt; Artemis, the name of a Grecian goddess borrowed by the Asiatics for one of their deities.

DEFINITION: something hung up or fastened, a foresail.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of arti; properly, something ready (or else more remotely from airo (compare artos); something hung up), i.e. (specially) the topsail (rather foresail or jib) of a vessel.

DEFINITION: now, just now, at this moment.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a derivative of airo (compare artos) through the idea of suspension; just now.
USAGE: this day (hour), hence(-forth), here(-after), hither(-to), (even) now, (this) present.

DEFINITION: newly begotten, newly born.
ORIGIN: From arti and gennetos; just born, i.e. (figuratively) a young convert.

DEFINITION: perfect, complete, fitted, ready.
ORIGIN: From arti; fresh, i.e. (by implication) complete.

DEFINITION: bread, a loaf, food.
ORIGIN: From airo; bread (as raised) or a loaf.

DEFINITION: prop: to arrange, make ready; to season, flavor.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of airo; to prepare, i.e. Spice (with stimulating condiments).

DEFINITION: Arphaxad, a son of Shem and an ancestor of Christ.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Arpakshad); Arphaxad, a post-diluvian patriarch.

DEFINITION: a ruler of angels, a superior angel, an archangel.
ORIGIN: From archo and aggelos; a chief angel.

DEFINITION: original, primitive, ancient.
ORIGIN: From arche; original or primeval.

DEFINITION: Archelaus, Herod Archelaus, son and successor of Herod to, reigned over Judea from 4 B.C. to A.D. 6 and died before A.D. 18.
ORIGIN: From archo and Laodikeus; people-ruling; Archelaus, a Jewish king.

DEFINITION: (a) rule (kingly or magisterial), (b) plur: in a quasi-personal sense, almost: rulers, magistrates, (c) beginning.
ORIGIN: From archomai; (properly abstract) a commencement, or (concretely) chief (in various applications of order, time, place, or rank).
USAGE: beginning, corner, (at the, the) first (estate), magistrate, power, principality, principle, rule.

DEFINITION: originator, author, founder, prince, leader.
ORIGIN: From arche and ago; a chief leader.

DEFINITION: high priestly, to which the chief priest belongs.
ORIGIN: From arche and a derivative of hieros; high-priestly.

DEFINITION: high priest, chief priest.
ORIGIN: From arche and hiereus; the high-priest (literally, of the Jews, typically, Christ); by extension a chief priest.
USAGE: chief (high) priest, chief of the priests.

DEFINITION: the chief shepherd.
ORIGIN: From arche and poimen; a head shepherd.

DEFINITION: "horse-ruler", Archippus, a Christian at Colossae.
ORIGIN: From arche and hippos; horse-ruler; Archippus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: a leader of the synagogue, a leader connected with the synagogue: sometimes there was only one, and the name was in some cases merely honorary.
ORIGIN: From arche and sunagoge; director of the synagogue services.

DEFINITION: master-builder, architect.
ORIGIN: From arche and tekton; a chief constructor, i.e. "architect".

DEFINITION: head of a custom-house, chief tax-gatherer or publican.
ORIGIN: From arche and telones; a principle tax-gatherer.

DEFINITION: master of ceremonies at a dinner, master of the feast.
ORIGIN: From arche and a compound of treis and klino (a dinner-bed, because composed of three couches); director of the entertainment.

DEFINITION: commence, rule.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of archo (through the implication, of precedence); to commence (in order of time).

DEFINITION: to rule, to begin.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to be first (in political rank or power).

DEFINITION: a ruler, governor, leader, leading man; with the Jews, an official member (a member of the executive) of the assembly of elders.
ORIGIN: Present participle of archo; a first (in rank or power).

DEFINITION: spice, perfume.
ORIGIN: From airo (in the sense of sending off scent); an aromatic.

DEFINITION: Asa, son of Abijah and father of Jehoshaphat, king of Judah about 900 B.C. for 41 years.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Aca'); Asa, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: unshaken, immovable.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of saleuo; unshaken, i.e. (by implication) immovable (figuratively).

DEFINITION: inextinguishable, unquenchable.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of sbennumi; not extinguished, i.e. (by implication) perpetual.

DEFINITION: impiety, irreverence, ungodliness, wickedness.
ORIGIN: From asebes; impiety, i.e. (by implication) wickedness.

DEFINITION: to be impious, to be ungodly.
ORIGIN: From asebes; to be (by implied act) impious or wicked.
USAGE: commit (live, that after should live) ungodly.

DEFINITION: impious, ungodly, wicked.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of sebomai; irreverent, i.e. (by extension) impious or wicked.

DEFINITION: (outrageous conduct, conduct shocking to public decency, a wanton violence), wantonness, lewdness.
ORIGIN: From a compound of a (as a negative particle) and a presumed selges (of uncertain derivation, but apparently meaning continent); licentiousness (sometimes including other vices).

DEFINITION: (lit: unmarked, unstamped), undistinguished, obscure, unknown.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and the base of semaino; unmarked, i.e. (figuratively) ignoble.

DEFINITION: Asher, one of the sons of Jacob, and founder of one of the Twelve Tribes.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Asher); Aser (i.e. Asher), an Israelite tribe.

DEFINITION: want of strength, weakness, illness, suffering, calamity, frailty.
ORIGIN: From asthenes; feebleness (of mind or body); by implication, malady; morally, frailty.

DEFINITION: to be weak (physically: then morally), to be sick.
ORIGIN: From asthenes; to be feeble (in any sense).
USAGE: be diseased, impotent folk (man), (be) sick, (be, be made) weak.

DEFINITION: weakness, infirmity, doubt, hesitation.
ORIGIN: From astheneo; a scruple of conscience.

DEFINITION: (lit: not strong), (a) weak (physically, or morally), (b) infirm, sick.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and the base of sthenoo; strengthless (in various applications, literal, figurative and moral).
USAGE: more feeble, impotent, sick, without strength, weak(-er, -ness, thing).

DEFINITION: the Roman province of Asia, roughly the western third of Asia Minor.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; Asia, i.e. Asia Minor, or (usually) only its western shore.

DEFINITION: belonging to the Roman province Asia.
ORIGIN: From Asia; an Asian (i.e. Asiatic) or an inhabitant of Asia.

DEFINITION: an Asiarch, an official connected with the worship of Rome and the Emperor in the Roman province Asia.
ORIGIN: From Asia and arche; an Asiarch or president of the public festivities in a city of Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: either: lack or wheat, lack of food (the literal meaning), or: abstinence from food, a fast, loss of appetite, sea-sickness (the extended meaning).
ORIGIN: From asitos; fasting (the state).

DEFINITION: without eating, fasting.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and sitos; without (taking) food.

DEFINITION: to train, practice, exercise.
ORIGIN: Probably from the same as skeuos; to elaborate, i.e. (figuratively) train (by implication, strive).

DEFINITION: a wine-skin, leather bottle.
ORIGIN: From the same as askeo; a leathern (or skin) bag used as a bottle.

DEFINITION: joyfully, with delight, gladly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a derivative of the base of hedone; with pleasure.

DEFINITION: unskilled, unwise, foolish.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and sophos; unwise.

DEFINITION: to greet, salute, pay respects to, welcome.
ORIGIN: From a (as a particle of union) and a presumed form of spao; to enfold in the arms, i.e. (by implication) to salute, (figuratively) to welcome.

DEFINITION: a greeting, salutation.
ORIGIN: From aspazomai; a greeting (in person or by letter).

DEFINITION: unstained, undefiled, spotless, pure.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and spiloo; unblemished (physically or morally).

DEFINITION: an asp (hooded-snake, cobra).
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a buckler (or round shield); used of a serpent (as coiling itself), probably the "asp".

DEFINITION: without libation, without truce, admitting of no truce.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of spendo; literally, without libation (which usually accompanied a treaty), i.e. (by implication) truceless.

DEFINITION: a small coin equal to the tenth part of a drachma.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; an assarius or as, a Roman coin.

DEFINITION: nearer, close by.
ORIGIN: Neuter comparative of the base of eggus; more nearly, i.e. Very near.

DEFINITION: Assos, a port of Mysia, in the Roman province Asia.
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin; Assus, a city of Asia minor.

DEFINITION: to be unsettled, have no fixed abode, lead a vagabond life.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of histemi; to be non-stationary, i.e. (figuratively) homeless.

DEFINITION: (lit: belonging to the city; then: witty, clever), elegant, pretty, fair, fine, beautiful.
ORIGIN: From astu (a city); urbane, i.e. (by implication) handsome.

DEFINITION: a star.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of stronnumi; a star (as strown over the sky), literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: (lit: unpropped), unsteady, unstable, unsettled.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of sterizo; unfixed, i.e. (figuratively) vacillating.

DEFINITION: unloving, devoid of affection.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of stergo (to cherish affectionately); hard-hearted towards kindred.

DEFINITION: to miss the mark, miss aim, make a false aim, fail.
ORIGIN: From a compound of a (as a negative particle) and stoichos (an aim); to miss the mark, i.e. (figuratively) deviate from truth.

DEFINITION: a flash of lightning, brightness, luster.
ORIGIN: From astrapto; lightning; by analogy, glare.

DEFINITION: to flash (with, then like, lightning), be lustrous.
ORIGIN: Probably from aster; to flash as lightning.

DEFINITION: a star.
ORIGIN: Neuter from aster; properly, a constellation; put for a single star (natural or artificial).

DEFINITION: "incomparable", Asyncritus, a Christian at Rome.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of sugkrino; incomparable; Asyncritus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: dissonant, discordant; met: at variance.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and sumphonos; inharmonious (figuratively).

DEFINITION: unintelligent, without wisdom, unwise, undiscerning (implying probably moral defect).
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and sunetos; unintelligent; by implication, wicked.

DEFINITION: not covenanting, untrue to an agreement, treacherous.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of suntithemai; properly, not agreed, i.e. Treacherous to compacts.

DEFINITION: safety, security, reliability, firmness.
ORIGIN: From asphales; security (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: (lit: unfailing), safe, reliable, trustworthy, certain, sure.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and sphallo (to "fail"); secure (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to make safe (secure, fast).
ORIGIN: From asphales; to render secure.

DEFINITION: safely, securely, assuredly, certainly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from asphales; securely (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to act improperly, be unseemly, behave unbecomingly (or even dishonorably); perhaps: to consider (something) unseemly.
ORIGIN: From askemon; to be (i.e. Act) unbecoming.

DEFINITION: unseemly behavior, unseemliness, indecency, shame, nakedness, an indecent (lewd) act.
ORIGIN: From askemon; an indecency; by implication, the pudenda.

DEFINITION: shapeless, unseemly.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of echo (in the sense of its congener schema); properly, shapeless, i.e. (figuratively) inelegant.

DEFINITION: wantonness, profligacy, wastefulness.
ORIGIN: From a compound of a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of sozo; properly, unsavedness, i.e. (by implication) profligacy.

DEFINITION: prodigally, with prodigal living, wastefully.
ORIGIN: Adverb from the same as asotia; dissolutely.

DEFINITION: (lit: to march out of order; then: to riot, rebel), behave disorderly, neglect duty, be careless (or idle) in habits.
ORIGIN: From ataktos; to be (i.e. Act) irregular.

DEFINITION: (lit: out of order), disorderly, slack (in performance of duty).
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of tasso; unarranged, i.e. (by implication) insubordinate (religiously).

DEFINITION: in a disorderly manner, irregularly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from ataktos, irregularly (morally).

DEFINITION: childless.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and teknon; childless.

DEFINITION: to direct gaze, look steadily.
ORIGIN: From a compound of a (as a particle of union) and teino (to stretch); to gaze intently.
USAGE: behold earnestly (stedfastly), fasten (eyes), look (earnestly, stedfastly, up stedfastly), set eyes.

DEFINITION: apart from, without.
ORIGIN: A particle probably akin to aneu; aloof, i.e. Apart from (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to disgrace, treat disgracefully, dishonor, insult; to despise.
ORIGIN: From atimos; to render infamous, i.e. (by implication) contemn or maltreat.
USAGE: despise, dishonour, suffer shame, entreat shamefully.

DEFINITION: disgrace, dishonor; a dishonorable use.
ORIGIN: From atimos; infamy, i.e. (subjectively) comparative indignity, (objectively) disgrace.

DEFINITION: without honor, dishonored.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and time; (negatively) unhonoured or (positively) dishonoured.
USAGE: despised, without honour, less honourable (comparative degree).

DEFINITION: to dishonor, treat shamefully.
ORIGIN: From atimos; used like atimazo, to maltreat.

DEFINITION: breath, steam, vapor.
ORIGIN: From the same as aer; mist.

DEFINITION: (lit: that cannot be cut), an indivisible part of time, a moment.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and the base of tomoteros; uncut, i.e. (by implication) indivisible (an "atom" of time).

DEFINITION: (lit: out of place, unusual, unbecoming), improper, unrighteous, perverse.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and topos; out of place, i.e. (figuratively) improper, injurious, wicked.

DEFINITION: Attalia, the port of Perga in Pamphylia.
ORIGIN: From Attalos (a king of Pergamus); Attaleia, a place in Pamphylia.

DEFINITION: to flash, gleam, shine forth, appear white, bright; but perhaps: to see, see clearly, discern.
ORIGIN: From auge; to beam forth (figuratively).

DEFINITION: brightness, daylight, dawn.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a ray of light, i.e. (by implication) radiance, dawn.

DEFINITION: Augustus, a title conferred on the first Roman Emperor, C. Iulius Octauianus, denoting sanctity (almost divinity).
ORIGIN: From Latin ("august"); Augustus, a title of the Roman emperor.

DEFINITION: self-satisfied, arrogant, stubborn.
ORIGIN: From autos and the base of hedone; self-pleasing, i.e. Arrogant.

DEFINITION: self-chosen, of one's own accord.
ORIGIN: From autos and the same as hairetizo; self-chosen, i.e. (by implication) voluntary.
USAGE: of own accord, willing of self.

DEFINITION: to domineer, govern, have mastery over.
ORIGIN: From a compound of autos and an obsolete hentes (a worker); to act of oneself, i.e. (figuratively) dominate.

DEFINITION: to play the flute, pipe.
ORIGIN: From aulos; to play the flute.

DEFINITION: court-yard, fore-court, sheep-fold; but it may be understood as: palace, house.
ORIGIN: From the same as aer; a yard (as open to the wind); by implication, a mansion.

DEFINITION: a flute player.
ORIGIN: From auleo; a flute-player.

DEFINITION: to lodge in the open, lodge, pass the night.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from aule; to pass the night (properly, in the open air).

DEFINITION: a pipe, flute.
ORIGIN: From the same as aer; a flute (as blown).

DEFINITION: (a) to cause to increase, become greater (b) to increase, grow.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary verb; to grow ("wax"), i.e. Enlarge (literal or figurative, active or passive).

DEFINITION: increasing, increase, growth.
ORIGIN: From auzano; growth.

DEFINITION: tomorrow.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of the same as aer (meaning a breeze, i.e. The morning air); properly, fresh, i.e. (adverb with ellipsis of hemera) to-morrow.

DEFINITION: grim, severe, strict, exacting, harsh, rigid.
ORIGIN: From a (presumed) derivative of the same as aer (meaning blown); rough (properly as a gale), i.e. (figuratively) severe.

DEFINITION: self-sufficiency, independence, contentment.
ORIGIN: From autarkes; self-satisfaction, i.e. (abstractly) contentedness, or (concretely) a competence.

DEFINITION: self-sufficient, contented, satisfied, independent.
ORIGIN: From autos and arkeo; self-complacent, i.e. Contented.

DEFINITION: (perhaps a new coinage), self-condemned.
ORIGIN: From autos and a derivative or katakrino; self-condemned.

DEFINITION: acting of one's own will, of its own accord.
ORIGIN: From autos and the same as maten; self-moved ("automatic"), i.e. Spontaneous.

DEFINITION: an eye-witness.
ORIGIN: From autos and optanomai; self-seeing, i.e. An eye-witness.

DEFINITION: (1) self (emphatic) (2) he, she, it (used for the third person pronoun) (3) the same.
ORIGIN: From the particle au (perhaps akin to the base of aer through the idea of a baffling wind) (backward); the reflexive pronoun self, used (alone or in the comparative heautou) of the third person, and (with the proper personal pronoun) of the other persons.
USAGE: her, it(-self), one, the other, (mine) own, said, (self-), the) same, ((him-, my-, thy-)self, (your-)selves, she, that, their(-s), them(-selves), there(-at, - by, -in, -into, -of, -on, -with), they, (these) things, this (man), those, together, very, which. Compare hautou.

DEFINITION: there, here.
ORIGIN: Genitive (i.e. Possessive) of autos, used as an adverb of location; properly, belonging to the same spot, i.e. In this (or that) place.

DEFINITION: her own, his own, their own, themselves, they.
ORIGIN: Contracted for heautou; self (in some oblique case or reflexively, relation).
USAGE: her (own), (of) him(-self), his (own), of it, thee, their (own), them(-selves), they.

DEFINITION: with one's own hand.
ORIGIN: From autos and cheir; self-handed, i.e. Doing personally.

DEFINITION: (poetical, lit: dry and parched; then: squalid and rough), dingy, murky, obscure, dark, funereal.
ORIGIN: From auchmos (probably from a base akin to that of aer) (dust, as dried by wind); properly, dirty, i.e. (by implication) obscure.

DEFINITION: to take from, take away.
ORIGIN: From apo and haireomai; to remove (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: invisible, unseen, hidden.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and phaino; non-apparent).

DEFINITION: to cause to disappear, hide, remove; to disfigure (probably by leaving unwashed for a long period), destroy.
ORIGIN: From aphanes; to render unapparent, i.e. (actively) consume (becloud), or (passively) disappear (be destroyed).

DEFINITION: disappearing, disappearance, obliteration.
ORIGIN: From aphanizo; disappearance, i.e. (figuratively) abrogation.

DEFINITION: disappearing, invisible, hidden.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of phaino; non-manifested, i.e. Invisible.

DEFINITION: a place of sitting apart, a privy, drain.
ORIGIN: From a compound of apo and the base of hedraios; a place of sitting apart, i.e. A privy.

DEFINITION: severity, severe treatment.
ORIGIN: From a compound of a (as a negative particle) and pheidomai; unsparingness, i.e. Austerity (asceticism).

DEFINITION: simplicity, sincerity.
ORIGIN: From a compound of a (as a negative particle) and phellos (in the sense of a stone as stubbing the foot); smoothness, i.e. (figuratively) simplicity.

DEFINITION: a sending away, a letting go, a release, pardon, complete forgiveness.
ORIGIN: From aphiemi; freedom; (figuratively) pardon.

DEFINITION: a band, fastening (hence, possibly: a ligament), joint.
ORIGIN: From haptomai; probably a ligament (as fastening).

DEFINITION: indestructibility, incorruptibility; hence: immortality.
ORIGIN: From aphthartos; incorruptibility; genitive, unending existence; (figuratively) genuineness.

DEFINITION: indestructible, imperishable, incorruptible; hence: immortal.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of phtheiro; undecaying (in essence or continuance).

DEFINITION: (a) to send away, (b) to let go, release, permit to depart, (c) to remit, forgive, (d) to permit, suffer.
ORIGIN: From apo and hiemi (to send; an intensive form of eimi, to go); to send forth, in various applications (as follow).
USAGE: cry, forgive, forsake, lay aside, leave, let (alone, be, go, have), omit, put (send) away, remit, suffer, yield up.

DEFINITION: to arrive at, reach, come to.
ORIGIN: From apo and the base of hikanos; to go (i.e. Spread) forth (by rumor).

DEFINITION: not loving that which is good.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and philagathos; hostile to virtue.
USAGE: despiser of those that are good.

DEFINITION: not loving money, not avaricious.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and philarguros; unavaricious.
USAGE: without covetousness, not greedy of filthy lucre.

DEFINITION: arrival, by implication departure.
ORIGIN: From aphikneomai; properly, arrival, i.e. (by implication) departure.

DEFINITION: to make to stand away, draw away, repel, take up a position away from, withdraw from, leave, abstain from.
ORIGIN: From apo and histemi; to remove, i.e. (actively) instigate to revolt; usually (reflexively) to desist, desert, etc..
USAGE: depart, draw (fall) away, refrain, withdraw self.

DEFINITION: suddenly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from aphanes (contraction); unawares, i.e. Unexpectedly.

DEFINITION: fearlessly, shamelessly, securely, tranquilly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a compound of a (as a negative particle) and phobos; fearlessly.

DEFINITION: to assimilate, make like to.
ORIGIN: From apo and homoioo; to assimilate closely.

DEFINITION: to look away from (something else) to, see distinctly.
ORIGIN: From apo and horao; to consider attentively.

DEFINITION: to mark off by boundaries from, set apart.
ORIGIN: From apo and horizo; to set off by boundary, i.e. (figuratively) limit, exclude, appoint, etc.

DEFINITION: (a) a starting, a start, (b) cause, occasion, opportunity.
ORIGIN: From a compound of apo and hormao; a starting-point, i.e. (figuratively) an opportunity.

DEFINITION: to foam (at the mouth), froth.
ORIGIN: From aphros; to froth at the mouth (in epilepsy).

DEFINITION: foam, froth.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; froth, i.e. Slaver.

DEFINITION: want of sense, foolishness, impiety, wickedness.
ORIGIN: From aphron; senselessness, i.e. (euphemistically) egotism; (morally) recklessness.

DEFINITION: senseless, foolish, inconsiderate.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and phren; properly, mindless, i.e. Stupid, (by implication) ignorant, (specially) egotistic, (practically) rash, or (morally) unbelieving.

DEFINITION: to fall asleep.
ORIGIN: From a compound of apo and hupnos; properly, to become awake, i.e. (by implication) to drop (off) in slumber.

DEFINITION: soundless, voiceless, speechless, dumb.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and phone; voiceless, i.e. Mute (by nature or choice); figuratively, unmeaning.

DEFINITION: Ahaz, son of Jotham and father of Hezekiah.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Achaz); Achaz, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: the Roman Province Achaia, governed by a proconsul, and practically conterminous with modern Greece before 1912.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; Achaia (i.e. Greece), a country of Europe.

DEFINITION: "an Achaian", Achaicus, a Christian at Corinth.
ORIGIN: From Achaia; an Achaian; Achaicus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: ungrateful, ungracious, unpleasing.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a presumed derivative of charizomai; thankless, i.e. Ungrateful.

DEFINITION: Achim, son of Zadok and father of Eliud.
ORIGIN: Probably of Hebrew origin (compare Yowqiym); Achim, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: not made with hands.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and cheiropoietos; unmanufactured, i.e. Inartificial.

DEFINITION: a mist, dimness, darkening.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; dimness of sight, i.e. (probably) a cataract.

DEFINITION: unprofitable, useless, unworthy.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of chre (compare chreia); useless, i.e. (euphemistically) unmeritorious.

DEFINITION: (lit: to become sour, to turn, of milk), to be good for nothing, render useless; met: to become corrupt.
ORIGIN: From achreios; to render useless, i.e. Spoil.

DEFINITION: unprofitable, useless, detrimental.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and chrestos; inefficient, i.e. (by implication) detrimental.

DEFINITION: as far as, up to, until, during.
ORIGIN: Or achris akh'-rece; akin to akron (through the idea of a terminus); (of time) until or (of place) up to.
USAGE: as far as, for, in(-to), till, (even, un-)to, until, while. Compare mechri.

DEFINITION: chaff.
ORIGIN: Perhaps remotely from cheo (to shed forth); chaff (as diffusive).

DEFINITION: not guilty of falsehood, truthful.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and pseudos; veracious.

DEFINITION: wormwood.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; wormwood (as a type of bitterness, i.e. (figuratively) calamity).

DEFINITION: lifeless, inanimate.
ORIGIN: From a (as a negative particle) and psuche; lifeless, i.e. Inanimate (mechanical).

DEFINITION: Baal, chief deity of the Phoenicians and other Semitic nations.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Ba'al); Baal, a Phoenician deity (used as a symbol of idolatry).

DEFINITION: (a) Babylon, the ancient city on the Euphrates, to which the people of Jerusalem, etc., were transported, (b) hence allegorically of Rome, from the point of view of the Christian people.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Babel); Babylon, the capitol of Chaldaea (literally or figuratively (as a type of tyranny)).

DEFINITION: a step (of a stairway); hence: a stage in a career, a position.
ORIGIN: From the same as bathos; a step, i.e. (figuratively) grade (of dignity).

DEFINITION: depth; deep water; met: fullness, immensity; an extreme degree; profundities, deep-laid plans.
ORIGIN: From the same as bathus; profundity, i.e. (by implication) extent; (figuratively) mystery.

DEFINITION: to deepen, excavate.
ORIGIN: From bathus; to deepen.

DEFINITION: deep (lit. and met.); in the depths of the early morning, while still very early; profound.
ORIGIN: From the base of basis; profound (as going down), literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: a palm branch.
ORIGIN: A diminutive of a derivative probably of the base of basis; a palm twig (as going out far).

DEFINITION: Balaam, son of Beor of Pethor on the Euphrates, a soothsayer in the Old Testament.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Bil'am); Balaam, a Mesopotamian (symbolic of a false teacher).

DEFINITION: Balak, son of Zippor, King of Moab.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Balaq); Balak, a Moabite.

DEFINITION: a purse, money-bag.
ORIGIN: Probably remotely from ballo (as a depository); a pouch (for money).

DEFINITION: (a) to cast, throw, rush, (b) often, in the weaker sense: to place, put, drop.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to throw (in various applications, more or less violent or intense).
USAGE: arise, cast (out), X dung, lay, lie, pour, put (up), send, strike, throw (down), thrust. Compare rhipto.

DEFINITION: lit: to dip, submerge, but specifically of ceremonial dipping; to baptize.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of bapto; to immerse, submerge; to make whelmed (i.e. Fully wet); used only (in the New Testament) of ceremonial ablution, especially (technically) of the ordinance of Christian baptism.

DEFINITION: (the result of) a dipping or sinking.
ORIGIN: From baptizo; baptism (technically or figuratively).

DEFINITION: dipping, washing (of a ceremonial character).
ORIGIN: From baptizo; ablution (ceremonial or Christian).

DEFINITION: the baptizer, the Baptist, epithet used only of John, the son of Zechariah and Elizabeth, forerunner of Jesus.
ORIGIN: From baptizo; a baptizer, as an epithet of Christ's forerunner.

DEFINITION: (a) to dip, (b) to dye.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to whelm, i.e. Cover wholly with a fluid; in the New Testament only in a qualified or special sense, i.e. (literally) to moisten (a part of one's person), or (by implication) to stain (as with dye).

DEFINITION: "son of Abba", Barabbas, the Israelite robber released instead of Christ.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (dikaiosis and Abba); son of Abba; Bar-abbas, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Barak, one of the judges of Israel.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Baraq); Barak, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Barachiah; his identity is uncertain, perhaps father of the Zechariah killed by the Zealots in the last Jewish War.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Berekyah); Barachias (i.e. Berechijah), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: a foreigner, one who speaks neither Greek nor Latin; as adj: foreign.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a foreigner (i.e. Non-Greek).

DEFINITION: to weight, load, burden, lit. and met.
ORIGIN: From barus; to weigh down (figuratively).

DEFINITION: heavily, with difficulty.
ORIGIN: Adverb from barus; heavily (figuratively).

DEFINITION: Bartholomew, surname of Nathanael, one of the twelve apostles of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (bar and Talmay); son of Tolmai; Bar-tholomoeus, a Christian apostle.

DEFINITION: Bar-Jesus, the name of the magician and false prophet at Paphos in Cyprus; he is also called Elymas.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (bar and Yhowshuwa'); son of Jesus (or Joshua); Bar-jesus, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Bar-Jonas, son of Jonas, the surname of Simon Peter.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (diakoneo and Malchos); son of Jonas (or Jonah); Bar-jonas, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Barnabas, a Cypriote Jew, uncle of John Mark; his other name was Joseph.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (diakoneo and tacha); son of Nabas (i.e. Prophecy); Barnabas, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: a weight, burden, lit. or met.
ORIGIN: Probably from the same as basis (through the notion of going down; compare bathos); weight; in the New Testament only, figuratively, a load, abundance, authority.

DEFINITION: "son of Sabba", Barsabbas, the surname of two Israelites Christian.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (bar and probably tsba'); son of Sabas (or Tsaba); Bar-sabas, the name of two Israelites.

DEFINITION: "son of Timaeus", Bartimaeus, a beggar.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (diakoneo and kruphe); son of Timoeus (or the unclean); Bar-timoeus, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: overcharge.
ORIGIN: From barus; to burden (figuratively).

DEFINITION: heavy, weighty, burdensome, lit. and met; violent, oppressive.
ORIGIN: From the same as baros; weighty, i.e. (fig) burdensome, grave.

DEFINITION: of great value.
ORIGIN: From barus and time; highly valuable.

DEFINITION: to examine, as by torture; to torment; to buffet, as of waves.
ORIGIN: From basanos; to torture.

DEFINITION: torture, torment.
ORIGIN: From basanizo; torture.

DEFINITION: one who tortures, a tormentor, jailor.
ORIGIN: From basanizo; a torturer.

DEFINITION: a touchstone (a dark stone used in testing metals), examination by torture, torture.
ORIGIN: Perhaps remotely from the same as basis (through the notion of going to the bottom); a touch-stone, i.e. (by analogy) torture.

DEFINITION: kingship, sovereignty, authority, rule, especially of God, both in the world, and in the hearts of men; hence: kingdom, in the concrete sense.
ORIGIN: From basileus; properly, royalty, i.e. (abstractly) rule, or (concretely) a realm (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: king's court.
ORIGIN: Neuter of basileios; a palace.

DEFINITION: courtiers, palaces, a body of kings, royal.
ORIGIN: From basileus; kingly (in nature).

DEFINITION: a king, ruler, but in some passages clearly to be translated: emperor.
ORIGIN: Probably from basis (through the notion of a foundation of power); a sovereign (abstractly, relatively, or figuratively).

DEFINITION: (a) to rule, reign, (b) to reign over.
ORIGIN: From basileus; to rule (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: connected with a king, royal, regal, (a) an officer in the service of the king, (b) the king's country.
ORIGIN: From basileus; regal (in relation), i.e. (literally) belonging to (or befitting) the sovereign (as land, dress, or a courtier), or (figuratively) preeminent.

DEFINITION: a queen.
ORIGIN: Feminine from basileuo; a queen.

DEFINITION: a step; hence: a foot.
ORIGIN: From baino (to walk); a pace ("base"), i.e. (by implication) the foot.

DEFINITION: to give the evil eye to, fascinate, bewitch, overpower.
ORIGIN: Akin to phasko; to malign, i.e. (by extension) to fascinate (by false representations).

DEFINITION: (a) to carry, bear, (b) to carry (take) away.
ORIGIN: Perhaps remotely derived from the base of basis (through the idea of removal); to lift, literally or figuratively (endure, declare, sustain, receive, etc.).

DEFINITION: a thorn bush or bramble.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a brier shrub.

DEFINITION: a bath, a liquid measure among the Jews, containing 72 sextarii, that is, between eight and nine gallons.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (bath); a bath, or measure for liquids.

DEFINITION: a frog.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a frog.

DEFINITION: to chatter, be long-winded, utter empty words, stammer, repeat.
ORIGIN: From Battos (a proverbial stammerer) and logos; to stutter, i.e. (by implication) to prate tediously.

DEFINITION: an abominable thing, an accursed thing.
ORIGIN: From bdelusso; a detestation, i.e. (specially) idolatry.

DEFINITION: abominable, detestable.
ORIGIN: From bdelusso; detestable, i.e. (specially) idolatrous.

DEFINITION: to abhor, detest, loathe.
ORIGIN: From a (presumed) derivative of bdeo (to stink); to be disgusted, i.e. (by implication) detest (especially of idolatry).

DEFINITION: firm, steadfast, enduring, sure, certain.
ORIGIN: From the base of basis (through the idea of basality); stable (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to confirm, ratify, secure, establish; pass: to guarantee.
ORIGIN: From bebaios; to stabilitate (figuratively).

DEFINITION: confirmation, ratification, establishment.
ORIGIN: From bebaioo; stabiliment.

DEFINITION: permitted to be trodden, by implication unhallowed.
ORIGIN: From the base of basis and belos (a threshold); accessible (as by crossing the door-way), i.e. (by implication, of Jewish notions) heathenish, wicked.

DEFINITION: to profane, pollute, violate.
ORIGIN: From bebelos; to desecrate.

DEFINITION: Beelzebul, a name of Satan, the chief of evil spirits.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (by parody on Ba'al Zbuwb); dung-god; Beelzebul, a name of Satan.

DEFINITION: "lord of the forest", Beliar, a name of Satan.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (bliya'al); worthlessness; Belial, as an epithet of Satan.

DEFINITION: a missile, dart, javelin, arrow.
ORIGIN: From ballo; a missile, i.e. Spear or arrow.

DEFINITION: better; adv: very well.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a compound of a derivative of ballo (used for the comparative of agathos); better.

DEFINITION: Benjamin, youngest son of Jacob, founder of one of the twelve tribes of Israel.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Binyamiyn); Benjamin, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Bernice, daughter of Agrippa to and Kypros, and sister of M. Julius Agrippa II.
ORIGIN: From a provincial form of phero and nike; victorious; Bernice, a member of the Herodian family.

DEFINITION: Berea, a town of the province Macedonia.
ORIGIN: Perhaps a provincial from a derivative of peran (Peroea, i.e. The region beyond the coast-line); Beroea, a place in Macedonia.

DEFINITION: belonging to Berea, Berean.
ORIGIN: From Beroia; a Beroeoean or native of Beroea.

DEFINITION: Bethabara.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (bayith and abarah); ferry-house; Bethabara (i.e. Bethabarah), a place on the Jordan.

DEFINITION: (a) Bethany, the home of Lazarus, Martha, and Mary, near Jerusalem, (b) Bethany, beyond Jordan.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin; date-house; Beth-any, a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: Bethesda, name of a pool in Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (compare bayith and checed); house of kindness; Beth-esda, a pool in Jerusalem.

DEFINITION: "house of bread", Bethlehem, a city near Jer.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Beyth l-'Aphrah); Bethleem (i.e. Beth-lechem), a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: "house of fish", Bethsaida, the name of two cities on the shore of the Sea of Galilee.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (compare bayith and tsayad); fishing-house; Bethsaida, a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: Bethphage, a village in the neighborhood of Jerusalem, on the Mt. of Olives.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (compare bayith and pag); fig-house; Beth-phage, a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: an elevated place ascended by steps, a throne, tribunal.
ORIGIN: From the base of basis; a step, i.e. Foot-breath; by implication, a rostrum, i.e. A tribunal.

DEFINITION: a beryl, a precious stone of various colors, the best known being sea-green.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a "beryl".

DEFINITION: force, violence, strength.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to bia (through the idea of vital activity); force.

DEFINITION: (a) mid: to use force, force way, come forward violently, (b) pass: to be forcibly treated, suffer violence.
ORIGIN: From bios; to force, i.e. (reflexively) to crowd oneself (into), or (passively) to be seized.

DEFINITION: strong, violent.
ORIGIN: From bia; violent.

DEFINITION: a forceful, violent man; one who is eager in pursuit.
ORIGIN: From biazo; a forcer, i.e. (figuratively) energetic.

DEFINITION: a little papyrus roll.
ORIGIN: A diminutive of biblion; a booklet.

DEFINITION: a papyrus roll.
ORIGIN: A diminutive of biblos; a roll.

DEFINITION: a written book, roll, or volume, sometimes with a sacred connotation.
ORIGIN: Properly, the inner bark of the papyrus plant, i.e. (by implication) a sheet or scroll of writing.

DEFINITION: to eat.
ORIGIN: A reduplicated and prolonged form of an obsolete primary verb (perhaps causative of bosko); to eat.

DEFINITION: Bithynia, a Roman province, north-west of Asia Minor and south-west of the Black Sea.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; Bithynia, a region of Asia.

DEFINITION: (a) life, (b) manner of life; livelihood.
ORIGIN: A primary word; life, i.e. (literally) the present state of existence; by implication, the means of livelihood.

DEFINITION: to live, pass life.
ORIGIN: From bios; to spend existence.

DEFINITION: manner of life.
ORIGIN: From bioo; living (properly, the act, by implication, the mode).

DEFINITION: belonging to ordinary life, worldly.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of bioo; relating to the present existence.
USAGE: of (pertaining to, things that pertain to) this life.

DEFINITION: injurious, hurtful.
ORIGIN: From blapto; injurious.

DEFINITION: to hurt, injure.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; properly, to hinder, i.e. (by implication) to injure.

DEFINITION: intrans: to sprout; trans: to cause to sprout, make to grow up.
ORIGIN: From blastos (a sprout); to germinate; by implication, to yield fruit.

DEFINITION: Blastus, chamberlain of King Herod Agrippa to.
ORIGIN: Perhaps the same as the base of blastano; Blastus, an officer of Herod Agrippa.

DEFINITION: to speak evil against, blaspheme, use abusive or scurrilous language about (God or men).
ORIGIN: From blasphemos; to vilify; specially, to speak impiously.
USAGE: (speak) blaspheme(-er, -mously, -my), defame, rail on, revile, speak evil.

DEFINITION: abusive or scurrilous language, blasphemy.
ORIGIN: From blasphemos; vilification (especially against God).

DEFINITION: slanderous; subst: a blasphemer.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of blapto and pheme; scurrilious, i.e. Calumnious (against men), or (specially) impious (against God).

DEFINITION: a look, glance; sight and hearing.
ORIGIN: From blepo; vision (properly concrete; by implication, abstract).

DEFINITION: (primarily physical), to look, see, perceive, discern.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to look at (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: behold, beware, lie, look (on, to), perceive, regard, see, sight, take heed. Compare optanomai.

DEFINITION: a verbal adj: one must put, that ought to be put.
ORIGIN: From ballo; fit to be cast (i.e. Applied).

DEFINITION: Boanerges, an epithet applied to the two sons of Zebedee.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (ben and rgaz); sons of commotion; Boanerges, an epithet of two of the apostles.

DEFINITION: to shout, call aloud, proclaim.
ORIGIN: Apparently a prolonged form of a primary verb; to halloo, i.e. Shout (for help or in a tumultuous way).

DEFINITION: a shout, cry.
ORIGIN: From boao; a halloo, i.e. Call (for aid, etc.).

DEFINITION: (a) abstr: assistance, (b) concr: (a technical term of nautical language), a help.
ORIGIN: From boethos; aid; specially, a rope or chain for frapping a vessel.

DEFINITION: to come to the rescue of, come to help, help.
ORIGIN: From boethos; to aid or relieve.

DEFINITION: helping, a helper.
ORIGIN: From boe and theo (to run); a succorer.

DEFINITION: a pit, ditch.
ORIGIN: Akin to bathuno; a hole (in the ground); specially, a cistern.

DEFINITION: a casting, throw; in acc: as measure of distance.
ORIGIN: From ballo; a throw (as a measure of distance).

DEFINITION: to cast the line (for sounding), to sound.
ORIGIN: From bolis; to heave the lead.

DEFINITION: a dart, javelin.
ORIGIN: From ballo; a missile, i.e. Javelin.

DEFINITION: Boaz, son of Salmon and Rahab, husband of Ruth, father of Obed.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Bo'az); Booz, (i.e. Boaz), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: mud, mire, filth.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; mud.

DEFINITION: the north wind, hence: the North.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; the north (properly, wind).

DEFINITION: to feed, pasture.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary verb (compare bibrosko, bous); to pasture; by extension to, fodder; reflexively, to graze.

DEFINITION: Bosor, father of Balaam.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (b'owr); Bosor (i.e. Beor), a Moabite.

DEFINITION: fodder, food, herbage.
ORIGIN: From bosko; herbage (as if for grazing).

DEFINITION: a cluster (bunch) of grapes.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a bunch (of grapes).

DEFINITION: a member of a city council, in NT of the Sanhedrin at Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: From bouleuo; an adviser, i.e. (specially) a councillor or member of the Jewish Sanhedrin.

DEFINITION: to deliberate, take counsel, determine.
ORIGIN: From boule; to advise, i.e. (reflexively) deliberate, or (by implication) resolve.
USAGE: consult, take counsel, determine, be minded, purpose.

DEFINITION: counsel, deliberate wisdom, decree.
ORIGIN: From boulomai; volition, i.e. (objectively) advice, or (by implication) purpose.

DEFINITION: will, counsel, purpose.
ORIGIN: From boulomai; a resolve.

DEFINITION: to will, intend, desire, wish.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of a primary verb; to "will," i.e. (reflexively) be willing.
USAGE: be disposed, minded, intend, list, (be, of own) will (-ing). Compare ethelo.

DEFINITION: a hillock, hill.
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin; a hillock.

DEFINITION: an ox, cow, bull.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of bosko; an ox (as grazing), i.e. An animal of that species ("beef").

DEFINITION: a prize.
ORIGIN: From brabeus (an umpire of uncertain derivation); an award (of arbitration), i.e. (specially) a prize in the public games.

DEFINITION: (lit: to act as arbiter in the games), to rule, arbitrate.
ORIGIN: From the same as brabeion; to arbitrate, i.e. (genitive case) to govern (figuratively, prevail).

DEFINITION: to be slow, to delay, tarry.
ORIGIN: From bradus; to delay.

DEFINITION: to sail slowly.
ORIGIN: From bradus and a prolonged form of pleo; to sail slowly.

DEFINITION: slow, slow of understanding.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; slow; figuratively, dull.

DEFINITION: tardiness, slowness, delay.
ORIGIN: From bradus; tardiness.

DEFINITION: the arm, strength.
ORIGIN: Properly, comparative of brachus, but apparently in the sense of brasso (to wield); the arm, i.e. (figuratively) strength.

DEFINITION: short, little, few.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; short (of time, place, quantity, or number).

DEFINITION: an unborn or a newborn child.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; an infant (properly, unborn) literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: to moisten, rain, send rain.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to moisten (especially by a shower).

DEFINITION: thunder.
ORIGIN: Akin to bremo (to roar); thunder.

DEFINITION: a heavy rain.
ORIGIN: From brecho; rain.

DEFINITION: a noose or snare; a cord.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a noose.

DEFINITION: a biting, a gnashing of teeth.
ORIGIN: From brucho; a grating (of the teeth).

DEFINITION: to grind or gnash, as with the teeth for rage or pain.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to grate the teeth (in pain or rage).

DEFINITION: to be full to bursting, to gush with.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to swell out, i.e. (by implication) to gush.

DEFINITION: food of any kind.
ORIGIN: From the base of bibrosko; food (literally or figuratively), especially (ceremonially) articles allowed or forbidden by the Jewish law.

DEFINITION: eatable, suitable for food.
ORIGIN: From brosis; eatable.

DEFINITION: (a) abstr: eating, (b) food, a meal, (c) rust.
ORIGIN: From the base of bibrosko; (abstractly) eating (literally or figuratively); by extension (concretely) food (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to cause to sink; mid: to sink, submerge, drown.
ORIGIN: From buthos; to sink; by implication, to drown.

DEFINITION: the deep sea, the bottom.
ORIGIN: A variation of bathos; depth, i.e. (by implication) the sea.

DEFINITION: a tanner.
ORIGIN: From bursa (a hide); a tanner.

DEFINITION: of fine linen, cotton.
ORIGIN: From bussos; made of linen (neuter a linen cloth).

DEFINITION: byssus (a species of flax), also (the) linen (made from it).
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (buwts); white linen.

DEFINITION: an altar, platform; a slightly-elevated spot.
ORIGIN: From the base of basis; properly, a stand, i.e. (specially) an altar.

DEFINITION: Gabbatha, a sort of paved square, on which the procurator had his judgment seat.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (compare gab); the knoll; gabbatha, a vernacular term for the Roman tribunal in Jerusalem.

DEFINITION: the angel Gabriel, a messenger of God.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Gabriy'el); Gabriel, an archangel.

DEFINITION: a gangrene, an eating sore.
ORIGIN: From graino (to gnaw); an ulcer ("gangrene").

DEFINITION: Gad, one of the twelve tribes of Israel.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Gad); Gad, a tribe of Israelites.

DEFINITION: Gadarene, belonging to Gadara (an important Hellenized town, one of the Decapolis, and south-east of the Sea of Galilee).
ORIGIN: From Gadara (a town east of the Jordan); a Gadarene or inhabitant of Gadara.

DEFINITION: treasure, treasury.
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin; a treasure.

DEFINITION: Gaza, an old town in the south of Palestine, on the sea-coast.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Azzah); Gazah (i.e. Azzah), a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: a treasury.
ORIGIN: From gaza and phulake; a treasure-house, i.e. A court in the temple for the collection-boxes.

DEFINITION: Gaius, (a) a Corinthian, (b) a Macedonian, (c) a citizen of Derbe, (d) an Ephesian.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; Gaius (i.e. Caius), a Christian.

DEFINITION: milk.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; milk (figuratively).

DEFINITION: a Galatian (meaning any inhabitant of the Roman province Galatia).
ORIGIN: From Galatia; a Galatian or inhabitant of Galatia.
