DEFINITION: Galatia, a large Roman province in central Asia Minor, comprising the districts of Paphlagonia, Pontus Galaticus, Galatia (in the narrower sense, which some still think is intended in the NT), Phrygia Galatica, Lycaonia Galatica, Pisidia and Isaurica.
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin; Galatia, a region of Asia.

DEFINITION: Galatic, belonging to the province Galatia.
ORIGIN: From Galatia; Galatic or relating to Galatia.

DEFINITION: a calm.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; tranquillity.

DEFINITION: Galilee, a district towards the southern end of the Roman province Syria; the northern division of Palestine.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Galiyl); Galiloea (i.e. The heathen circle), a region of Palestine.

DEFINITION: a Galilean, an inhabitant of Galilee.
ORIGIN: From Galilaia; Galilean or belonging to Galilea.

DEFINITION: Gallio, Lucius Iunius Gallio, who received this name by adoption into another family, but was born brother of the philosopher Seneca and originally named L. Annaeus Nouatus; proconsul of the Roman province Achaia from spring A.D. 52 to spring 53.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; Gallion (i.e. Gallio), a Roman officer.

DEFINITION: Gamaliel, a noted Pharisee, teacher of Saul.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Gamliy'el); Gamaliel (i.e. Gamliel), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: to marry, used of either sex.
ORIGIN: From gamos; to wed (of either sex).

DEFINITION: to give in marriage.
ORIGIN: From gamos; to espouse (a daughter to a husband).

DEFINITION: a marriage, wedding, wedding-ceremony; plur: a wedding-feast.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; nuptials.

DEFINITION: for, indeed (a conjunction used to express cause, explanation, inference or continuation).
ORIGIN: A primary particle; properly, assigning a reason (used in argument, explanation or intensification; often with other particles).
USAGE: and, as, because (that), but, even, for, indeed, no doubt, seeing, then, therefore, verily, what, why, yet.

DEFINITION: the womb, stomach; of a woman: to be with child (lit: to have [a child] in the belly).
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; the stomach; by analogy, the matrix; figuratively, a gourmand.

DEFINITION: an enclitic, emphasizing particle: at least, indeed, really, but generally too subtle to be represented in English.
ORIGIN: A primary particle of emphasis or qualification (often used with other particles prefixed).
USAGE: and besides, doubtless, at least, yet.

DEFINITION: Gideon, one of the Judges of Israel.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Gid'own); Gedeon (i.e. Gid(e)on), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Gehenna, and originally the name of a valley or cavity near Jerusalem, a place underneath the earth, a place of punishment for evil.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (gay' and Hinnom); valley of (the son of) Hinnom; ge-henna (or Ge-Hinnom), a valley of Jerusalem, used (figuratively) as a name for the place (or state) of everlasting punishment.

DEFINITION: Gethsemane, a small place between the brook Kidron and the Mount of Olives near Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (compare gath and shemen); oil-press; Gethsemane, a garden near Jerusalem.

DEFINITION: a neighbor.
ORIGIN: From ge; a neighbour (as adjoining one's ground); by implication, a friend.

DEFINITION: to laugh, smile.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; to laugh (as a sign of joy or satisfaction).

DEFINITION: laughter.
ORIGIN: From gelao; laughter (as a mark of gratification).

DEFINITION: to fill, load.
ORIGIN: Transitive from gemo; to fill entirely.

DEFINITION: to be full of.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to swell out, i.e. Be full.

DEFINITION: a generation; if repeated twice or with another time word, practically indicates infinity of time.
ORIGIN: From (a presumed derivative of) genos; a generation; by implication, an age (the period or the persons).

DEFINITION: to put into a genealogy, reckon descent.
ORIGIN: From genea and logos; to reckon by generations, i.e. Trace in genealogy.

DEFINITION: the making of a pedigree, a genealogy.
ORIGIN: From the same as genealogeo; tracing by generations, i.e. "genealogy".

DEFINITION: a birthday celebration.
ORIGIN: Neuter plural of a derivative of genesis; birthday ceremonies.

DEFINITION: birth, lineage, descent.
ORIGIN: From the same as genea; nativity; figuratively, nature.

DEFINITION: birth.
ORIGIN: Feminine of a presumed derivative of the base of genea; birth.

DEFINITION: to beget (of the male), (of the female) to bring forth, give birth to.
ORIGIN: From a variation of genos; to procreate (properly, of the father, but by extension of the mother); figuratively, to regenerate.
USAGE: bear, beget, be born, bring forth, conceive, be delivered of, gender, make, spring.

DEFINITION: offspring, child, fruit.
ORIGIN: From gennao; offspring; by analogy, produce (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: Gennesaret, a fertile district by the lake of Tiberias, which was in consequence sometimes called the Lake of Gennesaret.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (compare Kinnrowth); Gennesaret (i.e. Kinnereth), a lake and plain in Palestine.

DEFINITION: nativity, birth.
ORIGIN: From gennao; nativity.

DEFINITION: begotten, born.
ORIGIN: From gennao; born.

DEFINITION: offspring, family, race, nation, kind.
ORIGIN: From ginomai; "kin" (abstract or concrete, literal or figurative, individual or collective).
USAGE: born, country(-man), diversity, generation, kind(-red), nation, offspring, stock.

DEFINITION: Gerasene, of Gerasa, a city East of the Jordan.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Girgashiy); a Gergesene (i.e. Girgashite) or one of the aborigines of Palestine.

DEFINITION: the assembly or body of elders.
ORIGIN: From geron; the eldership, i.e. (collectively) the Jewish Sanhedrin.

DEFINITION: an old man.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity (compare geras); aged.

DEFINITION: (a) to taste, (b) to experience.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to taste; by implication, to eat; figuratively, to experience (good or ill).

DEFINITION: to work the soil, cultivate the earth.
ORIGIN: From georgos; to till (the soil).

DEFINITION: a tilled field, cultivation, husbandry.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a (presumed) derivative of georgos; cultivable, i.e. A farm.

DEFINITION: a worker of the soil, husbandman, farmer, farm-laborer, vine-dresser.
ORIGIN: From ge and the base of ergon; a land-worker, i.e. Farmer.

DEFINITION: the earth, soil, land, region, country, inhabitants of a region.
ORIGIN: Contracted from a primary word; soil; by extension a region, or the solid part or the whole of the terrene globe (including the occupants in each application).

DEFINITION: old age.
ORIGIN: Akin to geron; senility.

DEFINITION: to become old, grow old.
ORIGIN: From geras; to be senescent.

DEFINITION: to come into being, be born, become, come about, happen.
ORIGIN: A prolongation and middle voice form of a primary verb; to cause to be ("gen"-erate), i.e. (reflexively) to become (come into being), used with great latitude (literal, figurative, intensive, etc.).
USAGE: arise, be assembled, be(-come, -fall, -have self), be brought (to pass), (be) come (to pass), continue, be divided, draw, be ended, fall, be finished, follow, be found, be fulfilled, + God forbid, grow, happen, have, be kept, be made, be married, be ordained to be, partake, pass, be performed, be published, require, seem, be showed, X soon as it was, sound, be taken, be turned, use, wax, will, would, be wrought.

DEFINITION: to be taking in knowledge, come to know, learn; aor: to ascertained, realized.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary verb; to "know" (absolutely) in a great variety of applications and with many implications (as follow, with others not thus clearly expressed).
USAGE: allow, be aware (of), feel, (have) know(-ledge), perceived, be resolved, can speak, be sure, understand.

DEFINITION: the unfermented juice of grapes; hence: sweet new wine.
ORIGIN: Akin to glukus; sweet wine, i.e. (properly) must (fresh juice), but used of the more saccharine (and therefore highly inebriating) fermented wine.

DEFINITION: sweet.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; sweet (i.e. Not bitter nor salt).

DEFINITION: the tongue, a language, a nation (usually distinguished by their speech).
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; the tongue; by implication, a language (specially, one naturally unacquired).

DEFINITION: (a vernacular word), bag, purse; some prefer to take as: box, chest.
ORIGIN: From glossa and the base of kosmos; properly, a case (to keep mouthpieces of wind-instruments in) i.e. (by extension) a casket or (specially) purse.

DEFINITION: one who cleans woolen cloth.
ORIGIN: By variation for a derivative from knapto (to tease cloth); a cloth-dresser.

DEFINITION: (lit: born in wedlock), hence: real, true, genuine; with definite article: the true, genuine element.
ORIGIN: From the same as genesia; legitimate (of birth), i.e. Genuine.

DEFINITION: truly, genuinely, honorably, sincerely.
ORIGIN: Adverb from gnesios; genuinely, i.e. Really.

DEFINITION: darkness, gloom; a thick cloud.
ORIGIN: Akin to nephos; gloom (as of a storm).

DEFINITION: opinion, counsel, judgment, intention, decree.
ORIGIN: From ginosko; cognition, i.e. (subjectively) opinion, or (objectively) resolve (counsel, consent, etc.).
USAGE: advice, + agree, judgment, mind, purpose, will.

DEFINITION: to make known, declare, know, discover.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of ginosko; to make known; subjectively, to know.
USAGE: certify, declare, make known, give to understand, do to wit, wot.

DEFINITION: knowledge, doctrine, wisdom.
ORIGIN: From ginosko; knowing (the act), i.e. (by implication) knowledge.

DEFINITION: one who knows, an expert.
ORIGIN: From ginosko; a knower.

DEFINITION: known, an acquaintance.
ORIGIN: From ginosko; well-known.

DEFINITION: to whisper, murmur, grumble (generally of smoldering discontent).
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; to grumble.

DEFINITION: a muttering, murmuring.
ORIGIN: From gogguzo; a grumbling.

DEFINITION: a murmurer, grumbler.
ORIGIN: From gogguzo; a grumbler.

DEFINITION: a conjuror, juggler, sorcerer; a tricky (crafty) deceiver, imposter.
ORIGIN: From goao (to wail); properly, a wizard (as muttering spells), i.e. (by implication) an imposter.

DEFINITION: Golgotha, a knoll outside the wall of Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (compare gulgoleth); the skull; Golgotha, a knoll near Jerusalem.

DEFINITION: Gomorrah, one of the destroyed cities on the Dead Sea.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Amorah); Gomorrha (i.e. Amorah), a place near the Dead Sea.

DEFINITION: a ship's freight, cargo.
ORIGIN: From gemo; a load (as filling), i.e. (specially) a cargo, or (by extension) wares.

DEFINITION: a begetter, father; plur: parents.
ORIGIN: From the base of ginomai; a parent.

DEFINITION: the knee.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; the "knee".

DEFINITION: to fall on knees before (in supplication), supplicate, entreat.
ORIGIN: From a compound of gonu and the alternate of pipto; to fall on the knee.

DEFINITION: a letter of the alphabet; collectively: written (revelation); (a) a written document, a letter, an epistle, (b) writings, literature, learning.
ORIGIN: From grapho; a writing, i.e. A letter, note, epistle, book, etc.; plural learning.
USAGE: bill, learning, letter, scripture, writing, written.

DEFINITION: (a) in Jerusalem, a scribe, one learned in the Jewish Law, a religious teacher, (b) at Ephesus, the town-clerk, the secretary of the city, (c) a man of learning generally.
ORIGIN: From gramma. A writer, i.e. (professionally) scribe or secretary.

DEFINITION: written.
ORIGIN: From grapho; inscribed (figuratively).

DEFINITION: (a) a writing, (b) a passage of scripture; plur: the scriptures.
ORIGIN: A document, i.e. Holy Writ (or its contents or a statement in it).

DEFINITION: to write; pass: it is written, it stands written (in the scriptures).
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to "grave", especially to write; figuratively, to describe.

DEFINITION: belonging to old women, such as old women tell.
ORIGIN: From graus (an old woman) and eidos; crone-like, i.e. Silly.

DEFINITION: (a) to be awake (in the night), watch, (b) to be watchful, on the alert, vigilant.
ORIGIN: From egeiro; to keep awake, i.e. Watch (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to train by physical exercise; hence: train, in the widest sense.
ORIGIN: From gumnos; to practise naked (in the games), i.e. Train (figuratively).

DEFINITION: (physical) exercise, in a wide sense.
ORIGIN: From gumnazo; training, i.e. (figuratively) asceticism.

DEFINITION: to be poorly clad; to be habitually wearing an under-garment only.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of gumnos; to strip, i.e. (reflexively) go poorly clad.

DEFINITION: rarely: stark-naked; generally: wearing only the under-garment; bare, open, manifest; mere.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; nude (absolute or relative, literal or figurative).

DEFINITION: nakedness.
ORIGIN: From gumnos; nudity (absolute or comparative).

DEFINITION: a woman, with all a woman's weakness, a poor weak woman, a silly woman.
ORIGIN: A diminutive from gune; a little (i.e. Foolish) woman.

DEFINITION: belonging to woman, of woman, female.
ORIGIN: From gune; feminine.

DEFINITION: a woman, wife, lady.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of ginomai; a woman; specially, a wife.

DEFINITION: Gog, in Ezekiel a king of Magog, a land of the remote north; hence, in Revelation, of a people far remote from Palestine.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Gowg); Gog, a symbolic name for some future Antichrist.

DEFINITION: a corner; met: a secret place.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to gonu; an angle.

DEFINITION: David, King of Israel.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (David); Dabid (i.e. David), the Israelite king.

DEFINITION: to be possessed, be under the power of an evil-spirit or demon.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from daimon; to be exercised by a dæmon.
USAGE: have a (be vexed with, be possessed with) devil(-s).

DEFINITION: an evil-spirit, demon; a heathen deity.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of daimon; a dæmonic being; by extension a deity.

DEFINITION: demon-like, such as demons have.
ORIGIN: From daimonion and daimon; dæmon-like.

DEFINITION: an evil-spirit, demon.
ORIGIN: From daio (to distribute fortunes); a dæmon or supernatural spirit (of a bad nature).

DEFINITION: to bite; hence: to backbite, harm seriously.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary root; to bite, i.e. (figuratively) thwart.

DEFINITION: a teardrop.
ORIGIN: Or dakruon dak'-roo-on; of uncertain affinity; a tear.

DEFINITION: to shed tears, weep.
ORIGIN: From dakru; to shed tears.

DEFINITION: a finger-ring.
ORIGIN: From daktulos; a finger-ring.

DEFINITION: a finger.
ORIGIN: Probably from deka; a finger.

DEFINITION: Dalmanutha, an unidentified place near the Sea of Galilee.
ORIGIN: Probably of Chaldee origin; Dalmanutha, a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: Dalmatia, a province of the Roman Empire, east of the Adriatic, a later name for part of what was earlier called Illyricum.
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign derivation; Dalmatia, a region of Europe.

DEFINITION: to tame, subdue, involving obedience and restraint.
ORIGIN: A variation of an obsolete primary of the same meaning; to tame.

DEFINITION: a heifer, young cow.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of damazo; a heifer (as tame).

DEFINITION: Damaris, an Athenian woman.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of damazo; perhaps gentle; Damaris, an Athenian woman.

DEFINITION: a Damascene, an inhabitant of Damascus.
ORIGIN: From Damaskos; a Damascene or inhabitant of Damascus.

DEFINITION: Damascus, a city of Syria.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Dammeseq); Damascus, a city of Syria.

DEFINITION: to lend; mid: to borrow.
ORIGIN: From daneion; to loan on interest; reflexively, to borrow.

DEFINITION: a loan, debt.
ORIGIN: From danos (a gift); probably akin to the base of didomi; a loan.

DEFINITION: a money-lender, creditor.
ORIGIN: From daneizo; a lender.

DEFINITION: Daniel, the prophet.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Daniye'l); Daniel, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: to spend, bear expense, waste, squander.
ORIGIN: From dapane; to expend, i.e. (in a good sense) to incur cost, or (in a bad one) to waste.

DEFINITION: expense, cost.
ORIGIN: From dapto (to devour); expense (as consuming).

DEFINITION: a weak adversative particle, generally placed second in its clause; but, on the other hand, and.
ORIGIN: A primary particle (adversative or continuative); but, and, etc..
USAGE: also, and, but, moreover, now (often unexpressed in English).

DEFINITION: supplication, prayer, entreaty.
ORIGIN: From deomai; a petition.

DEFINITION: it is necessary, inevitable; less frequently: it is a duty, what is proper.
ORIGIN: 3d person singular active present of deo; also deon deh-on'; neuter active participle of the same; both used impersonally; it is (was, etc.) Necessary (as binding).
USAGE: behoved, be meet, must (needs), (be) need(-ful), ought, should.

DEFINITION: an example, type; a thing shown.
ORIGIN: From the base of deiknuo; a specimen (as shown).

DEFINITION: to hold up as an example, make a show of, expose.
ORIGIN: From deigma; to exhibit.

DEFINITION: to point out, show, exhibit; met: to teach, demonstrate, make known.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of an obsolete primary of the same meaning; to show (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: cowardice, timidity.
ORIGIN: From deilos; timidity.

DEFINITION: to shrink, be fearful, timid, cowardly.
ORIGIN: From deilia; to be timid.

DEFINITION: cowardly, timid, fearful.
ORIGIN: From deos (dread); timid, i.e. (by implication) faithless.

DEFINITION: so and so, such a one, where the name of the person is known but not used.
ORIGIN: Probably from the same as deinos (through the idea of forgetting the name as fearful, i.e. Strange); so and so (when the person is not specified).

DEFINITION: vehemently, terribly, grievously.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a derivative of the same as deilos; terribly, i.e. Excessively.

DEFINITION: to dine, sup, eat.
ORIGIN: From deipnon; to dine, i.e. Take the principle (or evening) meal.

DEFINITION: a dinner, an afternoon or evening meal.
ORIGIN: From the same as dapane; dinner, i.e. The chief meal (usually in the evening).

DEFINITION: respectful of what is divine; religious, perhaps, rather than superstitious (the usual meaning).
ORIGIN: The compound of a derivative of the base of deilos and daimon; more religious than others.

DEFINITION: religion in general; in a bad sense: superstition.
ORIGIN: From the same as deisidaimonesteros; religion.

DEFINITION: ten.
ORIGIN: A primary number; ten.

DEFINITION: twelve.
ORIGIN: From deka and duo; two and ten, i.e. Twelve.

DEFINITION: eighteen.
ORIGIN: From deka and pente; ten and five, i.e. Fifteen.

DEFINITION: Decapolis, meaning a group or district of ten cities (of the Greek type) in Palestine, mostly south-east of the Lake of Tiberias; the names and number vary in ancient authorities.
ORIGIN: From deka and polis; the ten-city region; the Decapolis, a district in Syria.

DEFINITION: fourteen.
ORIGIN: From deka and tessares; ten and four, i.e. Fourteen.

DEFINITION: a tenth part, a tithe.
ORIGIN: Feminine of dekatos; a tenth, i.e. As a percentage or (technically) tithe.

DEFINITION: tenth.
ORIGIN: Ordinal from deka; tenth.

DEFINITION: to tithe, collect tithe from.
ORIGIN: From dekate; to tithe, i.e. To give or take a tenth.

DEFINITION: acceptable, accepted.
ORIGIN: From dechomai; approved; (figuratively) propitious.

DEFINITION: to allure, entice (by a bait).
ORIGIN: From the base of dolos; to entrap, i.e. (figuratively) delude.

DEFINITION: a tree.
ORIGIN: Probably from drus (an oak); a tree.

DEFINITION: one posted on the right hand, a spear-man.
ORIGIN: From dexios and lambano; a guardsman (as if taking the right) or light-armed soldier.

DEFINITION: on the right hand, right hand, right.
ORIGIN: From dechomai; the right side or (feminine) hand (as that which usually takes).

DEFINITION: to want for myself; to want, need; to beg, request, beseech, pray.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of deo; to beg (as binding oneself), i.e. Petition.
USAGE: beseech, pray (to), make request. Compare punthanomai.

DEFINITION: Derbean, belonging to Derbe.
ORIGIN: From Derbe; a Derbæan or inhabitant of Derbe.

DEFINITION: Derbe, a town in Lycaonia and in the southern part of the Roman province Galatia.
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin; Derbe, a place in Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: the skin or hide of an animal.
ORIGIN: From dero; a hide.

DEFINITION: made of skin, leathern.
ORIGIN: From derma; made of hide.

DEFINITION: to flay, flog, scourge, beat.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; properly, to flay, i.e. (by implication) to scourge, or (by analogy) to thrash.

DEFINITION: to bind, put in chains, tie together.
ORIGIN: From a (presumed) derivative of desmeo; to be a binder (captor), i.e. To enchain (a prisoner), to tie on (a load).

DEFINITION: to bind, confine.
ORIGIN: From desmon; to tie, i.e. Shackle.

DEFINITION: a bundle.
ORIGIN: From desmeo; a bundle.

DEFINITION: one bound, a prisoner.
ORIGIN: From desmon; a captive (as bound).

DEFINITION: a bond, chain, imprisonment; a string or ligament, an impediment, infirmity.
ORIGIN: Or desmos des-mos' neuter and masculine respectively from deo; a band, i.e. Ligament (of the body) or shackle (of a prisoner); figuratively, an impediment or disability.

DEFINITION: a keeper of a prison, a jailer.
ORIGIN: From desmon and phulax; a jailer (as guarding the prisoners).

DEFINITION: a prison.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of desmon (equivalent to desmeo); a place of bondage, i.e. A dungeon.

DEFINITION: a prisoner, captive.
ORIGIN: From the same as desmoterion; (passively) a captive.

DEFINITION: a lord, master, or prince.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from deo and posis (a husband); an absolute ruler ("despot").

DEFINITION: (originally: hither, hence) (a) exclamatory: come, (b) temporal: now, the present.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; here; used also imperative hither!; and of time, hitherto.

DEFINITION: come hither, come, hither, an exclamatory word.
ORIGIN: From deuro and an imperative form of eimi (to go); come hither!.

DEFINITION: adj. where English requires an adv., on the second day, on the next day.
ORIGIN: From deuteros; secondary, i.e. (specially) on the second day.

DEFINITION: second-first, a word of uncertain meaning.
ORIGIN: From deuteros and protos; second-first, i.e. (specially) a designation of the Sabbath immediately after the Paschal week (being the second after Passover day, and the first of the seven Sabbaths intervening before Pentecost).

DEFINITION: second; with the article: in the second place, for the second time.
ORIGIN: As the compare of duo; (ordinal) second (in time, place, or rank; also adverb).

DEFINITION: to take, receive, accept, welcome.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of a primary verb; to receive (in various applications, literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to bind, tie, fasten; to impel, compel; to declare to be prohibited and unlawful.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to bind (in various applications, literally or figuratively).
USAGE: bind, be in bonds, knit, tie, wind. See also dei, deomai.

DEFINITION: (a) in a clause expressing demand: so, then, (b) indeed, (c) truly.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to de; a particle of emphasis or explicitness; now, then, etc..

DEFINITION: clear, manifest, evident.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; clear.

DEFINITION: to show, make clear, reveal.
ORIGIN: From delos; to make plain (by words).

DEFINITION: Demas, a helper of Paul in Rome.
ORIGIN: Probably for Demetrios; Demas, a Christian.

DEFINITION: to make a public speech, address a multitude.
ORIGIN: From a compound of demos and agora; to be a people-gatherer, i.e. To address a public assembly.

DEFINITION: Demetrius, the name of a silversmith and of a Christian.
ORIGIN: From Demeter (Ceres); Demetrius, the name of an Ephesian and of a Christian.

DEFINITION: an artisan, builder, maker; one who labors for the public.
ORIGIN: From demos and ergon; a worker for the people, i.e. Mechanic (spoken of the Creator).

DEFINITION: properly: the people, especially citizens of a Greek city in popular assembly, but in NT, multitude, rabble.
ORIGIN: From deo; the public (as bound together socially).

DEFINITION: public, publicly.
ORIGIN: From demos; public; (feminine singular dative case as adverb) in public.

DEFINITION: a denarius, a small Roman silver coin.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; a denarius (or ten asses).

DEFINITION: even at that time, whenever.
ORIGIN: From de and pote; a particle of generalization; indeed, at any time.

DEFINITION: of course, indeed, qualifying and yet strengthening the assertion.
ORIGIN: From de and pou; a particle of asseveration; indeed doubtless.

DEFINITION: (a) gen: through, throughout, by the instrumentality of, (b) acc: through, on account of, by reason of, for the sake of, because of.
ORIGIN: A primary preposition denoting the channel of an act; through (in very wide applications, local, causal, or occasional).
USAGE: after, always, among, at, to avoid, because of (that), briefly, by, for (cause)... Fore, from, in, by occasion of, of, by reason of, for sake, that, thereby, therefore, X though, through(-out), to, wherefore, with (-in). In composition it retains the same general importance.

DEFINITION: to cross, pass through, step across.
ORIGIN: From dia and the base of basis; to cross.

DEFINITION: to thrust through, slander, complain of, accuse.
ORIGIN: From dia and ballo; (figuratively) to traduce.

DEFINITION: to assert emphatically.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of a compound of dia and bebaioo; to confirm thoroughly (by words), i.e. Asseverate.

DEFINITION: to look through, to see clearly.
ORIGIN: From dia and blepo; to look through, i.e. Recover full vision.

DEFINITION: (adj. used often as a noun), slanderous; with the article: the Slanderer (par excellence), the Devil.
ORIGIN: From diaballo; a traducer; specially, Satan (compare satan).

DEFINITION: to announce throughout (the world), spread the news of, give notice of, teach.
ORIGIN: From dia and the base of aggelos; to herald thoroughly.

DEFINITION: to pass (of time); to continue through, intervene.
ORIGIN: From dia and ginomai; to elapse meanwhile.
USAGE: X after, be past, be spent.

DEFINITION: to know accurately, examine, decide.
ORIGIN: From dia and ginosko; to know thoroughly, i.e. Ascertain exactly.

DEFINITION: to tell abroad, make known.
ORIGIN: From graptos and gnorizo; to tell abroad.

DEFINITION: judicial examination, decision; an act of discernment.
ORIGIN: From diaginosko; (magisterial) examination ("diagnosis").

DEFINITION: to murmur greatly, continue murmuring.
ORIGIN: From dia and gogguzo; to complain throughout a crowd.

DEFINITION: to awake out of sleep, be thoroughly awake.
ORIGIN: From dia and gregoreuo; to waken thoroughly.

DEFINITION: (either trans. or intrans.), to spend time, pass time, live.
ORIGIN: From dia and ago; to pass time or life.

DEFINITION: to receive in turn, receive through another.
ORIGIN: From dia and dechomai; to receive in turn, i.e. (figuratively) succeed to.

DEFINITION: a head-wreath, crown, diadem.
ORIGIN: From a compound of dia and deo; a "diadem" (as bound about the head).

DEFINITION: to offer here and there, distribute, divide, hand over.
ORIGIN: From dia and didomi; to give throughout a crowd, i.e. Deal out; also to deliver over (as to a successor).

DEFINITION: a successor.
ORIGIN: From diadechomai; a successor in office.

DEFINITION: to gird, tie around; mid: to gird round myself.
ORIGIN: From dia and zonnumi; to gird tightly.

DEFINITION: (a) a covenant between two parties, (b) (the ordinary, everyday sense [found a countless number of times in papyri]) a will, testament.
ORIGIN: From diatithemai; properly, a disposition, i.e. (specially) a contract (especially a devisory will).

DEFINITION: division, distribution, difference, distinction.
ORIGIN: From diaireo; a distinction or (concretely) variety.

DEFINITION: to divide into parts, cut asunder, distribute.
ORIGIN: From dia and haireomai; to separate, i.e. Distribute.

DEFINITION: to cleanse thoroughly.
ORIGIN: From dia and katharizo; to cleanse perfectly, i.e. (specially) winnow.

DEFINITION: to effectively (utterly) refute.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from dia and a compound of kata and elegcho; to prove downright, i.e. Confute.

DEFINITION: to wait at table (particularly of a slave who waits on guests); to serve (generally).
ORIGIN: From diakonos; to be an attendant, i.e. Wait upon (menially or as a host, friend, or (figuratively) teacher); technically, to act as a Christian deacon.
USAGE: (ad-)minister (unto), serve, use the office of a deacon.

DEFINITION: waiting at table; in a wider sense: service, ministration.
ORIGIN: From diakonos; attendance (as a servant, etc.); figuratively (eleemosynary) aid, (official) service (especially of the Christian teacher, or technically of the diaconate).

DEFINITION: a waiter, servant; then of any one who performs any service, an administrator.
ORIGIN: Probably from an obsolete diako (to run on errands; compare dioko); an attendant, i.e. (genitive case) a waiter (at table or in other menial duties); specially, a Christian teacher and pastor (technically, a deacon or deaconess).

DEFINITION: two hundred.
ORIGIN: From dis and hekaton; two hundred.

DEFINITION: to hear throughout, of a judicial hearing.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from dia and akouo; to hear throughout, i.e. Patiently listen (to a prisoner's plea).

DEFINITION: to separate, distinguish, discern one thing from another; to doubt, hesitate, waver.
ORIGIN: From dia and krino; to separate thoroughly, i.e. (literally and reflexively) to withdraw from, or (by implication) oppose; figuratively, to discriminate (by implication, decide), or (reflexively) hesitate.
USAGE: contend, make (to) differ(-ence), discern, doubt, judge, be partial, stagger, waver.

DEFINITION: distinguishing; hence: deciding, passing sentence on; the act of judgment, discernment.
ORIGIN: From diakrino; judicial estimation.

DEFINITION: to obstinately prevent, hinder.
ORIGIN: From dia and koluo; to hinder altogether, i.e. Utterly prohibit.

DEFINITION: to converse together, talk of; of conversation passing from mouth to mouth.
ORIGIN: From dia and laleo; to talk throughout a company, i.e. Converse or (genitive case) publish.

DEFINITION: to converse, address, preach, lecture; to argue, reason.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from dia and lego; to say thoroughly, i.e. Discuss (in argument or exhortation).

DEFINITION: to cease, give over, give up.
ORIGIN: From dia and leipo; to leave off in the middle, i.e. Intermit.

DEFINITION: language, speech, conversation, manner of speaking.
ORIGIN: From dialegomai; a (mode of) discourse, i.e. "dialect".

DEFINITION: to change, exchange; to reconcile, change enmity for friendship.
ORIGIN: From dia and allasso; to change thoroughly, i.e. (mentally) to conciliate.

DEFINITION: to reason (with), debate (with), consider.
ORIGIN: From dia and logizomai; to reckon thoroughly, i.e. (genitive case) to deliberate (by reflection or discussion).
USAGE: cast in mind, consider, dispute, muse, reason, think.

DEFINITION: a calculation, reasoning, thought, movement of thought, deliberation, plotting.
ORIGIN: From dialogizomai; discussion, i.e. (internal) consideration (by implication, purpose), or (external) debate.

DEFINITION: to break up, disperse, dissolve.
ORIGIN: From dia and luo; to dissolve utterly.

DEFINITION: to give solemn evidence, testify (declare) solemnly.
ORIGIN: From dia and martureo; to attest or protest earnestly, or (by implication) hortatively.

DEFINITION: to strive greatly, contend fiercely.
ORIGIN: From dia and machomai; to fight fiercely (in altercation).

DEFINITION: to remain, continue.
ORIGIN: From dia and meno; to stay constantly (in being or relation).

DEFINITION: to divide up into parts, break up; to distribute.
ORIGIN: From dia and merizo; to partition thoroughly (literally in distribution, figuratively in dissension).

DEFINITION: breaking up; discord, hostility.
ORIGIN: From diamerizo; disunion (of opinion and conduct).

DEFINITION: to divide into portions, distribute; pass: to be spread about.
ORIGIN: From dia and the base of nomos; to distribute, i.e. (of information) to disseminate.

DEFINITION: to wink at, nod to, beckon to.
ORIGIN: From dia and neuo; to nod (or express by signs) across an intervening space.

DEFINITION: a reasoning, thought, cogitation.
ORIGIN: From a compound of dia and noieo; something thought through, i.e. A sentiment.

DEFINITION: understanding, intellect, mind, insight.
ORIGIN: From dia and nous; deep thought, properly, the faculty (mind or its disposition), by implication, its exercise.

DEFINITION: to open up completely.
ORIGIN: From dia and anoigo; to open thoroughly, literally (as a first-born) or figuratively (to expound).

DEFINITION: to spend the whole night.
ORIGIN: From dia and a derivative of nux; to sit up the whole night.

DEFINITION: to finish, complete, accomplish fully.
ORIGIN: From dia and anuo (to effect); to accomplish thoroughly.

DEFINITION: always, continually.
ORIGIN: From dia and the genitive case of pas; through all time, i.e. (adverbially) constantly.

DEFINITION: to cross over, pass over.
ORIGIN: From dia and a derivative of the base of peran; to cross entirely.

DEFINITION: to sail over (across).
ORIGIN: From dia and pleo; to sail through.

DEFINITION: to toil through, to be worn out or annoyed.
ORIGIN: From dia and a derivative of ponos; to toil through, i.e. (passively) be worried.

DEFINITION: to pass across, journey through.
ORIGIN: From dia and poreuomai; to travel through.
USAGE: go through, journey in, pass by.

DEFINITION: to be in trouble, doubt, difficulty; to be at a loss.
ORIGIN: From dia and aporeo; to be thoroughly nonplussed.

DEFINITION: to examine thoroughly, to gain by trading.
ORIGIN: From dia and pragmateuomai; to thoroughly occupy oneself, i.e. (transitively and by implication) to earn in business.

DEFINITION: (lit: to saw through), to cut to the quick (with indignation and envy).
ORIGIN: From dia and the base of prizo; to saw asunder, i.e. (figuratively) to exasperate.

DEFINITION: to plunder, rob thoroughly.
ORIGIN: From dia and harpazo; to seize asunder, i.e. Plunder.

DEFINITION: to tear asunder, burst, rend.
ORIGIN: From dia and rhegnumi; to tear asunder.

DEFINITION: to make clear, explain fully.
ORIGIN: From dia and saphes (clear); to clear thoroughly, i.e. (figuratively) declare.

DEFINITION: to blackmail, extort from, intimidate.
ORIGIN: From dia and seio; to shake thoroughly, i.e. (figuratively) to intimidate.

DEFINITION: generally to separate, to winnow, to squander.
ORIGIN: From dia and skorpizo; to dissipate, i.e. (genitive case) to rout or separate; specially, to winnow; figuratively, to squander.

DEFINITION: to draw apart, tear asunder.
ORIGIN: From dia and spao; to draw apart, i.e. Sever or dismember.

DEFINITION: to sow throughout, disperse (in foreign lands).
ORIGIN: From dia and speiro; to sow throughout, i.e. (figuratively) distribute in foreign lands.

DEFINITION: lit: scattering abroad of seed by the sower, hence: dispersion, used especially of the Jews who had migrated and were scattered over the ancient world.
ORIGIN: From diaspeiro; dispersion, i.e. (specially and concretely) the (converted) Israelite resident in Gentile countries.

DEFINITION: to give a commission (instructions), order; to admonish, prohibit.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from dia and stello; to set (oneself) apart (figuratively, distinguish), i.e. (by implication) to enjoin.

DEFINITION: an interval of time, distance.
ORIGIN: From diistemi; an interval.

DEFINITION: distinction, difference, separation.
ORIGIN: From diastellomai; a variation.

DEFINITION: to pervert, corrupt, oppose, distort.
ORIGIN: From dia and strepho; to distort, i.e. (figuratively) misinterpret, or (morally) corrupt.

DEFINITION: to save (rescue) through (some danger), bring safely to, escaped to.
ORIGIN: From dia and sozo; to save thoroughly, i.e. (by implication or analogy) to cure, preserve, rescue, etc.
USAGE: bring safe, escape (safe), heal, make perfectly whole, save.

DEFINITION: ordaining, ordinance, disposition.
ORIGIN: From diatasso; arrangement, i.e. Institution.

DEFINITION: a mandate, decree, edict.
ORIGIN: From diatasso; an arrangement, i.e. (authoritative) edict.

DEFINITION: to trouble greatly, agitate.
ORIGIN: From dia and tarasso; to disturb wholly, i.e. Agitate (with alarm).

DEFINITION: to arrange thoroughly, to charge, appoint.
ORIGIN: From dia and tasso; to arrange thoroughly, i.e. (specially) institute, prescribe, etc.
USAGE: appoint, command, give, (set in) order, ordain.

DEFINITION: to accomplish thoroughly, to persist.
ORIGIN: From dia and teleo; to accomplish thoroughly, i.e. (subjectively) to persist.

DEFINITION: to keep safe, hold fast.
ORIGIN: From dia and tereo; to watch thoroughly, i.e. (positively and transitively) to observe strictly, or (negatively and reflexively) to avoid wholly.

DEFINITION: wherefore, why.
ORIGIN: From dia and tis; through what cause ?, i.e. Why?.

DEFINITION: (a) to appoint, make (of a covenant), (b) to make (a will).
ORIGIN: Middle voice from dia and tithemi; to put apart, i.e. (figuratively) dispose (by assignment, compact, or bequest).

DEFINITION: to rub hard, rub away, to spend time.
ORIGIN: From dia and the base of tribos; to wear through (time), i.e. Remain.

DEFINITION: food, nourishment.
ORIGIN: From a compound of dia and trepho; nourishment.

DEFINITION: to shine through, dawn (of the light coming through the shadows).
ORIGIN: From dia and augazo; to glimmer through, i.e. Break (as day).

DEFINITION: through which light passes, transparent.
ORIGIN: From dia and phaino; appearing through, i.e. "diaphanous".

DEFINITION: (a) trans: to carry through, hither and thither, (b) intrans: to be different, differ, and sometimes: to surpass, excel.
ORIGIN: From dia and phero; to bear through, i.e. (literally) transport; usually to bear apart, i.e. (objectively) to toss about (figuratively, report); subjectively, to "differ", or (by implication) surpass.
USAGE: be better, carry, differ from, drive up and down, be (more) excellent, make matter, publish, be of more value.

DEFINITION: to flee through, escape.
ORIGIN: From dia and pheugo; to flee through, i.e. Escape.

DEFINITION: to report, publish abroad.
ORIGIN: From dia and a derivative of pheme; to report thoroughly, i.e. Divulgate.
USAGE: blaze abroad, commonly report, spread abroad, fame.

DEFINITION: to destroy, waste; hence met: to corrupt.
ORIGIN: From diaballo and phtheiro; to rot thoroughly, i.e. (by implication) to ruin (passively, decay utterly, figuratively, pervert).

DEFINITION: destruction, decay, corruption.
ORIGIN: From diaphtheiro; decay.

DEFINITION: differing, different; hence: excellent.
ORIGIN: From diaphero; varying; also surpassing.

DEFINITION: to guard carefully, protect, defend.
ORIGIN: From dia and phulasso; to guard thoroughly, i.e. Protect.

DEFINITION: to have in hand, thus to lay hands on (violently).
ORIGIN: From dia and a derivative of cheir; to handle thoroughly, i.e. Lay violent hands upon.

DEFINITION: to separate myself from, part from, go away.
ORIGIN: From dia and the middle voice of chorizo; to remove (oneself) wholly, i.e. Retire.

DEFINITION: able to teach, apt to teach.
ORIGIN: From didaktos; instructive ("didactic").

DEFINITION: instructed, taught.
ORIGIN: From didasko; (subjectively) instructed, or (objectively) communicated by teaching.

DEFINITION: instruction (the function or the information).
ORIGIN: From didaskalos; instruction (the function or the information).

DEFINITION: a teacher, master.
ORIGIN: From didasko; an instructor (genitive case or specially).

DEFINITION: to teach, direct, admonish.
ORIGIN: A prolonged (causative) form of a primary verb dao (to learn); to teach (in the same broad application).

DEFINITION: teaching, doctrine, what is taught.
ORIGIN: From didasko; instruction (the act or the matter).

DEFINITION: a double-drachma, two drachmae, a Greek silver coin.
ORIGIN: From dis and drachme; a double drachma (didrachm).

DEFINITION: the Twin; Didymus, the Greek name equivalent to Thomas.
ORIGIN: Prolongation from dis; double, i.e. Twin; Didymus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: to offer, give; to put, place.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary verb (which is used as an alternative in most of the tenses); to give (used in a very wide application, properly, or by implication, literally or figuratively; greatly modified by the connection).
USAGE: adventure, bestow, bring forth, commit, deliver (up), give, grant, hinder, make, minister, number, offer, have power, put, receive, set, shew, smite (+ with the hand), strike (+ with the palm of the hand), suffer, take, utter, yield.

DEFINITION: to wake out of sleep, arouse in general, stir up.
ORIGIN: From dia and egeiro; to wake fully; i.e. Arouse (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a meeting-place of roads, a public spot in a city.
ORIGIN: From dia and exodos; an outlet through, i.e. Probably an open square (from which roads diverge).

DEFINITION: an explainer, an interpreter.
ORIGIN: From diermeneuo; an explainer.

DEFINITION: to explain thoroughly, by implication to translate.
ORIGIN: From dia and hermeneuo; to explain thoroughly, by implication, to translate.

DEFINITION: to pass through, spread (as a report).
ORIGIN: From dia and erchomai; to traverse (literally).
USAGE: come, depart, go (about, abroad, everywhere, over, through, throughout), pass (by, over, through, throughout), pierce through, travel, walk through.

DEFINITION: to find by inquiry.
ORIGIN: From dia and erotao; to question throughout, i.e. Ascertain by interrogation.

DEFINITION: lasting two years, two years old.
ORIGIN: From dis and etos; of two years (in age).

DEFINITION: a period of two years, two years; according to ancient practice this means any period between one and two years.
ORIGIN: From dietes; a space of two years (biennium).

DEFINITION: to relate in full, describe, narrate.
ORIGIN: From dia and hegeomai; to relate fully.

DEFINITION: a narrative.
ORIGIN: From diegeomai; a recital.

DEFINITION: continuous, continually, unbroken.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a compound of dia and a derivative of an alternate of phero; carried through, i.e. (adverbially with eis and ho prefixed) perpetually.

DEFINITION: divided into two seas, dividing the sea (as a reef).
ORIGIN: From dis and thalassa; having two seas, i.e. A sound with a double outlet.

DEFINITION: to pass through (to), come through (to), pierce.
ORIGIN: From dia and the base of hikanos; to reach through, i.e. Penetrate.

DEFINITION: to put apart, separate, put some distance between.
ORIGIN: From dia and histemi; to stand apart, i.e. (reflexively) to remove, intervene.
USAGE: go further, be parted, after the space of.

DEFINITION: to assert emphatically, lean upon.
ORIGIN: From dia and a derivative of ischuros; to stout it through, i.e. Asservate.

DEFINITION: just judging, just judgment.
ORIGIN: From dikaios and krisis; a just sentence.

DEFINITION: just; especially, just in the eyes of God; righteous; the elect (a Jewish idea).
ORIGIN: From dike; equitable (in character or act); by implication, innocent, holy (absolutely or relatively).

DEFINITION: (usually if not always in a Jewish atmosphere), justice, justness, righteousness, righteousness of which God is the source or author, but practically: a divine righteousness.
ORIGIN: From dikaios; equity (of character or act); specially (Christian) justification.

DEFINITION: to make righteous, defend the cause of, plead for the righteousness (innocence) of, acquit, justify; hence: to regard as righteous.
ORIGIN: From dikaios; to render (i.e. Show or regard as) just or innocent.

DEFINITION: a thing pronounced (by God) to be righteous (just, the right); or the restoration of a criminal, a fresh chance given him; a righteous deed, an instance of perfect righteousness.
ORIGIN: From dikaioo; an equitable deed; by implication, a statute or decision.

DEFINITION: righteously, justly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from dikaios; equitably.

DEFINITION: acquittal, justifying, justification, a process of absolution.
ORIGIN: From dikaioo; aquittal (for Christ's sake).

DEFINITION: a judge.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of dike; a judger.

DEFINITION: (a) (originally: custom, usage) right, justice, (b) process of law, judicial hearing, (c) execution of sentence, punishment, penalty, (d) justice, vengeance.
ORIGIN: Probably from deiknuo; right (as self-evident), i.e. Justice (the principle, a decision, or its execution).

DEFINITION: a fishing-net.
ORIGIN: Probably from a primary verb diko (to cast); a seine (for fishing).

DEFINITION: given to repetition, double-tongued.
ORIGIN: From dis and logos; equivocal, i.e. Telling a different story.

DEFINITION: wherefore, on which account, therefore.
ORIGIN: From dia and hos; through which thing, i.e. Consequently.

DEFINITION: to journey through, go about.
ORIGIN: From dia and hodeuo; to travel through.

DEFINITION: Dionysius, an Athenian.
ORIGIN: From Dionusos (Bacchus); reveller; Dionysius, an Athenian.

DEFINITION: wherefore (emphatically), for which very reason.
ORIGIN: From dio and per; on which very account.

DEFINITION: fallen from the sky.
ORIGIN: From the alternate of Zeus and the alternate of pipto; sky-fallen (i.e. An aerolite).

DEFINITION: amendment, improvement, reformation.
ORIGIN: From a compound of dia and a derivative of orthos, meaning to straighten thoroughly; rectification, i.e. (specially) the Messianic restauration.

DEFINITION: to dig through (as of breaking into a house).
ORIGIN: From dia and orusso; to penetrate burglariously.

DEFINITION: the Dioscuri, Castor and Pollux, sons of Zeus and Leda, and patrons of sailors.
ORIGIN: From the alternate of Zeus and a form of the base of korasion; sons of Jupiter, i.e. The twins Dioscuri.

DEFINITION: on the very account that, because, inasmuch as.
ORIGIN: From dia and hoti; on the very account that, or inasmuch as.

DEFINITION: "cherished by Zeus", Diotrephes, an opponent of the apostle John.
ORIGIN: From the alternate of Zeus and trepho; Jove-nourished; Diotrephes, an opponent of Christianity.

DEFINITION: double, two-fold.
ORIGIN: From dis and (probably) the base of pleion; two-fold.

DEFINITION: to double, render back double.
ORIGIN: From diplous; to render two-fold.

DEFINITION: twice, entirely, utterly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from duo; twice.

DEFINITION: to waver, doubt, hesitate.
ORIGIN: From dis; properly, to duplicate, i.e. (mentally) to waver (in opinion).

DEFINITION: (lit: twain-mouthed; hence: of a sword, as a drinker of blood), two-edged.
ORIGIN: From dis and stoma; double-edged.

DEFINITION: two thousand.
ORIGIN: From dis and chilioi; two thousand.

DEFINITION: to strain thoroughly, strain out.
ORIGIN: From dia and hulizo hoo-lid'-zo (to filter); to strain out.

DEFINITION: to cut asunder; met: to set at variance, make to be hostile.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of dis; to make apart, i.e. Sunder (figuratively, alienate).

DEFINITION: division, dissension, standing apart.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of dis and stasis; disunion, i.e. (figuratively) dissension.

DEFINITION: to cut in two, perhaps: scourge severely.
ORIGIN: From a compound of a derivative of dis and a derivative of temno (to cut); to bisect, i.e. (by extension) to flog severely.

DEFINITION: to thirst for, desire earnestly.
ORIGIN: From a variation of dipsos; to thirst for (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: thirst.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; thirst.

DEFINITION: (lit: of two souls, of two selves), double-minded, wavering.
ORIGIN: From dis and psuche; two-spirited, i.e. Vacillating (in opinion or purpose).

DEFINITION: chase, pursuit; persecution.
ORIGIN: From dioko; persecution.

DEFINITION: a persecutor.
ORIGIN: From dioko; a persecutor.

DEFINITION: to put to flight, pursue, by implication to persecute.
ORIGIN: A prolonged (and causative) form of a primary verb dio (to flee; compare the base of deilos and diakonos); to pursue (literally or figuratively); by implication, to persecute.
USAGE: ensue, follow (after), given to, (suffer) persecute(-ion), press forward.

DEFINITION: an opinion, (a public) decree.
ORIGIN: From the base of dokeo; a law (civil, ceremonial or ecclesiastical).

DEFINITION: to subject to regulations, decree; mid: to subject myself to regulations, be decree-ridden.
ORIGIN: From dogma; to prescribe by statute, i.e. (reflexively) to submit to, ceremonially rule.

DEFINITION: to think, seem, appear, it seems.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary verb, doko dok'-o (used only in an alternate in certain tenses; compare the base of deiknuo) of the same meaning; to think; by implication, to seem (truthfully or uncertainly).
USAGE: be accounted, (of own) please(-ure), be of reputation, seem (good), suppose, think, trow.

DEFINITION: to put to the test, prove, examine; to distinguish by testing, approve after testing; to be fit.
ORIGIN: From dokimos; to test (literally or figuratively); by implication, to approve.
USAGE: allow, discern, examine, X like, (ap-)prove, try.

DEFINITION: (the process or result of) trial, proving, approval.
ORIGIN: From the same as dokimos; test (abstractly or concretely); by implication, trustiness.

DEFINITION: a test, trial, what is genuine.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of dokime; a testing; by implication, trustworthiness.

DEFINITION: approved, acceptable, tried.
ORIGIN: From dokeo; properly, acceptable (current after assayal), i.e. Approved.

DEFINITION: a beam or spar of timber.
ORIGIN: From dechomai (through the idea of holding up); a stick of timber.

DEFINITION: treacherous, deceitful, fraudulent.
ORIGIN: From dolos; guileful.

DEFINITION: to act deceitfully, deceive, use fraud.
ORIGIN: From dolios; to be guileful.

DEFINITION: deceit, guile, treachery.
ORIGIN: From an obsolete primary verb, dello (probably meaning to decoy; compare deleazo); a trick (bait), i.e. (figuratively) wile.

DEFINITION: to adulterate, corrupt, ensnare.
ORIGIN: From dolos; to ensnare, i.e. (figuratively) adulterate.

DEFINITION: a gift, present.
ORIGIN: From the base of didomi; a present.

DEFINITION: honor, renown; glory, an especially divine quality, the unspoken manifestation of God, splendor.
ORIGIN: From the base of dokeo; glory (as very apparent), in a wide application (literal or figurative, objective or subjective).

DEFINITION: to render or esteem glorious (in a wide application).
ORIGIN: From doxa; to render (or esteem) glorious (in a wide application).
USAGE: (make) glorify(-ious), full of (have) glory, honour, magnify.

DEFINITION: "gazelle" (an animal with large bright eyes), Dorcas, a Christian woman.
ORIGIN: Gazelle; Dorcas, a Christian woman.

DEFINITION: the act of giving, a gift.
ORIGIN: From the base of didomi; a giving; by implication, (concretely) a gift.

DEFINITION: a giver.
ORIGIN: From the base of didomi; a giver.

DEFINITION: to bring into subjection, enslave, treat as a slave.
ORIGIN: From a presumed compound of doulos and ago; to be a slave-driver, i.e. To enslave (figuratively, subdue).

DEFINITION: slavery, bondage.
ORIGIN: From douleuo; slavery (ceremonially or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to be a slave, be subject to, obey, be devoted.
ORIGIN: From doulos; to be a slave to (literal or figurative, involuntary or voluntary).

DEFINITION: a female slave, bonds-maid.
ORIGIN: Feminine of doulos; a female slave (involuntarily or voluntarily).

DEFINITION: slavish, servile.
ORIGIN: Neuter of doulos; subservient.

DEFINITION: (a) (as adj.) enslaved, (b) (as noun) a (male) slave.
ORIGIN: From deo; a slave (literal or figurative, involuntary or voluntary; frequently, therefore in a qualified sense of subjection or subserviency).

DEFINITION: to enslave, bring under subjection.
ORIGIN: From doulos; to enslave (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: bring into (be under) bondage, X given, become (make) servant.

DEFINITION: a feast, banquet, reception.
ORIGIN: From dechomai; a reception, i.e. Convivial entertainment.

DEFINITION: a dragon or huge serpent; met: Satan.
ORIGIN: Probably from an alternate form of derkomai (to look); a fabulous kind of serpent (perhaps as supposed to fascinate).

DEFINITION: to take hold of, grasp, catch.
ORIGIN: Perhaps akin to the base of drakon (through the idea of capturing); to grasp, i.e. (figuratively) entrap.

DEFINITION: as much as one can hold in the hand, a drachma (a Greek coin made of silver).
ORIGIN: From drassomai; a drachma or (silver) coin (as handled).

DEFINITION: a sickle, a pruning hook.
ORIGIN: From drepo (to pluck); a gathering hook (especially for harvesting).

DEFINITION: a running, course, career, race.
ORIGIN: From the alternate of trecho; a race, i.e. (figuratively) career.

DEFINITION: Drusilla (born A.D. 39), daughter of Herod Agrippa to.
ORIGIN: A feminine diminutive of Drusus (a Roman name); Drusilla, a member of the Herodian family.

DEFINITION: (a) to be powerful, have (the) power, (b) to be able, to can.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; to be able or possible.
USAGE: be able, can (do, + -not), could, may, might, be possible, be of power.

DEFINITION: (a) physical power, force, might, ability, efficacy, energy, meaning (b) plur: powerful deeds, deeds showing (physical) power, marvelous works.
ORIGIN: From dunamai; force (literally or figuratively); specially, miraculous power (usually by implication, a miracle itself).
USAGE: ability, abundance, meaning, might(-ily, -y, -y deed), (worker of) miracle(-s), power, strength, violence, mighty (wonderful) work.

DEFINITION: to empower, fill with power, strengthen.
ORIGIN: From dunamis; to enable.

DEFINITION: (lit: a man who rules by force), a ruler, potentate; also: courtier, member of the court.
ORIGIN: From dunamai; a ruler or officer.

DEFINITION: to be powerful, have power, be able, be mighty.
ORIGIN: From dunatos; to be efficient (figuratively).

DEFINITION: (a) of persons: powerful, able, (b) of things: possible.
ORIGIN: From dunamai; powerful or capable (literally or figuratively); neuter possible.
USAGE: able, could, (that is) mighty (man), possible, power, strong.

DEFINITION: to sink, set (as the sun).
ORIGIN: Or dumi doo'-mee prolonged forms of an obsolete primary duo doo'-o (to sink) to go "down".

DEFINITION: two.
ORIGIN: A primary numeral; "two".

DEFINITION: like un- or mis- (as in unrest, misjudge), nullifies good sense or increases bad sense of a word.
ORIGIN: A primary inseparable particle of uncertain derivation; used only in composition as a prefix; hard, i.e. With difficulty.

DEFINITION: difficult to carry, oppressive.
ORIGIN: From dus- and a derivative of bastazo; oppressive.

DEFINITION: dysentery.
ORIGIN: From dus- and a comparative of entos (meaning a bowel); a "dysentery".

DEFINITION: difficult to interpret, hard to be understood.
ORIGIN: From dus- and a presumed derivative of hermeneuo; difficult of explanation.

DEFINITION: difficult, hard; of persons: hard to please.
ORIGIN: From dus- and kolon (food); properly, fastidious about eating (peevish), i.e. (genitive case) impracticable.

DEFINITION: with difficulty, hardly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from duskolos; impracticably.

DEFINITION: a setting (as of the sun), by implication (the) western (region).
ORIGIN: From duno; the sun-set, i.e. (by implication) the western region.

DEFINITION: hard to understand.
ORIGIN: From dus- and a derivative of noieo; difficult of perception.

DEFINITION: evil report, defamation, words of ill omen.
ORIGIN: From a compound of dus- and pheme; defamation.

DEFINITION: twelve; the usual way in which the Twelve apostles of Jesus are referred to.
ORIGIN: From duo and deka; two and ten, i.e. A dozen.

DEFINITION: twelfth.
ORIGIN: From dodeka; twelfth.

DEFINITION: the Twelve Tribes (of Israel).
ORIGIN: From dodeka and phule; the commonwealth of Israel.

DEFINITION: the roof (of a house), the top of the house.
ORIGIN: From demo (to build); properly, an edifice, i.e. (specially) a roof.

DEFINITION: a (free) gift, a gift (without repayment).
ORIGIN: From doron; a gratuity.

DEFINITION: as a free gift, without payment, freely.
ORIGIN: Accusative case of dorea as adverb; gratuitously (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: without a cause, freely, for naught, in vain.

DEFINITION: to give, present, bestow.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from doron; to bestow gratuitously.

DEFINITION: a gift, a bestowment.
ORIGIN: From doreomai; a bestowment.

DEFINITION: a gift, present, a sacrifice.
ORIGIN: A present; specially, a sacrifice.

DEFINITION: an interjection, Ho! Ah! Ha! It is supposed to imply surprise, fear and indignation.
ORIGIN: Apparent imperative of eao; properly, let it be, i.e. (as interjection) aha!.

DEFINITION: if.
ORIGIN: From ei and an; a conditional particle; in case that, provided, etc.; often used in connection with other particles to denote indefiniteness or uncertainty.
USAGE: before, but, except, (and) if, (if) so, (what-, whither-)soever, though, when (-soever), whether (or), to whom, (who-)so(-ever). See me.

DEFINITION: of himself, herself, itself.
ORIGIN: From a reflexive pronoun otherwise obsolete and the genitive case (dative case or accusative case) of autos; him- (her-, it-, them-, also (in conjunction with the personal pronoun of the other persons) my-, thy-, our-, your-) self (selves), etc..
USAGE: alone, her (own, -self), (he) himself, his (own), itself, one (to) another, our (thine) own(-selves), + that she had, their (own, own selves), (of) them(-selves), they, thyself, you, your (own, own conceits, own selves, -selves).

DEFINITION: to allow, permit, let alone, leave.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; to let be, i.e. Permit or leave alone.
USAGE: commit, leave, let (alone), suffer. See also ea.

DEFINITION: seventy.
ORIGIN: From hebdomos and a modified form of deka; seventy.

DEFINITION: seventy times.
ORIGIN: Multiple adverb from hebdomekonta; seventy times.

DEFINITION: seventh.
ORIGIN: Ordinal from hepta; seventh.

DEFINITION: Eber, father of Peleg and son of Shelah.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Eber); Eber, a patriarch.

DEFINITION: Hebrew, the Jewish language.
ORIGIN: From Eber; Hebraic or the Jewish language.

DEFINITION: a Hebrew, particularly one who speaks Hebrew (Aramaic).
ORIGIN: From Eber; a Hebræan (i.e. Hebrew) or Jew.

DEFINITION: the Hebrew language, or rather: Aramaic.
ORIGIN: From Eber; the Hebraistic (Hebrew) or Jewish (Chaldee) language.

DEFINITION: in the Hebrew, or rather, in the Aramaic dialect.
ORIGIN: Adverb from Hebrais; Hebraistically or in the Jewish (Chaldee) language.

DEFINITION: trans: to bring near; intrans: to come near, approach.
ORIGIN: From eggus; to make near, i.e. (reflexively) approach.
USAGE: approach, be at hand, come (draw) near, be (come, draw) nigh.

DEFINITION: to inscribe, to enter in a register.
ORIGIN: From en and grapho; to "engrave", i.e. Inscribe.

DEFINITION: under good security (adjective), guarantee (noun).
ORIGIN: From en and guion (a limb); pledged (as if articulated by a member), i.e. A bondsman.

DEFINITION: near (in place or time).
ORIGIN: From a primary verb agcho (to squeeze or throttle; akin to the base of agkale); near (literally or figuratively, of place or time).
USAGE: from, at hand, near, nigh (at hand, unto), ready.

DEFINITION: nearer.
ORIGIN: Neuter of the comparative of eggus; nearer.

DEFINITION: (a) to wake, arouse, (b) to raise up.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to the base of agora (through the idea of collecting one's faculties); to waken (transitively or intransitively), i.e. Rouse (literally, from sleep, from sitting or lying, from disease, from death; or figuratively, from obscurity, inactivity, ruins, nonexistence).
USAGE: awake, lift (up), raise (again, up), rear up, (a-)rise (again, up), stand, take up.

DEFINITION: a rousing, a rising (from death).
ORIGIN: From egeiro; a resurgence (from death).

DEFINITION: hired to lie in wait, lying in wait.
ORIGIN: From en and a derivative of kathiemi; subinduced, i.e. Surreptitiously suborned as a lier-in-wait.

DEFINITION: a renewal, dedication; the feast of rededication.
ORIGIN: Neuter plural of a presumed compound from en and kainos; innovatives, i.e. (specially) renewal (of religious services after the Antiochian interruption).

DEFINITION: to consecrate, dedicate, renovate.
ORIGIN: From egkainia; to renew, i.e. Inaugurate.

DEFINITION: to call in (as a debt or demand), bring to account.
ORIGIN: From en and kaleo; to call in (as a debt or demand), i.e. Bring to account (charge, criminate, etc.).
USAGE: accuse, call in question, implead, lay to the charge.

DEFINITION: to leave behind, (in a good sense) let remain over or (in a bad sense) desert.
ORIGIN: From en and kataleipo; to leave behind in some place, i.e. (in a good sense) let remain over, or (in a bad sense) to desert.

DEFINITION: to settle down in (a place), reside.
ORIGIN: From en and katoikeo; to settle down in a place, i.e. Reside.

DEFINITION: to take pride in, glory in.
ORIGIN: From en and a derivative of kentron; to prick in, i.e. Ingraft.

DEFINITION: an accusation, charge.
ORIGIN: From egkaleo; an accusation, i.e. Offence alleged.
USAGE: crime laid against, laid to charge.

DEFINITION: to clothe myself (originally: to tie round in a knot).
ORIGIN: Middle voice from en and komboo (to gird); to engirdle oneself (for labor), i.e. Figuratively (the apron as being a badge of servitude) to wear (in token of mutual deference).

DEFINITION: an incision, a cutting, break; met: an interruption, a hindrance.
ORIGIN: From egkopto; a hindrance.

DEFINITION: to cut into, impede, detain.
ORIGIN: From en and kopto; to cut into, i.e. (figuratively) impede, detain.

DEFINITION: self-mastery, self-restraint, self-control, continence.
ORIGIN: From egkrates; self-control (especially continence).

DEFINITION: to exercise self-control, be continent.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from egkrates; to exercise self-restraint (in diet and chastity).

DEFINITION: strong, master of, self-controlled.
ORIGIN: From en and kratos; strong in a thing (masterful), i.e. (figuratively and reflexively) self-controlled (in appetite, etc.).

DEFINITION: to judge in, to reckon among.
ORIGIN: From en and krino; to judge in, i.e. Count among.

DEFINITION: to hide in, mix with.
ORIGIN: From en and krupto; to conceal in, i.e. Incorporate with.

DEFINITION: with child, pregnant.
ORIGIN: From en and the base of kuma; swelling inside, i.e. Pregnant.

DEFINITION: to rub in, anoint.
ORIGIN: From en and chrio; to rub in (oil), i.e. Besmear.

DEFINITION: I (only expressed when emphatic).
ORIGIN: A primary pronoun of the first person I (only expressed when emphatic).
USAGE: I, me. For the other cases and the plural see eme, emoi, emou, hemas, hemeis, hemin, hemon, etc.

DEFINITION: to dash to the ground, level with the ground.
ORIGIN: From edaphos; to raze.

DEFINITION: the base, ground, bottom.
ORIGIN: From the base of hedraios; a basis (bottom), i.e. The soil.

DEFINITION: sitting, seated; steadfast, firm.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of hezomai (to sit); sedentary, i.e. (by implication) immovable.

DEFINITION: a foundation, stay, support.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of hedraios; a support, i.e. (figuratively) basis.

DEFINITION: Hezekiah, son of Ahaz, father of Manasseh, and king of Judah (727-686 [?] B.C.).
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Chizqiyah); Ezekias (i.e. Hezekeiah), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: self-willed (arbitrary and unwarranted) piety.
ORIGIN: From ethelo and threskeia; voluntary (arbitrary and unwarranted) piety, i.e. Sanctimony.

DEFINITION: to accustom, the established custom.
ORIGIN: From ethos; to accustom, i.e. (neuter passive participle) customary.

DEFINITION: an ethnarch, a governor (not king) of a province.
ORIGIN: From ethnos and arche; the governor (not king) of a district.

DEFINITION: pagan, heathen, gentile; subst: a Gentile, non-Jew.
ORIGIN: From ethnos; national ("ethnic"), i.e. (specially) a Gentile.

DEFINITION: in the manner of Gentiles, like the rest of the world.
ORIGIN: Adverb from ethnikos; as a Gentile.

DEFINITION: a race, people, nation; the nations, heathen world, Gentiles.
ORIGIN: Probably from etho; a race (as of the same habit), i.e. A tribe; specially, a foreign (non-Jewish) one (usually, by implication, pagan).

DEFINITION: custom, a usage (prescribed by habit or law).
ORIGIN: From etho; a usage (prescribed by habit or law).

DEFINITION: to be accustomed, custom, what was customary.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to be used (by habit or conventionality); neuter perfect participle usage.

DEFINITION: forasmuch as, if, that.
ORIGIN: A primary particle of conditionality; if, whether, that, etc..
USAGE: forasmuch as, if, that, (al-)though, whether. Often used in connection or composition with other particles, especially as in eige, ei de me(ge), ei kai, ei me, ei me ti, ei per, ei pos, ei tis, ek. See also ean.

DEFINITION: are, be.
ORIGIN: Second person singular present of eimi; thou art.

DEFINITION: if indeed, seeing that, unless, with negative otherwise.
ORIGIN: From ei and ge; if indeed, seeing that, unless, (with negative) otherwise.

DEFINITION: but if not, else, otherwise.
ORIGIN: From ei, de, and me (sometimes with ge added); but if not.

DEFINITION: visible form, shape, appearance, outward show, kind, species, class.
ORIGIN: From eido; a view, i.e. Form (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: be aware, behold, consider, perceive.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; used only in certain past tenses, the others being borrowed from the equivalent optanomai and horao; properly, to see (literally or figuratively); by implication, (in the perfect tense only) to know.
USAGE: be aware, behold, X can (+ not tell), consider, (have) know(-ledge), look (on), perceive, see, be sure, tell, understand, wish, wot. Compare optanomai.

DEFINITION: a temple for (containing) an image (an idol).
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of eidolon; an image-fane.

DEFINITION: (of meat), sacrificed to an image (or an idol).
ORIGIN: Neuter of a compound of eidolon and a presumed derivative of thuo; an image-sacrifice, i.e. Part of an idolatrous offering.
USAGE: (meat, thing that is) offered (in sacrifice, sacrificed) to (unto) idols.

DEFINITION: service (worship) of an image (an idol).
ORIGIN: From eidolon and latreia; image-worship (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a server (worshipper) of an image (an idol).
ORIGIN: From eidolon and the base of latreuo; an image- (servant or) worshipper (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: an image (for worship), by implication a false god.
ORIGIN: From eidos; an image (i.e. For worship); by implication, a heathen god, or (plural) the worship of such.

DEFINITION: should be, was, were.
ORIGIN: Optative (i.e. English subjunctive) present of eimi (including the other person); might (could, would, or should) be.
USAGE: mean, + perish, should be, was, were.

DEFINITION: if that, though.
ORIGIN: From ei and kai; if also (or even).

DEFINITION: without a cause, purpose; purposelessly, in vain, for nothing.
ORIGIN: Probably from eiko (through the idea of failure); idly, i.e. Without reason (or effect).

DEFINITION: twenty.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a score.

DEFINITION: to give way, yield, submit.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; properly, to be weak, i.e. Yield.

DEFINITION: to be like, resemble.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb (perhaps akin to eiko through the idea of faintness as a copy); to resemble.

DEFINITION: an image, statue, representation.
ORIGIN: From eiko; a likeness, i.e. (literally) statue, profile, or (figuratively) representation, resemblance.

DEFINITION: clearness, by implication purity, sincerity.
ORIGIN: From eilikrines; clearness, i.e. (by implication) purity (figuratively).

DEFINITION: (originally: unmixed), pure, uncontaminated, sincere.
ORIGIN: From heile (the sun's ray) and krino; judged by sunlight, i.e. Tested as genuine (figuratively).

DEFINITION: roll together.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary but defective verb heilo (of the same meaning); to coil or wrap.

DEFINITION: but, except that, if not, save only.
ORIGIN: From ei and me; if not.
USAGE: but, except (that), if not, more than, save (only) that, saving, till.

DEFINITION: if not somewhat.
ORIGIN: From ei me and the neuter of tis; if not somewhat.

DEFINITION: I exist, I am.
ORIGIN: The first person singular present indicative; a prolonged form of a primary and defective verb; I exist (used only when emphatic).
USAGE: am, have been, X it is I, was. See also ei, eien, einai, heis kath heis, en, esomai, esmen, este, esti, kerdos, isthi, o.

DEFINITION: am, was, come, is, there is, to be, was.
ORIGIN: Present infinitive from eimi; to exist.
USAGE: am, was. Come, is, X lust after, X please well, there is, to be, was.

DEFINITION: if indeed, if so.
ORIGIN: From ei and per; if perhaps.

DEFINITION: if by any means, if somehow.
ORIGIN: From ei and pos; if somehow.

DEFINITION: to be peaceful, keep the peace, be at peace.
ORIGIN: From eirene; to be (act) peaceful.
USAGE: be at (have, live in) peace, live peaceably.

DEFINITION: peace, peace of mind; invocation of peace a common Jewish farewell, in the Hebraistic sense of the health (welfare) of an individual.
ORIGIN: Probably from a primary verb eiro (to join); peace (literally or figuratively); by implication, prosperity.
USAGE: one, peace, quietness, rest, + set at one again.

DEFINITION: peaceable, disposed to peace, profitable.
ORIGIN: From eirene; pacific; by implication, salutary.

DEFINITION: to make peace, reconcile.
ORIGIN: From eirenopoios; to be a peace-maker, i.e. (figuratively) to harmonize.

DEFINITION: pacific, loving peace, a peace-maker.
ORIGIN: From eirenopoios and poieo; pacificatory, i.e. (subjectively) peaceable.

DEFINITION: to or into (indicating the point reached or entered, of place, time, purpose, result).
ORIGIN: A primary preposition; to or into (indicating the point reached or entered), of place, time, or (figuratively) purpose (result, etc.); also in adverbial phrases.
USAGE: (abundant-)ly, against, among, as, at, (back-)ward, before, by, concerning, + continual, + far more exceeding, for (intent, purpose), fore, + forth, in (among, at, unto, -so much that, -to), to the intent that, + of one mind, + never, of, (up-)on, + perish, + set at one again, (so) that, therefore(-unto), throughout, til, to (be, the end, -ward), (here-)until(-to),...ward, (where-)fore, with. Often used in composition with the same general import, but only with verbs (etc.) Expressing motion (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: one.
ORIGIN: (including the neuter (etc.) Hen); a primary numeral; one.
USAGE: a(-n, -ny, certain), + abundantly, man, one (another), only, other, some. See also heis kath heis, medeis, mia, oudeis.

DEFINITION: to lead in, bring in, introduce.
ORIGIN: From eis and ago; to introduce (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: bring in(-to), (+ was to) lead into.

DEFINITION: to hear, listen to, heed.
ORIGIN: From eis and akouo; to listen to.

DEFINITION: to admit, to receive (into one's favor).
ORIGIN: From eis and dechomai; to take into one's favor.

DEFINITION: to go in, enter (originally: to shall go in).
ORIGIN: From eis and eimi (to go); to enter.

DEFINITION: to go in, come in, enter.
ORIGIN: From eis and erchomai; to enter (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: X arise, come (in, into), enter in(-to), go in (through).

DEFINITION: agree, are, be, were.
ORIGIN: 3d person plural present indicative of eimi; they are.
USAGE: agree, are, be, dure, X is, were.

DEFINITION: one by one.
ORIGIN: From heis repeated with kata inserted; severally.

DEFINITION: to call in (to house), invite.
ORIGIN: From eis and kaleo; to invite in.

DEFINITION: an entrance, a means or place of entering.
ORIGIN: From eis and hodos; an entrance (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to leap into, rush into.
ORIGIN: From eis and pedao (to leap); to rush in.

DEFINITION: to journey in(to), to go in(to), enter, intervene.
ORIGIN: From eis and poreuomai; to enter (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to run in, run into.
ORIGIN: From eis and trecho; to hasten inward.

DEFINITION: to lead into, bring in, announce.
ORIGIN: From eis and phero; to carry inward (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: then, thereafter, next (marking a fresh stage); therefore, then, furthermore.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a particle of succession (in time or logical enumeration), then, moreover.
USAGE: after that(-ward), furthermore, then. See also epeita.

DEFINITION: if, whether, or.
ORIGIN: From ei and te; if too.

DEFINITION: he that, if a man, whether any, whosoever.
ORIGIN: From ei and tis; if any.
USAGE: he that, if a(-ny) man('s thing, from any, ought), whether any, whosoever.

DEFINITION: from out, out from among, from, suggesting from the interior outwards.
ORIGIN: A primary preposition denoting origin (the point whence action or motion proceeds), from, out (of place, time, or cause; literal or figurative; direct or remote).
USAGE: after, among, X are, at, betwixt(-yond), by (the means of), exceedingly, (+ abundantly above), for(- th), from (among, forth, up), + grudgingly, + heartily, X heavenly, X hereby, + very highly, in,...ly, (because, by reason) of, off (from), on, out among (from, of), over, since, X thenceforth, through, X unto, X vehemently, with(-out). Often used in composition, with the same general import; often of completion.

DEFINITION: each (of more than two), every one.
ORIGIN: As if a superlative of hekas (afar); each or every.
USAGE: any, both, each (one), every (man, one, woman), particularly.

DEFINITION: at every time, always.
ORIGIN: As if from hekastos and tote; at every time.

DEFINITION: one hundred.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a hundred.

DEFINITION: a hundred years old.
ORIGIN: From hekaton and etos; centenarian.

DEFINITION: a hundred times.
ORIGIN: From hekaton and a presumed derivative of plasso; a hundred times.

DEFINITION: a centurion, a captain of one hundred men.
ORIGIN: Or hekatontarchos hek-at-on'-tar-khos; from hekaton and archo; the captain of one hundred men.

DEFINITION: to throw (cast, put) out; to banish; to bring forth, produce.
ORIGIN: From ek and ballo; to eject (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: bring forth, cast (forth, out), drive (out), expel, leave, pluck (pull, take, thrust) out, put forth (out), send away (forth, out).

DEFINITION: (a) a way out, escape, (b) result, issue.
ORIGIN: From a compound of ek and the base of basis (meaning to go out); an exit (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a throwing out, a jettisoning of cargo to lighten a ship.
ORIGIN: From ekballo; ejection, i.e. (specially) a throwing overboard of the cargo.

DEFINITION: to give in marriage, marry.
ORIGIN: From ek and a form of gamisko (compare ekgamisko); to marry off a daughter.

DEFINITION: to give in marriage.
ORIGIN: From ek and gamisko; the same as ekgamizo.

DEFINITION: born of, a descendant, a grandchild.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of a compound of ek and ginomai; a descendant, i.e. (specially) grandchild.

DEFINITION: to spend (give out) completely, exhaust.
ORIGIN: From ek and dapanao; to expend (wholly), i.e. (figuratively) exhaust.

DEFINITION: to take or receive, by implication to await, expect.
ORIGIN: From ek and dechomai; to accept from some source, i.e. (by implication) to await.

DEFINITION: perfectly evident, manifest.
ORIGIN: From ek and delos; wholly evident.

DEFINITION: to be away from home, absent.
ORIGIN: From a compound of ek and demos; to emigrate, i.e. (figuratively) vacate or quit.

DEFINITION: to give out, let; middle: to let out for own advantage.
ORIGIN: From ek and didomi; to give forth, i.e. (specially) to lease.

DEFINITION: to narrate at length, declare.
ORIGIN: From ek and a compound of dia and hegeomai; to narrate through wholly.

DEFINITION: to give justice over, defend, avenge, vindicate.
ORIGIN: From ekdikos; to vindicate, retaliate, punish.

DEFINITION: (a) a defense, avenging, vindication, vengeance, (b) full (complete) punishment.
ORIGIN: From ekdikeo; vindication, retribution.

DEFINITION: avenging, subst: an avenger (the word occurs frequently in the sense of a special advocate [champion] of a city).
ORIGIN: From ek and dike; carrying justice out, i.e. A punisher.

DEFINITION: to persecute, expel by persecuting, drive out, vex, harass.
ORIGIN: From ek and dioko; to pursue out, i.e. Expel or persecute implacably.

DEFINITION: given out or over, surrendered.
ORIGIN: From ek and a derivative of didomi; given out or over, i.e. Surrendered.

DEFINITION: a receiving from, expectation.
ORIGIN: From ekdechomai; expectation.

DEFINITION: to put off, take off, strip off, with acc. of person or garment or both.
ORIGIN: From ek and the base of duno; to cause to sink out of, i.e. (specially as of clothing) to divest.

DEFINITION: (a) there, yonder, in that place, (b) thither, there.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; there; by extension, thither.

DEFINITION: thence, from that place.
ORIGIN: From ekei; thence.

DEFINITION: that one (or neut. that thing), often intensified by the article preceding.
ORIGIN: From ekei; that one (or (neuter) thing); often intensified by the article prefixed.
USAGE: he, it, the other (same), selfsame, that (same, very), X their, X them, they, this, those. See also houtos.

DEFINITION: thither, there, at that place.
ORIGIN: From ekei; thither.

DEFINITION: to seek out, seek out after, require.
ORIGIN: From ek and zeteo; to search out, i.e. (figuratively)investigate, crave, demand, (by Hebraism) worship.

DEFINITION: to be greatly astonished, be awe-struck.
ORIGIN: From ekthambos; to astonish utterly.

DEFINITION: full of astonishment, amazed.
ORIGIN: From ek and thambos; utterly astounded.

DEFINITION: cast out, exposed (to the elements), abandoned.
ORIGIN: From ek and a derivative of tithemi; put out, i.e. Exposed to perish.

DEFINITION: to clean (cleanse) out, clean thoroughly.
ORIGIN: From ek and kathairo; to cleanse thoroughly.

DEFINITION: to kindle, to be inflamed.
ORIGIN: From ek and kaio; to inflame deeply.

DEFINITION: to be faint, be weary.
ORIGIN: From ek and kakos; to be (bad or) weak, i.e. (by implication) to fail (in heart).

DEFINITION: to pierce through (or deeply), transfix.
ORIGIN: From ek and the base of kentron; to transfix.

DEFINITION: to break off.
ORIGIN: From ek and klao; to exscind.

DEFINITION: to shut out, exclude, separate.
ORIGIN: From ek and kleio; to shut out (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: an assembly, congregation, church; the Church, the whole body of Christian believers.
ORIGIN: From a compound of ek and a derivative of kaleo; a calling out, i.e. (concretely) a popular meeting, especially a religious congregation (Jewish synagogue, or Christian community of members on earth or saints in heaven or both).

DEFINITION: (lit: to bend away from), to fall away from, turn away (from), deviate.
ORIGIN: From ek and klino; to deviate, i.e. (absolutely) to shun (literally or figuratively), or (relatively) to decline (from piety).
USAGE: avoid, eschew, go out of the way.

DEFINITION: to swim out (of the water).
ORIGIN: From ek and kolumbao; to escape by swimming.

DEFINITION: to carry out (of the city gate for burial).
ORIGIN: From ek and komizo; to bear forth (to burial).

DEFINITION: to cut off, cut down, cut out, to frustrate.
ORIGIN: From ek and kopto; to exscind; figuratively, to frustrate.
USAGE: cut down (off, out), hew down, hinder.

DEFINITION: to hang from, hang upon (the lips of a speaker), to listen closely.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from ek and kremannumi; to hang upon the lips of a speaker, i.e. Listen closely.

DEFINITION: to speak out, disclose, divulge.
ORIGIN: From ek and laleo; to divulge.

DEFINITION: to shine forth (out).
ORIGIN: From ek and lampo; to be resplendent.

DEFINITION: to forget entirely, make to forget.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from ek and lanthano; to be utterly oblivious of.

DEFINITION: to pick out for myself, choose, elect, select.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from ek and lego (in its primary sense); to select.

DEFINITION: to leave out, leave off, by implication to cease.
