ORIGIN: From ek and leipo; to omit, i.e. (by implication) cease (die).

DEFINITION: chosen out, elect, choice, select, sometimes as subst: of those chosen out by God for the rendering of special service to Him (of the Hebrew race, particular Hebrews, the Messiah, and the Christians).
ORIGIN: From eklegomai; select; by implication, favorite.

DEFINITION: a choosing out, selecting, choice (by God).
ORIGIN: From eklegomai; (divine) selection (abstractly or concretely).

DEFINITION: to loose, release, unloose (as a bow-string), relax, enfeeble; pass: to be faint, grow weary.
ORIGIN: From ek and luo; to relax (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to knead out, by anal. to wipe dry.
ORIGIN: From ek and the base of massaomai; to knead out, i.e. (by analogy) to wipe dry.

DEFINITION: to hold up the nose in derision of.
ORIGIN: From ek and mukterizo; to sneer outright at.

DEFINITION: to escape, get clear of, deviate, withdraw.
ORIGIN: From ek and neuo; (by analogy) to slip off, i.e. Quietly withdraw.

DEFINITION: to become sober (after drunkenness).
ORIGIN: From ek and nepho; (figuratively) to rouse (oneself) out of stupor.

DEFINITION: willing, with right good will, voluntary, spontaneous.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative from hekon; voluntariness.

DEFINITION: willingly, of one's own accord, spontaneously.
ORIGIN: Adverb from the same as hekousion; voluntarily.

DEFINITION: long ago, for a long while.
ORIGIN: From ek and palai; long ago, for a long while.
USAGE: of a long time, of old.

DEFINITION: to put to the test, make trial of, tempt, try.
ORIGIN: From ek and peirazo; to test thoroughly.

DEFINITION: to send out, send forth.
ORIGIN: From ek and pempo; to despatch.

DEFINITION: to spread (stretch) out, expand, extend.
ORIGIN: From ek and a form of petomai; to fly out, i.e. (by analogy) to extend.

DEFINITION: to fall out, fall off, fall away; hence in nautical language: to fall off from the straight course; of flowers: to fade away, wither away; to fall from, lose, forfeit; to be cast ashore; to be fruitless.
ORIGIN: From ek and pipto; to drop away; specially, be driven out of one's course; figuratively, to lose, become inefficient.
USAGE: be cast, fail, fall (away, off), take none effect.

DEFINITION: to sail out (of harbor), sail away.
ORIGIN: From ek and pleo; to depart by ship.

DEFINITION: to fill completely, fulfill in every particular (to the utmost), make good.
ORIGIN: From ek and pleroo; to accomplish entirely.

DEFINITION: a completion, fulfillment, accomplishment.
ORIGIN: From ekpleroo; completion.

DEFINITION: to strike with panic or shock; to amaze, astonish.
ORIGIN: From ek and plesso; to strike with astonishment.

DEFINITION: (lit: to breathe out), to breathe last, expire.
ORIGIN: From ek and pneo; to expire.

DEFINITION: to depart from; to be voided, cast out; to proceed from, be spoken; to burst forth, flow out, be spread abroad.
ORIGIN: From ek and poreuomai; to depart, be discharged, proceed, project.
USAGE: come (forth, out of), depart, go (forth, out), issue, proceed (out of).

DEFINITION: mid. to give oneself up to fornication.
ORIGIN: From ek and porneuo; to be utterly unchaste.

DEFINITION: to spit out, disdain, reject, loathe.
ORIGIN: From ek and ptuo; to spit out, i.e. (figuratively) spurn.

DEFINITION: to root out, pluck up by the roots.
ORIGIN: From ek and rhizoo; to uproot.
USAGE: pluck up by the root, root up.

DEFINITION: (properly: distraction or disturbance of mind caused by shock), bewilderment, amazement; a trance.
ORIGIN: From existemi; a displacement of the mind, i.e. Bewilderment, "ecstasy".

DEFINITION: to change for the worse, corrupt, pervert.
ORIGIN: From ek and strepho; to pervert (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to disturb (trouble) greatly (exceedingly).
ORIGIN: From ek and tarasso; to disturb wholly.

DEFINITION: to stretch out (forth), cast forth (as of an anchor), lay hands on.
ORIGIN: From ek and teino (to stretch); to extend.

DEFINITION: to complete, bring to completion, carry out, perform.
ORIGIN: From ek and teleo; to complete fully.

DEFINITION: earnestness, strenuousness, intentness, zeal.
ORIGIN: From ektenes; intentness.

DEFINITION: more earnestly.
ORIGIN: Neuter of the comparative of ektenes; more intently.

DEFINITION: intent, constant, strenuous, intense; met: earnest, zealous.
ORIGIN: From ekteino; intent.

DEFINITION: earnestly, strenuously, fervently.
ORIGIN: Adverb from ektenes; intently.

DEFINITION: (a) to put out or expose a child, (b) mid: to set forth, expound, explain.
ORIGIN: From ek and tithemi; to expose; figuratively, to declare.

DEFINITION: to shake off; mid: to shake off from myself.
ORIGIN: From ek and tinasso (to swing); to shake violently.

DEFINITION: (a) adv: (1) without, outside, beyond, (2) except, (3) subst: the outside, (b) prep: outside, apart from.
ORIGIN: From ek; the exterior; figuratively (as a preposition) aside from, besides.
USAGE: but, except(-ed), other than, out of, outside, unless, without.

DEFINITION: sixth.
ORIGIN: Ordinal from hex; sixth.

DEFINITION: (lit: to turn out from); mid. and pass: to turn aside (from the right road), wander, forsake, and with an object: to remove from myself, shun, avoid.
ORIGIN: From ek and the base of trope; to deflect, i.e. Turn away (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: avoid, turn (aside, out of the way).

DEFINITION: to bring up to maturity, to nourish.
ORIGIN: From ek and trepho; to rear up to maturity, i.e. (genitive case) to cherish or train.

DEFINITION: (strictly: a lifeless abortion) an untimely birth.
ORIGIN: From a comparative of ek and titrosko (to wound); a miscarriage (abortion), i.e. (by analogy) untimely birth.

DEFINITION: to bring out, carry out, sometimes out of the city for burial; to bring forth, bear, produce.
ORIGIN: From ek and phero; to bear out (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to flee out, away, escape; with an acc: to escape something.
ORIGIN: From ek and pheugo; to flee out.

DEFINITION: to frighten away, terrify.
ORIGIN: From ek and phobeo; to frighten utterly.

DEFINITION: greatly terrified, horrified.
ORIGIN: From ek and phobos.
USAGE: frightened out of one's wits; sore afraid, exceedingly fear.

DEFINITION: to put forth, cause to sprout.
ORIGIN: From ek and phuo; to sprout up.

DEFINITION: to pour out (liquid or solid); to shed, bestow liberally.
ORIGIN: Or (by variation) ekchuno ek-khoo'-no from ek and cheo (to pour); to pour forth; figuratively, to bestow.
USAGE: gush (pour) out, run greedily (out), shed (abroad, forth), spill.

DEFINITION: to go out, depart from, withdraw, flee.
ORIGIN: From ek and choreo; to depart.

DEFINITION: to expire, breathe one's last.
ORIGIN: From ek and psucho; to expire.

DEFINITION: of one's own free will, voluntary.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; voluntary.

DEFINITION: an olive tree; the Mount of Olives.
ORIGIN: Feminine of a presumed derivative from an obsolete primary; an olive (the tree or the fruit).

DEFINITION: olive oil, oil.
ORIGIN: Neuter of the same as elaia; olive oil.

DEFINITION: Olive-grove, Olive-yard, the mount Olivet.
ORIGIN: From elaia; an olive-orchard, i.e. (specially) the Mount of Olives.

DEFINITION: an Elamite, one of a people living to the north of the Persian Gulf in the southern part of Persia.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Eylam); an Elamite or Persian.

DEFINITION: less, smaller; poorer, inferior.
ORIGIN: Or elatton el-at-tone'; comparative of the same as elachistos; smaller (in size, quantity, age or quality).

DEFINITION: to have less, lack.
ORIGIN: From elasson; to diminish, i.e. Fall short.

DEFINITION: to make less (in rank or influence).
ORIGIN: From elasson; to lessen (in rank or influence).

DEFINITION: to drive or push (as wind, oars, or demoniacal power).
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary verb (obsolete except in certain tenses as an alternative of this) of uncertain affinity; to push (as wind, oars or dæmonical power).

DEFINITION: levity, fickleness, lightness.
ORIGIN: From elaphros; levity (figuratively), i.e. Fickleness.

DEFINITION: light, not burdensome.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to elauno and the base of elasson; light, i.e. Easy.

DEFINITION: least, smallest, but perhaps oftener in the weaker sense: very little, very small.
ORIGIN: Superlative of elachus (short); used as equivalent to mikros; least (in size, amount, dignity, etc.).

DEFINITION: the smallest, least important.
ORIGIN: Comparative of elachistos; far less.

DEFINITION: Eleazar, son of Eliud, and father of Matthan.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (El'azar); Eleazar, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: rebuke, reproof, refutation.
ORIGIN: From elegcho; refutation, i.e. Reproof.

DEFINITION: a proof, possibly: a persuasion; reproof.
ORIGIN: From elegcho; proof, conviction.

DEFINITION: (a) to reprove, rebuke, discipline, (b) to expose, show to be guilty.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; to confute, admonish.
USAGE: convict, convince, tell a fault, rebuke, reprove.

DEFINITION: merciful, pitiful, miserable.
ORIGIN: From eleos; pitiable.

DEFINITION: to have pity or mercy on, to show mercy.
ORIGIN: From eleos; to compassionate (by word or deed, specially, by divine grace).
USAGE: have compassion (pity on), have (obtain, receive, shew) mercy (on).

DEFINITION: abstr: alms-giving, charity; concr: alms, charity.
ORIGIN: From eleos; compassionateness, i.e. (as exercised towards the poor) beneficence, or (concretely) a benefaction.

DEFINITION: full of pity, merciful, compassionate.
ORIGIN: From eleeo; compassionate (actively).

DEFINITION: mercy, pity, compassion.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; compassion (human or divine, especially active).

DEFINITION: freedom, liberty, especially: a state of freedom from slavery.
ORIGIN: From eleutheros; freedom (legitimate or licentious, chiefly moral or ceremonial).

DEFINITION: free, not a slave or not under restraint.
ORIGIN: Probably from the alternate of erchomai; unrestrained (to go at pleasure), i.e. (as a citizen) not a slave (whether freeborn or manumitted), or (genitive case) exempt (from obligation or liability).

DEFINITION: to make free, to exempt (from liability).
ORIGIN: From eleutheros; to liberate, i.e. (figuratively) to exempt (from moral, ceremonial or mortal liability).

DEFINITION: a coming, arrival, advent.
ORIGIN: From the alternate of erchomai; an advent.

DEFINITION: made of ivory, subst: ivory.
ORIGIN: From elephas (an "elephant"); elephantine, i.e. (by implication) composed of ivory.

DEFINITION: Eliakim, son of Abiud and father of Azor; son of Melea and father of Jonam.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Elyaqiym'); Eliakim, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Eliezer, son of Joram and father of Joshua.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Eliy'ezer); Eliezer, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Eliud, son of Achim, and father of Eleazar.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('el and howd); God of majesty; Eliud, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Elizabeth, mother of John the Baptizer.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Eliysheba'); Elisabet, an Israelitess.

DEFINITION: Elisha, an Israelite prophet.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Eliysha'); Elissaeus, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: to roll, roll up, fold up.
ORIGIN: A form of heilisso; to coil or wrap.

DEFINITION: a (festering) sore, a wound.
ORIGIN: Probably from helkuo; an ulcer (as if drawn together).

DEFINITION: to afflict with sores; pass: to be afflicted with sores.
ORIGIN: From helkos; to cause to ulcerate, i.e. (passively) be ulcerous.

DEFINITION: to drag, draw, pull, persuade, unsheathe.
ORIGIN: Or helko hel'-ko; probably akin to haireomai; to drag (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: Hellas, Greece, a country of Europe.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; Hellas (or Greece), a country of Europe.

DEFINITION: a Hellene, the native word for a Greek; it is, however, a term wide enough to include all Greek-speaking (i.e. educated) non-Jews.
ORIGIN: From Hellas; a Hellen (Grecian) or inhabitant of Hellas; by extension a Greek-speaking person, especially a non-Jew.

DEFINITION: Hellenic, Grecian (in language).
ORIGIN: From Hellen; Hellenic, i.e. Grecian (in language).

DEFINITION: a Greek (i.e. Gentile) woman.
ORIGIN: Feminine of Hellen; a Grecian (i.e. Non-Jewish) woman.

DEFINITION: a Hellenist, Grecian Jew, a Greek-speaking Jew, that is one who can speak Greek only and not Hebrew (or Aramaic).
ORIGIN: From a derivative of Hellen; a Hellenist or Greek-speaking Jew.

DEFINITION: in the Greek language.
ORIGIN: Adverb from the same as Hellenistes; Hellenistically, i.e. In the Grecian language.

DEFINITION: to charge to, put to one's account, impute.
ORIGIN: From en and logos (in the sense of account); to reckon in, i.e. Attribute.

DEFINITION: Elmadam, father of Cosam, son of Er.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (perhaps for antiloidoreo); Elmodam, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: to hope, hope for, expect, trust.
ORIGIN: From elpis; to expect or confide.

DEFINITION: hope, expectation, trust, confidence.
ORIGIN: From a primary elpo (to anticipate, usually with pleasure); expectation (abstractly or concretely) or confidence.

DEFINITION: Elymas, the name of the sorcerer at Paphos.
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin; Elymas, a wizard.

DEFINITION: (Aramaic), God.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldean origin ('elahh with pronominal suffix) my God.

DEFINITION: of myself.
ORIGIN: Genitive case compound of emou and autos; of myself so likewise the dative case emautoi em-ow-to', and accusative case emauton em-ow-ton'.

DEFINITION: to step in; to go onboard a ship, embark.
ORIGIN: From en and the base of basis; to walk on, i.e. Embark (aboard a vessel), reach (a pool).
USAGE: come (get) into, enter (into), go (up) into, step in, take ship.

DEFINITION: to cast into, subject to.
ORIGIN: From en and ballo; to throw on, i.e. (figuratively) subject to (eternal punishment).

DEFINITION: to dip into.
ORIGIN: From en and bapto; to whelm on, i.e. Wet (a part of the person, etc.) By contact with a fluid.

DEFINITION: to enter, set foot on, intrude, pry into.
ORIGIN: From en and a presumed derivative of the base of basis; equivalent to embaino; to intrude on (figuratively).

DEFINITION: trans: to embark, put on board, step into.
ORIGIN: From en and bibazo (to mount; causative of embaino); to place on, i.e. Transfer (aboard a vessel).

DEFINITION: to look into (upon); met: to consider; to see clearly.
ORIGIN: From en and blepo; to look on, i.e. (relatively) to observe fixedly, or (absolutely) to discern clearly.
USAGE: behold, gaze up, look upon, (could) see.

DEFINITION: to snort (with the notion of coercion springing out of displeasure, anger, indignation, antagonism), express indignant displeasure with some one; to charge sternly.
ORIGIN: From en and brimaomai (to snort with anger); to have indignation on, i.e. (transitively) to blame, (intransitively) to sigh with chagrin, (specially) to sternly enjoin.

DEFINITION: I, me, myself.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of me; me.

DEFINITION: to vomit forth.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; to vomit.

DEFINITION: to be madly enraged with.
ORIGIN: From en and mainomai; to rave on, i.e. Rage at.

DEFINITION: Emmanuel, a Messianic title derived from Isaiah 7:14 = God with us.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Immanuw'el); God with us; Emmanuel, a name of Christ.

DEFINITION: Emmaus, a place 60 stadia (7.5 miles) west of Jer.
ORIGIN: Probably of Hebrew origin (compare yem); Emmaus, a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: to remain (abide) in, abide by, maintain, persevere in.
ORIGIN: From en and meno; to stay in the same place, i.e. (figuratively) persevere.

DEFINITION: Hamor, a man whose sons sold a field at Shechem to Jacob.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Chamowr); Emmor (i.e. Chamor), a Canaanite.

DEFINITION: I, me, mine, my.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of moi; to me.

DEFINITION: my, mine.
ORIGIN: From the oblique cases of ego (emoi, emou, eme); my.

DEFINITION: me, mine, my.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of mochthos; of me.

DEFINITION: mockery, scoffing, scorn.
ORIGIN: From empaizo; derision.

DEFINITION: to mock, ridicule.
ORIGIN: From en and paizo; to jeer at, i.e. Deride.

DEFINITION: a mocker, by implication a false teacher.
ORIGIN: From empaizo; a derider, i.e. (by implication) a false teacher.

DEFINITION: to walk about in a place, live among, be conversant with.
ORIGIN: From en and peripateo; to perambulate on a place, i.e. (figuratively) to be occupied among persons.

DEFINITION: to fill up, by implication to satisfy.
ORIGIN: Or empletho em-play'-tho; from en and the base of pleistos;to fill in (up), i.e. (by implication) to satisfy (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to fall in, be cast in, be involved in.
ORIGIN: From en and pipto; to fall on, i.e. (literally) to be entrapped by, or (figuratively) be overwhelmed with.

DEFINITION: to enfold, entangle; pass: to be involved in.
ORIGIN: From en and pleko; to entwine, i.e. (figuratively) involve with.

DEFINITION: (elaborate) braiding (of the hair).
ORIGIN: From empleko; elaborate braiding of the hair.

DEFINITION: to breathe, breathe into, inhale.
ORIGIN: From en and pneo; to inhale, i.e. (figuratively) to be animated by (bent upon).

DEFINITION: to travel as a merchant, engage in trade; to traffic in, make gain or business of.
ORIGIN: From en and poreuomai; to travel in (a country as a pedlar), i.e. (by implication) to trade.

DEFINITION: trading, trade, trafficking, business.
ORIGIN: Feminine from emporos; traffic.

DEFINITION: a place of traffic, mart, market, market-house.
ORIGIN: Neuter from emporos; a mart ("emporium").

DEFINITION: a passenger on shipboard, a merchant.
ORIGIN: From en and the base of poreuomai; a (wholesale) tradesman.

DEFINITION: to burn, set on fire, suffer inflammation.
ORIGIN: From en and pretho (to blow a flame); to enkindle, i.e. Set on fire.

DEFINITION: in front, before the face; sometimes made a subst. by the addition of the article: in front of, before the face of.
ORIGIN: From en and pros; in front of (in place (literally or figuratively) or time).
USAGE: against, at, before, (in presence, sight) of.

DEFINITION: to spit upon.
ORIGIN: From en and ptuo; to spit at or on.

DEFINITION: manifest, visible, comprehended.
ORIGIN: From a compound of en and phaino; apparent in self.

DEFINITION: to make visible (manifest); hence: to report (inform) against; pass: to appear before.
ORIGIN: From emphanes; to exhibit (in person) or disclose (by words).
USAGE: appear, declare (plainly), inform, (will) manifest, shew, signify.

DEFINITION: terrible, in fear (used of godly fear).
ORIGIN: From en and phobos; in fear, i.e. Alarmed.

DEFINITION: to breathe into, breathe upon.
ORIGIN: From en and phusao (to puff) (compare phuo); to blow at or on.

DEFINITION: inborn, ingrown, congenital, natural, rooted, implanted.
ORIGIN: From en and a derivative of phuo; implanted (figuratively).

DEFINITION: in, on, at, by, with.
ORIGIN: A primary preposition denoting (fixed) position (in place, time or state), and (by implication) instrumentality (medially or constructively), i.e. A relation of rest (intermediate between eis and ek); "in," at, (up-)on, by, etc..
USAGE: about, after, against, + almost, X altogether, among, X as, at, before, between, (here-)by (+ all means), for (... Sake of), + give self wholly to, (here-)in(-to, -wardly), X mightily, (because) of, (up-)on, (open-)ly, X outwardly, one, X quickly, X shortly, (speedi-)ly, X that, X there(-in, -on), through(-out), (un-)to(-ward), under, when, where(-with), while, with(-in). Often used in compounds, with substantially the same import; rarely with verbs of motion, and then not to indicate direction, except (elliptically) by a separate (and different) preposition.

DEFINITION: to take into one's arms, to embrace.
ORIGIN: From en and a derivative of agkale; to take in one's arms, i.e. Embrace.

DEFINITION: in or of the sea, marine creatures.
ORIGIN: From en and hals; in the sea, i.e. Marine.

DEFINITION: before, in the presence of.
ORIGIN: From en and anti; in front (i.e. Figuratively, presence) of.

DEFINITION: before, in the presence of, in the eyes of.
ORIGIN: Neuter of enantios; (adverbially) in the presence (view) of.

DEFINITION: opposite, opposed, contrary; the adversary.
ORIGIN: From enanti; opposite; figuratively, antagonistic.

DEFINITION: to begin (in), make a beginning, commence.
ORIGIN: From en and archomai; to commence on.

DEFINITION: in need, needy, poor.
ORIGIN: From a compound of en and deo (in the sense of lacking); deficient in.

DEFINITION: (a thing proved, hence) a plain token (sign, proof).
ORIGIN: From endeiknumi; an indication (concretely).

DEFINITION: to indicate (by word or act), to prove.
ORIGIN: From en and deiknuo; to indicate (by word or act).

DEFINITION: a showing, proof, demonstration, sign, token.
ORIGIN: From endeiknumi; indication (abstractly).

DEFINITION: eleven.
ORIGIN: From (the neuter of) heis and deka; one and ten, i.e. Eleven.

DEFINITION: eleventh.
ORIGIN: Ordinal from hendeka; eleventh.

DEFINITION: to admit, approve, to be possible.
ORIGIN: Third person singular present of a compound of en and dechomai; (impersonally) it is accepted in, i.e. Admitted (possible).

DEFINITION: to be in one's own country, to be at home.
ORIGIN: From a compound of en and demos; to be in one's own country, i.e. Home (figuratively).

DEFINITION: (somewhat rare) (of clothing: to put on another); mid: to put on (myself).
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of enduo; to invest (with a garment).

DEFINITION: righteous, just.
ORIGIN: From en and dike; in the right, i.e. Equitable.

DEFINITION: the material of a building, a structure.
ORIGIN: From a compound of en and a derivative of the base of demos; a housing in (residence), i.e. Structure.

DEFINITION: to glorify, acknowledge the glory belonging to, recognize as glorious; pass: to be glorified in.
ORIGIN: From endoxos; to glorify.

DEFINITION: highly esteemed, splendid, glorious.
ORIGIN: From en and doxa; in glory, i.e. Splendid, (figuratively) noble.

DEFINITION: apparel (esp. the outer robe).
ORIGIN: From enduo; apparel (especially the outer robe).

DEFINITION: to fill with power, strengthen, make strong.
ORIGIN: From en and dunamoo; to empower.

DEFINITION: to clothe; mid: to enter, creep into.
ORIGIN: From ennomos and duno; to sink (by implication, wrap (compare enduo) on, i.e. (figuratively) sneak.

DEFINITION: a putting on, investment (with clothing).
ORIGIN: From enduo; investment with clothing.

DEFINITION: to clothe or be clothed with (in the sense of sinking into a garment).
ORIGIN: From en and duno (in the sense of sinking into a garment); to invest with clothing (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: an ambush, plot, treachery, fraud.
ORIGIN: Feminine from en and the base of hedraios; an ambuscade, i.e. (figuratively) murderous purpose.

DEFINITION: to lie in wait (ambush) for, seek to entrap (hence: to defraud, deceive).
ORIGIN: From enedra; to lurk, i.e. (figuratively) plot assassination.

DEFINITION: lying in wait.
ORIGIN: Neuter of the same as enedra; an ambush, i.e. (figuratively) murderous design.

DEFINITION: to wrap up, roll up in (something), wind in.
ORIGIN: From ennomos and the base of heilisso; to enwrap.

DEFINITION: to be in, within.
ORIGIN: From ennomos and eimi; to be within (neuter participle plural).
USAGE: such things as... Have. See also eni.

DEFINITION: for the sake of, on account of, on account of which, wherefore, on account of what, why.
ORIGIN: Or heneken hen'-ek-en or heineken hi'-nek-en; of uncertain affinity; on account of.
USAGE: because, for (cause, sake), (where-)fore, by reason of, that.

DEFINITION: working, action, productive work, activity; in the NT, confined to superhuman activity.
ORIGIN: From energes; efficiency ("energy").

DEFINITION: to work, be operative, be at work, be made to work, accomplish; mid: to work, display activity.
ORIGIN: From energes; to be active, efficient.
USAGE: do, (be) effectual (fervent), be mighty in, shew forth self, work (effectually in).

DEFINITION: a working, an effect, operation.
ORIGIN: From energeo; an effect.

DEFINITION: effective, productive of due result, at work.
ORIGIN: From en and ergon; active, operative.

DEFINITION: to confer a benefit on, to bless.
ORIGIN: From en and eulogeo; to confer a benefit on.

DEFINITION: (a) to have a grudge against, be angry (with), (b) pass. or mid: to be entangled, entangle myself.
ORIGIN: From en and echo; to hold in or upon, i.e. Ensnare; by implication, to keep a grudge.
USAGE: entangle with, have a quarrel against, urge.

DEFINITION: prop. within, (of place) here, to here.
ORIGIN: From a prolonged form of en; properly, within, i.e. (of place) here, hither.

DEFINITION: to meditate upon, reflect upon, ponder.
ORIGIN: From a compound of en and thumos; to be inspirited, i.e. Ponder.

DEFINITION: inward thought, reflection, plur: thoughts.
ORIGIN: From enthumeomai; deliberation.

DEFINITION: is in, has place, can be.
ORIGIN: Contraction for the third person singular present indicative of eneimi; impersonally, there is in or among.

DEFINITION: a cycle of time, a year.
ORIGIN: Prolongation from a primary enos (a year); a year.

DEFINITION: to place in or upon; only in the intrans. tenses: to impend, be at hand, be present, threaten; as adj: present.
ORIGIN: From en and histemi; to place on hand, i.e. (reflexively) impend, (participle) be instant.

DEFINITION: to invigorate, strengthen.
ORIGIN: From en and ischuo; to invigorate (transitively or reflexively).

DEFINITION: ninth.
ORIGIN: Ordinal from ennea; ninth.

DEFINITION: nine.
ORIGIN: A primary number; nine.

DEFINITION: ninety-nine.
ORIGIN: From a (tenth) multiple of ennea and ennea itself; ninety-nine.

DEFINITION: dumb, speechless (as with amazement).
ORIGIN: From enneuo; dumb (as making signs), i.e. Silent from astonishment.

DEFINITION: to nod at, beckon or communicate by gesture.
ORIGIN: From en and neuo; to nod at, i.e. Beckon or communicate by gesture.

DEFINITION: thinking, consideration; a thought, purpose, design, intention.
ORIGIN: From a compound of en and nous; thoughtfulness, i.e. Moral understanding.

DEFINITION: (a) legal, statutory, duly constituted, (b) under the law, obedient to the law.
ORIGIN: From en and nomos; (subjectively) legal, or (objectively) subject to.

DEFINITION: nightly, neut. as adverb by night.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a compound of en and nux; (adverbially) by night.

DEFINITION: to dwell in, be settled (stationary) in; met: to be indwelling.
ORIGIN: From en and oikeo; to inhabit (figuratively).

DEFINITION: oneness, unity, unanimity.
ORIGIN: From heis; oneness, i.e. (figuratively) unanimity.

DEFINITION: to disturb, cause tumult, trouble, annoy.
ORIGIN: From en and ochleo; to crowd in, i.e. (figuratively) to annoy.

DEFINITION: involved in, held in, hence: liable, generally with dat. (or gen.) of the punishment.
ORIGIN: From enecho; liable to (a condition, penalty or imputation).
USAGE: in danger of, guilty of, subject to.

DEFINITION: an injunction, ordinance, precept.
ORIGIN: From entellomai; an injunction, i.e. Religious precept.

DEFINITION: to embalm, prepare for burial.
ORIGIN: From a compound of en and taphos; to inswathe with cerements for interment.

DEFINITION: embalming, preparation of a body for burial.
ORIGIN: From entaphiazo; preparation for interment.

DEFINITION: to give orders (injunctions, instructions, commands).
ORIGIN: From en and the base of telos; to enjoin.

DEFINITION: hence, from this place, on this side and on that.
ORIGIN: From the same as enthade; hence (literally or figuratively); (repeated) on both sides.

DEFINITION: (lit: approaching the king, hence a technical term), a petition, prayer, intercession.
ORIGIN: From entugchano; an interview, i.e. (specially) supplication.

DEFINITION: (held precious, hence) precious, honored, honorable in rank.
ORIGIN: From en and time; valued (figuratively).
USAGE: dear, more honourable, precious, in reputation.

DEFINITION: an ordinance, injunction, command, law.
ORIGIN: From entellomai; injunction, i.e. An authoritative prescription.

DEFINITION: belonging to the place, native, resident; subst: a citizen.
ORIGIN: From en and topos; a resident.

DEFINITION: within, inside, the inside.
ORIGIN: From en; inside (adverb or noun).

DEFINITION: (a) to turn to confusion, put to shame, (b) mid: to reverence, regard.
ORIGIN: From en and the base of trope; to invert, i.e. (figuratively and reflexively) in a good sense, to respect; or in a bad one, to confound.

DEFINITION: to nourish (sustain) on, be educated in.
ORIGIN: From en and trepho; (figuratively) to educate.

DEFINITION: trembling with fear, terrified.
ORIGIN: From en and tromos; terrified.

DEFINITION: respect, shame.
ORIGIN: From entrepo; confusion.

DEFINITION: to revel (in), live luxuriously, riot.
ORIGIN: From en and truphao; to revel in.

DEFINITION: (a) to meet, encounter, hence: (b) to call (upon), make a petition, make suit, supplication.
ORIGIN: From en and tugchano; to chance upon, i.e. (by implication) confer with; by extension to entreat (in favor or against).

DEFINITION: to wrap up, roll round, envelop.
ORIGIN: From en and tulisso (to twist; probably akin to heilisso); to entwine, i.e. Wind up in.

DEFINITION: to imprint, engrave.
ORIGIN: From en and a derivative of tupos; to enstamp, i.e. Engrave.

DEFINITION: to insult, outrage, treat contemptuously, mock at.
ORIGIN: From en and hubrizo; to insult.

DEFINITION: to dream (see visions) in sleep.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from enupnion; to dream.

DEFINITION: a dream, vision.
ORIGIN: From en and hupnos; something seen in sleep, i.e. A dream (vision in a dream).

DEFINITION: before the face of, in the presence of, in the eyes of.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a compound of en and a derivative of optanomai; in the face of (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: before, in the presence (sight) of, to.

DEFINITION: Enosh (also Enos), son of Seth, and father of Cainan.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Enowsh); Enos (i.e. Enosh), a patriarch.

DEFINITION: to take into ear, give ear to, listen to.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from a compound of en and ous; to take in one's ear, i.e. To listen.

DEFINITION: Enoch, son of Jared and father of Methuselah.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Chanowk); Enoch (i.e. Chanok), an antediluvian.

DEFINITION: six.
ORIGIN: A primary numeral; six.

DEFINITION: to announce publicly, proclaim.
ORIGIN: From ek and the base of aggelos; to publish, i.e. Celebrate.

DEFINITION: to buy out, buy away from, ransom; mid: to purchase out, buy, redeem, choose.
ORIGIN: From ek and agorazo; to buy up, i.e. Ransom; figuratively, to rescue from loss (improve opportunity).

DEFINITION: to lead out, sometimes to death, execution.
ORIGIN: From ek and ago; to lead forth.

DEFINITION: to take out, remove; sometimes (mid): to choose, sometimes: to rescue.
ORIGIN: From ek and haireomai; actively, to tear out; middle voice, to select; figuratively, to release.

DEFINITION: to lift up, remove, eject.
ORIGIN: From ek and airo; to remove.

DEFINITION: to demand of, ask for, beg earnestly for.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from ek and aiteo; to demand (for trial).

DEFINITION: suddenly, unexpectedly.
ORIGIN: From ek and the base of aiphnidios; of a sudden (unexpectedly).

DEFINITION: to follow (out, up), to imitate.
ORIGIN: From ek and akoloutheo; to follow out, i.e. (figuratively) to imitate, obey, yield to.

DEFINITION: six hundred.
ORIGIN: Plural ordinal from hex and hekaton; six hundred.

DEFINITION: to plaster, wash over; to wipe off, wipe out, obliterate.
ORIGIN: From ek and aleipho; to smear out, i.e. Obliterate (erase tears, figuratively, pardon sin).

DEFINITION: to leap up (for joy).
ORIGIN: From ek and hallomai; to spring forth.

DEFINITION: a rising up and out, resurrection.
ORIGIN: From exanistemi; a rising from death.

DEFINITION: to rise (spring) up out (of the ground).
ORIGIN: From ek and anatello; to start up out of the ground, i.e. Germinate.

DEFINITION: (a) in trans. tenses: to raise up, cause to grow, (b) in intrans. tenses: to rise up from.
ORIGIN: From ek and anistemi; objectively, to produce, i.e. (figuratively) beget; subjectively, to arise, i.e. (figuratively) object.

DEFINITION: to seduce wholly, deceive.
ORIGIN: From ek and apatao; to seduce wholly.

DEFINITION: suddenly, unexpectedly.
ORIGIN: From ek and a derivative of the same as aiphnidios; of a sudden, i.e. Unexpectedly.

DEFINITION: to be utterly without resource, be in despair.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from ek and aporeo; to be utterly at a loss, i.e. Despond.

DEFINITION: to send away, send forth (a person qualified for a task).
ORIGIN: From ek and apostello; to send away forth, i.e. (on a mission) to despatch, or (peremptorily) to dismiss.

DEFINITION: (a) to fit up, completely furnish, equip, furnish, supply, (b) to accomplish, finish.
ORIGIN: From ek and a derivative of artios; to finish out (time); figuratively, to equip fully (a teacher).

DEFINITION: to flash forth like lightning, gleam, be radiant.
ORIGIN: From ek and astrapto; to lighten forth, i.e. (figuratively) to be radiant (of very white garments).

DEFINITION: immediately, instantly, at once.
ORIGIN: From ek and the genitive case singular feminine of autos (hora being understood); from that hour, i.e. Instantly.
USAGE: by and by, immediately, presently, straightway.

DEFINITION: to raise up, arouse.
ORIGIN: From ek and egeiro; to rouse fully, i.e. (figuratively) to resuscitate (from death), release (from infliction).

DEFINITION: (originally: to shall go out), to go out (away), depart.
ORIGIN: From ek and eimi (to go); to issue, i.e. Leave (a place), escape (to the shore).

DEFINITION: convince.
ORIGIN: From ek and elegcho; to convict fully, i.e. (by implication) to punish.

DEFINITION: (lit: to draw out of the right place, or to draw aside out of the right way), to entice.
ORIGIN: From ek and helkuo; to drag forth, i.e. (figuratively) to entice (to sin).

DEFINITION: vomit (noun).
ORIGIN: From a comparative of ek and a presumed erao (to spue); vomit, i.e. Food disgorged.

DEFINITION: to search diligently, to examine carefully (minutely).
ORIGIN: From ek and ereunao; to explore (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to go or come out of.
ORIGIN: From ek and erchomai; to issue (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: come (forth, out), depart (out of), escape, get out, go (abroad, away, forth, out, thence), proceed (forth), spread abroad.

DEFINITION: it is permitted, lawful, possible.
ORIGIN: Third person singular present indicative of a compound of ek and eimi; so also exon ex-on' neuter present participle of the same (with or without some form of eimi expressed); impersonally, it is right (through the figurative idea of being out in public).

DEFINITION: to examine, question, inquire at, search out.
ORIGIN: From ek and etazo (to examine); to test thoroughly (by questions), i.e. Ascertain or interrogate.

DEFINITION: to lead, show the way; met: to unfold, narrate, declare.
ORIGIN: From ek and hegeomai; to consider out (aloud), i.e. Rehearse, unfold.

DEFINITION: sixty.
ORIGIN: The tenth multiple of hex; sixty.

DEFINITION: next in order, the next day, the following day, at the period immediately following.
ORIGIN: From echo (in the sense of taking hold of, i.e. Adjoining); successive.

DEFINITION: to sound out (forth) (referring either to the clearness or to the loudness of the sound).
ORIGIN: Middle voice from ek and echeo; to "echo" forth, i.e. Resound (be generally reported).

DEFINITION: condition, state, habit, use, especially: good condition of body or soul.
ORIGIN: From echo; habit, i.e. (by implication) practice.

DEFINITION: (lit: to remove from a standing position), (a) in trans. tenses: to astonish, amaze, (b) in intrans. tenses: to be astonished, amazed; to be out of mind, be mad.
ORIGIN: From ek and histemi; to put (stand) out of wits, i.e. Astound, or (reflexively) become astounded, insane.
USAGE: amaze, be (make) astonished, be beside self (selves), bewitch, wonder.

DEFINITION: to have strength for (a difficult task), be perfectly able.
ORIGIN: From ek and ischuo; to have full strength, i.e. Be entirely competent.

DEFINITION: (a) an exit, going out, departure from a place; the exodus, (b) death.
ORIGIN: From ek and hodos; an exit, i.e. (figuratively) death.

DEFINITION: to destroy utterly, annihilate, exterminate, root out.
ORIGIN: From ek and olothreuo; to extirpate.

DEFINITION: (a) to consent fully, agree out and out, (b) to confess, admit, acknowledge (cf. the early Hellenistic sense of the middle: to acknowledge a debt), (c) to give thanks, praise.
ORIGIN: From ek and homologeo; to acknowledge or (by implication, of assent) agree fully.

DEFINITION: to adjure, put to oath; to exorcise.
ORIGIN: From ek and horkizo; to exact an oath, i.e. Conjure.

DEFINITION: an exorcist, a caster out of evil spirits by the use of names or spells.
ORIGIN: From exorkizo; one that binds by an oath (or spell), i.e. (by implication) an "exorcist" (conjurer).

DEFINITION: (a) to dig out, hence: to open up, (b) to gouge.
ORIGIN: From ek and orusso; to dig out, i.e. (by extension) to extract (an eye), remove (roofing).

DEFINITION: to set at naught, ignore, despise.
ORIGIN: From ek and a derivative of the neuter of oudeis; to make utterly nothing of, i.e. Despise.
USAGE: set at nought. See also exoutheneo.

DEFINITION: to set at naught, ignore, despise.
ORIGIN: A variation of exoudenoo and meaning the same.
USAGE: contemptible, despise, least esteemed, set at nought.

DEFINITION: (a) power, authority, weight, especially: moral authority, influence, (b) in a quasi-personal sense, derived from later Judaism, of a spiritual power, and hence of an earthly power.
ORIGIN: From exesti (in the sense of ability); privilege, i.e. (subjectively) force, capacity, competency, freedom, or (objectively) mastery (concretely, magistrate, superhuman, potentate, token of control), delegated influence.
USAGE: authority, jurisdiction, liberty, power, right, strength.

DEFINITION: to exercise (wield) power (authority), pass: to be ruled, be held under authority.
ORIGIN: From exousia; to control.
USAGE: exercise authority upon, bring under the (have) power of.

DEFINITION: eminence, distinction, excellence.
ORIGIN: From a compound of ek and echo (meaning to stand out); prominence (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to awaken out of sleep.
ORIGIN: From exupnos; to waken.

DEFINITION: roused out of sleep.
ORIGIN: From ek and hupnos; awake.

DEFINITION: outside, without.
ORIGIN: Adverb from ek; out(-side, of doors), literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: (a) from outside, from without, (b) outside, both as adj. and prep; with article: the outside.
ORIGIN: From exo; external(-ly).

DEFINITION: to drive out, expel, propel, thrust out; to drive out of the sea, drive on shore.
ORIGIN: Or exotho ex-o'-tho from ek and otheo (to push); to expel; by implication, to propel.

DEFINITION: outmost, outer, external.
ORIGIN: Comparative of exo; exterior.

DEFINITION: to take part in a festival, keep a feast (allegorically).
ORIGIN: From heorte; to observe a festival.

DEFINITION: a festival, feast, periodically recurring.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a festival.

DEFINITION: a summons, a promise.
ORIGIN: From epaggello; an announcement (for information, assent or pledge; especially a divine assurance of good).

DEFINITION: to proclaim, to promise.
ORIGIN: From epi and the base of aggelos; to announce upon (reflexively), i.e. (by implication) to engage to do something, to assert something respecting oneself.

DEFINITION: a promise.
ORIGIN: From epaggello; a self-committal (by assurance of conferring some good).

DEFINITION: to bring upon; met: to cause to be imputed to.
ORIGIN: From epi and ago; to superinduce, i.e. Inflict (an evil), charge (a crime).

DEFINITION: to contend earnestly for.
ORIGIN: From epi and agonizomai; to struggle for.

DEFINITION: to gather together, pass: to crowd upon (some one), press around.
ORIGIN: From epi and athroizo (to assemble); to accumulate.

DEFINITION: "praiseworthy", Epaenetus, a Christian of Rome.
ORIGIN: From epaineo; praised; Epaenetus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: to praise, commend, applaud.
ORIGIN: From epi and aineo; to applaud.

DEFINITION: commendation, praise, approval.
ORIGIN: From epi and the base of aineo; laudation; concretely, a commendable thing.

DEFINITION: to raise, lift up.
ORIGIN: From epi and airo; to raise up (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to be ashamed, be ashamed of.
ORIGIN: From epi and aischunomai; to feel shame for something.

DEFINITION: to beg, be a beggar, ask alms.
ORIGIN: From epi and aiteo; to ask for.

DEFINITION: to follow close after, accompany, dog; to imitate, pursue, be studious of.
ORIGIN: From epi and akoloutheo; to accompany.

DEFINITION: to listen to, hear favorably.
ORIGIN: From epi and akouo; to hearken (favorably) to.

DEFINITION: to listen to, hear, hearken to.
ORIGIN: From epi and the base of akroates; to listen (intently) to.

DEFINITION: after, when, as soon as.
ORIGIN: From epi and an; a particle of indefinite contemporaneousness; whenever, as soon as.

DEFINITION: necessarily; as subst: necessary things.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed compound of epi and anagke; (adverbially) on necessity, i.e. Necessarily.

DEFINITION: (a) nautical: to put out (from the shore), (lit: to take up a ship on to the high seas), (b) to go up, possibly: to go up again, return.
ORIGIN: From epi and anago; to lead up on, i.e. (technical) to put out (to sea); (intransitively) to return.

DEFINITION: to remind, possibly: to remind again.
ORIGIN: From epi and anamimnesko; to remind of.

DEFINITION: to rest upon, rely on, trust in.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from epi and anapano; to settle on; literally (remain) or figuratively (rely).

DEFINITION: to return, come back again.
ORIGIN: From epi and anerchomai; to come up on, i.e. Return.

DEFINITION: intrans. tenses: to rise up against.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from epi and anistemi; to stand up on, i.e. (figuratively) to attack.

DEFINITION: correction, reformation, setting straight (right) again.
ORIGIN: From a compound of epi and anorthoo; a straightening up again, i.e. (figuratively) rectification (reformation).

DEFINITION: (a) adv: on the top, above, (b) prep: on the top of, above, over, on, above, more than, superior to.
ORIGIN: From epi and ano; up above, i.e. Over or on (of place, amount, rank, etc.).

DEFINITION: to aid, relieve, do service, render help, be strong enough for.
ORIGIN: From epi and arkeo; to avail for, i.e. Help.

DEFINITION: sphere of duty, province.
ORIGIN: From a compound of epi and archo (meaning a governor of a district, "eparch"); a special region of government, i.e. A Roman præfecture.

DEFINITION: a farm, estate, dwelling, habitation.
ORIGIN: From epi and an equivalent of aule; a hut over the head, i.e. A dwelling.

DEFINITION: on the next day.
ORIGIN: From epi and aurion; occurring on the succeeding day, i.e. (hemera being implied) to-morrow.

DEFINITION: in the very act.
ORIGIN: From epi and autos and (the dative case singular of) a derivative of phor (a thief); in theft itself, i.e. (by analogy) in actual crime.

DEFINITION: Epaphras, Epaphroditus, a Colossian Christian, in captivity with Paul in Rome.
ORIGIN: Contracted from Epaphroditos; Epaphras, a Christian.

DEFINITION: to foam out (a metaphor from the seaweed and refuse borne on the crest of waves), vomit forth.
ORIGIN: From epi and aphrizo; to foam upon, i.e. (figuratively) to exhibit (a vile passion).

DEFINITION: Epaphras, Epaphroditus, a Colossian Christian, in captivity with Paul in Rome.
ORIGIN: From epi (in the sense of devoted to) and Aphrodite (Venus); Epaphroditus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: to arouse, stimulate, excite against.
ORIGIN: From epi and egeiro; to rouse upon, i.e. (figuratively) to excite against.

DEFINITION: of time: when, after; of cause: since, because; otherwise: else.
ORIGIN: From epi and ei; thereupon, i.e. Since (of time or cause).
USAGE: because, else, for that (then, -asmuch as), otherwise, seeing that, since, when.

DEFINITION: of time: when, now, after that; of cause: seeing that, forasmuch as.
ORIGIN: From epei and de; since now, i.e. (of time) when, or (of cause) whereas.
USAGE: after that, because, for (that, -asmuch as), seeing, since.

DEFINITION: since, forasmuch as.
ORIGIN: From epeide and per; since indeed (of cause).

DEFINITION: to looked upon, regarded.
ORIGIN: And other moods and persons of the same tense; from epi and eido; to regard (favorably or otherwise).

DEFINITION: since indeed, seeing that.
ORIGIN: From epei and per; since indeed (of cause).

DEFINITION: bringing in (besides or in addition), introduction, importation.
ORIGIN: From a compound of epi and eisago; a superintroduction.

DEFINITION: then, thereafter, afterwards.
ORIGIN: From epi and eita; thereafter.

DEFINITION: beyond, on yonder side.
ORIGIN: From epi and (the accusative case plural neuter of) ekeinos; upon those parts of, i.e. On the further side of.

DEFINITION: to extend, mid. to stretch forward.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from epi and ekteino; to stretch (oneself) forward upon.

DEFINITION: to have on over (as a garment); mid: to put on myself in addition.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from epi and enduo; to invest upon oneself.

DEFINITION: a coat, outer wrap or tunic.
ORIGIN: From ependuomai; a wrapper, i.e. Outer garment.

DEFINITION: to come to, arrive, come on, come upon, attack.
ORIGIN: From epi and erchomai; to supervene, i.e. Arrive, occur, impend, attack, (figuratively) influence.

DEFINITION: to interrogate, question, demand of.
ORIGIN: From epi and erotao; to ask for, i.e. Inquire, seek.

DEFINITION: inquiry, request, appeal, demand; a profession, pledge.
ORIGIN: From eperotao; an inquiry.

DEFINITION: (a) trans: to hold forth, (b) intrans: to mark, pay attention (heed), note; to delay, stay, wait.
ORIGIN: From epi and echo; to hold upon, i.e. (by implication) to retain; (by extension) to detain; (with implication, of nous) to pay attention to.
USAGE: give (take) heed unto, hold forth, mark, stay.

DEFINITION: to insult, treat wrongfully, molest, revile.
ORIGIN: From a comparative of epi and (probably) areia (threats); to insult, slander.

DEFINITION: on, to, against, on the basis of, at.
ORIGIN: A primary preposition; properly, meaning superimposition (of time, place, order, etc.), as a relation of distribution (with the genitive case), i.e. Over, upon, etc.; of rest (with the dative case) at, on, etc.; of direction (with the accusative case) towards, upon, etc.
USAGE: about (the times), above, after, against, among, as long as (touching), at, beside, X have charge of, (be-, (where-))fore, in (a place, as much as, the time of, -to), (because) of, (up-)on (behalf of), over, (by, for) the space of, through(-out), (un-)to(-ward), with. In compounds it retains essentially the same import, at, upon, etc. (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: (a) to set foot on, step on, (b) to mount (a horse), board (a vessel).
ORIGIN: From epi and the base of basis; to walk upon, i.e. Mount, ascend, embark, arrive.
USAGE: come (into), enter into, go abroad, sit upon, take ship.

DEFINITION: (a) to throw upon, cast over, (b) to place upon, (c) to lay, (d) intrans: to strike upon, rush.
ORIGIN: From epi and ballo; to throw upon (literal or figurative, transitive or reflexive; usually with more or less force); specially (with heautou implied) to reflect; impersonally, to belong to.
USAGE: beat into, cast (up-)on, fall, lay (on), put (unto), stretch forth, think on.

DEFINITION: to put a burden on, be burdensome.
ORIGIN: From epi and bareo; to be heavy upon, i.e. (pecuniarily) to be expensive to; figuratively, to be severe towards.

DEFINITION: to place upon (a horse, mule).
ORIGIN: From epi and a reduplicated derivative of the base of basis (compare anabibazo); to cause to mount (an animal).

DEFINITION: to look with favor on, regard.
ORIGIN: From epi and blepo; to gaze at (with favor, pity or partiality).
USAGE: look upon, regard, have respect to.

DEFINITION: that which is put on, a patch.
ORIGIN: From epiballo; a patch.

DEFINITION: to cry out to or against.
ORIGIN: From epi and boao; to exclaim against.

DEFINITION: a plot, design against.
ORIGIN: From a presumed compound of epi and boulomai; a plan against someone, i.e. A plot.

DEFINITION: to take to wife after, marry a deceased brother's wife.
ORIGIN: From epi and a derivative of gamos; to form affinity with, i.e. (specially) in a levirate way.

DEFINITION: (a) on the earth, belonging to the earth (as opposed to the sky), (b) in a spiritual sense, belonging to the earthly sphere, earthly (as opposed to heavenly).
ORIGIN: From epi and ge; worldly (physically or morally).

DEFINITION: to arise, spring up, arrive, come on.
ORIGIN: From epi and ginomai; to arrive upon, i.e. Spring up (as a wind).

DEFINITION: to come to know by directing attention to him or it, to perceive, discern, recognize; aor: to found out.
ORIGIN: From epi and ginosko; to know upon some mark, i.e. Recognize; by implication, to become fully acquainted with, to acknowledge.

DEFINITION: knowledge of a particular point (directed towards a particular object); perception, discernment, recognition, intuition.
ORIGIN: From epiginosko; recognition, i.e. (by implication) full discernment, acknowledgement.

DEFINITION: an inscription, title, label.
ORIGIN: From epigrapho; an inscription.

DEFINITION: to write upon, inscribe, imprint a mark on.
ORIGIN: From epi and grapho; to inscribe (physically or mentally).

DEFINITION: to show, display, point out, indicate; to prove, demonstrate.
ORIGIN: From epi and deiknuo; to exhibit (physically or mentally).

DEFINITION: to accept as true, to receive besides.
ORIGIN: From epi and dechomai; to admit (as a guest or (figuratively) teacher).

DEFINITION: to sojourn, be resident (temporarily, in a foreign city).
ORIGIN: From a compound of epi and demos; to make oneself at home, i.e. (by extension) to reside (in a foreign country).

DEFINITION: to make an additional testamentary disposition, to furnish with additions.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from epi and diatasso; to appoint besides, i.e. Supplement (as a codicil).

DEFINITION: (a) trans: to hand in, give up, (b) intrans: to give way (to the wind).
ORIGIN: From epi and didomi; to give over (by hand or surrender).
USAGE: deliver unto, give, let (+ (her drive)), offer.

DEFINITION: to set in order besides, put in order, correct.
ORIGIN: From epi and a derivative of orthos; to straighten further, i.e. (figuratively) arrange additionally.

DEFINITION: to sink, set, set during, go down.
ORIGIN: From epi and duno; to set fully (as the sun).

DEFINITION: considerateness, forbearance, fairness, gentleness, mildness.
ORIGIN: From epieikes; suitableness, i.e. (by implication) equity, mildness.

DEFINITION: gentle, mild, forbearing, fair, reasonable, moderate.
ORIGIN: From epi and eiko; appropriate, i.e. (by implication) mild.

DEFINITION: to seek after, desire, search for, make inquiries about.
ORIGIN: From epi and zeteo; to search (inquire) for; intensively, to demand, to crave.

DEFINITION: at the point of death, condemned to death.
ORIGIN: From epi and thanatos; doomed to death.

DEFINITION: a laying on; an attack, assault.
ORIGIN: From epitithemi; an imposition (of hands officially).

DEFINITION: to long for, covet, lust after, set the heart upon.
ORIGIN: From epi and thumos; to set the heart upon, i.e. Long for (rightfully or otherwise).

DEFINITION: an eager desirer of.
ORIGIN: From epithumeo.

DEFINITION: desire, eagerness for, inordinate desire, lust.
ORIGIN: From epithumeo; a longing (especially for what is forbidden).

DEFINITION: to sit upon, cause to sit upon.
ORIGIN: From epi and kathizo; to seat upon.

DEFINITION: (a) to call (name) by a supplementary (additional, alternative) name, (b) mid: to call upon, appeal to, address.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from epi and kaleo; to entitle; by implication, to invoke (for aid, worship, testimony, decision, etc.).

DEFINITION: a covering, cloak, veil, pretext.
ORIGIN: From epikalupto; a covering, i.e. (figuratively) pretext.

DEFINITION: to put a cover on, cover up.
ORIGIN: From epi and kalupto; to conceal, i.e. (figuratively) forgive.

DEFINITION: on whom a curse has been invoked, accursed, doomed to destruction.
ORIGIN: From epi and a derivative of kataraomai; imprecated, i.e. Execrable.

DEFINITION: (a) dat: to be placed upon, be laid upon, lie upon, be imposed; to press upon, (b) absol: to press hard, be insistent, insist.
ORIGIN: From epi and keimai; to rest upon (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: impose, be instant, (be) laid (there-, up-)on, (when) lay (on), lie (on), press upon.

DEFINITION: an Epicurean, one who holds the tenets of Epicurus.
ORIGIN: From Epikouros (compare epikouria) (a noted philosopher); an Epicurean or follower of Epicurus.

DEFINITION: succor (against foes), help, aid, assistance.
ORIGIN: From a compound of epi and a (prolonged) form of the base of korasion (in the sense of servant); assistance.

DEFINITION: to decree, give sentence, decide.
ORIGIN: From epi and krino; to adjudge.

DEFINITION: to lay hold of, take hold of, seize (sometimes with beneficent, sometimes with hostile, intent).
ORIGIN: Middle voice from epi and lambano; to seize (for help, injury, attainment, or any other purpose; literally or figuratively).
USAGE: catch, lay hold (up-)on, take (by, hold of, on).

DEFINITION: to forget, neglect.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from epi and lanthano; to lose out of mind; by implication, to neglect.

DEFINITION: to call; mid: to choose for myself; pass: to be named.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from epi and lego; to surname, select.

DEFINITION: to fail, fall short.
ORIGIN: From epi and leipo; to leave upon, i.e. (figuratively) to be insufficient for.

DEFINITION: forgetfulness, oblivion.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of epilanthanomai; negligence.

DEFINITION: remaining, that is left over, still left.
ORIGIN: From epi and loipoy; left over, i.e. Remaining.

DEFINITION: solution, explanation, interpretation; release.
ORIGIN: From epiluo; explanation, i.e. Application.

DEFINITION: to loose, release; to solve, settle, explain, interpret, decide.
ORIGIN: From epi and luo; to solve further, i.e. (figuratively) to explain, decide.

DEFINITION: to testify earnestly, bear witness to.
ORIGIN: From epi and martureo; to attest further, i.e. Corroborate.

DEFINITION: attention, care.
ORIGIN: From epimeleomai; carefulness, i.e. Kind attention (hospitality).

DEFINITION: to take care of, attend to.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from epi and the same as melo; to care for (physically or otherwise).

DEFINITION: carefully, diligently.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a derivative of epimeleomai; carefully.

DEFINITION: (a) to remain, tarry, (b) to remain in, persist in.
ORIGIN: From epi and meno; to stay over, i.e. Remain (figuratively, persevere).

DEFINITION: to nod to, assent to, consent.
ORIGIN: From epi and neuo; to nod at, i.e. (by implication) to assent.

DEFINITION: thought, purpose, design, intent.
ORIGIN: From epi and nous; attention of the mind, i.e. (by implication) purpose.

DEFINITION: to take an oath, swear falsely.
ORIGIN: From epiorkos; to commit perjury.

DEFINITION: sworn falsely, a perjurer.
ORIGIN: From epi and horkos; on oath, i.e. (falsely) a forswearer.

DEFINITION: following, next.
ORIGIN: Feminine singular participle of a comparative of epi and heimi (to go); supervening, i.e. (hemera or nux being expressed or implied) the ensuing day or night.

DEFINITION: for the morrow, necessary, sufficient.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from the same as epiousa; tomorrow's; but more probably from epi and a derivative of the present participle feminine of eimi; for subsistence, i.e. Needful.

DEFINITION: to fall upon, press upon, light upon, come over.
ORIGIN: From epi and pipto; to embrace (with affection) or seize (with more or less violence; literally or figuratively).
USAGE: fall into (on, upon) lie on, press upon.

DEFINITION: to strike at, to rebuke (with words).
ORIGIN: From epi and plesso; to chastise, i.e. (with words) to upbraid.

DEFINITION: choke.
ORIGIN: From epi and pnigo; to throttle upon, i.e. (figuratively) overgrow.

DEFINITION: to long for, strain after, desire greatly, have affection for.
ORIGIN: From epi and potheo (to yearn); to dote upon, i.e. Intensely crave possession (lawfully or wrongfully).

DEFINITION: eager longing (desire), strong affection.
ORIGIN: From epipotheo; a longing for.

DEFINITION: longed for, missed, greatly desired.
ORIGIN: From epi and a derivative of the latter part of epipotheo; yearned upon, i.e. Greatly loved.

DEFINITION: longing, eager desire.
ORIGIN: From epipotheo; intense longing.

DEFINITION: to travel, journey (to).
ORIGIN: From epi and poreuomai; to journey further, i.e. Travel on (reach).

DEFINITION: to sew upon.
ORIGIN: From epi and the base of rhaphis; to stitch upon, i.e. Fasten with the needle.

DEFINITION: to throw (cast) (upon), as of cares.
ORIGIN: From epi and rhipto; to throw upon (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: bearing a mark, notable.
ORIGIN: From epi and some form of the base of semaino; remarkable, i.e. (figuratively) eminent.

DEFINITION: provision, nourishment, food.
ORIGIN: From a compound of epi and a derivative of sitos; a provisioning, i.e. (concretely) food.

DEFINITION: to look upon, visit, look out, select.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from epi and the base of skopos; to inspect, i.e. (by implication) to select; by extension, to go to see, relieve.

DEFINITION: to raise a tent (over), dwell, spread a tabernacle over.
ORIGIN: From epi and skenoo; to tent upon, i.e. (figuratively) abide with.

DEFINITION: to overshadow, envelop.
ORIGIN: From epi and a derivative of skia; to cast a shade upon, i.e. (by analogy) to envelop in a haze of brilliancy; figuratively, to invest with preternatural influence.

DEFINITION: to exercise oversight, care for, visit.
ORIGIN: From epi and skopeo; to oversee; by implication, to beware.

DEFINITION: (a) visitation (of judgment), (b) oversight, supervision, overseership.
ORIGIN: From episkeptomai; inspection (for relief); by implication, superintendence; specially, the Christian "episcopate".
USAGE: the office of a "bishop", bishoprick, visitation.

DEFINITION: (used as an official title in civil life), overseer, supervisor, ruler, especially used with reference to the supervising function exercised by an elder or presbyter of a church or congregation.
ORIGIN: From epi and skopos (in the sense of episkopeo); a superintendent, i.e. Christian officer in genitive case charge of a (or the) church (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: (lit: to draw over), mid: to become as uncircumcised.
ORIGIN: From epi and spao; to draw over, i.e. (with akrobustia implied) efface the mark of circumcision (by recovering with the foreskin).

DEFINITION: to know, know of, understand.
ORIGIN: Apparently a middle voice of ephistemi (with nous implied); to put the mind upon, i.e. Comprehend, or be acquainted with.

DEFINITION: master, teacher, chief, commander.
ORIGIN: From epi and a presumed derivative of histemi; an appointee over, i.e. Commander (teacher).

DEFINITION: to send a message (by letter).
ORIGIN: From epi and stello; to enjoin (by writing), i.e. (genitive case) to communicate by letter (for any purpose).

DEFINITION: skillful, experienced, knowing.
ORIGIN: From epistamai; intelligent.

DEFINITION: to prop up, uphold, support, confirm, make stronger.
ORIGIN: From epi and sterizo; to support further, i.e. Reestablish.

DEFINITION: a letter, dispatch, epistle, message.
ORIGIN: From epistello; a written message.

DEFINITION: to muzzle, silence, stop the mouth.
ORIGIN: From epi and stoma; to put something over the mouth, i.e. (figuratively) to silence.

DEFINITION: (a) trans: to turn (back) to (towards), (b) intrans: to turn (back) (to [towards]); to come to myself.
ORIGIN: From epi and strepho; to revert (literally, figuratively or morally).

DEFINITION: a turning (to God), conversion.
ORIGIN: From epistrepho; reversion, i.e. Morally, revolution.

DEFINITION: to collect, gather together, assemble.
ORIGIN: From epi and sunago; to collect upon the same place.

DEFINITION: a gathering (collecting) together, assembling.
ORIGIN: From episunago; a complete collection; especially a Christian meeting (for worship).

DEFINITION: to run together again.
ORIGIN: From epi and suntrecho; to hasten together upon one place (or a particular occasion).

DEFINITION: a gathering, concourse, tumult.
ORIGIN: From the middle voice of a compound of epi and sunistao; a conspiracy, i.e. Concourse (riotous or friendly).
USAGE: that which cometh upon, + raising up.

DEFINITION: dangerous, likely to fall.
ORIGIN: From a compound of epi and sphallo (to trip); figuratively, insecure.

DEFINITION: to persist, insist, be more urgent.
ORIGIN: From epi and ischuo; to avail further, i.e. (figuratively) insist stoutly.

DEFINITION: to heap up, obtain a multitude of.
ORIGIN: From epi and soreuo; to accumulate further, i.e. (figuratively) seek additionally.

DEFINITION: instruction, command, order, authority.
ORIGIN: From epitasso; an injunction or decree; by implication, authoritativeness.

DEFINITION: to give order, command, charge.
ORIGIN: From epi and tasso; to arrange upon, i.e. Order.

DEFINITION: to complete, accomplish, perfect.
ORIGIN: From epi and teleo; to fulfill further (or completely), i.e. Execute; by implication, to terminate, undergo.

DEFINITION: necessary, suitable, fit.
ORIGIN: From epitedes (enough); serviceable, i.e. (by implication) requisite.

DEFINITION: to put, place upon, lay on; to add, give in addition.
ORIGIN: From epi and tithemi; to impose (in a friendly or hostile sense).
USAGE: add unto, lade, lay upon, put (up) on, set on (up), + surname, X wound.

DEFINITION: to honor, to mete out due measure, to censure.
ORIGIN: From epi and timao; to tax upon, i.e. Censure or admonish; by implication, forbid.

DEFINITION: punishment, penalty.
ORIGIN: From a compound of epi and time; properly, esteem, i.e. Citizenship; used (in the sense of epitimao) of a penalty.

DEFINITION: to turn to, commit, entrust; to allow, yield, permit.
ORIGIN: From epi and the base of trope; to turn over (transfer), i.e. Allow.
USAGE: give leave (liberty, license), let, permit, suffer.

DEFINITION: power to decide, authority, commission.
ORIGIN: From epitrepo; permission, i.e. (by implication) full power.

DEFINITION: (a) (procurator) a steward, (b) (tutor) a guardian (appointed for an infant [under 14 perhaps] by the father or by a magistrate).
ORIGIN: From epi and tropos (in the sense of epitrope); a commissioner, i.e. Domestic manager, guardian.

DEFINITION: to attain, obtain, acquire.
ORIGIN: From epi and tugchano; to chance upon, i.e. (by implication) to attain.

DEFINITION: to appear (as of a light in the heavens or from the heavens), shine upon.
ORIGIN: From epi and phaino; to shine upon, i.e. Become (literally) visible or (figuratively) known.

DEFINITION: appearing, manifestation, glorious display.
ORIGIN: From epiphanes; a manifestation, i.e. (specially) the advent of Christ (past or future).

DEFINITION: manifest, glorious, illustrious.
ORIGIN: From epiphaino; conspicuous, i.e. (figuratively) memorable.

DEFINITION: to shine upon, give light to.
ORIGIN: A form of epiphaino; to illuminate (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to bring forward (against), impose, inflict.
ORIGIN: From epi and phero; to bear upon (or further), i.e. Adduce (personally or judicially (accuse, inflict)), superinduce.

DEFINITION: to call out, shout, clamor at.
ORIGIN: From epi and phoneo; to call at something, i.e. Exclaim.

DEFINITION: to dawn, be near commencing.
ORIGIN: A form of epiphauo; to begin to grow light.
USAGE: begin to dawn, X draw on.

DEFINITION: to put one's hand to, to attempt.
ORIGIN: From epi and cheir; to put the hand upon, i.e. Undertake.

DEFINITION: to pour upon.
ORIGIN: From epi and cheo (to pour).

DEFINITION: to supply, provide (perhaps lavishly), furnish.
ORIGIN: From epi and choregeo; to furnish besides, i.e. Fully supply, (figuratively) aid or contribute.

DEFINITION: supply, provision, equipment, support.
ORIGIN: From epichoregeo; contribution.

DEFINITION: to spread on, to anoint.
ORIGIN: From epi and chrio; to smear over.

DEFINITION: to build upon (above) a foundation.
ORIGIN: From epi and oikodomeo; to build upon, i.e. (figuratively) to rear up.

DEFINITION: to force forward, run (a ship) aground.
ORIGIN: From epi and okello (to urge); to drive upon the shore, i.e. To beach a vessel.

DEFINITION: to name, impose a name on; pass: be named.
ORIGIN: From epi and onomazo; to name further, i.e. Denominate.

DEFINITION: to be an eyewitness of, behold, look upon.
ORIGIN: From epi and a derivative of optanomai; to inspect, i.e. Watch.

DEFINITION: an eyewitness, spectator, looker-on.
ORIGIN: From epi and a presumed derivative of optanomai; a looker-on.

DEFINITION: a word, so to speak.
ORIGIN: From epo; a word.

DEFINITION: heavenly, celestial, in the heavenly sphere, the sphere of spiritual activities; met: divine, spiritual.
ORIGIN: From epi and ouranos; above the sky.

DEFINITION: seven.
ORIGIN: A primary number; seven.

DEFINITION: seven times.
ORIGIN: Adverb from hepta; seven times.

DEFINITION: seven thousand.
ORIGIN: From heptakis and chilioi; seven times a thousand.

DEFINITION: answer, bid, bring word, command.
ORIGIN: A primary verb (used only in the definite past tense, the others being borrowed from ereo, rheo, and phemi); to speak or say (by word or writing).
USAGE: answer, bid, bring word, call, command, grant, say (on), speak, tell. Compare lego.

DEFINITION: "beloved", Erastus, the name of two Christians.
ORIGIN: From erao (to love); beloved; Erastus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: to work, trade, perform, do, practice, commit, acquire by labor.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from ergon; to toil (as a task, occupation, etc.), (by implication) effect, be engaged in or with, etc.
USAGE: commit, do, labor for, minister about, trade (by), work.

DEFINITION: working, activity, work, service, trade, business, gains of business, performance, practice.
ORIGIN: From ergates; occupation; by implication, profit, pains.

DEFINITION: a field-laborer; then: a laborer, workman in general.
ORIGIN: From ergon; a toiler; figuratively, a teacher.

DEFINITION: work, task, employment; a deed, action; that which is wrought or made, a work.
ORIGIN: From a primary (but obsolete) ergo (to work); toil (as an effort or occupation); by implication, an act.

DEFINITION: to stir up, arouse to anger, provoke, irritate, incite.
ORIGIN: From a presumed prolonged form of eris; to stimulate (especially to anger).

DEFINITION: to stick fast, prop, fix firmly.
ORIGIN: Of obscure affinity; to prop, i.e. (reflexively) get fast.

DEFINITION: (lit: to belch forth, hence) to utter, declare.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; to belch, i.e. (figuratively) to speak out.

DEFINITION: to search diligently, examine.
ORIGIN: Apparently from ereo (through the idea of inquiry); to seek, i.e. (figuratively) to investigate.

DEFINITION: (denoting speech in progress), (a) to say, speak; to mean, mention, tell, (b) to call, name, especially in the pass., (c) to tell, command.
ORIGIN: Probably a fuller form of rheo; an alternate for epo in certain tenses; to utter, i.e. Speak or say.

DEFINITION: a desert place, desert, uninhabited region.
ORIGIN: From eremos; solitude (concretely).

DEFINITION: as an adj: deserted, desolate, waste; hence: the desert, to the east and south of Palestine; of a person: deserted, abandoned, desolate.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; lonesome, i.e. (by implication) waste (usually as a noun, chora being implied).

DEFINITION: (a) to make desolate, bring to desolation, destroy, waste, (b) of a person: to strip, rob.
ORIGIN: From eremos; to lay waste (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: (bring to, make) desolate(-ion), come to nought.

DEFINITION: a desolation, devastation.
ORIGIN: From eremoo; despoliation.

DEFINITION: to contend, dispute, wrangle, strive.
ORIGIN: From eris; to wrangle.

DEFINITION: (the seeking of followers and adherents by means of gifts, the seeking of followers, hence) ambition, rivalry, self-seeking; a feud, faction.
ORIGIN: Perhaps as the same as erethizo; properly, intrigue, i.e. (by implication) faction.

DEFINITION: wool.
ORIGIN: Of obscure affinity; wool.

DEFINITION: contention, strife, wrangling.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a quarrel, i.e. (by implication) wrangling.

DEFINITION: a little young goat.
ORIGIN: From eriphos; a kidling, i.e. (genitive case) goat (symbolically, wicked person).

DEFINITION: a young goat.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from the same as erion (through the idea of hairiness); a kid or (genitive case) goat.

DEFINITION: Hermas, a Christian at Rome.
ORIGIN: Probably from Hermes; Hermas, a Christian.

DEFINITION: translation, interpretation, explanation.
ORIGIN: From the same as hermeneuo; translation.

DEFINITION: (a) to translate, explain, (b) to interpret the meaning of.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of Hermes (as the god of language); to translate.

DEFINITION: (a) Hermes, the messenger and herald of the Greek gods, or rather the corresponding Lycaonian deity, (b) Hermes, a Roman Christian.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from ereo; Hermes, the name of the messenger of the Greek deities; also of a Christian.

DEFINITION: "born of Hermes", Hermogenes, one who deserted Paul.
ORIGIN: From Hermes and ginomai; born of Hermes; Hermogenes, an apostate Christian.

DEFINITION: a creeping creature, reptile, especially a serpent.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of herpo (to creep); a reptile, i.e. (by Hebraism (compare remes)) a small animal.

DEFINITION: red.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; red, i.e. (with thalassa) the Red Sea.

DEFINITION: to come, go.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of a primary verb (used only in the present and imperfect tenses, the others being supplied by a kindred (middle voice) eleuthomai el-yoo'-thom-ahee, or (active) eltho el'-tho, which do not otherwise occur) to come or go (in a great variety of applications, literally and figuratively).
USAGE: accompany, appear, bring, come, enter, fall out, go, grow, X light, X next, pass, resort, be set.

DEFINITION: (a) to ask (a question), question, (b) to request, make a request to, pray.
ORIGIN: Apparently from ereo (compare ereunao); to interrogate; by implication, to request.
USAGE: ask, beseech, desire, intreat, pray. Compare punthanomai.

DEFINITION: clothing, raiment, vestment, robe.
ORIGIN: From hennumi (to clothe); dress.

DEFINITION: clothing, a garment.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of esthes; clothing (concretely).

DEFINITION: to eat, partake of food; met: to devour, consume (e.g. as rust does).
ORIGIN: Strengthened for a primary edo (to eat); used only in certain tenses, the rest being supplied by phago; to eat (usually literal).

DEFINITION: Esli, son of Naggai and father of Nahum.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (probably for Elyhow'eynay); Esli, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: are, be, have our being, have hope.
ORIGIN: First person plural indicative of eimi; we are.
USAGE: are, be, have our being, X have hope, + (the gospel) was (preached unto) us.

DEFINITION: should be, shall come to pass, may have.
ORIGIN: Future of eimi; will be.
USAGE: shall (should) be (have), (shall) come (to pass), X may have, X fall, what would follow, X live long, X sojourn.

DEFINITION: a mirror, looking-glass (made of highly polished metal).
ORIGIN: From eis and a presumed derivative of optanomai; a mirror (for looking into).

DEFINITION: evening.
ORIGIN: Feminine of an adjective hesperos (evening); the eve (hora being implied).

DEFINITION: Hezron, son of Perez, father of Ram.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Chetsrown); Esrom (i.e. Chetsron), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: be, have been, belong.
ORIGIN: Second person plural present indicative of eimi; ye are.

DEFINITION: are, belong, call, come, consist.
ORIGIN: Third person singular present indicative of eimi; he (she or it) is; also (with neuter plural) they are.
USAGE: are, be(-long), call, X can(-not), come, consisteth, X dure for a while, + follow, X have, (that) is (to say), make, meaneth, X must needs, + profit, + remaineth, + wrestle.

DEFINITION: be.
ORIGIN: Second person singular present imperative of eimi; be thou; also estosan es'-to-san, third person of the same let them be.

DEFINITION: last, at the last, finally, till the end.
ORIGIN: A superlative probably from echo (in the sense of contiguity); farthest, final (of place or time).
USAGE: ends of, last, latter end, lowest, uttermost.

DEFINITION: extremely, utterly; to be at the extremity, to be in extremis, to be at the last grasp.
ORIGIN: Adverb from eschatos; finally, i.e. (with echo) at the extremity of life.

DEFINITION: within, inside, with verbs either of rest or of motion; prep: within, to within, inside.
ORIGIN: From eis; inside (as preposition or adjective).

DEFINITION: (a) from within, from inside, (b) within, inside; with the article: the inner part, the inner element, (c) the mind, soul.
ORIGIN: From eso; from inside; also used as equivalent to eso (inside).

DEFINITION: inner; with the article: the part that is within.
ORIGIN: Comparative of eso; interior.

DEFINITION: a companion, comrade, friend.
ORIGIN: From etes (a clansman); a comrade.

DEFINITION: speaking another language; subst: one who speaks another language.
ORIGIN: From heteros and glossa; other- tongued, i.e. A foreigner.

DEFINITION: to teach different things, that is, different from the true or necessary teaching.
ORIGIN: From heteros and didaskalos; to instruct differently.

DEFINITION: to be yoked with one different from myself, unequally yoked.
ORIGIN: From a compound of heteros and zugos; to yoke up differently, i.e. (figuratively) to associate discordantly.

DEFINITION: (a) of two: another, a second, (b) other, different, (c) one's neighbor.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; (an-, the) other or different.
USAGE: altered, else, next (day), one, (an-)other, some, strange.

DEFINITION: otherwise, differently.
ORIGIN: Adverb from heteros; differently.

DEFINITION: (a) of time: still, yet, even now, (b) of degree: even, further, more, in addition.
ORIGIN: Perhaps akin to etos; "yet," still (of time or degree).
USAGE: after that, also, ever, (any) further, (t-)henceforth (more), hereafter, (any) longer, (any) more(-one), now, still, yet.

DEFINITION: to make ready, prepare.
ORIGIN: From hetoimos; to prepare.
USAGE: prepare, provide, make ready. Compare kataskeuazo.

DEFINITION: foundation, firm footing; preparation, readiness.
ORIGIN: From hetoimazo; preparation.

DEFINITION: ready, prepared.
ORIGIN: From an old noun heteos (fitness); adjusted, i.e. Ready.

DEFINITION: readily.
ORIGIN: Adverb from hetoimos; in readiness.

DEFINITION: a year.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a year.

DEFINITION: well, well done, good, rightly; also used as an exclamation.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a primary eus (good); (adverbially) well.

DEFINITION: Eve, the first woman; wife of first man Adam.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Chavvah); Eua (or Eva, i.e. Chavvah), the first woman.

DEFINITION: to bring good news, preach good tidings, with or without an object, expressing either the persons who receive the good news or the good news itself (the good news being sometimes expressed as a person).
ORIGIN: From eu and aggelos; to announce good news ("evangelize") especially the gospel.
USAGE: declare, bring (declare, show) glad (good) tidings, preach (the gospel).

DEFINITION: the good news of the coming of the Messiah, the gospel; the gen. after it expresses sometimes the giver (God), sometimes the subject (the Messiah, etc.), sometimes the human transmitter (an apostle).
ORIGIN: From the same as euaggelizo; a good message, i.e. The gospel.

DEFINITION: an evangelist, a missionary, bearer of good tidings.
ORIGIN: From euaggelizo; a preacher of the gospel.

DEFINITION: to give pleasure to, please (perhaps with the added idea of: rendering good service to).
ORIGIN: From euarestos; to gratify entirely.

DEFINITION: acceptable, well-pleasing (especially to God), grateful.
ORIGIN: From eu and arestos; fully agreeable.

DEFINITION: acceptably, in a well-pleasing way.
ORIGIN: Adverb from euarestos; quite agreeably.

DEFINITION: Eubulus, a Christian with Paul in Rome.
ORIGIN: From eu and boulomai; good-willer; Eubulus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: (a) of noble birth, of high birth, (b) noble in nature.
ORIGIN: From eu and ginomai; well born, i.e. (literally) high in rank, or (figuratively) generous.

DEFINITION: fair weather, good weather.
ORIGIN: Feminine from eu and the alternate of Zeus (as the god of the weather); a clear sky, i.e. Fine weather.

DEFINITION: to be well-pleased, think it good, be resolved.
ORIGIN: From eu and dokeo; to think well of, i.e. Approve (an act); specially, to approbate (a person or thing).
USAGE: think good, (be well) please(-d), be the good (have, take) pleasure, be willing.

DEFINITION: (a) good-will (good-pleasure), favor, feeling of complacency of God to man, (b) good-pleasure, satisfaction, happiness, delight of men.
ORIGIN: From a presumed compound of eu and the base of dokeo; satisfaction, i.e. (subjectively) delight, or (objectively) kindness, wish, purpose.
USAGE: desire, good pleasure (will), X seem good.

DEFINITION: good action, well-doing, benefiting, kind service.
ORIGIN: From euergetes; beneficence (genitive case or specially).

DEFINITION: to do good deeds, perform kind service, benefit.
ORIGIN: From euergetes; to be philanthropic.

DEFINITION: a doer of good, a benefactor.
ORIGIN: From eu and the base of ergon; a worker of good, i.e. (specially) a philanthropist.

DEFINITION: well-placed, ready for use.
ORIGIN: From eu and a derivative of tithemi; well placed, i.e. (figuratively) appropriate.

DEFINITION: immediately, soon, at once.
ORIGIN: Adverb from euthus; directly, i.e. At once or soon.
USAGE: anon, as soon as, forthwith, immediately, shortly, straightway.

DEFINITION: to run a straight course.
ORIGIN: From euthus and dromos; to lay a straight course, i.e. Sail direct.

DEFINITION: to keep up spirit, be cheerful, be of good courage.
ORIGIN: From euthumos; to cheer up, i.e. (intransitively) be cheerful; neuter comparative (adverbially) more cheerfully.

DEFINITION: cheerful, having good courage.
ORIGIN: From eu and thumos; in fine spirits, i.e. Cheerful.
USAGE: of good cheer, the more cheerfully.

DEFINITION: (a) to make straight (of the direction, not the surface, of a road), (b) to guide, steer.
ORIGIN: From euthus; to straighten (level); technically, to steer.

DEFINITION: adj: (a) straight of direction, as opposed to crooked, (b) upright; adv: immediately.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from eu and tithemi; straight, i.e. (literally) level, or (figuratively) true; adverbially (of time) at once.
USAGE: anon, by and by, forthwith, immediately, straightway.

DEFINITION: straightness, uprightness.
ORIGIN: From euthus; rectitude.

DEFINITION: to have a good (favorable) opportunity, have leisure; to devote leisure to.
ORIGIN: From eukairos; to have good time, i.e. Opportunity or leisure.

DEFINITION: a convenient time, opportunity.
ORIGIN: From eukairos; a favorable occasion.

DEFINITION: opportune, timely, suitable; perhaps sometimes: holiday, festival.
ORIGIN: From eu and kairos; well-timed, i.e. Opportune.

DEFINITION: opportunely, in season, conveniently.
ORIGIN: Adverb from eukairos; opportunely.

DEFINITION: with easier labor.
ORIGIN: Comparative of a compound of eu and kopos; better for toil, i.e. More facile.

DEFINITION: reverence, fear of God, piety.
ORIGIN: From eulabes; properly, caution, i.e. (religiously) reverence (piety); by implication, dread (concretely).

DEFINITION: to fear, be anxious, be cautious; to reverence.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from eulabes; to be circumspect, i.e. (by implication) to be apprehensive; religiously, to reverence.

DEFINITION: (lit: handling well, hence) cautious, circumspect; hence: God-fearing, pious.
ORIGIN: From eu and lambano; taking well (carefully), i.e. Circumspect (religiously, pious).
