DEFINITION: (lit: to speak well of) to bless; pass: to be blessed.
ORIGIN: From a compound of eu and logos; to speak well of, i.e. (religiously) to bless (thank or invoke a benediction upon, prosper).

DEFINITION: (used only of God), blessed (as entitled to receive blessing from man), worthy of praise.
ORIGIN: From eulogeo; adorable.

DEFINITION: adulation, praise, blessing, gift.
ORIGIN: From the same as eulogeo; fine speaking, i.e. Elegance of language; commendation ("eulogy"), i.e. (reverentially) adoration; religiously, benediction; by implication, consecration; by extension, benefit or largess.
USAGE: blessing (a matter of) bounty (X -tifully), fair speech.

DEFINITION: willingly sharing, ready to impart, generous.
ORIGIN: From eu and a presumed derivative of metadidomi; good at imparting, i.e. Liberal.

DEFINITION: "victorious", Eunice, the mother of Timothy.
ORIGIN: From eu and nike; victorious; Eunice, a Jewess.

DEFINITION: to think kindly of, to be favorable.
ORIGIN: From a compound of eu and nous; to be well- minded, i.e. Reconcile.

DEFINITION: good-will, kindliness; enthusiasm.
ORIGIN: From the same as eunoeo; kindness; euphemistically, conjugal duty.

DEFINITION: to make into a eunuch, emasculate, castrate.
ORIGIN: From eunouchos; to castrate (figuratively, live unmarried).

DEFINITION: (a) a chamberlain, keeper of the bed-chamber of an eastern potentate, eunuch, (b) a eunuch, castrated person, or one who voluntarily abstains from marriage.
ORIGIN: From eune (a bed) and echo; a castrated person (such being employed in Oriental bed-chambers); by extension an impotent or unmarried man; by implication, a chamberlain (state-officer).

DEFINITION: Euodia, or rather Euhodia, a Christian woman of Philippi.
ORIGIN: From the same as euodoo; fine travelling; Euodia, a Christian woman.

DEFINITION: to cause to prosper, pass: to have a happy (successful) journey, hence: to prosper.
ORIGIN: From a compound of eu and hodos; to help on the road, i.e. (passively) succeed in reaching; figuratively, to succeed in business affairs.

DEFINITION: compliant, ready to obey.
ORIGIN: From eu and peitho; good for persuasion, i.e. (intransitively) complaint.

DEFINITION: easily surrounding, encircling, easily distracted.
ORIGIN: From eu and a derivative of a presumed compound of peri and histemi; well standing around, i.e. (a competitor) thwarting (a racer) in every direction (figuratively, of sin in genitive case).

DEFINITION: good-doing, doing of good.
ORIGIN: From a compound of eu and poieo; well-doing, i.e. Beneficence.

DEFINITION: to have means, be prosperous, enjoy plenty.
ORIGIN: From a compound of hetoimazo and the base of poreia; (intransitively) to be good for passing through, i.e. (figuratively) have pecuniary means.

DEFINITION: wealth, gain, plenty.
ORIGIN: From the same as euporeo; pecuniary resources.

DEFINITION: beauty, gracefulness, comeliness.
ORIGIN: From a compound of eu and prepo; good suitableness, i.e. Gracefulness.

DEFINITION: well-received, acceptable, welcome, pleasing.
ORIGIN: From eu and a derivative of prosdechomai; well-received, i.e. Approved, favorable.

DEFINITION: constantly attending to, devoted.
ORIGIN: From eu and the same as prosedreuo; sitting well towards, i.e. (figuratively) assiduous (neuter, diligent service).

DEFINITION: to look well, make a fair show (a good outward appearance, and so win good opinion).
ORIGIN: From a compound of eu and prosopon; to be of good countenance, i.e. (figuratively) to make a display.

DEFINITION: to find, learn, discover, especially after searching.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary heuro (hyoo'-ro), which (together with another cognate form) heureo (hyoo-reh'-o) is used for it in all the tenses except the present and imperfect to find (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: A prolonged form of a primary heuro (hyoo'-ro), which (together with another cognate form) heureo (hyoo-reh'-o) is used for it in all the tenses except the present and imperfect to find (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: Euroklydon, northeast wind.
ORIGIN: From Euros (the east wind) and kludon; a storm from the East (or southeast), i.e. (in modern phrase) a Levanter.

DEFINITION: broad, spacious, wide.
ORIGIN: From eurus (wide) and chora; spacious.

DEFINITION: piety (towards God), godliness, devotion, godliness.
ORIGIN: From eusebes; piety; specially, the gospel scheme.

DEFINITION: to be dutiful, pious, show piety towards, worship.
ORIGIN: From eusebes; to be pious, i.e. (towards God) to worship, or (towards parents) to respect (support).

DEFINITION: pious, God-fearing, devout.
ORIGIN: From eu and sebomai; well-reverent, i.e. Pious.

DEFINITION: piously, religiously.
ORIGIN: Adverb from eusebes; piously.

DEFINITION: with clear meaning, intelligible, clear to the understanding.
ORIGIN: From eu and the base of semaino; well indicated, i.e. (figuratively) significant.

DEFINITION: tender-hearted, merciful, compassionate.
ORIGIN: From eu and splagchnon; well compassioned, i.e. Sympathetic.

DEFINITION: becomingly, decorously, decently.
ORIGIN: Adverb from euschemon; decorously.

DEFINITION: decorum, becomingness, embellishment.
ORIGIN: From euschemon; decorousness.

DEFINITION: (a) comely, seemly, decorous, (b) of honorable position (in society), wealthy, influential.
ORIGIN: From eu and schema; well-formed, i.e. (figuratively) decorous, noble (in rank).

DEFINITION: in a well-strung manner, vigorously.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a compound of eu and a derivative of teino (to stretch); in a well-strung manner, i.e. (figuratively) intensely (in a good sense, cogently; in a bad one, fiercely).

DEFINITION: ready wit, coarse jesting.
ORIGIN: From a compound of eu and a derivative of the base of trope (meaning well-turned, i.e. Ready at repartee, jocose); witticism, i.e. (in a vulgar sense) ribaldry.

DEFINITION: "well-fated", Eutychus, a young man restored to life by Paul.
ORIGIN: From eu and a derivative of tugchano; well- fated, i.e. Fortunate; Eutychus, a young man.

DEFINITION: commendation, good report, praise.
ORIGIN: From euphemos; good language ("euphemy"), i.e. Praise (repute).

DEFINITION: well reported of, spoken in a kindly spirit, laudable, reputable.
ORIGIN: From eu and pheme; well spoken of, i.e. Reputable.

DEFINITION: to bear well, bring a good harvest, yield abundantly.
ORIGIN: From eu and phoreo; to bear well, i.e. Be fertile.

DEFINITION: to cheer, make glad; generally mid. or pass: to be glad, make merry, revel, feast.
ORIGIN: From eu and phren; to put (middle voice or passively, be) in a good frame of mind, i.e. Rejoice.
USAGE: fare, make glad, be (make) merry, rejoice.

DEFINITION: the Euphrates, boundary river of the province Syria.
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin (compare Prath); Euphrates, a river of Asia.

DEFINITION: joy, gladness, rejoicing.
ORIGIN: From the same as euphraino; joyfulness.

DEFINITION: to thank, give thanks; pass. 3 sing: is received with thanks.
ORIGIN: From eucharistos; to be grateful, i.e. (actively) to express gratitude (towards); specially, to say grace at a meal.

DEFINITION: thankfulness, gratitude; giving of thanks, thanksgiving.
ORIGIN: From eucharistos; gratitude; actively, grateful language (to God, as an act of worship).

DEFINITION: thankful, grateful.
ORIGIN: From eu and a derivative of charizomai; well favored, i.e. (by implication) grateful.

DEFINITION: a prayer comprising a vow; a prayer, vow.
ORIGIN: From euchomai; properly, a wish, expressed as a petition to God, or in votive obligation.

DEFINITION: to pray, wish.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of a primary verb; to wish; by implication, to pray to God.

DEFINITION: useful, serviceable, very profitable.
ORIGIN: From eu and chrestos; easily used, i.e. Useful.

DEFINITION: to be of good courage.
ORIGIN: From a compound of eu and psuche; to be in good spirits, i.e. Feel encouraged.

DEFINITION: a sweet smell, fragrance.
ORIGIN: From a compound of eu and a derivative of ozo; good-scentedness, i.e. Fragrance.

DEFINITION: (lit: well-named, to avoid the evil omen attaching to the left), on the left-hand side, left.
ORIGIN: From eu and onoma; properly, well-named (good-omened), i.e. The left (which was the lucky side among the pagan Greeks); neuter as adverbial, at the left hand.

DEFINITION: to leap upon, assault.
ORIGIN: From epi and hallomai; to spring upon.

DEFINITION: once, once for all; at once.
ORIGIN: From epi and hapax; upon one occasion (only).

DEFINITION: of Ephesus.
ORIGIN: From Ephesos; Ephesine, or situated at Ephesus.

DEFINITION: Ephesian, of Ephesus.
ORIGIN: From Ephesos; an Ephesian or inhabitant of Ephesus.

DEFINITION: Ephesus, a coast city, capital of the Roman province Asia.
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin; Ephesus, a city of Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: an inventor, contriver, discoverer.
ORIGIN: From a compound of epi and heurisko; a discoverer, i.e. Contriver.

DEFINITION: a class of priests who served for a stated number of days.
ORIGIN: From ephemeros; diurnality, i.e. (specially) the quotidian rotation or class of the Jewish priests' service at the Temple, as distributed by families.

DEFINITION: for the day, daily, necessary for every day.
ORIGIN: From epi and hemera; for a day ("ephemeral"), i.e. Diurnal.

DEFINITION: to come to, reach as far as.
ORIGIN: From epi and a cognate of heko; to arrive upon, i.e. Extend to.

DEFINITION: to stand by, be urgent, befall one (as of evil), be at hand, impend.
ORIGIN: From epi and histemi; to stand upon, i.e. Be present (in various applications, friendly or otherwise, usually literal).
USAGE: assault, come (in, to, unto, upon), be at hand (instant), present, stand (before, by, over).

DEFINITION: Ephraim, a city near Jer.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Ephrayim or better Ephrown); Ephraim, a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: (Aramaic, meaning) be opened up.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (pthach); be opened!.

DEFINITION: enmity, hostility, alienation.
ORIGIN: Feminine of echthros; hostility; by implication, a reason for opposition.

DEFINITION: hated, hostile; subst: an enemy.
ORIGIN: From a primary echtho (to hate); hateful (passively, odious, or actively, hostile); usually as a noun, an adversary (especially Satan).

DEFINITION: a serpent, snake, viper.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain origin; an adder or other poisonous snake (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to have, hold, possess.
ORIGIN: Including an alternate form scheo skheh'-o; (used in certain tenses only); a primary verb; to hold (used in very various applications, literally or figuratively, direct or remote; such as possession; ability, contiuity, relation, or condition).
USAGE: be (able, X hold, possessed with), accompany, + begin to amend, can(+ -not), X conceive, count, diseased, do + eat, + enjoy, + fear, following, have, hold, keep, + lack, + go to law, lie, + must needs, + of necessity, + need, next, + recover, + reign, + rest, + return, X sick, take for, + tremble, + uncircumcised, use.

DEFINITION: (a) conj: until, (b) prep: as far as, up to, as much as, until.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a conjunction, preposition and adverb of continuance, until (of time and place).
USAGE: even (until, unto), (as) far (as), how long, (un-)til(-l), (hither-, un-, up) to, while(-s).

DEFINITION: Zebulon, one of the sons of Jacob, and founder of one of the twelve tribes.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Zbuwluwn); Zabulon (i.e. Zebulon), a region of Palestine.

DEFINITION: Zacchaeus, a Jewish tax-gatherer.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (compare Zakkay); Zacchaeus, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Zerah, son of Judah and Tamar.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Zerach); Zara, (i.e. Zerach), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Zechariah, (a) a priest referred to as a son of Jehoiada, (b) another priest, father of John the Baptist.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Zkaryah); Zacharias (i.e. Zechariah), the name of two Israelites.

DEFINITION: to live, be alive.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to live (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: Zebedee, the father of the apostles James and John.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (compare Zabdiy); Zebedaeus, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: boiling hot; met: fervent.
ORIGIN: From zeo; boiled, i.e. (by implication) calid (figuratively, fervent).

DEFINITION: a yoke, team; hence: a pair.
ORIGIN: From the same as zugos; a couple, i.e. A team (of oxen yoked together) or brace (of birds tied together).

DEFINITION: a band, fastening.
ORIGIN: Feminine of a derivative (at the second stage) from the same as zugos; a fastening (tiller-rope).

DEFINITION: Zeus, the Greek god of the sky in all its manifestations, corresponding to the Roman Jupiter and to the leading god of the native Lycaonians.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; in the oblique cases there is used instead of it a (probably cognate) name; Dis (deece), which is otherwise obsolete; Zeus or Dis (among the Latins, Jupiter or Jove), the supreme deity of the Greeks.

DEFINITION: (lit: to boil, be boiling), to burn (in spirit), be fervent.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to be hot (boil, of liquids; or glow, of solids), i.e. (figuratively) be fervid (earnest).

DEFINITION: to have warmth of feeling for or against, to be zealous or jealous.
ORIGIN: From zeo; properly, heat, i.e. (figuratively) "zeal" (in a favorable sense, ardor; in an unfavorable one, jealousy, as of a husband (figuratively, of God), or an enemy, malice).
USAGE: emulation, envy(-ing), fervent mind, indignation, jealousy, zeal.

DEFINITION: (a) intrans: to be jealous, (b) trans: to be jealous of, with acc. of a person; to be eager for, be eager to possess, with acc. of a thing.
ORIGIN: From zelos; to have warmth of feeling for or against.
USAGE: affect, covet (earnestly), (have) desire, (move with) envy, be jealous over, (be) zealous(-ly affect).

DEFINITION: one who is eagerly devoted to a person or a thing, a zealot.
ORIGIN: From zeloo; a "zealot".

DEFINITION: the Zealot, a member of a Jewish political party.
ORIGIN: The same as Zelotes; a Zealot, i.e. (specially) partisan for Jewish political independence.

DEFINITION: damage, loss, detriment.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to the base of damazo (through the idea of violence); detriment.

DEFINITION: to inflict loss (damage) upon, fine, punish, sometimes with the acc. of the penalty, even when the verb is passive.
ORIGIN: From zemia; to injure, i.e. (reflexively or passively) to experience detriment.
USAGE: be cast away, receive damage, lose, suffer loss.

DEFINITION: "Zeus-given", Zenas, a Christian lawyer.
ORIGIN: Probably contracted from a poetic form of Zeus and doron; Jove-given; Zenas, a Christian.

DEFINITION: to seek, search for, desire, require, demand.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; to seek (literally or figuratively); specially, (by Hebraism) to worship (God), or (in a bad sense) to plot (against life).
USAGE: be (go) about, desire, endeavour, enquire (for), require, (X will) seek (after, for, means). Compare punthanomai.

DEFINITION: a question, subject of inquiry, dispute.
ORIGIN: From zeteo; a search (properly concretely), i.e. (in words) a debate.

DEFINITION: a question, debate, controversy; a seeking, search.
ORIGIN: From zeteo; a searching (properly, the act), i.e. A dispute or its theme.

DEFINITION: spurious wheat, darnel; a plant that grows in Palestine which resembles wheat in many ways but is worthless.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain origin; darnel or false grain.

DEFINITION: Zerubbabel, son of Shealtiel (Salathiel) and father of Abiud and Rhesa.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Zrubbabel); Zorobabel (i.e. Zerubbabel), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: darkness, murkiness, gloom.
ORIGIN: Akin to the base of nephos; gloom (as shrouding like a cloud).

DEFINITION: a yoke; hence met: (a Jewish idea) of a heavy burden, comparable to the heavy yokes resting on the bullocks' necks; a balance, pair of scales.
ORIGIN: From the root of zeugnumi (to join, especially by a "yoke"); a coupling, i.e. (figuratively) servitude (a law or obligation); also (literally) the beam of the balance (as connecting the scales).

DEFINITION: leaven, ferment, both lit. and met.
ORIGIN: Probably from zeo; ferment (as if boiling up).

DEFINITION: to leaven, ferment.
ORIGIN: From zume; to cause to ferment.

DEFINITION: to capture alive, capture for life, enthrall.
ORIGIN: From the same as zoon and agreuo; to take alive (make a prisoner of war), i.e. (figuratively) to capture or ensnare.

DEFINITION: life, both of physical (present) and of spiritual (particularly future) existence.
ORIGIN: From zao; life (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a girdle, belt, waistband; because the purse was kept there, also: a purse.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to the base of zugos; a belt; by implication, a pocket.

DEFINITION: to gird, put on the girdle, especially as preparatory to active work.
ORIGIN: From zone; to bind about (especially with a belt).

DEFINITION: to preserve alive (lit: bring to birth), save.
ORIGIN: From the same as zoon and a derivative of ginomai; to engender alive, i.e. (by analogy) to rescue (passively, be saved) from death.

DEFINITION: an animal, living creature.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of zao; a live thing, i.e. An animal.

DEFINITION: to make that which was dead to live, cause to live, quicken.
ORIGIN: From the same as zoon and poieo; to (re-)vitalize (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: or, than.
ORIGIN: A primary particle of distinction between two connected terms; disjunctive, or; comparative, than.
USAGE: and, but (either), (n-)either, except it be, (n-)or (else), rather, save, than, that, what, yea. Often used in connection with other particles. Compare especially ede, eper, etoi.

DEFINITION: truly, surely.
ORIGIN: An adverb of confirmation; perhaps intensive of e; used only (in the New Testament) before men; assuredly.

DEFINITION: to command.
ORIGIN: From hegemon; to act as ruler.

DEFINITION: rule, authority, sovereignty; a reign.
ORIGIN: From hegemon; government, i.e. (in time) official term.

DEFINITION: a leader, guide; a commander; a governor (of a province); plur: leaders.
ORIGIN: From hegeomai; a leader, i.e. Chief person (or figuratively, place) of a province.

DEFINITION: (a) to lead, (b) to think, be of opinion, suppose, consider.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of a (presumed) strengthened form of ago; to lead, i.e. Command (with official authority); figuratively, to deem, i.e. Consider.
USAGE: account, (be) chief, count, esteem, governor, judge, have the rule over, suppose, think.

DEFINITION: gladly, pleasantly, with pleasure.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a derivative of the base of hedone; sweetly, i.e. (figuratively) with pleasure.

DEFINITION: already; now at length, now after all this waiting.
ORIGIN: Apparently from e (or possibly e) and de; even now.

DEFINITION: most gladly, most pleasantly.
ORIGIN: Neuter plural of the superlative of the same as hedeos; with great pleasure.

DEFINITION: pleasure, a pleasure, especially sensuous pleasure; a strong desire, passion.
ORIGIN: From handano (to please); sensual delight; by implication, desire.

DEFINITION: mint, peppermint.
ORIGIN: Neuter of the compound of the same as hedeos and osme; a sweet-scented plant, i.e. Mint.

DEFINITION: habit, manner, custom, morals.
ORIGIN: A strengthened form of ethos; usage, i.e. (plural) moral habits.

DEFINITION: to have come, be present, have arrived.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to arrive, i.e. Be present (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: Eli, God (Hebrew).
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('el with pronominal suffix); my God.

DEFINITION: Heli, an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Eliy); Heli (i.e. Eli), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Elijah, an Israelite prophet.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Eliyah); Helias (i.e. Elijah), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: age, term of life; full age, maturity; stature.
ORIGIN: From the same as helikos; maturity (in years or size).

DEFINITION: of which size, of what size, how small, how much.
ORIGIN: From helix (a comrade, i.e. One of the same age); as big as, i.e. (interjectively) how much.

DEFINITION: the sun, sunlight.
ORIGIN: From hele (a ray; perhaps akin to the alternate of haireomai); the sun; by implication, light.

DEFINITION: a nail.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a stud, i.e. Spike.

DEFINITION: our, us, we.
ORIGIN: Accusative case plural of ego; us.

DEFINITION: us, we ourselves.
ORIGIN: Nominative plural of ego; we (only used when emphatic).

DEFINITION: a day, the period from sunrise to sunset.
ORIGIN: Feminine (with hora implied) of a derivative of hemai (to sit; akin to the base of hedraios) meaning tame, i.e. Gentle; day, i.e. (literally) the time space between dawn and dark, or the whole aganaktesis hours (but several days were usually reckoned by the Jews as inclusive of the parts of both extremes); figuratively, a period (always defined more or less clearly by the context).
USAGE: age, + alway, (mid-)day (by day, (-ly)), + for ever, judgment, (day) time, while, years.

DEFINITION: our, our own.
ORIGIN: From thnetos; our.

DEFINITION: I was.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of thriambeuo; I was.

DEFINITION: half dead.
ORIGIN: From a presumed compound of the base of hemisu and thnesko; half dead, i.e. Entirely exhausted.

DEFINITION: our, for us, we.
ORIGIN: Dative case plural of ego; to (or for, with, by) us.

DEFINITION: half.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative from an inseparable prefix akin to hama (through the idea of partition involved in connection) and meaning semi-; (as noun) half.

DEFINITION: half an hour.
ORIGIN: From the base of hemisu and hora; a half-hour.

DEFINITION: our company, us, we.
ORIGIN: Genitive case plural of ego; of (or from) us.

DEFINITION: agree, be, have charge of, hold, use.
ORIGIN: Imperfect of eimi; I (thou, etc.) Was (wast or were).
USAGE: + agree, be, X have (+ charge of), hold, use, was(-t), were.

DEFINITION: when, whenever, at which time.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; at which time.

DEFINITION: than.
ORIGIN: From e and per; than at all (or than perhaps, than indeed).

DEFINITION: placid, gentle, mild.
ORIGIN: Probably from epos; properly, affable, i.e. Mild or kind.

DEFINITION: Er, son of Joshua and father of Elmadam.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Er); Er, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: quiet, tranquil.
ORIGIN: Perhaps by transposition from eremos (through the idea of stillness); tranquil.

DEFINITION: Herod; four persons are called by this name: Herod the Great, Herod Antipas, Herod Agrippa, and Herod Agrippa the younger.
ORIGIN: Compound of heros (a "hero") and eidos; heroic; Herod, the name of four Jewish kings.

DEFINITION: the Herodians, the partisans of Herod (Antipas).
ORIGIN: Plural of a derivative of Herodes; Herodians, i.e. Partisans of Herod.

DEFINITION: Herodias (died after A.D. 40), daughter of Aristobulus and granddaughter of Herod to, wife, first, of her uncle Herod, second, of his half-brother, her uncle Herod Antipas.
ORIGIN: From Herodes; Herodias, a woman of the Heodian family.

DEFINITION: Herodion, a Christian in Rome, a relative of Paul.
ORIGIN: From Herodes; Herodion, a Christian.

DEFINITION: Isaiah, an Israelite prophet.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Ysha'yah); Hesaias (i.e. Jeshajah), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Esau, elder son of Isaac the patriarch, brother of Jacob.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Esav); Esau, an Edomite.

DEFINITION: to rest from work, cease from altercation, be silent, live quietly.
ORIGIN: From the same as hesuchios; to keep still (intransitively), i.e. Refrain from labor, meddlesomeness or speech.
USAGE: cease, hold peace, be quiet, rest.

DEFINITION: quietness, stillness, silence.
ORIGIN: Feminine of hesuchios; (as noun) stillness, i.e. Desistance from bustle or language.

DEFINITION: quiet, tranquil, peaceful.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a compound probably of a derivative of the base of hedraios and perhaps echo; properly, keeping one's seat (sedentary), i.e. (by implication) still (undisturbed, undisturbing).

DEFINITION: whether.
ORIGIN: From e and toi; either indeed.

DEFINITION: to be defeated, be overcome, be made inferior.
ORIGIN: From the same as hetton; to make worse, i.e. Vanquish (literally or figuratively); by implication, to rate lower.

DEFINITION: defect, loss, defeat, failure, shortcoming.
ORIGIN: From hettao; a deterioration, i.e. (objectively) failure or (subjectively) loss.

DEFINITION: lesser, inferior, weaker.
ORIGIN: Neuter of comparative of heka (slightly) used for that of kakos; worse (as noun); by implication, less (as adverb).

DEFINITION: let be.
ORIGIN: Third person singular imperative of eimi; let him (or it) be.

DEFINITION: to make a sound, give forth a sound, sound (when struck); to roar (as the sea).
ORIGIN: From echos; to make a loud noise, i.e. Reverberate.

DEFINITION: (a) a sound, noise, (b) a rumor, report.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a loud or confused noise ("echo"), i.e. Roar; figuratively, a rumor.

DEFINITION: Thaddaeus, one of the twelve apostles.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain origin; Thaddaeus, one of the Apostles.

DEFINITION: (a) the sea, in contrast to the land, (b) a particular sea or lake, e.g. the sea of Galilee (Tiberias), the Red Sea.
ORIGIN: Probably prolonged from hals; the sea (genitive case or specially).

DEFINITION: (properly: to warm, then) to cherish, nourish, foster, comfort.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to thallo (to warm); to brood, i.e. (figuratively) to foster.

DEFINITION: Tamar, mother of Perez and Zerah by Judah, son of Jacob.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Tamar); Thamar (i.e. Tamar), an Israelitess.

DEFINITION: to amaze; pass: to be amazed (almost terrified).
ORIGIN: From thambos; to stupefy (with surprise), i.e. Astound.

DEFINITION: astonishment, amazement (allied to terror or awe).
ORIGIN: Akin to an obsolete tapho (to dumbfound); stupefaction (by surprise), i.e. Astonishment.

DEFINITION: deadly, mortal, fatal.
ORIGIN: From thanatos; fatal, i.e. Poisonous.

DEFINITION: death-bringing, deadly.
ORIGIN: From (the feminine form of) thanatos and phero; death-bearing, i.e. Fatal.

DEFINITION: death, physical or spiritual.
ORIGIN: From thnesko; (properly, an adjective used as a noun) death (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to put to death, subdue; pass: to be in danger of death, be dead to, be rid of, be parted from.
ORIGIN: From thanatos to kill (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: become dead, (cause to be) put to death, kill, mortify.

DEFINITION: to bury.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to celebrate funeral rites, i.e. Inter.

DEFINITION: Terah, the father of Abraham.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Terach); Thara (i.e. Terach), the father of Abraham.

DEFINITION: to be courageous, confident, of good cheer.
ORIGIN: Another form for tharseo; to exercise courage.
USAGE: be bold, X boldly, have confidence, be confident. Compare tolmao.

DEFINITION: to be of good courage, good cheer, be bold.
ORIGIN: From tharsos; to have courage.
USAGE: be of good cheer (comfort). Compare tharrheo.

DEFINITION: courage, confidence.
ORIGIN: Akin (by transposition) to thrasos (daring); boldness (subjectively).

DEFINITION: (a) concr: a marvel, wonder, (b) abstr: wonder, amazement.
ORIGIN: Apparently from a form of theaomai; wonder (properly concrete; but by implication, abstract).

DEFINITION: (a) intrans: to wonder, marvel, (b) trans: to wonder at, admire.
ORIGIN: From thauma; to wonder; by implication, to admire.
USAGE: admire, have in admiration, marvel, wonder.

DEFINITION: wonderful, admirable; subst: a wonder.
ORIGIN: From thauma; wondrous, i.e. (neuter as noun) a miracle.

DEFINITION: to be wondered at, wonderful, marvelous.
ORIGIN: From thaumazo; wondered at, i.e. (by implication) wonderful.

DEFINITION: a goddess.
ORIGIN: Feminine of theos; a female deity.

DEFINITION: to see, behold, contemplate, look upon, view; to see, visit.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary verb; to look closely at, i.e. (by implication) perceive (literally or figuratively); by extension to visit.

DEFINITION: to make a public show of, expose to public shame.
ORIGIN: From theatron; to expose as a spectacle.

DEFINITION: (a) a theatre, a semi-circular stone building, generally open to the sky, (b) a spectacle, show.
ORIGIN: From theaomai; a place for public show ("theatre"), i.e. General audience-room; by implication, a show itself (figuratively).

DEFINITION: brimstone, sulfur.
ORIGIN: Probably neuter of theios (in its original sense of flashing); sulphur.

DEFINITION: divine; subst: the Deity.
ORIGIN: From theos.
USAGE: godlike (neuter as noun, divinity); divine, godhead.

DEFINITION: divinity, divine nature.
ORIGIN: From theios; divinity (abstractly).

DEFINITION: of brimstone, sulfurous.
ORIGIN: From theion and eidos; sulphur-like, i.e. Sulphurous.

DEFINITION: an act of will, will; plur: wishes, desires.
ORIGIN: From the prolonged form of ethelo; a determination (properly, the thing), i.e. (actively) choice (specially, purpose, decree; abstractly, volition) or (passively) inclination.

DEFINITION: a willing, will.
ORIGIN: From ethelo; determination (properly, the act), i.e. Option.

DEFINITION: to will, wish, desire, be willing, intend, design.
ORIGIN: Thel'-o or thel'-o or in certain tenses theleo thel-eh'-o, and etheleo eth-el-eh'-o, which are otherwise obsolete; apparently strengthened from the alternate form of haireomai; to determine (as an active option from subjective impulse; whereas boulomai properly denotes rather a passive acquiescence in objective considerations), i.e. Choose or prefer (literally or figuratively); by implication, to wish, i.e. Be inclined to (sometimes adverbially, gladly); impersonally for the future tense, to be about to; by Hebraism, to delight in.
USAGE: desire, be disposed (forward), intend, list, love, mean, please, have rather, (be) will (have, -ling, - ling(-ly)).

DEFINITION: (properly, an adj: belonging to the foundation), a foundation stone.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of tithemi; something put down, i.e. A substruction (of a building, etc.), (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to found, lay the foundation (lit. and met.).
ORIGIN: From themelios; to lay a basis for, i.e. (literally) erect, or (figuratively) consolidate.

DEFINITION: taught by God, divinely instructed.
ORIGIN: From theos and didasko; divinely instructed.

DEFINITION: to fight against God.
ORIGIN: From theomachos; to resist deity.

DEFINITION: fighting against God.
ORIGIN: From theos and machomai; an opponent of deity.

DEFINITION: God-breathed, inspired by God, due to the inspiration of God.
ORIGIN: From theos and a presumed derivative of pneo; divinely breathed in.

DEFINITION: (a) God, (b) a god, generally.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a deity, especially (with ho) the supreme Divinity; figuratively, a magistrate; by Hebraism, very.

DEFINITION: reverence for God, fear of God, godliness, piety.
ORIGIN: From theosebes; devoutness, i.e. Piety.

DEFINITION: devout, pious, God-fearing.
ORIGIN: From theos and sebomai; reverent of God, i.e. Pious.

DEFINITION: hating God, hateful to God.
ORIGIN: From theos and the base of stugnetos; hateful to God, i.e. Impious.

DEFINITION: deity, Godhead.
ORIGIN: From theos; divinity (abstractly).

DEFINITION: Theophilus, a friend of Luke of equestrian rank, to whom the Gospel and Acts are dedicated.
ORIGIN: From theos and philos; friend of God; Theophilus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: care, attention, especially medical attention (treatment); hence almost: healing; meton: those who render service.
ORIGIN: From therapeuo; attendance (specially, medical, i.e. Cure); figuratively and collectively, domestics.

DEFINITION: to care for, attend, serve, treat, especially of a physician; hence: to heal.
ORIGIN: From the same as therapon; to wait upon menially, i.e. (figuratively) to adore (God), or (specially) to relieve (of disease).

DEFINITION: a servant, attendant, minister.
ORIGIN: Apparently a participle from an otherwise obsolete derivative of the base of theros; a menial attendant (as if cherishing).

DEFINITION: to reap, gather, harvest.
ORIGIN: From theros (in the sense of the crop); to harvest.

DEFINITION: reaping, harvest; met: the harvest, crop.
ORIGIN: From therizo; reaping, i.e. The crop.

DEFINITION: a reaper, harvester.
ORIGIN: From therizo; a harvester.

DEFINITION: to warm; mid: to warm myself.
ORIGIN: From therme; to heat (oneself).

DEFINITION: heat.
ORIGIN: From the base of theros; warmth.

DEFINITION: summer.
ORIGIN: From a primary thero (to heat); properly, heat, i.e. Summer.

DEFINITION: a Thessalonian.
ORIGIN: From Thessalonike; a Thessalonican, i.e. Inhabitant of Thessalonice.

DEFINITION: Thessalonica (modern Saloniki), an important city of the Roman province Macedonia.
ORIGIN: From Thessalos (a Thessalian) and nike; Thessalonice, a place in Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: Theudas, a Jewish pretender of date about 4 B.C., otherwise unknown.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain origin; Theudas, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: to look at, gaze, behold; to see, experience, discern; to partake of.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of theaomai (perhaps by addition of horao); to be a spectator of, i.e. Discern, (literally, figuratively (experience) or intensively (acknowledge)).
USAGE: behold, consider, look on, perceive, see. Compare optanomai.

DEFINITION: a viewing, a spectacle.
ORIGIN: From the same as theoreo; spectatorship, i.e. (concretely) a spectacle.

DEFINITION: a repository, receptacle; a case, sheath, scabbard.
ORIGIN: From tithemi; a receptacle, i.e. Scabbard.

DEFINITION: (a) to give suck, (b) to suck.
ORIGIN: From thele (the nipple); to suckle, (by implication) to suck.

DEFINITION: female.
ORIGIN: From the same as thelazo; female.

DEFINITION: hunting, entrapping; prey, game; a net, means of capture.
ORIGIN: From ther (a wild animal, as game); hunting, i.e. (figuratively) destruction.

DEFINITION: to hunt, seek to catch or entrap; met: to lay hold of.
ORIGIN: From thera; to hunt (an animal), i.e. (figuratively) to carp at.

DEFINITION: to fight with wild beasts (i.e. wild beasts in human form); met: to be exposed to fierce hostility.
ORIGIN: From a compound of therion and machomai; to be a beast-fighter (in the gladiatorial show), i.e. (figuratively) to encounter (furious men).

DEFINITION: properly: a wild beast, hence: any animal; met: a brute.
ORIGIN: Diminutive from the same as thera; a dangerous animal.

DEFINITION: to store up, treasure up, save, lay up.
ORIGIN: From thesauros; to amass or reserve (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: lay up (treasure), (keep) in store, (heap) treasure (together, up).

DEFINITION: a store-house for precious things; hence: a treasure, a store.
ORIGIN: From tithemi; a deposit, i.e. Wealth (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to touch, handle, injure, harm.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of an obsolete primary thigo (to finger); to manipulate, i.e. Have to do with; by implication, to injure.

DEFINITION: (a) to make narrow (strictly: by pressure); to press upon, (b) to persecute, press hard.
ORIGIN: Akin to the base of tribos; to crowd (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: afflict, narrow, throng, suffer tribulation, trouble.

DEFINITION: persecution, affliction, distress, tribulation.
ORIGIN: From thlibo; pressure (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: afflicted(-tion), anguish, burdened, persecution, tribulation, trouble.

DEFINITION: to die, be dying, be dead.
ORIGIN: A strengthened form of a simpler primary thano than'-o (which is used for it only in certain tenses); to die (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: mortal, subject to death.
ORIGIN: From thnesko; liable to die.

DEFINITION: to disturb greatly, terrify, strike with panic; mid: to show agitation of mind.
ORIGIN: From thorubos; to be in tumult, i.e. Disturb, clamor.
USAGE: make ado (a noise), trouble self, set on an uproar.

DEFINITION: (a) din, hubbub, confused noise, outcry, (b) riot, disturbance.
ORIGIN: From the base of throeo; a disturbance.

DEFINITION: to crush, break, shatter; met: to break down.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to crush.

DEFINITION: (lit: a nursling, hence probably) plur: cattle.
ORIGIN: From trepho; stock (as raised on a farm).

DEFINITION: intrans: to lament, wail; trans: to bewail.
ORIGIN: From threnos; to bewail.

DEFINITION: wailing, lamentation, dirge.
ORIGIN: From the base of throeo; wailing.

DEFINITION: (underlying sense: reverence or worship of the gods), worship as expressed in ritual acts, religion.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of threskos; ceremonial observance.

DEFINITION: (refers probably to a careful observance of religious restrictions), religious (probably in a limited sense), devout.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of throeo; ceremonious in worship (as demonstrative), i.e. Pious.

DEFINITION: (properly: to lead one as prisoner in a triumphal procession, hence) to lead around, make a show (spectacle) of, cause to triumph.
ORIGIN: From a prolonged compound of the base of throeo; and a derivative of haptomai (meaning a noisy iambus, sung in honor of Bacchus); to make an acclamatory procession, i.e. (figuratively) to conquer or (by Hebraism) to give victory.

DEFINITION: hair (of the head or of animals).
ORIGIN: Genitive case trichos, etc.; of uncertain derivation; hair.

DEFINITION: to disturb, agitate; pass: to be troubled, alarmed.
ORIGIN: From threomai to wail; to clamor, i.e. (by implication) to frighten.

DEFINITION: a clot, large drop (of blood).
ORIGIN: Perhaps from trepho (in the sense of thickening); a clot.

DEFINITION: a (king's) throne, seat; meton: power, dominion; a potentate.
ORIGIN: From thrao (to sit); a stately seat ("throne"); by implication, power or (concretely) a potentate.

DEFINITION: Thyatira, a city of the old district Lydia, in the Roman province Asia.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; Thyatira, a place in Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: a daughter; hence (Hebraistic?), of any female descendent, however far removed; even of one unrelated: young lady.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word (compare "daughter"); a female child, or (by Hebraism) descendant (or inhabitant).

DEFINITION: a little (young) daughter.
ORIGIN: From thugater; a daughterling.

DEFINITION: a storm, tempest, whirlwind.
ORIGIN: From thuo (in the sense of blowing) a storm.

DEFINITION: of the sandarach (so-called citron) tree.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of thuo (in the sense of blowing; denoting a certain fragrant tree); made of citron-wood.

DEFINITION: incense.
ORIGIN: From thumiao; an aroma, i.e. Fragrant powder burnt in religious service; by implication, the burning itself.

DEFINITION: (ordinarily: censer, but) either the altar of incense, or the shovel, on which the high-priest poured the coals, when he entered the Holy of Holies on the Day of Atonement.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of thumiao; a place of fumigation, i.e. The alter of incense (in the Temple).

DEFINITION: to burn incense.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of thuo (in the sense of smoking); to fumigate, i.e. Offer aromatic fumes.

DEFINITION: (lit: to fight desperately, hence) to be furiously angry with.
ORIGIN: From a presumed compound of thumos and machomai; to be in a furious fight, i.e. (figuratively) to be exasperated.

DEFINITION: an outburst of passion, wrath.
ORIGIN: From thuo; passion (as if breathing hard).

DEFINITION: to provoke to anger; pass: to be wroth or very angry.
ORIGIN: From thumos; to put in a passion, i.e. Enrage.

DEFINITION: (a) a door, (b) met: an opportunity.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word (compare "door"); a portal or entrance (the opening or the closure, literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: the heavy oblong Roman shield.
ORIGIN: From thura; a large shield (as door-shaped).

DEFINITION: a small opening, window.
ORIGIN: From thura; an aperture, i.e. Window.

DEFINITION: a door-keeper, porter.
ORIGIN: From thura and ouros (a watcher); a gate- warden.

DEFINITION: abstr. and concr: sacrifice; a sacrifice, offering.
ORIGIN: From thuo; sacrifice (the act or the victim, literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: an altar (for sacrifice).
ORIGIN: From a derivative of thusia; a place of sacrifice, i.e. An altar (special or genitive case, literal or figurative).

DEFINITION: to sacrifice, generally an animal; hence: to kill.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; properly, to rush (breathe hard, blow, smoke), i.e. (by implication) to sacrifice (properly, by fire, but genitive case); by extension to immolate (slaughter for any purpose).

DEFINITION: "the twin", Thomas, one of the twelve apostles.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (compare ta'owm); the twin; Thomas, a Christian.

DEFINITION: a breast-plate, corslet, cuirass.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; the chest ("thorax"), i.e. (by implication) a corslet.

DEFINITION: Jairus, the ruler of a synagogue in Palestine.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Ya'iyr); Jairus (i.e. Jair), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Jacob, (a) the patriarch, son of Isaac, (b) father of Joseph, the husband of Mary.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Ya'aqob); Jacob (i.e. Ja'akob), the progenitor of the Israelites.

DEFINITION: James, (a) the Small, son of Alphaeus, and one of the Twelve, (b) half-brother of Jesus, (c) father (?) of Jude, (d) son of Zebedee, and brother of John, one of the Twelve, killed A.D. 44.
ORIGIN: The same as Iakob Graecized; Jacobus, the name of three Israelites.

DEFINITION: healing, curing, remedy.
ORIGIN: From iaomai; a cure (the effect).

DEFINITION: Jambres, a sorcerer at the court of the Pharaoh.
ORIGIN: Of Egyptian origin; Jambres, an Egyptian.

DEFINITION: Jannai, an ancestor of Jesus; Jannai was the son of Joseph, and father of Melchi.
ORIGIN: Probably of Hebrew origin (compare yanah); Janna, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Jannes, a sorcerer at the court of the Pharaoh.
ORIGIN: Of Egyptian origin; Jannes, an Egyptian.

DEFINITION: to heal, generally of the physical, sometimes of spiritual, disease.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of apparently a primary verb; to cure (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Jared, son of Mahalalel and father of Enoch.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yered); Jared (i.e. Jered), an antediluvian.

DEFINITION: a cure, healing.
ORIGIN: From iaomai; curing (the act).

DEFINITION: jasper (a translucent stone).
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin (see yashpheh); "jasper", a gem.

DEFINITION: Jason, a Christian of Thessalonica, perhaps the same as the relative of Paul.
ORIGIN: Future active participle masculine of iaomai; about to cure; Jason, a Christian.

DEFINITION: a physician.
ORIGIN: From iaomai; a physician.

DEFINITION: See! Lo! Behold! Look!.
ORIGIN: Second person singular imperative active of eido; used as an interjection to denote surprise; lo!.

DEFINITION: form, outward appearance.
ORIGIN: From eido; a sight (comparative figuratively "idea"), i.e. Aspect.

DEFINITION: one's own, belonging to one, private, personal; one's own people, one's own family, home, property.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; pertaining to self, i.e. One's own; by implication, private or separate.
USAGE: X his acquaintance, when they were alone, apart, aside, due, his (own, proper, several), home, (her, our, thine, your) own (business), private(-ly), proper, severally, their (own).

DEFINITION: (unofficial, hence) an amateur, an unprofessional man, a layman; an ungifted person.
ORIGIN: From idios; a private person, i.e. (by implication) an ignoramus (compare "idiot").

DEFINITION: See! Lo! Behold! Look!.
ORIGIN: Second person singular imperative middle voice of eido; used as imperative lo!.

DEFINITION: Idumea, Edom, a district of Arabia, immediately south of Judea.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Edom); Idumaea (i.e. Edom), a region East (and South) of Palestine.

DEFINITION: sweat, perspiration.
ORIGIN: A strengthened form of a primary idos (sweat): perspiration.

DEFINITION: Jezebel, name given to a false prophetess of Thyatira, possibly borrowed from the name of Ahab's wife, queen of Israel.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Iyzebel); Jezabel (i.e. Jezebel), a Tyrian woman (used as a synonym of a termagant or false teacher).

DEFINITION: Hierapolis, a city of the Lycus valley in Phrygia, near Laodicea and Colossae.
ORIGIN: From hieros and polis; holy city; Hierapolis, a place in Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: the duty (office) of a priest, priesthood.
ORIGIN: From hierateuo; priestliness, i.e. The sacerdotal function.
USAGE: office of the priesthood, priest's office.

DEFINITION: the act or office of priesthood.
ORIGIN: From hierateuo; the priestly fraternity, i.e. Sacerdotal order (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to serve as priest.
ORIGIN: Prolongation from hiereus; to be a priest, i.e. Perform his functions.

DEFINITION: Jeremiah, an O.T. prophet.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yirmyah); Hieremias (i.e. Jermijah), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: a priest, one who offers sacrifice to a god (in Jewish and pagan religions; of Christians only met.).
ORIGIN: From hieros; a priest (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: Jericho, a city a little north of the Dead Sea.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yriychow); Jericho, a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: a temple, either the whole building, or specifically the outer courts, open to worshippers.
ORIGIN: Neuter of hieros; a sacred place, i.e. The entire precincts (whereas naos denotes the central sanctuary itself) of the Temple (at Jerusalem or elsewhere).

DEFINITION: suitable to a sacred character, reverent.
ORIGIN: From hieros and the same as prepo; reverent.

DEFINITION: sacred, a sacred thing, a temple.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; sacred.

DEFINITION: Jerusalem, the capital of united Israel and Judah.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yruwshalaim); Hierosolyma (i.e. Jerushalaim}, the capitol of Palestine.

DEFINITION: an inhabitant of Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: From Hierosoluma; a Hierosolymite, i.e. Inhabitant of Hierosolyma.

DEFINITION: to commit sacrilege, rob a temple.
ORIGIN: From hierosulos; to be a temple-robber (figuratively).

DEFINITION: robbing temples, but possibly simply: sacrilegious.
ORIGIN: From hieron and sulao; a temple-despoiler.

DEFINITION: to minister in holy things.
ORIGIN: From a compound of hieron and the base of ergon; to be a temple-worker, i.e. Officiate as a priest (figuratively).

DEFINITION: (Aramaic form), Jerusalem, the capital of Palestine: hence Judaism, and allegorically, Christendom, the Christian Church.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yruwshalaim); Hierusalem (i.e. Jerushalem), the capitol of Palestine.

DEFINITION: the abstract notion of the priestly office.
ORIGIN: From hieros; sacredness, i.e. (by implication) the priestly office.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Jesse, son of Obed, and father of King David.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yishay); Jessae (i.e. Jishai), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Jephthah, one of the Judges of Israel.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yiphtach); Jephthae (i.e. Jiphtach), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Jechoniah, son of Josiah and father of Salathiel.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Ykonyah); Jechonias (i.e. Jekonjah), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Jesus; the Greek form of Joshua; Jesus, son of Eliezer; Jesus, surnamed Justus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yhowshuwa'); Jesus (i.e. Jehoshua), the name of our Lord and two (three) other Israelites.

DEFINITION: (a) considerable, sufficient, of number, quantity, time, (b) of persons: sufficiently strong (good, etc.), worthy, suitable, with various constructions, (c) many, much.
ORIGIN: From hiko (hikano or hikneomai, akin to heko) (to arrive); competent (as if coming in season), i.e. Ample (in amount) or fit (in character).
USAGE: able, + content, enough, good, great, large, long (while), many, meet, much, security, sore, sufficient, worthy.

DEFINITION: sufficiency, ability, power, fitness.
ORIGIN: From hikanos; ability.

DEFINITION: to make sufficient, render fit, qualify.
ORIGIN: From hikanos; to enable, i.e. Qualify.

DEFINITION: (originally: the olive branch held in the hand of the suppliant), supplication, entreaty.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of the base of hikanos (through the idea of approaching for a favor); intreaty.

DEFINITION: moisture.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; dampness.

DEFINITION: Iconium, a Phrygian city of the Roman province Galatia (modern Konia).
ORIGIN: Perhaps from eikon; image-like; Iconium, a place in Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: joyous, cheerful, not grudging.
ORIGIN: From the same as hileos; propitious or merry ("hilarious"), i.e. Prompt or willing.

DEFINITION: cheerfulness, graciousness.
ORIGIN: From hilaros; alacrity.

DEFINITION: (a) to have mercy on, show favor to, (b) trans. with object of sins: to forgive, pardon.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from the same as hileos; to conciliate, i.e. (transitively) to atone for (sin), or (intransitively) be propitious.

DEFINITION: a propitiation (of an angry god), atoning sacrifice.
ORIGIN: Atonement, i.e. (concretely) an expiator.

DEFINITION: (a) a sin offering, by which the wrath of the deity shall be appeased; a means of propitiation, (b) the covering of the ark, which was sprinkled with the atoning blood on the Day of Atonement.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of hilaskomai; an expiatory (place or thing), i.e. (concretely) an atoning victim, or (specially) the lid of the Ark (in the Temple).

DEFINITION: propitious, forgiving, merciful.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from the alternate form of haireomai; cheerful (as attractive), i.e. Propitious; adverbially (by Hebraism) God be gracious!, i.e. (in averting some calamity) far be it.

DEFINITION: Illyricum, a Roman province, afterwards called Dalmatia, bounded by Pannonia on the north, Macedonia on the south, Moesia on the east, and the Adriatic Sea on the west.
ORIGIN: Neuter of an adjective from a name of uncertain derivation: (the) Illyrican (shore), i.e. (as a name itself) Illyricum, a region of Europe.

DEFINITION: a thong, strap, (a) for binding a man who is to be flogged, (b) for fastening a sandal or shoe.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from the same as hama; a strap, i.e. (specially) the tie (of a sandal) or the lash (of a scourge).

DEFINITION: to clothe, provide clothing for; pass: to be clothed.
ORIGIN: From himation; to dress.

DEFINITION: a long flowing outer garment, tunic.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of ennumi (to put on); a dress (inner or outer).
USAGE: apparel, cloke, clothes, garment, raiment, robe, vesture.

DEFINITION: a collective word: raiment, clothing.
ORIGIN: From himatizo; clothing.

DEFINITION: to desire earnestly, long for; to have a strong affection for, love fervently.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from himeros (a yearning; of uncertain affinity); to long for.

DEFINITION: in order that, that, so that.
ORIGIN: Probably from the same as the former part of heautou (through the demonstrative idea; compare ho); in order that (denoting the purpose or the result).
USAGE: albeit, because, to the intent (that), lest, so as, (so) that, (for) to. Compare hina me.

DEFINITION: for what purpose?.
ORIGIN: From hina and tis; for what reason ?, i.e. Why?.

DEFINITION: Joppa, a coast town of Judea, west-north-west of Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yapho); Joppe (i.e. Japho), a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: the Jordan, a great river flowing due south and bounding Galilee, Samaria, and Judea on the east.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yarden); the Jordanes (i.e. Jarden), a river of Palestine.

DEFINITION: poison, rust; an arrow.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from eimi (to go) or hiemi (to send); rust (as if emitted by metals); also venom (as emitted by serpents).

DEFINITION: Judah, Judas, Jude.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yhuwdah or perhaps Yuttah); Judah (i.e. Jehudah or Juttah), a part of (or place in) Palestine.

DEFINITION: Judea, a Roman province, capital Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: Feminine of Ioudaios (with ge implied); the Judaean land (i.e. Judaea), a region of Palestine.

DEFINITION: to live as a Jew (in religion, ceremonially).
ORIGIN: From Ioudaios; to become a Judaean, i.e. "Judaize".

DEFINITION: Jewish, Judaic.
ORIGIN: From Ioudaios; Judaic, i.e. Resembling a Judaean.

DEFINITION: in the manner of Jews (religiously, ceremonially).
ORIGIN: Adverb from Ioudaikos; Judaically or in a manner resembling a Judaean.

DEFINITION: Jewish, a Jew, Judea.
ORIGIN: From Iouda (in the sense of Ioudas as a country); Judaean, i.e. Belonging to Jehudah.

DEFINITION: the Jewish religion, Judaism.
ORIGIN: From Ioudaizo; "Judaism", i.e. The Jewish faith and usages.

DEFINITION: Judah, Judas, the name of several Israelites, also one of the twelve tribes of Isr., also the Southern kingdom.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yhuwdah); Judas (i.e. Jehudah), the name of ten Israelites; also of the posterity of one of them and its region.

DEFINITION: Julia, a Roman Christian, probably a slave or freed from the Imperial household.
ORIGIN: Feminine of the same as Ioulios; Julia, a Christian woman.

DEFINITION: Julius, a Roman centurion on special service.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; Julius, a centurion.

DEFINITION: Junia, Junias, a Roman Christian.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; Junias, a Christian.

DEFINITION: Justus, (a) a surname of Joseph Barsabbas, one of the two nominated to fill Judas' place as apostle, (b) Titius Justus, a Corinthian Christian, (c) surname of Jesus, a Christian with Paul in Rome.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin ("just"); Justus, the name of three Christian.

DEFINITION: a horse-soldier, a mounted soldier, a cavalryman.
ORIGIN: From hippos; an equestrian, i.e. Member of a cavalry corps.

DEFINITION: horsemen, cavalry.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of hippos; the cavalry force.

DEFINITION: a horse.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a horse.

DEFINITION: a rainbow or halo.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from ereo (as a symbol of the female messenger of the pagan deities); a rainbow ("iris").

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Isaac, the patriarch.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yitschaq); Isaac (i.e. Jitschak), the son of Abraham.

DEFINITION: equal to or like the angels.
ORIGIN: From isos and aggelos; like an angel, i.e. Angelic.

DEFINITION: Issachar, a proper name.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yissaskar); Isachar (i.e. Jissaskar), a son of Jacob (figuratively, his descendant).

DEFINITION: know.
ORIGIN: Assumed by some as the base of certain irregular forms of epikaluma; to know.

DEFINITION: agree, give thyself wholly to.
ORIGIN: Second person imperative present of eimi; be thou.
USAGE: + agree, be, X give thyself wholly to.

DEFINITION: Iscariot, surname of Judas and his father.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (probably 'iysh and qirya'); inhabitant of Kerioth; Iscariotes (i.e. Keriothite), an epithet of Judas the traitor.

DEFINITION: equal, equivalent, identical.
ORIGIN: Probably from eido (through the idea of seeming); similar (in amount and kind).

DEFINITION: equality; equality of treatment, fairness.
ORIGIN: Likeness (in condition or proportion); by implication, equity.

DEFINITION: equally privileged, equal in honor.
ORIGIN: From isos and time; of equal value or honor.

DEFINITION: like-minded, of the same mind or spirit.
ORIGIN: From isos and psuche; of similar spirit.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Israel, surname of Jacob, then the Jewish people, the people of God.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yisra'el); Israel (i.e. Jisrael), the adopted name of Jacob, including his descendants (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: an Israelite, one of the chosen people of Israel, a Jew.
ORIGIN: From Israel; an "Israelite", i.e. Descendant of Israel (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: trans: (a) to make to stand, place, set up, establish, appoint; mid: to place myself, stand, (b) to set in balance, weigh; intrans: (c) to stand, stand by, stand still; met: to stand ready, stand firm, be steadfast.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary stao stah'-o (of the same meaning, and used for it in certain tenses); to stand (transitively or intransitively), used in various applications (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: abide, appoint, bring, continue, covenant, establish, hold up, lay, present, set (up), stanch, stand (by, forth, still, up). Compare tithemi.

DEFINITION: to get acquainted with, visit.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of eido; to be knowing (learned), i.e. (by implication) to visit for information (interview).

DEFINITION: strong (originally and generally of physical strength); mighty, powerful, vehement, sure.
ORIGIN: From ischus; forcible (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: boisterous, mighty(-ier), powerful, strong(-er, man), valiant.

DEFINITION: strength (absolutely), power, might, force, ability.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of is (force; compare eschon, a form of echo); forcefulness (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to have strength, be strong, be in full health and vigor, be able; meton: to prevail.
ORIGIN: From ischus; to have (or exercise) force (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: be able, avail, can do(-not), could, be good, might, prevail, be of strength, be whole, + much work.

DEFINITION: perhaps, equally; it may be that.
ORIGIN: Adverb from isos; likely, i.e. Perhaps.

DEFINITION: Italy, a region of western Europe.
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin; Italia, a region of Europe.

DEFINITION: Italian.
ORIGIN: From Italia; Italic, i.e. Belonging to Italia.

DEFINITION: Ituraean, an adjective applied to a district also called Trachonitis, about 60 miles east of the Sea of Galilee, and partly inhabited by the nomad tribe called Ituraeans.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Ytuwr); Ituraea (i.e. Jetur), a region of Palestine.

DEFINITION: a little fish.
ORIGIN: Diminutive from ichthus; a petty fish.

DEFINITION: a fish.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a fish.

DEFINITION: a track, footstep.
ORIGIN: From ikneomai (to arrive; compare heko); a track (figuratively).

DEFINITION: Jotham, son of Uzziah and father of Ahaz.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yowtham); Joatham (i.e. Jotham), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Joanna, Johanna, wife of Chuza, Herod's steward.
ORIGIN: Feminine of the same as Ioannes; Joanna, a Christian.

DEFINITION: Joanan, a proper name.
ORIGIN: A form of Ioannes; Joannas, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: John: the Baptist, the apostle, a member of the Sanhedrin, or John Mark.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yowchanan); Joannes (i.e. Jochanan), the name of four Israelites.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Job, the hero of the book of that name in the Old Testament.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Iyowb); Job (i.e. Ijob), a patriarch.

DEFINITION: Joel, the Hebrew prophet.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yow'el); Joel, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Jonam, an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Probably for Ioannes or Ionas; Jonan, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Jonah, the Hebrew prophet.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yonah); Jonas (i.e. Jonah), the name of two Israelites.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Joram, Jehoram, son of Jehoshaphat and father of Uzziah.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yowram); Joram, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Jorim, an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Perhaps for Ioram; Jorim, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Jehoshaphat, king of Judah, son of Asaph, father of Joram, an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yhowshaphat); Josaphat (i.e. Jehoshaphat), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), gen. case of Joses (a) son of Eliezer, (b) son of Mary, brother of Jesus, (c) surnamed Barnabas (also called Joseph).
ORIGIN: Genitive case of Ioses; Jose, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Joses (a) son of Eliezer, (b) son of Mary, half-brother of Jesus, (c) surnamed Barnabas (also called Joseph).
ORIGIN: Perhaps for Ioseph; Joses, the name of two Israelites.

DEFINITION: Joseph, the name of several Israelites.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yowceph); Joseph, the name of seven Israelites.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Josiah, king of Judah.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Yo'shiyah); Josias (i.e. Joshiah), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: iota, a small letter of the Greek alphabet, used in the NT (like yod, the Hebrew or rather Aramaic letter which was the smallest of all) to indicate the smallest part.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (the tenth letter of the Hebrew alphabet); "iota", the name of the eighth letter of the Greek alphabet, put (figuratively) for a very small part of anything.

DEFINITION: to also, to too, but to.
ORIGIN: From kai and ego; so also the dative case kamoi (kam-oy'),and accusative case kame (kam-eh') and (or also, even, etc.) I, (to) me.
USAGE: (and, even, even so, so) I (also, in like wise), both me, me also.

DEFINITION: according to which.
ORIGIN: From kata and the neuter plural of hos; according to which things, i.e. Just as.

DEFINITION: taking down, razing, destroying.
ORIGIN: From kathaireo; demolition; figuratively, extinction.

DEFINITION: (a) to take down, pull down, depose, destroy.
ORIGIN: From kata and haireomai (including its alternate); to lower (or with violence) demolish (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to cleanse, purify, prune.
ORIGIN: From katharos; to cleanse, i.e. (specially) to prune; figuratively, to expiate.

DEFINITION: even as, just as.
ORIGIN: From katha and per; exactly as.

DEFINITION: to lay hold of, fasten on to, seize, attack.
ORIGIN: From kata and haptomai; to seize upon.

DEFINITION: to cleanse, make clean, literally, ceremonially, or spiritually, according to context.
ORIGIN: From katharos; to cleanse (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: cleansing, purifying, purification, literal, ceremonial, or moral; met: expiation.
ORIGIN: From katharizo; a washing off, i.e. (ceremonially) ablution, (morally) expiation.

DEFINITION: clean, pure, unstained, either literally or ceremonially or spiritually; guiltless, innocent, upright.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; clean (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: cleanness, purity.
ORIGIN: From katharos; cleanness (ceremonially).

DEFINITION: a seat, chair.
ORIGIN: From kata and the same as hedraios; a bench (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to be sitting, sit down, be seated.
ORIGIN: From kata and the base of hedraios; to sit down.

DEFINITION: in order, in succession, in the time immediately after, just after.
ORIGIN: From kata and hexes; thereafter, i.e. Consecutively; as a noun (by ellipsis of noun) a subsequent person or time.

DEFINITION: to sleep, be sleeping.
ORIGIN: From kata and heudo (to sleep); to lie down to rest, i.e. (by implication) to fall asleep (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a leader, teacher, guide, master.
ORIGIN: From a compound of kata and hegeomai; a guide, i.e. (figuratively) a teacher.

DEFINITION: to come down, come to; to be unfit, proper.
ORIGIN: From kata and heko; to reach to, i.e. (neuter of present active participle, figuratively as adjective) becoming.

DEFINITION: to sit, be seated, enthroned; to dwell, reside.
ORIGIN: From kata; and hemai (to sit; akin to the base of hedraios); to sit down; figuratively, to remain, reside.

DEFINITION: daily, day-by-day.
ORIGIN: From kata and hemera; quotidian.

DEFINITION: (a) trans: to make to sit; to set, appoint, (b) intrans: to sit down, be seated, stay.
ORIGIN: Another (active) form for kathezomai; to seat down, i.e. Set (figuratively, appoint); intransitively, to sit (down); figuratively, to settle (hover, dwell).

DEFINITION: to send, let down, lower.
ORIGIN: From kata; and hiemi (to send); to lower.

DEFINITION: to set down, bring down to a place; to set in order, appoint, make, constitute.
ORIGIN: From kata and histemi; to place down (permanently), i.e. (figuratively) to designate, constitute, convoy.
USAGE: appoint, be, conduct, make, ordain, set.

DEFINITION: according to which thing, as, according as.
ORIGIN: From kata and hos; according to which thing, i.e. Precisely as, in proportion as.

DEFINITION: one the whole, in general, altogether.
ORIGIN: From kata and holos; on the whole, i.e. Entirely.

DEFINITION: to arm completely.
ORIGIN: From kata; and hoplizo; to equip fully with armor.

DEFINITION: to see clearly, perceive, discern.
ORIGIN: From kata and horao; to behold fully, i.e. (figuratively) distinctly apprehend.

DEFINITION: (a) in proportion as, according as, (b) because.
ORIGIN: From kata; and hos and tis; according to which certain thing, i.e. As far (or inasmuch) as.

DEFINITION: according to the manner in which, in the degree that, just as, as.
ORIGIN: From kata and hos; just (or inasmuch) as, that.
USAGE: according to, (according, even) as, how, when.

DEFINITION: and, even, also, namely.
ORIGIN: Apparently, a primary particle, having a copulative and sometimes also a cumulative force; and, also, even, so then, too, etc.; often used in connection (or composition) with other particles or small words.
USAGE: and, also, both, but, even, for, if, or, so, that, then, therefore, when, yet.

DEFINITION: Caiaphas, an Israelite high priest.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin; the dell; Caiaphas (i.e. Cajepha), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: and, at least.
ORIGIN: From kai and ge; and at least (or even, indeed).

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Cain, son of Adam and Eve and brother of Abel.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Qayin); Cain, (i.e. Cajin), the son of Adam.

DEFINITION: (Hebrew), Cainan, one of the ancestors of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Qeynan); Cainan (i.e. Kenan), the name of two patriarchs.

DEFINITION: fresh, new, unused, novel.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; new (especially in freshness; while neos is properly so with respect to age.

DEFINITION: freshness, newness, novelty.
ORIGIN: From kainos; renewal (figuratively).

DEFINITION: although, though.
ORIGIN: From kai and per; and indeed, i.e. Nevertheless or notwithstanding.

DEFINITION: fitting season, season, opportunity, occasion, time.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; an occasion, i.e. Set or proper time.
USAGE: X always, opportunity, (convenient, due) season, (due, short, while) time, a while. Compare chronos.

DEFINITION: Caesar, a surname of the gens Iulia, which became practically synonymous with the Emperor for the time being; in the Gospels it always refers to Tiberias.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; Caesar, a title of the Roman emperor.

DEFINITION: Two cities of Palestine: one in Galilee (Caesarea Philippi), the other on the coast of the Mediterranean.
ORIGIN: From Kaisar; Caesaria, the name of two places in Palestine.

DEFINITION: and yet, although, though.
ORIGIN: From kai and toi; and yet, i.e. Nevertheless.

DEFINITION: and yet, although, indeed.
ORIGIN: From kaitoi and ge; and yet indeed, i.e. Although really.

DEFINITION: to ignite, light, burn, lit. and met; to consume with fire.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to set on fire, i.e. Kindle or (by implication) consume.

DEFINITION: and there, and yonder, there also.
ORIGIN: From kai and ekei; likewise in that place.

DEFINITION: and thence, and from there; and then afterwards.
ORIGIN: From kai and ekeithen; likewise from that place (or time).

DEFINITION: and he, she, it, and that.
ORIGIN: From kai and ekeinos; likewise that (or those).
USAGE: and him (other, them), even he, him also, them (also), (and) they.

DEFINITION: (a) evil (i.e. trouble, labor, misfortune), (b) wickedness, (c) vicious disposition, malice, spite.
ORIGIN: From kakos; badness, i.e. (subjectively) depravity, or (actively) malignity, or (passively) trouble.

DEFINITION: evil-mindedness, malignity, malevolence.
ORIGIN: From a compound of kakos and ethos; bad character, i.e. (specially) mischievousness.

DEFINITION: to speak evil of, curse, revile, abuse.
ORIGIN: From a compound of kakos and logos; to revile.

DEFINITION: experience of evil, suffering, distress, affliction, perseverance.
ORIGIN: From a compound of hemiorion and pathos; hardship.

DEFINITION: to suffer evil, endure affliction.
ORIGIN: From the same as kakopatheia; to undergo hardship.
USAGE: be afflicted, endure afflictions (hardness), suffer trouble.

DEFINITION: to do harm, do wrong, do evil, commit sin.
ORIGIN: From kakopoios; to be a bad-doer, i.e. (objectively) to injure, or (genitive) to sin.

DEFINITION: doing evil; subst: an evil-doer.
ORIGIN: From kakos and poieo; a bad-doer; (specially), a criminal.

DEFINITION: bad, evil, in the widest sense.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; worthless (intrinsically, such; whereas poneros properly refers to effects), i.e. (subjectively) depraved, or (objectively) injurious.
USAGE: bad, evil, harm, ill, noisome, wicked.

DEFINITION: (lit: an evil-worker), a criminal.
ORIGIN: From kakos and the base of ergon; a wrong-doer, i.e. Criminal.

DEFINITION: to treat evilly, hurt, torment.
ORIGIN: From a presumed compound of kakos and echo; to maltreat.

DEFINITION: to treat badly, afflict, embitter, make angry.
ORIGIN: From kakos; to injure; figuratively, to exasperate.
USAGE: make evil affected, entreat evil, harm, hurt, vex.

DEFINITION: badly, evilly, wrongly.
ORIGIN: From kakos; badly (physically or morally).
USAGE: amiss, diseased, evil, grievously, miserably, sick, sore.

DEFINITION: affliction, ill-treatment, oppression, misery.
ORIGIN: From kakoo; maltreatment.

DEFINITION: stubble, straw, the stalk.
ORIGIN: Feminine of kalamos; a stalk of grain, i.e. (collectively) stubble.

DEFINITION: a reed; a reed-pen, reed-staff, measuring rod.
ORIGIN: Or uncertain affinity; a reed (the plant or its stem, or that of a similar plant); by implication, a pen.

DEFINITION: (a) to call, summon, invite, (b) to call, name.
ORIGIN: Akin to the base of keleuo; to "call" (properly, aloud, but used in a variety of applications, directly or otherwise).

DEFINITION: a cultivated olive (tree).
ORIGIN: From the base of kallion and elaia; a cultivated olive tree, i.e. A domesticated or improved one.

DEFINITION: very well.
ORIGIN: Neuter of the (irregular) comparative of kalos; (adverbially) better than many.

DEFINITION: a teacher of that which is noble (honorable) and good.
ORIGIN: From kalos and didaskalos; a teacher of the right.

DEFINITION: Fair Havens, a harbor in Crete.
ORIGIN: Plural of kalos and limen; Good Harbors, i.e. Fairhaven, a bay of Crete.

DEFINITION: to do well, act honorably, do what is right.
ORIGIN: From kalos and poieo; to do well, i.e. Live virtuously.

DEFINITION: beautiful, as an outward sign of the inward good, noble, honorable character; good, worthy, honorable, noble, and seen to be so.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; properly, beautiful, but chiefly (figuratively) good (literally or morally), i.e. Valuable or virtuous (for appearance or use, and thus distinguished from agathos, which is properly intrinsic).
USAGE: X better, fair, good(-ly), honest, meet, well, worthy.

DEFINITION: a covering, especially a covering of head and face, a veil.
ORIGIN: From kalupto; a cover, i.e. Veil.

DEFINITION: to veil, hide, conceal, envelop.
ORIGIN: Akin to klepto and krupto; to cover up (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: well, nobly, honorably, rightly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from kalos; well (usually morally).

DEFINITION: a camel or dromedary.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (gamal); a "camel".

DEFINITION: a furnace, oven, kiln.
ORIGIN: Probably from kaio; a furnace.

DEFINITION: to close, shut the eyes.
ORIGIN: From a compound of kata and the base of musterion; to shut down, i.e. Close the eyes.

DEFINITION: to work, be weary, be sick.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; properly, to toil, i.e. (by implication) to tire (figuratively, faint, sicken).

DEFINITION: to bend, bow.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to bend.

DEFINITION: and if, even if, even, at least.
ORIGIN: From kai and ean; and (or even) if.
USAGE: and (also) if (so much as), if but, at the least, though, yet.

DEFINITION: Cana, a city in Galilee.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (compare Qanah); Cana, a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: Cananaean, Aramaic for Zealot, surname of one of the twelve apostles.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (compare qanna'); zealous; Cananites, an epithet.
USAGE: Canaanite (by mistake for a derivative from Chanaan).

DEFINITION: Candace, a proper name; the Candace, a dynastic name for queens of the Ethiopians in Abyssinia.
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin.

DEFINITION: (lit: a level, ruler), a rule, regulation, rule of conduct or doctrine, (b) a measured (defined) area, province.
ORIGIN: From kane (a straight reed, i.e. Rod); a rule ("canon"), i.e. (figuratively) a standard (of faith and practice); by implication, a boundary, i.e. (figuratively) a sphere (of activity).

DEFINITION: Capernaum, a town of Galilee.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (probably kaphar and Nachuwm); Capernaum (i.e. Caphanachum), a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: to hawk, trade in, deal in for purposes of gain.
ORIGIN: From kapelos (a huckster); to retail, i.e. (by implication) to adulterate (figuratively).

DEFINITION: smoke.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; smoke.

DEFINITION: Cappadocia, a large Roman province in the central eastern part of Asia Minor.
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin; Cappadocia, a region of Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: lit: the heart; mind, character, inner self, will, intention, center.
ORIGIN: Prolonged from a primary kar (Latin cor, "heart"); the heart, i.e. (figuratively) the thoughts or feelings (mind); also (by analogy) the middle.

DEFINITION: a knower of the inner life (character, hearts).
ORIGIN: From kardia and ginosko; a heart-knower.

DEFINITION: (a) fruit, generally vegetable, sometimes animal, (b) met: fruit, deed, action, result, (c) profit, gain.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of harpazo; fruit (as plucked), literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: Carpus, a Christian of Troas.
ORIGIN: Perhaps for karpos; Carpus, probably a Christian.

DEFINITION: to bear fruit.
ORIGIN: From karpophoros; to be fertile (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: fruitful.
ORIGIN: From karpos and phero; fruitbearing (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to persevere, endure, be steadfast, patient.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of kratos (transposed); to be strong, i.e. (figuratively) steadfast (patient).

DEFINITION: a dry stalk, chip of wood, twig, splinter, chaff.
ORIGIN: From karpho (to wither); a dry twig or straw.

DEFINITION: gen: against, down from, throughout, by; acc: over against, among, daily, day-by-day, each day, according to, by way of.
ORIGIN: A primary particle; (prepositionally) down (in place or time), in varied relations (according to the case (genitive, dative or accusative) with which it is joined).
USAGE: about, according as (to), after, against, (when they were) X alone, among, and, X apart, (even, like) as (concerning, pertaining to touching), X aside, at, before, beyond, by, to the charge of, (charita-)bly, concerning, + covered, (dai-)ly, down, every, (+ far more) exceeding, X more excellent, for, from... To, godly, in(-asmuch, divers, every, -to, respect of),... By, after the manner of, + by any means, beyond (out of) measure, X mightily, more, X natural, of (up-)on (X part), out (of every), over against, (+ your) X own, + particularly, so, through(-oughout, -oughout every), thus, (un-)to(-gether, -ward), X uttermost, where(-by), with. In composition it retains many of these applications, and frequently denotes opposition, distribution, or intensity.

DEFINITION: to go down, come down, either from the sky or from higher land, descend.
ORIGIN: From kata and the base of basis; to descend (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: (a) mid: to lay, of a foundation, (b) met: to cast down, prostrate.
ORIGIN: From kata and ballo; to throw down.

DEFINITION: to burden, oppress, weigh down.
ORIGIN: From kata and bareo; to impose upon.

DEFINITION: descent.
ORIGIN: From katabaino; a declivity.

DEFINITION: to bring down, cast down, cause to go down.
ORIGIN: From kata and a derivative of the base of basis; to cause to go down, i.e. Precipitate.

DEFINITION: (a) foundation, (b) depositing, sowing, deposit, technically used of the act of conception.
ORIGIN: From kataballo; a deposition, i.e. Founding; figuratively, conception.

DEFINITION: of the umpire in a contest: to decide against, take part against, condemn (perhaps with the idea of assumption, officialism).
ORIGIN: From kata and brabeuo (in its original sense); to award the price against, i.e. (figuratively) to defraud (of salvation).

DEFINITION: a reporter, announcer, proclaimer, herald.
ORIGIN: From kataggello; a proclaimer.

DEFINITION: to declare openly, proclaim, preach, laud, celebrate.
ORIGIN: From kata and the base of aggelos; to proclaim, promulgate.
USAGE: declare, preach, shew, speak of, teach.

DEFINITION: to laugh at, ridicule.
ORIGIN: To laugh down, i.e. Deride.

DEFINITION: to condemn, blame.
ORIGIN: From kata and ginosko; to note against, i.e. Find fault with.

DEFINITION: to break down (in pieces), crush, break into.
ORIGIN: From kata and the base of rhegnumi; to rend in pieces, i.e. Crack apart.

DEFINITION: to lead down, bring down, either from a high place on land or to a lower (or actually to the sea-coast), or from the high seas to land.
ORIGIN: From kata and ago; to lead down; specially, to moor a vessel.

DEFINITION: to subdue (in warfare); to struggle against, conquer, overcome.
ORIGIN: From kata and agonizomai; to struggle against, i.e. (by implication) to overcome.

DEFINITION: to bind up, bandage.
ORIGIN: From kata and deo; to tie down, i.e. Bandage (a wound).

DEFINITION: quite clear, evident.
ORIGIN: From kata intensive and delos; manifest.

DEFINITION: to condemn, pass sentence upon.
ORIGIN: From kata and a derivative of dike; to adjudge against, i.e. Pronounce guilty.

DEFINITION: to hunt down, follow closely.
ORIGIN: From kata and dioko; to hunt down, i.e. Search for.

DEFINITION: to enslave.
ORIGIN: From kata and douloo; to enslave utterly.

DEFINITION: to overpower, quell, treat harshly.
ORIGIN: From kata and a derivative of dunastes; to exercise dominion against, i.e. Oppress.

DEFINITION: to shame, disgrace, bring to shame, put to utter confusion, frustrate.
ORIGIN: From kata and aischunomai; to shame down, i.e. Disgrace or (by implication) put to the blush.

DEFINITION: to burn up, consume entirely.
ORIGIN: From kata and kaio; to burn down (to the ground), i.e. Consume wholly.

DEFINITION: to veil, cover the head.
ORIGIN: From kata and kalupto; to cover wholly, i.e. Veil.

DEFINITION: to boast against, exult over.
ORIGIN: From kata and kauchaomai; to exult against (i.e. Over).

DEFINITION: to recline (at table); more often: to keep bed, be lying ill (in bed).
ORIGIN: From kata and keimai; to lie down, i.e. (by implication) be sick; specially, to recline at a meal.

DEFINITION: to break in pieces, break up.
ORIGIN: From kata and klao; to break down, i.e. Divide.

DEFINITION: to shut up, confine.
ORIGIN: From kata and kleio; to shut down (in a dungeon), i.e. Incarcerate.

DEFINITION: to give as an inheritance, distribute by lot.
ORIGIN: From kata and a derivative of a compound of kleros and didomi; to be a giver of lots to each, i.e. (by implication) to apportion an estate.

DEFINITION: to cause to recline at table; mid. and pass: to recline at table.
ORIGIN: From kata and klino; to recline down, i.e. (specially) to take a place at table.

DEFINITION: to flood over, overwhelm, inundate.
ORIGIN: From kata and the base of kludon; to dash (wash) down, i.e. (by implication) to deluge.

DEFINITION: a deluge, flood.
ORIGIN: From katakluzo; an inundation.

DEFINITION: to follow after.
ORIGIN: From kata and akoloutheo; to accompany closely.

DEFINITION: to cut up, cut in pieces, mangle, wound.
ORIGIN: From kata and kopto; to chop down, i.e. Mangle.

DEFINITION: to cast down headlong, throw over a precipice.
ORIGIN: From kata and a derivative of kremnos; to precipitate down.

DEFINITION: punishment following condemnation, penal servitude, penalty.
ORIGIN: From katakrino; an adverse sentence (the verdict).

DEFINITION: to condemn, judge worthy of punishment.
ORIGIN: From kata and krino; to judge against, i.e. Sentence.

DEFINITION: condemnation, censure.
ORIGIN: From katakrino; sentencing adversely (the act).

DEFINITION: to exercise authority over, overpower, master.
ORIGIN: From kata and kurieuo; to lord against, i.e. Control, subjugate.
USAGE: exercise dominion over (lordship), be lord over, overcome.

DEFINITION: to speak evil of, rail at, slander.
ORIGIN: From katalalos; to be a traducer, i.e. To slander.

DEFINITION: evil-speaking, backbiting, detraction, slander.
ORIGIN: From katalalos; defamation.

DEFINITION: slanderous, back-biting; subst: a railer, defamer.
ORIGIN: From kata and the base of laleo; talkative against, i.e. A slanderer.
