DEFINITION: Matthat, an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Probably a shortened form of Mattathias; Matthat (i.e. Mattithjah), the name of two Israelites.

DEFINITION: Matthias.
ORIGIN: Apparently a shortened form of Mattathias; Matthias (i.e. Mattithjah), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Mattatha, an Israelite.
ORIGIN: Probably a shortened form of Mattathias (compare soterion); Mattatha (i.e. Mattithjah), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Mattathias, an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Mattithyah); Mattathias (i.e. Mattithjah), an Israelite and a Christian.

DEFINITION: a short sword or dagger.
ORIGIN: Probably feminine of a presumed derivative of mache; a knife, i.e. Dirk; figuratively, war, judicial punishment.

DEFINITION: (earlier: a battle, conflict, hence) in the sphere of words, etc: strife, contention, quarrel.
ORIGIN: From machomai; a battle, i.e. (figuratively) controversy.

DEFINITION: to engage in battle, fight; hence: to strive, contend, dispute.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to war, i.e. (figuratively) to quarrel, dispute.

DEFINITION: I, me, my.
ORIGIN: A shorter (and probably originally) from of eme; me.

DEFINITION: to boast, be arrogant, vaunt.
ORIGIN: From a compound of megas and aucheo (to boast; akin to auzano and kauchaomai); to talk big, i.e. Be grandiloquent (arrogant, egotistic).

DEFINITION: grand, magnificent, splendid.
ORIGIN: From megas; magnificent, i.e. (neuter, plural as noun) a conspicuous favor, or (subjectively) perfection.

DEFINITION: (divine) majesty or magnificence, glory.
ORIGIN: From megaleios; superbness, i.e. Glory or splendor.

DEFINITION: magnificent, superb, transcendent, majestic.
ORIGIN: From megas and prepo; befitting greatness or magnificence (majestic).

DEFINITION: (a) to enlarge, lengthen, (b) to increase, magnify, extol.
ORIGIN: From megas; to make (or declare) great, i.e. Increase or (figuratively) extol.

DEFINITION: greatly, very much, vehemently.
ORIGIN: Adverb from megas; much.

DEFINITION: (divine) majesty, greatness.
ORIGIN: From megas; greatness, i.e. (figuratively) divinity (often God himself).

DEFINITION: large, great, in the widest sense.
ORIGIN: (including the prolonged forms, feminine megale, plural megaloi, etc.; compare also megistos, meizon); big (literally or figuratively, in a very wide application).
USAGE: (+ fear) exceedingly, great(-est), high, large, loud, mighty, + (be) sore (afraid), strong, X to years.

DEFINITION: greatness, vastness.
ORIGIN: From megas; magnitude (figuratively).

DEFINITION: a great one, a lord; a courtier, satrap, nobleman.
ORIGIN: Plural from megistos; grandees.

DEFINITION: greatest.
ORIGIN: Superlative of megas; greatest or very great.

DEFINITION: to translate (from one language into another), interpret.
ORIGIN: From meta and hermeneuo; to explain over, i.e. Translate.

DEFINITION: deep drinking, drunkenness.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; an intoxicant, i.e. (by implication) intoxication.

DEFINITION: to cause to change its place, move out of its place; to translate, transfer, remove.
ORIGIN: Methistano meth-is-tan'-o from meta and histemi; to transfer, i.e. Carry away, depose or (figuratively) exchange, seduce.
USAGE: put out, remove, translate, turn away.

DEFINITION: (a way of search after something, an inquiry; a method), scheming, craftiness, deceit.
ORIGIN: From a compound of meta and hodeuo (compare "method"); travelling over, i.e. Travesty (trickery).

DEFINITION: confine, border, boundary.
ORIGIN: From meta and horion; bounded alongside, i.e. Contiguous (neuter plural as noun, frontier).

DEFINITION: to make drunk; pass: to become drunk.
ORIGIN: A prolonged (transitive) form of methuo; to intoxicate.

DEFINITION: a drunkard.
ORIGIN: From methuo; tipsy, i.e. (as noun) a sot.

DEFINITION: to be intoxicated with wine, be drunk.
ORIGIN: From another form of methe; to drink to intoxication, i.e. Get drunk.

DEFINITION: greater, greatest.
ORIGIN: Neuter of meizon; (adverbially) in greater degree.

DEFINITION: greater.
ORIGIN: Continued comparative of meizon; still larger (figuratively).

DEFINITION: elder, greater, more.
ORIGIN: Irregular comparative of megas; larger (literally or figuratively, specially, in age).

DEFINITION: ink.
ORIGIN: Neuter of melas as noun; ink.

DEFINITION: black.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; black.

DEFINITION: Melea, one of the ancestors of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain origin; Meleas, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: to devise, plan; practice, exercise myself in, study, ponder.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of melo; to take care of, i.e. (by implication) revolve in the mind.

DEFINITION: honey.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; honey.

DEFINITION: belonging to bees, coming from bees.
ORIGIN: From meli; relating to honey, i.e. Bee (comb).

DEFINITION: Melita (Malta), an island in the Mediterranean.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain origin; Melita, an island in the Mediterranean.

DEFINITION: to intend, be about to; to delay, linger.
ORIGIN: A strengthened form of melo (through the idea of expectation); to intend, i.e. Be about to be, do, or suffer something (of persons or things, especially events; in the sense of purpose, duty, necessity, probability, possibility, or hesitation).
USAGE: about, after that, be (almost), (that which is, things, + which was for) to come, intend, was to (be), mean, mind, be at the point, (be) ready, + return, shall (begin), (which, that) should (after, afterwards, hereafter) tarry, which was for, will, would, be yet.

DEFINITION: a member or limb (of the body).
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a limb or part of the body.

DEFINITION: Melchi, one of the ancestors of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (melek with pronominal suffix, my king); Melchi (i.e. Malki), the name of two Israelites.

DEFINITION: Melchizedek, king and priest of Salem.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Malkiy-Tsedeq); Melchisedek (i.e. Malkitsedek), a patriarch.

DEFINITION: it is a care, it is an object of anxiety, it concerns.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to be of interest to, i.e. To concern (only third person singular present indicative used impersonally, it matters).

DEFINITION: a parchment leaf, perhaps for notes.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin ("membrane"); a (written) sheep-skin.

DEFINITION: to blame, censure, find fault.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to blame.

DEFINITION: blaming one's lot or destiny, discontented, complaining.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of memphomai and moira (fate; akin to the base of meros); blaming fate, i.e. Querulous (discontented).

DEFINITION: an untranslatable particle, generally answered by de, each of the two introducing a clause intended to be contrasted with the other.
ORIGIN: A primary particle; properly, indicative of affirmation or concession (in fact); usually followed by a contrasted clause with de (this one, the former, etc.).
USAGE: even, indeed, so, some, truly, verily. Often compounded with other particles in an intensive or asseverative sense.

DEFINITION: nay rather; indeed, truly, really.
ORIGIN: From Not Used and oun and ge; so then at least.

DEFINITION: (a) indeed, really, (b) yet, however, nevertheless.
ORIGIN: From Not Used and toi; indeed though, i.e. However.

DEFINITION: to remain, abide, stay, wait; with acc: to wait for, await.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to stay (in a given place, state, relation or expectancy).
USAGE: abide, continue, dwell, endure, be present, remain, stand, tarry (for), X thine own.

DEFINITION: to divide into parts, divide, part, share, distribute; mid: to share, take part in a partitioning; to distract.
ORIGIN: From meros; to part, i.e. (literally) to apportion, bestow, share, or (figuratively) to disunite, differ.
USAGE: deal, be difference between, distribute, divide, give participle

DEFINITION: care, worry, anxiety.
ORIGIN: From merizo (through the idea of distraction); solicitude.

DEFINITION: to be over-anxious; with acc: to be anxious about, distracted; to care for.
ORIGIN: From merimna; to be anxious about.

DEFINITION: (a) a part, division of a country, (b) a share, portion.
ORIGIN: Feminine of meros; a portion, i.e. Province, share or (abstractly) participation.

DEFINITION: (a) a distributing, a distribution, (b) a parting, dividing, severance, separation.
ORIGIN: From merizo; a separation or distribution.

DEFINITION: a divider, partitioner, distributor.
ORIGIN: From merizo; an apportioner (administrator).

DEFINITION: a part, share, portion.
ORIGIN: From an obsolete but more primary form of meiromai (to get as a section or allotment); a division or share (literally or figuratively, in a wide application).
USAGE: behalf, course, coast, craft, particular (+ -ly), part (+ -ly), piece, portion, respect, side, some sort(-what).

DEFINITION: (lit: midday, hence, the position of the sun at midday), the South.
ORIGIN: From mesos and hemera; midday; by implication, the south.

DEFINITION: to mediate, interpose, give bail.
ORIGIN: From mesites; to interpose (as arbiter), i.e (by implication) to ratify (as surety).

DEFINITION: (a) a mediator, intermediary, (b) a go-between, arbiter, agent of something good.
ORIGIN: From mesos; a go-between, i.e. (simply) an internunciator, or (by implication) a reconciler (intercessor).

DEFINITION: midnight, the middle of the period between sunset and sunrise.
ORIGIN: Neuter of compound of mesos and nux; midnight (especially as a watch).

DEFINITION: Mesopotamia, the Country between the (two) Rivers, i.e. the Euphrates and the Tigris.
ORIGIN: From mesos and potamos; Mesopotamia (as lying between the Euphrates and the Tigris; compare 'Aram Naharayim), a region of Asia.

DEFINITION: middle, in the middle, between, in the midst of.
ORIGIN: From meta; middle (as an adjective or (neuter) noun).
USAGE: among, X before them, between, + forth, mid(-day, -night), midst, way.

DEFINITION: a middle wall, partition wall, barrier.
ORIGIN: From mesos and toichos; a partition (figuratively).

DEFINITION: mid-heaven, the middle of heaven, the zenith.
ORIGIN: From a presumed compound of mesos and ouranos; mid-sky.

DEFINITION: to be in the middle, be advanced midway.
ORIGIN: From mesos; to form the middle, i.e. (in point of time), to be half-way over.

DEFINITION: Messiah, the O.T. title corresponding to Christ.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (mashiyach); the Messias (i.e. Mashiach), or Christ.

DEFINITION: full, filled with.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation.

DEFINITION: to fill.
ORIGIN: From mestos; to replenish, i.e. (by implication) to intoxicate.

DEFINITION: (a) gen: with, in company with, (b) acc: (1) behind, beyond, after, of place, (2) after, of time, with nouns, neut. of adjectives.
ORIGIN: A primary preposition (often used adverbially); properly, denoting accompaniment; "amid" (local or causal); modified variously according to the case (genitive association, or accusative succession) with which it is joined; occupying an intermediate position between apo or ek and eis or pros; less intimate than en and less close than sun).
USAGE: after(-ward), X that he again, against, among, X and, + follow, hence, hereafter, in, of, (up-)on, + our, X and setting, since, (un-)to, + together, when, with (+ -out). Often used in composition, in substantially the same relations of participation or proximity, and transfer or sequence.

DEFINITION: to change place (abode), leave, depart, remove, pass over.
ORIGIN: From meta and the base of basis; to change place.

DEFINITION: to change; mid: to change mind.
ORIGIN: From meta and ballo; to throw over, i.e. (middle voice figuratively) to turn about in opinion.

DEFINITION: (usually: transfer, transport, and met: to a better mind), to turn about, change the position of; pass: to be brought back.
ORIGIN: From meta and harmozo; to lead over, i.e. Transfer (direct).

DEFINITION: (lit: to offer by way of change, offer so that a change of owner is produced), to share; sometimes merely: to impart, bestow.
ORIGIN: From meta and didomi; to give over, i.e. Share.

DEFINITION: (a) change, transformation, (b) removal.
ORIGIN: From metatithemi; transposition, i.e. Transferral (to heaven), disestablishment (of a law).

DEFINITION: to change position, depart, remove.
ORIGIN: From meta and airo; to betake oneself, i.e. Remove (locally).

DEFINITION: mid: to summon to myself, send for.
ORIGIN: From meta and kaleo; to call elsewhere, i.e. Summon.

DEFINITION: trans: to move away, dislodge, remove.
ORIGIN: From meta and kineo; to stir to a place elsewhere, i.e. Remove (figuratively).

DEFINITION: (a) with gen: to take a share (part) of, share in, partake of, (b) with acc: to take after (later) or take instead.
ORIGIN: From meta and lambano; to participate; genitive case, to accept (and use).
USAGE: eat, have, be partaker, receive, take.

DEFINITION: participation, sharing in, receiving.
ORIGIN: From metalambano; participation.

DEFINITION: to change, transform, alter, exchange.
ORIGIN: From meta and allasso; to exchange.

DEFINITION: (lit: to change one care or interest for another), to change mind (generally for the better), repent, regret.
ORIGIN: From meta and the middle voice of melo; to care afterwards, i.e. Regret.

DEFINITION: to transform, transfigure.
ORIGIN: From meta and morphoo; to transform (literally or figuratively, "metamorphose").

DEFINITION: to repent, change mind, change the inner man (particularly with reference to acceptance of the will of God), repent.
ORIGIN: From meta and noieo; to think differently or afterwards, i.e. Reconsider (morally, feel compunction).

DEFINITION: repentance, a change of mind, change in the inner man.
ORIGIN: From metanoeo; (subjectively) compunction (for guilt, including reformation); by implication, reversal (of (another's) decision).

DEFINITION: meanwhile, afterwards, between.
ORIGIN: From meta and a form of sun; betwixt (of place or person); (of time) as adjective, intervening, or (by implication) adjoining.

DEFINITION: to send after or for.
ORIGIN: From meta and pempo; to send from elsewhere, i.e. (middle voice) to summon or invite.

DEFINITION: to turn, change, corrupt, pervert.
ORIGIN: From meta and strepho; to turn across, i.e. Transmute or (figuratively) corrupt.

DEFINITION: to change the outward appearance (the dress, the form of presentment) of something, transfigure; to adapt.
ORIGIN: From meta and a derivative of schema; to transfigure or disguise; figuratively, to apply (by accommodation).

DEFINITION: (a) to transfer, mid: to go over to another party, desert, (b) to change.
ORIGIN: From meta and tithemi; to transfer, i.e. (literally) transport, (by implication) exchange, (reflexively) change sides, or (figuratively) pervert.
USAGE: carry over, change, remove, translate, turn.

DEFINITION: afterwards.
ORIGIN: From meta and epeita; thereafter.

DEFINITION: to have a share of, participate in, share, partake of, be a member of.
ORIGIN: From meta and echo; to share or participate; by implication, belong to, eat (or drink).
USAGE: be partaker, pertain, take part, use.

DEFINITION: to raise on high, to be in suspense.
ORIGIN: From a compound of meta and a collateral form of airo or perhaps rather aer (compare "meteor"); to raise in mid-air, i.e. (figuratively) suspend (passively, fluctuate or be anxious).

DEFINITION: change of abode, migration, deportation.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of a compound of meta and oikos; a change of abode, i.e. (specially), expatriation.

DEFINITION: to transport, cause to migrate, remove.
ORIGIN: From the same as metoikesia; to transfer as a settler or captive, i.e colonize or exile.

DEFINITION: sharing, partnership, fellowship.
ORIGIN: From metecho; participation, i.e. Intercourse.

DEFINITION: a sharer, partner, associate.
ORIGIN: From metecho; participant, i.e. (as noun) a sharer; by implication, an associate.

DEFINITION: to measure (out), estimate.
ORIGIN: From metron; to measure (i.e. Ascertain in size by a fixed standard); by implication, to admeasure (i.e. Allot by rule).

DEFINITION: a measure, amphora, about 39.39 liters or 8.75 gallons.
ORIGIN: From metreo; a measurer, i.e. (specially), a certain standard measure of capacity for liquids.

DEFINITION: to bear gently with, have compassion.
ORIGIN: From a compound of the base of metrios and pathos; to be moderate in passion, i.e. Gentle (to treat indulgently).

DEFINITION: moderately, greatly, exceedingly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a derivative of metron; moderately, i.e. Slightly.

DEFINITION: a measure, whether lineal or cubic; a measuring rod.
ORIGIN: An apparently primary word; a measure ("metre"), literally or figuratively; by implication, a limited portion (degree).

DEFINITION: the forehead, front.
ORIGIN: From meta and ops (the face); the forehead (as opposite the countenance).

DEFINITION: as far as, until, even to.
ORIGIN: Or mechris (mekh-ris'); from mekos; as far as, i.e. Up to a certain point (as a preposition, of extent (denoting the terminus, whereas achri refers especially to the space of time or place intervening) or conjunction).

DEFINITION: not, that...not, lest (used for qualified negation).
ORIGIN: A primary particle of qualified negation (whereas ou expresses an absolute denial); (adverb) not, (conjunction) lest; also (as an interrogative implying a negative answer (whereas ou expects an affirmative one)) whether.
USAGE: any but (that), X forbear, + God forbid, + lack, lest, neither, never, no (X wise in), none, nor, (can-)not, nothing, that not, un(-taken), without. Often used in compounds in substantially the same relations. See also ean me, hina me, ou me, mekos, mekuno, men, me ouk.

DEFINITION: before, but, except.
ORIGIN: I.e. ean and me; if not, i.e. Unless.
USAGE: X before, but, except, if, no, (if, + whosoever) not.

DEFINITION: albeit not, lest, that.
ORIGIN: I.e. hina and me; in order (or so) that not.

DEFINITION: anymore, at all, neither, never.
ORIGIN: I.e. ou and me; a double negative strengthening the denial; not at all.
USAGE: any more, at all, by any (no) means, neither, never, no (at all), in no case (wise), nor ever, not (at all, in any wise). Compare me ouk.

DEFINITION: by no means, not at all.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a compound of me and amos (somebody); by no means.

DEFINITION: and not, not even, neither…nor.
ORIGIN: From me and de; but not, not even; in a continued negation, nor.
USAGE: neither, nor (yet), (no) not (once, so much as).

DEFINITION: no one, none, nothing.
ORIGIN: Including the irregular feminine medemia may-dem-ee'-ah, and the neuter meden (may-den') from me and heis; not even one (man, woman, thing).
USAGE: any (man, thing), no (man), none, not (at all, any man, a whit), nothing, + without delay.

DEFINITION: not at any time, never.
ORIGIN: From mede and pote; not even ever.

DEFINITION: not yet.
ORIGIN: From mede and po; not even yet.

DEFINITION: a Mede, Median, an inhabitant of Media.
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin (compare Maday); a Median, or inhabitant of Media.

DEFINITION: no longer, not anymore.
ORIGIN: From me and eti; no further.
USAGE: any longer, (not) henceforth, hereafter, no henceforward (longer, more, soon), not any more.

DEFINITION: length.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to megas.

DEFINITION: to lengthen, extend, grow.
ORIGIN: From mekos; to lengthen, i.e. (middle voice) to enlarge.

DEFINITION: a sheep's (sometimes pig's) hide, sheepskin.
ORIGIN: From melon (a sheep); a sheep-skin.

DEFINITION: assuredly, certainly.
ORIGIN: A stronger form of men; a particle of affirmation (only with e); assuredly.

DEFINITION: a (lunar) month.
ORIGIN: A primary word; a month.

DEFINITION: (a) to reveal, make known (in a law court), to lay information, inform, (b) to make known, point out.
ORIGIN: Probably from the same base as massaomai and mnaomai (i.e. Mao, to strive); to disclose (through the idea of mental effort and thus calling to mind), i.e. Report, declare, intimate.

DEFINITION: neither, never, not.
ORIGIN: I.e. me and ou; as interrogative and negative, is it not that?.
USAGE: neither (followed by no), + never, not. Compare ou me.

DEFINITION: lest at any time, lest; then weakened: whether perhaps, whether at all; in a principal clause: perhaps.
ORIGIN: Or me pote (may pot'-eh) from me and pote; not ever; also if (or lest) ever (or perhaps).
USAGE: if peradventure, lest (at any time, haply), not at all, whether or not.

DEFINITION: lest anywhere, lest perhaps.
ORIGIN: From me and po; not yet.

DEFINITION: lest perhaps, whether perhaps.
ORIGIN: Or me pos (may poce) from me and pos; lest somehow.
USAGE: lest (by any means, by some means, haply, perhaps).

DEFINITION: the thigh.
ORIGIN: Perhaps a primary word; a thigh.

DEFINITION: nor, neither, not even, neither…nor.
ORIGIN: From me and te; not too, i.e. (in continued negation) neither or nor; also, not even.

DEFINITION: a mother.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a "mother" (literally or figuratively, immediate or remote).

DEFINITION: can this be? (interrogative particle expecting a negative answer).
ORIGIN: From me and the neuter of tis; whether at all.
USAGE: not (the particle usually not expressed, except by the form of the question).

DEFINITION: let alone, much less, much more.
ORIGIN: From meti and ge; not at all then, i.e. Not to say (the rather still).

DEFINITION: any.
ORIGIN: Or me tis (may tis) from me and tis; whether any.
USAGE: any (sometimes unexpressed except by the simple interrogative form of the sentence).

DEFINITION: the womb.
ORIGIN: From meter; the matrix.

DEFINITION: a matricide, smiter of his mother.
ORIGIN: From meter and the base of halon; a mother-thresher, i.e. Matricide.

DEFINITION: chief city, mother city.
ORIGIN: From meter and polis; a mother city, i.e. "metropolis".

DEFINITION: first, one, other.
ORIGIN: Irregular feminine of heis; one or first.
USAGE: a (certain), + agree, first, one, X other.

DEFINITION: to stain, pollute, defile, corrupt.
ORIGIN: Perhaps a primary verb; to sully or taint, i.e. Contaminate (ceremonially or morally).

DEFINITION: pollution, defilement; a stain.
ORIGIN: From miaino ("miasma"); (morally) foulness (properly, the effect).

DEFINITION: the act of pollution, defilement.
ORIGIN: From miaino; (morally) contamination (properly, the act).

DEFINITION: a mixture.
ORIGIN: From mignumi; a compound.

DEFINITION: to mix, mingle.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to mix.

DEFINITION: a little, little while.
ORIGIN: Masculine or neuter singular of mikros (as noun); a small space of time or degree.

DEFINITION: small, little.
ORIGIN: Including the comparative mikroteros (ik-rot'-er-os) apparently a primary word; small (in size, quantity, number or (figuratively) dignity).

DEFINITION: Miletus, a city on the coast of the Roman province Asia.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain origin; Miletus, a city of Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: a Roman mile, measuring 1478.5 meters or 5820.9 feet.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; a thousand paces, i.e. A "mile".

DEFINITION: to imitate, follow.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from mimos (a "mimic"); to imitate.

DEFINITION: an imitator, follower.
ORIGIN: From mimeomai; an imitator.

DEFINITION: to remember, call to mind, recall, mention.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of mnaomai (from which some of the tenses are borrowed); to remind, i.e. (middle voice) to recall to mind.

DEFINITION: to hate, detest, love less, esteem less.
ORIGIN: From a primary misos (hatred); to detest (especially to persecute); by extension, to love less.

DEFINITION: (lit: repayment of price or payment of price due), reward, due punishment.
ORIGIN: From misthapodotes; requital (good or bad).

DEFINITION: one who pays wages.
ORIGIN: From misthoo and apodidomi; a renumerator.

DEFINITION: a paid worker, hired servant, hireling (contrasted with a slave).
ORIGIN: From misthos; a wage-earner.

DEFINITION: (a) pay, wages, salary, (b) reward, recompense, punishment.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; pay for service (literally or figuratively), good or bad.

DEFINITION: to hire out, mid: to hire, engage.
ORIGIN: From misthos; to let out for wages, i.e. (middle voice) to hire.

DEFINITION: a rented house, hired dwelling.
ORIGIN: From misthoo; a rented building.

DEFINITION: a hired servant, hireling.
ORIGIN: From misthoo; a wage-worker (good or bad).

DEFINITION: Mitylene, the capital of the island of Lesbos in the northern Aegean sea.
ORIGIN: For mutilene (abounding in shellfish); Mitylene (or Mytilene), a town on the island of Lesbos.

DEFINITION: Michael, the archangel.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Miyka'el); Michael, an archangel.

DEFINITION: a mina, a Greek monetary unit equal to 100 drachma.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; a mna (i.e. Mina), a certain weight.

DEFINITION: to remember, recollect.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of a derivative of meno or perhaps of the base of massaomai (through the idea of fixture in the mind or of mental grasp); to bear in mind, i.e. Recollect; by implication, to reward or punish.
USAGE: be mindful, remember, come (have) in remembrance. Compare mimnesko.

DEFINITION: Mnason, an early Christian, native of Cyprus, resident at a place between Caesarea and Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain origin; Mnason, a Christian.

DEFINITION: remembrance, recollection, mention; commemoration.
ORIGIN: From mnaomai or mimnesko; recollection; by implication, recital.

DEFINITION: a tomb, monument, memorial.
ORIGIN: From mnaomai; a memorial, i.e. Sepulchral monument (burial-place).

DEFINITION: a tomb, sepulcher, monument.
ORIGIN: From mneme; a remembrance, i.e. Cenotaph (place of interment).

DEFINITION: memory, remembrance, mention.
ORIGIN: From mimnesko; memory.

DEFINITION: to remember, hold in remembrance, make mention of.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of mneme; to exercise memory, i.e. Recollect; by implication, to punish; also to rehearse.

DEFINITION: reminder, memorial; a remembrance offering.
ORIGIN: From mnemoneuo; a reminder (memorandum), i.e. Record.

DEFINITION: to ask in marriage; pass: to be betrothed.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of mnaomai; to give a souvenir (engagement present), i.e. Betroth.

DEFINITION: one speaking with difficulty, a stammerer.
ORIGIN: From mogis and laleo; hardly talking, i.e. Dumb (tongue-tied).
USAGE: having an impediment in his speech.

DEFINITION: with difficulty; scarcely, hardly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a primary mogos (toil); with difficulty.

DEFINITION: a dry measure, nearly two English gallons.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; a modius, i.e. Certain measure for things dry (the quantity or the utensil).

DEFINITION: I, me, mine, my.
ORIGIN: The simpler form of emoi; to me.

DEFINITION: (a) an adulteress (that is, a married woman who commits adultery), (b) Hebraistically: extended to those who worship any other than the true God.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of the feminine of moichos; an adulteress (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to commit adultery, not only of a married woman but of a married man.
ORIGIN: From moichos; (middle voice) to commit adultery.

DEFINITION: adultery.
ORIGIN: From moicheuo; adultery.

DEFINITION: to commit adultery (of a man with a married woman, but also of a married man).
ORIGIN: From moichos; to commit adultery.

DEFINITION: an adulterer, that is, a man who is guilty with a married woman.
ORIGIN: Perhaps a primary word; a (male) paramour; figuratively, apostate.

DEFINITION: with difficulty, hardly, scarcely.
ORIGIN: Probably by variation for mogis; with difficulty.

DEFINITION: Moloch, a god worshipped by several Semitic peoples.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Molek); Moloch (i.e. Molek), an idol.

DEFINITION: to soil, stain, pollute, defile, lit. and met.
ORIGIN: Probably from melas; to soil (figuratively).

DEFINITION: staining, defilement, pollution.
ORIGIN: From moluno; a stain; i.e. (figuratively) immorality.

DEFINITION: a complaint, fault, blame.
ORIGIN: From memphomai; blame, i.e. (by implication), a fault.

DEFINITION: lodging, dwelling-place, room, abode, mansion.
ORIGIN: From meno; a staying, i.e. Residence (the act or the place).

DEFINITION: only, only-begotten; unique.
ORIGIN: From monos and ginomai; only-born, i.e. Sole.

DEFINITION: alone, but, only.
ORIGIN: Neuter of monos as adverb; merely.

DEFINITION: only, solitary, desolate.
ORIGIN: Probably from meno; remaining, i.e. Sole or single; by implication, mere.

DEFINITION: one-eyed, with one eye only.
ORIGIN: From monos and ophthalmos; one-eyed.

DEFINITION: to leave alone (solitary), forsake.
ORIGIN: From monos; to isolate, i.e. Bereave.

DEFINITION: form, shape, outward appearance.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from the base of meros (through the idea of adjustment of parts); shape; figuratively, nature.

DEFINITION: to form, fashion, shape, mold.
ORIGIN: From the same as morphe; to fashion (figuratively).

DEFINITION: form, outline, semblance.
ORIGIN: From morphoo; formation, i.e. (by implication), appearance (semblance or (concretely) formula).

DEFINITION: to make a calf (as an image).
ORIGIN: From moschos and poieo; to fabricate the image of a bullock.

DEFINITION: a calf, heifer, young bull.
ORIGIN: Probably strengthened for oschos (a shoot); a young bullock.

DEFINITION: wearisome labor, toil, hardship.
ORIGIN: From the base of mogis; toil, i.e. (by implication) sadness.

DEFINITION: I, me, mine own, my.
ORIGIN: The simpler form of emou; of me.

DEFINITION: skilled in music; subst: a musician, singer.
ORIGIN: From Mousa (a Muse); "musical", i.e. (as noun) a minstrel.

DEFINITION: marrow.
ORIGIN: Perhaps a primary word; the marrow.

DEFINITION: to initiate, instruct; pass: to be disciplined, learn (a lesson).
ORIGIN: From the base of musterion; to initiate, i.e. (by implication) to teach.

DEFINITION: an idle tale, fable, fanciful story.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from the same as mueo (through the idea of tuition); a tale, i.e. Fiction ("myth").

DEFINITION: to bellow, roar.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of muzo (to "moo"); to bellow (roar).

DEFINITION: (properly: to turn up the nose as a sign of contempt), to sneer at, disdain.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of the base of mukaomai (meaning snout, as that whence lowing proceeds); to make mouths at, i.e. Ridicule.

DEFINITION: belonging to a mill.
ORIGIN: From mulos; belonging to a mill.

DEFINITION: a mill, a millstone.
ORIGIN: Probably ultimately from the base of molis (through the idea of hardship); a "mill", i.e. (by implication), a grinder (millstone).

DEFINITION: a mill-house, the place where grain was ground.
ORIGIN: From mulos; a mill-house.

DEFINITION: Myra, a port in Lycia, south-west Asia Minor.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; Myra, a place in Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: a myriad, group of ten thousand, a ten thousand.
ORIGIN: From murioi; a ten-thousand; by extension, a "myriad" or indefinite number.

DEFINITION: to anoint.
ORIGIN: From muron; to apply (perfumed) unguent to.

DEFINITION: ten thousand; also used for a very large number, innumerable.
ORIGIN: Plural of an apparently primary word (properly, meaning very many); ten thousand; by extension, innumerably many.

DEFINITION: anointing-oil, ointment.
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin (compare more, smurna); "myrrh", i.e. (by implication) perfumed oil.

DEFINITION: Mysia, a country in the north-west of the Roman province Asia (and of Asia Minor).
ORIGIN: Of uncertain origin; Mysia, a region of Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: a mystery, secret, of which initiation is necessary; in the NT: the counsels of God, once hidden but now revealed in the Gospel or some fact thereof; the Christian revelation generally; particular truths or details of the Christian revelation.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of muo (to shut the mouth); a secret or "mystery" (through the idea of silence imposed by initiation into religious rites).

DEFINITION: to be short-sighted, blink, see dimly.
ORIGIN: From a compound of the base of musterion and ops (the face; from optanomai); to shut the eyes, i.e. Blink (see indistinctly).

DEFINITION: a bruise, stripe, left on the body by scourging.
ORIGIN: From molos ("moil"; probably akin to the base of molis) and probably ops (the face; from optanomai); a mole ("black eye") or blow-mark.

DEFINITION: to blame, find fault with, slander.
ORIGIN: From momos; to carp at, i.e. Censure (discredit).

DEFINITION: a blemish, disgrace; blame.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from memphomai; a flaw or blot, i.e. (figuratively) disgraceful person.

DEFINITION: (a) to make foolish, turn to foolishness, (b) to taint, and thus: to be tasteless, make useless.
ORIGIN: From moros; to become insipid; figuratively, to make (passively, act) as a simpleton.
USAGE: become fool, make foolish, lose savour.

DEFINITION: folly, absurdity, foolishness.
ORIGIN: From moros; silliness, i.e. Absurdity.

DEFINITION: foolish talking.
ORIGIN: From a compound of moros and lego; silly talk, i.e. Buffoonery.

DEFINITION: (a) adj: stupid, foolish, (b) noun: a fool.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of musterion; dull or stupid (as if shut up), i.e. Heedless, (morally) blockhead, (apparently) absurd.

DEFINITION: Moses; met: the books of Moses, the Pentateuch.
ORIGIN: Or Moses (mo-sace'), or Mouses (mo-oo-sace') of Hebrew origin; (Mosheh) Moseus, Moses, or Mouses (i.e. Mosheh), the Hebrew lawgiver.

DEFINITION: Nahshon, son of Amminadab and father of Salmon, and one of the ancestors of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Nachshown); Naasson (i.e. Nachshon), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Naggai, one of the ancestors of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Probably of Hebrew origin (compare Nogahh); Nangae (i.e. Perhaps Nogach), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Nazareth, a city of Galilee, where Jesus lived before His ministry.
ORIGIN: Or Nazaret nad-zar-et'; of uncertain derivation; Nazareth or Nazaret, a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: a Nazarene, an inhabitant of Nazareth.
ORIGIN: From Nazareth; a Nazarene, i.e. Inhabitant of Nazareth.

DEFINITION: a Nazarene, an inhabitant of Nazareth.
ORIGIN: From Nazareth; a Nazoraean, i.e. Inhabitant of Nazareth; by extension, a Christian.

DEFINITION: Nathan, son of David, and an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Nathan); Nathan, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Nathanael, of Cana in Galilee, an early disciple, probably to be identified with Bartholomew.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Nthane'l); Nathanael (i.e. Nathanel), an Israelite and Christian.

DEFINITION: yes (indeed), certainly.
ORIGIN: A primary particle of strong affirmation; yes.
USAGE: even so, surely, truth, verily, yea, yes.

DEFINITION: Nain, a city south-west of the Sea of Galilee.
ORIGIN: Probably of Hebrew origin (compare na'ah); Nain, a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: a temple, a shrine, that part of the temple where God himself resides.
ORIGIN: From a primary naio (to dwell); a fane, shrine, temple.

DEFINITION: Nahum, an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Nachuwm); Naum (i.e. Nachum), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: spikenard, a perfume made originally from a plant growing on the Himalayas.
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin (compare nerd); "nard".

DEFINITION: Narcissus, a resident of Rome.
ORIGIN: A flower of the same name, from narke (stupefaction, as a "narcotic"); Narcissus, a Roman.

DEFINITION: (a) to be shipwrecked; so (b) fig: to come to ruin.
ORIGIN: From a compound of naus and ago; to be shipwrecked (stranded, "navigate"), literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: a captain (master) of a ship, ship-owner.
ORIGIN: From naus and kleros ("clerk"); a captain.

DEFINITION: a ship, vessel.
ORIGIN: From nao or neo (to float); a boat (of any size).

DEFINITION: a sailor, seaman.
ORIGIN: From naus; a boatman, i.e. Seaman.

DEFINITION: Nahor, one of the ancestors of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Nachowr); Nachor, the grandfather of Abraham.

DEFINITION: a young man, youth; a man in his prime (used even of a man of 40).
ORIGIN: From a derivative of neos; a youth (up to about forty years).

DEFINITION: a young man, youth, an attendant.
ORIGIN: From the same as neanias; a youth (under forty).

DEFINITION: Neapolis, a city of Macedonia.
ORIGIN: From neos and polis; new town; Neapolis, a place in Macedonia.

DEFINITION: Naaman.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Na'aman); Neeman (i.e. Naaman), a Syrian.

DEFINITION: (a) adj: dead, lifeless, subject to death, mortal, (b) noun: a dead body, a corpse.
ORIGIN: From an apparently primary nekus (a corpse); dead (literally or figuratively; also as noun).

DEFINITION: lit. and met: to put to death, make as dead; to render weak, impotent.
ORIGIN: From nekros; to deaden, i.e. (figuratively) to subdue.

DEFINITION: (a) putting to death, (b) dead or lifeless condition.
ORIGIN: From nekroo; decease; figuratively, impotency.

DEFINITION: (a) young, youthful, (b) new, fresh.
ORIGIN: Including the comparative neoteros neh-o'-ter-os; a primary word; "new", i.e. (of persons) youthful, or (of things) fresh; figuratively, regenerate.

DEFINITION: a young bird, nestling; a young one.
ORIGIN: From neos; a youngling (nestling).

DEFINITION: youth, youthfulness.
ORIGIN: From neos; newness, i.e. Youthfulness.

DEFINITION: (lit: newly-planted), newly converted to Christianity, recent convert.
ORIGIN: From neos and a derivative of phuo; newly planted, i.e. (figuratively) a young convert ("neophyte").

DEFINITION: Nero.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; Neron (i.e. Nero), a Roman emperor.

DEFINITION: to nod or beckon (as a sign).
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to "nod", i.e. (by analogy), signal.

DEFINITION: a cloud.
ORIGIN: From nephos; properly, cloudiness, i.e. (concretely) a cloud.

DEFINITION: Naphtali, son of Jacob, founder of a tribe which occupied territory.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Naphtaliy); Nephthaleim (i.e. Naphthali), a tribe in Palestine.

DEFINITION: a cloud; met: a dense crowd, a multitude, great company.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a cloud.

DEFINITION: a kidney (as a general emotional center), the reins.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a kidney (plural), i.e. (figuratively) the inmost mind.

DEFINITION: (lit: temple-sweeper), temple-warden; an honorary title.
ORIGIN: From a form of naos and koreo (to sweep); a temple-servant, i.e. (by implication) a votary.

DEFINITION: associated with youth, youthful, juvenile.
ORIGIN: From the comparative of neos; appertaining to younger persons, i.e. Juvenile.

DEFINITION: of affirmative swearing: by, with acc. of person or thing sworn by.
ORIGIN: Probably an intensive form of nai; a particle of attestation (accompanied by the object invoked or appealed to in confirmation); as sure as.

DEFINITION: to spin.
ORIGIN: From neo (of like meaning); to spin.

DEFINITION: to be childlike, childish, infantile.
ORIGIN: From nepios; to act as a babe, i.e. (figuratively) innocently.

DEFINITION: unlearned, unenlightened; noun: an infant, child.
ORIGIN: From an obsolete particle ne- (implying negation) and epos; not speaking, i.e. An infant (minor); figuratively, a simple-minded person, an immature Christian.

DEFINITION: Nereus, a Christian in Rome.
ORIGIN: Apparently from a derivative of the base of naus (meaning wet); Nereus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: Neri, an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Neriyah); Neri (i.e. Nerijah), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: a little island, an islet.
ORIGIN: Diminutive of nesos; an islet.

DEFINITION: an island.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of naus; an island.

DEFINITION: fasting, the day of atonement.
ORIGIN: From nesteuo; abstinence (from lack of food, or voluntary and religious); specially, the fast of the Day of Atonement.

DEFINITION: to fast, abstain from food.
ORIGIN: From nestis; to abstain from food (religiously).

DEFINITION: fasting, not eating.
ORIGIN: From the inseparable negative particle ne- (not) and esthio; not eating, i.e. Abstinent from food (religiously).

DEFINITION: sober, not intoxicated (with wine), temperate, vigilant.
ORIGIN: Or nephalios (nay-fal'-ee-os) from nepho; sober, i.e. (figuratively) circumspect.

DEFINITION: (lit: to be sober), to be calm (vigilant), circumspect.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity: to abstain from wine (keep sober), i.e. (figuratively) be discreet.

DEFINITION: Niger, a proper name.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; black; Niger, a Christian.

DEFINITION: Nicanor, a proper name.
ORIGIN: Probably from nikao; victorious; Nicanor, a Christian.

DEFINITION: to conquer, be victorious, overcome, prevail, subdue.
ORIGIN: From nike; to subdue (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: conquer, overcome, prevail, get the victory.

DEFINITION: victory, a victorious principle.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; conquest (abstractly), i.e. (figuratively) the means of success.

DEFINITION: Nicodemus, a member of the Sanhedrin.
ORIGIN: From nikos and demos; victorious among his people; Nicodemus, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: a Nicolaitan, possibly a follower of Nicolaus (a heretic at Ephesus).
ORIGIN: From Nikolaos; a Nicolaite, i.e. Adherent of Nicolaus.

DEFINITION: Nicolaus, a Christian, probably not connected with the sect bearing the same name.
ORIGIN: From nikos and Laodikeus; victorious over the people; Nicolaus, a heretic.

DEFINITION: "victorious city", Nicopolis, a city in Achaia.
ORIGIN: From nikos and polis; victorious city; Nicopolis, a place in Macedonia.

DEFINITION: victory.
ORIGIN: From nike; a conquest (concretely), i.e. (by implication) triumph.

DEFINITION: Nineveh, a city on the Tigris in Assyria.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Niynveh); Ninevi (i.e. Nineveh), the capital of Assyria.

DEFINITION: a Ninevite, an inhabitant of Nineveh, a city on the Tigris in Assyria.
ORIGIN: From Nineui; a Ninevite, i.e. Inhabitant of Nineveh.

DEFINITION: a basin for washing hands or feet.
ORIGIN: From nipto; a ewer.

DEFINITION: to wash; mid. to wash own (hands, etc.).
ORIGIN: To cleanse (especially the hands or the feet or the face); ceremonially, to perform ablution.

DEFINITION: to understand, think, consider, conceive, apprehend; aor. possibly: realize.
ORIGIN: From nous; to exercise the mind (observe), i.e. (figuratively) to comprehend, heed.

DEFINITION: a thought, purpose, design; the mind; the heart, soul, feelings.
ORIGIN: From noieo; a perception, i.e. Purpose, or (by implication) the intellect, disposition, itself.

DEFINITION: illegitimate, base-born.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a spurious or illegitimate son.

DEFINITION: (a) pasture, pasturage, (b) met: growth, increase.
ORIGIN: Feminine from the same as nomos; pasture, i.e. (the act) feeding (figuratively, spreading of a gangrene), or (the food) pasturage.

DEFINITION: to practice, hold by custom; to deem, think, consider, suppose.
ORIGIN: From nomos; properly, to do by law (usage), i.e. To accustom (passively, be usual); by extension, to deem or regard.

DEFINITION: (a) adj: connected with law, about law, (b) noun: a lawyer, one learned in the Law, one learned in the Old Testament.
ORIGIN: From nomos; according (or pertaining) to law, i.e. Legal (ceremonially); as noun, an expert in the (Mosaic) law.

DEFINITION: lawfully, rightfully.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a derivative of nomos; legitimately (specially, agreeably to the rules of the lists).

DEFINITION: a custom, current coin.
ORIGIN: From nomizo; what is reckoned as of value (after the Latin numisma), i.e. Current coin.

DEFINITION: a teacher and interpreter of the Mosaic Law.
ORIGIN: From nomos and didaskalos; an expounder of the (Jewish) law, i.e. A Rabbi.

DEFINITION: legislation, lawgiving.
ORIGIN: From nomothetes; legislation (specially, the institution of the Mosaic code).

DEFINITION: (a) to ordain, lay down, give the sanction of law to, enact, (b) to base legally, regulate, direct.
ORIGIN: From nomothetes; to legislate, i.e. (passively) to have (the Mosaic) enactments injoined, be sanctioned (by them).

DEFINITION: a law-giver, legislator.
ORIGIN: From nomos and a derivative of tithemi; a legislator.

DEFINITION: usage, custom, law; in NT: of law in general, plur: of divine laws; of a force or influence impelling to action; of the Mosaic law; meton: of the books which contain the law, the Pentateuch, the Old Testament scriptures in general.
ORIGIN: From a primary nemo (to parcel out, especially food or grazing to animals); law (through the idea of prescriptive usage), genitive case (regulation), specially, (of Moses (including the volume); also of the Gospel), or figuratively (a principle).

DEFINITION: to be diseased, hence of mental or spiritual disease.
ORIGIN: From nosos; to be sick, i.e. (by implication, of a diseased appetite) to hanker after (figuratively, to harp upon).

DEFINITION: a trouble, disease, sickness.
ORIGIN: From noseo; an ailment.

DEFINITION: a disease, malady, sickness.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a malady (rarely figuratively, of moral disability).

DEFINITION: a brood of young birds.
ORIGIN: From neossos; a brood (of chickens).

DEFINITION: a nestling, the young of birds.
ORIGIN: Diminutive of neossos; a birdling.

DEFINITION: to rob; mid: to set apart for myself, appropriate for own benefit, purloin.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from nosphi (apart or clandestinely); to sequestrate for oneself, i.e. Embezzle.

DEFINITION: the south wind, the southern quarter.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; the south(-west) wind; by extension, the southern quarter itself.

DEFINITION: a warning, admonition, counsel.
ORIGIN: From nous and a derivative of tithemi; calling attention to, i.e. (by implication) mild rebuke or warning.

DEFINITION: to admonish, warn, counsel, exhort.
ORIGIN: From the same as nouthesia; to put in mind, i.e. (by implication) to caution or reprove gently.

DEFINITION: the new moon, first of the month.
ORIGIN: Feminine of a compound of neos and men (as noun by implication, of hemera); the festival of new moon.

DEFINITION: wisely, discreetly, reasonably, sensibly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a comparative of the accusative case of nous and echo; in a mind-having way, i.e. Prudently.

DEFINITION: the mind, the reason, the reasoning faculty, intellect.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of ginosko; the intellect, i.e. Mind (divine or human; in thought, feeling, or will); by implication, meaning.

DEFINITION: Nympha, a Christian of Laodicea.
ORIGIN: Probably contracted for a compound of numphe and doron; nymph-given (i.e. -born); Nymphas, a Christian.

DEFINITION: (a) a bride, young wife, young woman, (b) a daughter-in-law.
ORIGIN: From a primary but obsolete verb nupto (to veil as a bride; compare Latin "nupto," to marry); a young married woman (as veiled), including a betrothed girl; by implication, a son's wife.

DEFINITION: a bridegroom.
ORIGIN: From numphe; a bride-groom (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: the bridechamber.
ORIGIN: From numphe; the bridal room.

DEFINITION: adv. (a) of time: just now, even now; just at hand, immediately, (b) of logical connection: now then, (c) in commands and appeals: at this instant.
ORIGIN: A primary particle of present time; "now" (as adverb of date, a transition or emphasis); also as noun or adjective present or immediate.
USAGE: henceforth, + hereafter, of late, soon, present, this (time). See also tanun, nuni.

DEFINITION: but now.
ORIGIN: Or ta nun (tah noon) from neuter plural of ho and nun; the things now, i.e. (adverbially) at present.

DEFINITION: adv. (a) of time: just now, even now; just at hand, immediately, (b) of logical connection: now then, (c) in commands and appeals: at this instant.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of nun for emphasis; just now.

DEFINITION: the night, night-time.
ORIGIN: A primary word; "night" (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to prick, pierce.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; to prick ("nudge").

DEFINITION: to nod in sleep, be drowsy, slumber.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of neuo; to nod, i.e. (by implication) to fall asleep; figuratively, to delay.

DEFINITION: a night and day, twenty-four hours.
ORIGIN: From nux and hemera; a day-and-night, i.e. Full day of twenty-four hours.

DEFINITION: Noah, a patriarch.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Noach); Noe, (i.e. Noach), a patriarch.

DEFINITION: blunt, dull, hence spiritually; sluggish, remiss, slack.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of nothos; sluggish, i.e. (literally) lazy, or (figuratively) stupid.

DEFINITION: the back (of men or animals).
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; the back.

DEFINITION: hospitality, a lodging place.
ORIGIN: From xenos; hospitality, i.e. (by implication) a place of entertainment.

DEFINITION: (a) to entertain a stranger, (b) to startle, bewilder.
ORIGIN: From xenos; to be a host (passively, a guest); by implication, be (make, appear) strange.

DEFINITION: to entertain strangers, practice hospitality.
ORIGIN: From a compound of xenos and dechomai; to be hospitable.

DEFINITION: alien, new, novel; noun: a guest, stranger, foreigner.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; foreign (literally, alien, or figuratively, novel); by implication, a guest or (vice-versa) entertainer.

DEFINITION: a sextarius (about a pint), a pitcher (of wood or stone).
ORIGIN: As if from xeo (properly, to smooth; by implication, (of friction) to boil or heat); a vessel (as fashioned or for cooking) (or perhaps by corruption from the Latin sextarius, the sixth of a modius, i.e. About a pint), i.e. (specially), a measure for liquids or solids, (by analogy, a pitcher).

DEFINITION: to dry up, parch, be ripened, wither, waste away.
ORIGIN: From xeros; to desiccate; by implication, to shrivel, to mature.
USAGE: dry up, pine away, be ripe, wither (away).

DEFINITION: dry, withered; noun: dry land.
ORIGIN: From the base of xestes (through the idea of scorching); arid; by implication, shrunken, earth (as opposed to water).

DEFINITION: wooden.
ORIGIN: From xulon; wooden.

DEFINITION: anything made of wood, a piece of wood, a club, staff; the trunk of a tree, used to support the cross-bar of a cross in crucifixion.
ORIGIN: From another form of the base of xestes; timber (as fuel or material); by implication, a stick, club or tree or other wooden article or substance.

DEFINITION: to shave, shear, cut off the hair.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of the same as xulon (meaning a razor); to shave or "shear" the hair.

DEFINITION: the, the definite article.
ORIGIN: Including the feminine he (hay), and the neuter to (to) in all their inflections; the definite article; the (sometimes to be supplied, at others omitted, in English idiom).
USAGE: the, this, that, one, he, she, it, etc.

DEFINITION: eighty.
ORIGIN: From ogdoos; ten times eight.

DEFINITION: the eighth, one of eight, with seven others.
ORIGIN: From oktos; the eighth.

DEFINITION: (properly: bulk, mass, hence) a weight, burden, encumbrance.
ORIGIN: Probably from the same as agkale; a mass (as bending or bulging by its load), i.e. Burden (hindrance).

DEFINITION: this (referring to what is present).
ORIGIN: Including the feminine hede (hay'-deh), and the neuter tode (tod'-e) from ho and de; the same, i.e. This or that one (plural these or those); often used as a personal pronoun.

DEFINITION: to journey, travel.
ORIGIN: From hodos; to travel.

DEFINITION: to lead, guide; met: to instruct, teach.
ORIGIN: From hodegos; to show the way (literally or figuratively (teach)).

DEFINITION: a leader, guide; met: an instructor, teacher.
ORIGIN: From hodos and hegeomai; a conductor (literally or figuratively (teacher)).

DEFINITION: to travel, pursue a way, journey.
ORIGIN: From a compound of hodos and poreuomai; to be a wayfarer, i.e. Travel.

DEFINITION: a journey, journeying, travel.
ORIGIN: From the same as hodoiporeo; travel.

DEFINITION: a way, road, journey, path.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a road; by implication, a progress (the route, act or distance); figuratively, a mode or means.

DEFINITION: a tooth.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from the base of esthio; a "tooth".

DEFINITION: to torment, pain; mid. and pass: to be tormented, pained; to suffer acute pain, physical or mental.
ORIGIN: From odune; to grieve.

DEFINITION: pain, sorrow, distress, of body or mind.
ORIGIN: From duno; grief (as dejecting).

DEFINITION: lamentation, wailing, mourning, sorrow.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of the base of duno; moaning, i.e. Lamentation.

DEFINITION: called, that is to say.
ORIGIN: From the neuter of hos and the third person singular present indicative of eimi; which is.
USAGE: called, which is (make), that is (to say).

DEFINITION: Uzziah, son of Joram and father of Jotham, and king of Judah from about 785 to 746 B.C., an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Uzziyah); Ozias (i.e. Uzzijah), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: to stink, be offensive.
ORIGIN: A primary verb (in a strengthened form).

DEFINITION: (a) whence, from which place, (b) wherefore.
ORIGIN: From hos with the directive enclitic of source; from which place or source or cause (adverb or conjunction).

DEFINITION: a linen cloth, a sheet, sail.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a linen cloth, i.e. (especially) a sail.

DEFINITION: a linen bandage, a wrapping.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of othone; a linen bandage.

DEFINITION: of one's family, domestic, intimate.
ORIGIN: From oikos; domestic, i.e. (as noun), a relative, adherent.

DEFINITION: a household (of servants).
ORIGIN: From oikeo; a fellow resident, i.e. Menial domestic.

DEFINITION: to inhabit, dwell, indwell.
ORIGIN: From oikos; to occupy a house, i.e. Reside (figuratively, inhabit, remain, inhere); by implication, to cohabit.

DEFINITION: a prison cell.
ORIGIN: From oikeo; a tenement, i.e. (specially), a jail.

DEFINITION: a dwelling-place, habitation, abode.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of oikeo (equivalent to oikema); a residence (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a house, household, dwelling; meton: goods, property, means.
ORIGIN: From oikos; properly, residence (abstractly), but usually (concretely) an abode (literally or figuratively); by implication, a family (especially domestics).

DEFINITION: one of a family, whether child or servant.
ORIGIN: From oikia; familiar, i.e. (as noun) relatives.

DEFINITION: to manage a household.
ORIGIN: From oikodespotes; to be the head of (i.e. Rule) a family.

DEFINITION: the master of a house.
ORIGIN: From oikos and despotes; the head of a family.
USAGE: goodman (of the house), householder, master of the house.

DEFINITION: to erect a building, build; fig. of the building up of character: to build up, edify, encourage.
ORIGIN: From the same as oikodome; to be a house-builder, i.e. Construct or (figuratively) confirm.

DEFINITION: (a) the act of building, (b) a building, (c) met: spiritual advancement, edification.
ORIGIN: Feminine (abstract) of a compound of oikos and the base of doma; architecture, i.e. (concretely) a structure; figuratively, confirmation.

DEFINITION: edifying.
ORIGIN: From the same as oikodome; confirmation.

DEFINITION: to be a steward, manage a household.
ORIGIN: From oikonomos; to manage (a house, i.e. An estate).

DEFINITION: management of household affairs, stewardship, administration.
ORIGIN: From oikonomos; administration (of a household or estate); specially, a (religious) "economy".

DEFINITION: a household manager, a steward, guardian.
ORIGIN: From oikos and the base of nomos; a house-distributor (i.e. Manager), or overseer, i.e. An employee in that capacity; by extension, a fiscal agent (treasurer); figuratively, a preacher (of the Gospel).

DEFINITION: (a) a house, the material building, (b) a household, family, lineage, nation.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a dwelling (more or less extensive, literal or figurative); by implication, a family (more or less related, literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: (properly: the land that is being inhabited, the land in a state of habitation), the inhabited world, that is, the Roman world, for all outside it was regarded as of no account.
ORIGIN: Feminine participle present passive of oikeo (as noun, by implication, of ge); land, i.e. The (terrene part of the) globe; specially, the Roman empire.

DEFINITION: a keeper-at-home, a housekeeper.
ORIGIN: From oikos and ouros (a guard; be "ware"); a stayer at home, i.e. Domestically inclined (a "good housekeeper").

DEFINITION: to pity, to have compassion on.
ORIGIN: Also (in certain tenses) prolonged oiktereo oyk-ter-eh'-o from oiktos (pity); to exercise pity.

DEFINITION: pity, compassion, favor, grace, mercy.
ORIGIN: From oikteiro; pity.

DEFINITION: compassionate, merciful.
ORIGIN: From oikteiro; compassionate.

DEFINITION: an excessive wine-drinker.
ORIGIN: From oinos and a derivative of the alternate of pino; a tippler.

DEFINITION: wine.
ORIGIN: A primary word (or perhaps of Hebrew origin (yayin)); "wine" (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: drunkenness, debauchery.
ORIGIN: From oinos and a form of the base of phluaros; an overflow (or surplus) of wine, i.e. Vinolency (drunkenness).

DEFINITION: to think, suppose, expect, imagine.
ORIGIN: Or (shorter) oimai (oy'-mahee) middle voice apparently from hoios; to make like (oneself), i.e. Imagine (be of the opinion).

DEFINITION: what sort or manner of.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to ho, hos, and hosos; such or what sort of (as a correlation or exclamation); especially the neuter (adverbially) with negative, not so.
USAGE: so (as), such as, what (manner of), which.

DEFINITION: to shrink (from doing), to hesitate (to do).
ORIGIN: From oknos (hesitation); to be slow (figuratively, loath).

DEFINITION: slothful, backward, hesitating; of things: irksome.
ORIGIN: From okneo; tardy, i.e. Indolent; (figuratively) irksome.

DEFINITION: of or belonging to the eighth day, eight days old.
ORIGIN: From oktos and hemera; an eight-day old person or act.

DEFINITION: eight.
ORIGIN: A primary numeral; "eight".

DEFINITION: ruin, doom, destruction, death.
ORIGIN: From a primary ollumi (to destroy; a prolonged form); ruin, i.e. Death, punishment.

DEFINITION: of little faith.
ORIGIN: From oligos and pistis; incredulous, i.e. Lacking confidence (in Christ).

DEFINITION: (a) especially in plur: few, (b) in sing: small; hence, of time: short, of degree: light, slight, little.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; puny (in extent, degree, number, duration or value); especially neuter (adverbially) somewhat.
USAGE: + almost, brief(-ly), few, (a) little, + long, a season, short, small, a while.

DEFINITION: faint-hearted, of small courage.
ORIGIN: From oligos and pshar; little-spirited, i.e. Faint-hearted.

DEFINITION: to despise, hold in low esteem, make light of.
ORIGIN: From a compound of oligos and ora ("care"); to have little regard for, i.e. To disesteem.

DEFINITION: a destroyer.
ORIGIN: From olothreuo; a ruiner, i.e. (specially), a venomous serpent.

DEFINITION: to destroy, cause to perish.
ORIGIN: From olethros; to spoil, i.e. Slay.

DEFINITION: a whole burnt offering.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of a compound of holos and a derivative of kaio; a wholly-consumed sacrifice ("holocaust").

DEFINITION: perfect soundness, completeness.
ORIGIN: From holokleros; integrity, i.e. Physical wholeness.

DEFINITION: complete in every part, sound, perfect, entire.
ORIGIN: From holos and kleros; complete in every part, i.e. Perfectly sound (in body).

DEFINITION: to howl, lament loudly, cry aloud, bewail.
ORIGIN: A reduplicated primary verb; to "howl" or "halloo", i.e. Shriek.

DEFINITION: all, the whole, entire, complete.
ORIGIN: A primary word; "whole" or "all", i.e. Complete (in extent, amount, time or degree), especially (neuter) as noun or adverb.
USAGE: all, altogether, every whit, + throughout, whole.

DEFINITION: perfect, complete, all.
ORIGIN: From holos and telos; complete to the end, i.e. Absolutely perfect.

DEFINITION: Olympas, a Christian man in Rome.
ORIGIN: Probably a contraction from Olumpiodoros (Olympian-bestowed, i.e. Heaven-descended); Olympas, a Christian.

DEFINITION: an unripe fig, one which, not ripening in due time, grows through the winter and falls off in the spring.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; an unripe (because out of season) fig.

DEFINITION: wholly, altogether, actually, really; with negative: not at all.
ORIGIN: Adverb from holos; completely, i.e. Altogether; (by analogy), everywhere; (negatively) not by any means.

DEFINITION: a violent rain, a shower.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a thunder storm.

DEFINITION: to consort with, associate with, commune with; particularly, to talk (converse) with.
ORIGIN: From homilos; to be in company with, i.e. (by implication) to converse.

DEFINITION: intercourse, companionship, conversation, association.
ORIGIN: From homilos; companionship ("homily"), i.e. (by implication) intercourse.

DEFINITION: a mist or fog.
ORIGIN: From the base of homou and a derivative of the alternate of haireomai (meaning a crowd); association together, i.e. A multitude.

DEFINITION: an eye.
ORIGIN: From optanomai; a sight, i.e. (by implication) the eye.

DEFINITION: to swear, take an oath, promise with an oath.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary, but obsolete omo, for which another prolonged form omoo (om-o'-o) is used in certain tenses; to swear, i.e. Take (or declare on) oath.

DEFINITION: with one mind, unanimously, with one accord, at the same time.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a compound of the base of homou and thumos; unanimously.

DEFINITION: to be like, resemble.
ORIGIN: From homoios; to resemble.

DEFINITION: of like feelings, having similar passions and feelings, of like infirmities.
ORIGIN: From homoios and the alternate of pascho; similarly affected.

DEFINITION: like, similar to, resembling, of equal rank.
ORIGIN: From the base of homou; similar (in appearance or character).

DEFINITION: likeness, in like manner.
ORIGIN: From homoios; resemblance.

DEFINITION: to make like, liken; to compare.
ORIGIN: From homoios; to assimilate, i.e. Compare; passively, to become similar.

DEFINITION: (originally: a thing made like something else), a likeness, or rather: form; a similitude.
ORIGIN: From homoioo; a form; abstractly, resemblance.
USAGE: made like to, likeness, shape, similitude.

DEFINITION: in like manner, similarly, in the same way, equally.
ORIGIN: Adverb from homoios; similarly.

DEFINITION: making like, likeness, resemblance.
ORIGIN: From homoioo; assimilation, i.e. Resemblance.

DEFINITION: (a) to promise, agree, (b) to confess, (c) to publicly declare, (d) a Hebraism, to praise, celebrate.
ORIGIN: From a compound of the base of homou and logos; to assent, i.e. Covenant, acknowledge.
USAGE: con- (pro-)fess, confession is made, give thanks, promise.

DEFINITION: an agreement, confession.
ORIGIN: From the same as homologeo; acknowledgment.

DEFINITION: admittedly, without controversy.
ORIGIN: Adverb of present passive participle of homologeo; confessedly.

DEFINITION: of the same trade or craft.
ORIGIN: From the base of homou and techne; a fellow-artificer.

DEFINITION: together, at the same place and time.
ORIGIN: Genitive case of homos (the same; akin to hama) as adverb; at the same place or time.

DEFINITION: of one mind (intent, purpose), like-minded.
ORIGIN: From the base of homou and phren; like-minded, i.e. Harmonious.

DEFINITION: yet, nevertheless, even.
ORIGIN: Adverb from the base of homou; at the same time, i.e. (conjunctionally) notwithstanding, yet still.

DEFINITION: a dream, in a dream.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a dream.

DEFINITION: a little donkey.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of onos; a little ass.

DEFINITION: to reproach, revile, upbraid.
ORIGIN: From oneidos; to defame, i.e. Rail at, chide, taunt.
USAGE: cast in teeth, (suffer) reproach, revile, upbraid.

DEFINITION: reproach, reviling.
ORIGIN: From oneidizo; contumely.

DEFINITION: reproach, disgrace.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to the base of onoma; notoriety, i.e. A taunt (disgrace).

DEFINITION: (originally adj: useful, hence the play upon words in Philemon 10, 11, and very common as slave name), Onesimus, a slave of Philemon, a Christian of Colossae.
ORIGIN: From oninemi; profitable; Onesimus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: Onesiphorus, a Christian of the province of Asia.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of oninemi and phoros; profit-bearer; Onesiphorus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: pertaining to an ass.
ORIGIN: From onos; belonging to a ass, i.e. Large (so as to be turned by a ass).

DEFINITION: to profit, benefit, help; mid: to have profit, derive benefit.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of an apparently primary verb (onomai, to slur); for which another prolonged form (onao) is used as an alternate in some tenses (unless indeed it be identical with the base of onoma through the idea of notoriety); to gratify, i.e. (middle voice) to derive pleasure or advantage from.

DEFINITION: name, character, fame, reputation.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of the base of ginosko (compare oninemi); a "name" (literally or figuratively) (authority, character).

DEFINITION: to give a name to, mention, call upon the name of.
ORIGIN: From onoma; to name, i.e. Assign an appellation; by extension, to utter, mention, profess.

DEFINITION: a donkey, an ass.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a donkey.

DEFINITION: really, truly, actually.
ORIGIN: Adverb of the oblique cases of on; really.
USAGE: certainly, clean, indeed, of a truth, verily.

DEFINITION: vinegar, sour wine mixed with water, a common drink of Roman soldiers.
ORIGIN: From oxus; vinegar, i.e. Sour wine.

DEFINITION: (a) sharp, (b) swift, eager.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to the base of akmen ("acid"); keen; by analogy, rapid.

DEFINITION: a crevice (in a rock), a cave, an opening, hole.
ORIGIN: Probably from optanomai; a hole (as if for light), i.e. Cavern; by analogy, a spring (of water).

DEFINITION: from behind, after.
ORIGIN: From opis (regard; from optanomai) with enclitic of source; from the rear (as a secure aspect), i.e. At the back (adverb and preposition of place or time).

DEFINITION: behind, after; back, backwards.
ORIGIN: From the same as opisthen with enclitic of direction; to the back, i.e. Aback (as adverb or preposition of time or place; or as noun).

DEFINITION: to make ready, arm, equip.
ORIGIN: From hoplon; to equip (with weapons (middle voice and figuratively)).

DEFINITION: an instrument; plur: arms, weapons.
ORIGIN: Probably from a primary hepo (to be busy about); an implement or utensil or tool (literally or figuratively, especially, offensive for war).

DEFINITION: of what kind or manner, of what sort.
ORIGIN: From hos and poios; of what kind that, i.e. How (as) great (excellent) (specially, as an indefinite correlative to the definite antecedent toioutos of quality).
USAGE: what manner (sort) of, such as whatsoever.

DEFINITION: when.
ORIGIN: From hos and pote; what(-ever) then, i.e. (of time) as soon as.

DEFINITION: where, whither, in what place.
ORIGIN: From hos and pou; what(-ever) where, i.e. At whichever spot.
USAGE: in what place, where(-as, -soever), whither (+ soever).

DEFINITION: to appear, be seen (by), let myself be seen (by).
ORIGIN: A (middle voice) prolonged form of the primary (middle voice) optomai (op'-tom-ahee); which is used for it in certain tenses; and both as alternate of horao; to gaze (i.e. With wide-open eyes, as at something remarkable; and thus differing from blepo, which denotes simply voluntary observation; and from eido, which expresses merely mechanical, passive or casual vision; while theaomai, and still more emphatically its intensive theoreo, signifies an earnest but more continued inspection; and skopeo a watching from a distance).

DEFINITION: a vision, supernatural appearance.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of optanomai; visuality, i.e. (concretely) an apparition.

DEFINITION: roasted, broiled.
ORIGIN: From an obsolete verb akin to hepso (to "steep"); cooked, i.e. Roasted.

DEFINITION: late summer, ripe fruits.
ORIGIN: Apparently from the base of opse and hora; properly, even-tide of the (summer) season (dog-days), i.e. (by implication) ripe fruit.

DEFINITION: how, in order that, so that, that.
ORIGIN: From hos and pos; what(-ever) how, i.e. In the manner that (as adverb or conjunction of coincidence, intentional or actual).

DEFINITION: a spectacle, vision, that which is seen.
ORIGIN: From horao; something gazed at, i.e. A spectacle (especially supernatural).

DEFINITION: the act of seeing, a vision, appearance.
ORIGIN: From horao; the act of gazing, i.e. (externally) an aspect or (internally) an inspired appearance.

DEFINITION: visible.
ORIGIN: From horao; gazed at, i.e. (by implication) capable of being seen.

DEFINITION: to see, look upon, experience, perceive, discern, beware.
ORIGIN: Properly, to stare at (compare optanomai), i.e. (by implication) to discern clearly (physically or mentally); by extension, to attend to; by Hebraism, to experience; passively, to appear.

DEFINITION: anger, wrath, passion; punishment, vengeance.
ORIGIN: From oregomai; properly, desire (as a reaching forth or excitement of the mind), i.e. (by analogy), violent passion (ire, or (justifiable) abhorrence); by implication punishment.

DEFINITION: to irritate, provoke, be angry.
ORIGIN: From orge; to provoke or enrage, i.e. (passively) become exasperated.

DEFINITION: inclined to anger, passionate.
ORIGIN: From orge; irascible.

DEFINITION: a fathom (the length of the outstretched arms).
ORIGIN: From oregomai; a stretch of the arms, i.e. A fathom.

DEFINITION: to stretch forth, mid: to hanker after, long for, be eager for, aspire to.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of apparently a prolonged form of an obsolete primary (compare oros); to stretch oneself, i.e. Reach out after (long for).

DEFINITION: mountainous, hilly, the hill-country.
ORIGIN: From oros; mountainous, i.e. (feminine by implication, of chora) the Highlands (of Judaea).

DEFINITION: strong desire, lust, appetite.
ORIGIN: From oregomai; excitement of the mind, i.e. Longing after.

DEFINITION: to walk in a straight course, walk uprightly.
ORIGIN: From a compound of orthos and pous; to be straight-footed, i.e. (figuratively) to go directly forward.

DEFINITION: upright, straight, direct.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of oros; right (as rising), i.e. (perpendicularly) erect (figuratively, honest), or (horizontally) level or direct.

DEFINITION: to cut straight; met: to handle correctly, teach rightly.
ORIGIN: From a compound of orthos and the base of tomoteros, to make a straight cut, i.e. (figuratively) to dissect (expound) correctly (the divine message).

DEFINITION: to rise early, come in the morning.
ORIGIN: From orthros; to use the dawn, i.e. (by implication) to repair betimes.

DEFINITION: morning.
ORIGIN: From orthros; relating to the dawn, i.e. Matutinal (as an epithet of Venus, especially brilliant in the early day).

DEFINITION: early in the morning.
ORIGIN: From orthros; in the dawn, i.e. Up at day-break.

DEFINITION: early dawn, day-break.
ORIGIN: From the same as oros; dawn (as sun-rise, rising of light); by extension, morn.

DEFINITION: rightly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from orthos; in a straight manner, i.e. (figuratively) correctly (also morally).

DEFINITION: to separate, mark off by boundaries; to determine, appoint, designate.
ORIGIN: From horion; to mark out or bound ("horizon"), i.e. (figuratively) to appoint, decree, specify.

DEFINITION: the boundaries of a place, hence: districts, territory.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of an apparently primary horos (a bound or limit); a boundary-line, i.e. (by implication) a frontier (region).

DEFINITION: to adjure by, charge solemnly by.
ORIGIN: From horkos; to put on oath, i.e. Make swear; by analogy, to solemnly enjoin.

DEFINITION: an oath.
ORIGIN: From herkos (a fence; perhaps akin to horion); a limit, i.e. (sacred) restraint (specially, an oath).

DEFINITION: the taking of an oath, an oath.
ORIGIN: From a compound of horkos and a derivative of omnuo; asseveration on oath.

DEFINITION: to set in motion, to hasten on.
ORIGIN: From horme; to start, spur or urge on, i.e. (reflexively) to dash or plunge.

DEFINITION: a rapid motion forwards, onrush, assault.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a violent impulse, i.e. Onset.

DEFINITION: a rushing on, impulse, violence.
ORIGIN: From horme; an attack, i.e. (abstractly) precipitancy.

DEFINITION: a bird, fowl.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of ornis; a birdling.

DEFINITION: a bird, a rooster or hen.
ORIGIN: Probably from a prolonged form of the base of oros; a bird (as rising in the air), i.e. (specially), a hen (or female domestic fowl).

DEFINITION: a setting of boundaries, definite limit; plur: bounds.
ORIGIN: From a compound of the base of horion and a derivative of tithemi; a limit-placing, i.e. (concretely) boundary-line.

DEFINITION: a mountain, hill.
ORIGIN: Probably from an obsolete oro (to rise or "rear"; perhaps akin to airo; compare ornis); a mountain (as lifting itself above the plain): -hill, mount(-ain)..
USAGE: a mountain (as lifting itself above the plain); hill, mount(-ain).

DEFINITION: to dig, dig out, excavate.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to "burrow" in the ground, i.e. Dig.

DEFINITION: bereaved, an orphan, fatherless, desolate.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; bereaved ("orphan"), i.e. Parentless.

DEFINITION: to dance.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from orchos (a row or ring); to dance (from the ranklike or regular motion).

DEFINITION: usually rel. who, which, that, also demonstrative this, that.
ORIGIN: Including feminine he (hay), and neuter ho (ho) probably a primary word (or perhaps a form of the article ho); the relatively (sometimes demonstrative) pronoun, who, which, what, that.
USAGE: one, (an-, the) other, some, that, what, which, who(-m, -se), etc. See also hou.

DEFINITION: as often as, as many times as.
ORIGIN: Multiple adverb from hos; how (i.e. With an, so) many times as.

DEFINITION: holy, pious, godly, beloved of God.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; properly, right (by intrinsic or divine character; thus distinguished from dikaios, which refers rather to human statutes and relations; from hieros, which denotes formal consecration; and from hagios, which relates to purity from defilement), i.e. Hallowed (pious, sacred, sure).

DEFINITION: holiness, godliness, piety.
ORIGIN: From hosios; piety.

DEFINITION: religiously, piously.
ORIGIN: Adverb from hosios; piously.

DEFINITION: a smell, odor, savor.
ORIGIN: From ozo; fragrance (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: how much, how great, how many, as great as, as much.
ORIGIN: By reduplication from hos; as (much, great, long, etc.) As.
USAGE: all (that), as (long, many, much) (as), how great (many, much), (in-)asmuch as, so many as, that (ever), the more, those things, what (great, -soever), wheresoever, wherewithsoever, which, X while, who(-soever).

DEFINITION: the very one who.
ORIGIN: From hos and per; who especially.

DEFINITION: a bone.
ORIGIN: Or contracted ostoun (os-toon') of uncertain affinity; a bone.

DEFINITION: whosoever, whichsoever, whatsoever.
ORIGIN: Including the feminine hetis (hay'-tis), and the neuter ho,ti (hot'-ee) from hos and tis; which some, i.e. Any that; also (definite) which same.
USAGE: X and (they), (such) as, (they) that, in that they, what(-soever), whereas ye, (they) which, who(-soever). Compare hoti.

DEFINITION: made of clay, earthen.
ORIGIN: From ostrakon ("oyster") (a tile, i.e. Terra cotta); earthen-ware, i.e. Clayey; by implication, frail.

DEFINITION: the sense of smell, smelling.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of ozo; smell (the sense).

DEFINITION: the loins.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; the loin (externally), i.e. The hip; internally (by extension) procreative power.

DEFINITION: when, whenever.
ORIGIN: From hote and an; whenever (implying hypothesis or more or less uncertainty); also causatively (conjunctionally) inasmuch as.
USAGE: as long (soon) as, that, + till, when(-soever), while.

DEFINITION: when, at which time.
ORIGIN: From hos and te; at which (thing) too, i.e. When.
USAGE: after (that), as soon as, that, when, while.

DEFINITION: that, since, because; may introduce direct discourse.
ORIGIN: Neuter of hostis as conjunction; demonstrative, that (sometimes redundant); causative, because.
USAGE: as concerning that, as though, because (that), for (that), how (that), (in) that, though, why.

DEFINITION: while.
ORIGIN: For the genitive case of hostis (as adverb); during which same time, i.e. Whilst.

DEFINITION: not, no.
ORIGIN: Also (before a vowel) ouk (ook), and (before an aspirate) ouch (ookh) a primary word; the absolute negative (compare me) adverb; no or not.
USAGE: + long, nay, neither, never, no (X man), none, (can-)not, + nothing, + special, un(-worthy), when, + without, + yet but. See also ou me, mekos.

DEFINITION: where, whither, when, in what place.
ORIGIN: Genitive case of hos as adverb; at which place, i.e. Where.

DEFINITION: ah! ha! (an expression of wonder or surprise).
ORIGIN: A primary exclamation of surprise; "ah".

DEFINITION: alas! woe! (an expression of grief or denunciation).
ORIGIN: A primary exclamation of grief; "woe".

DEFINITION: by no means, not at all.
ORIGIN: Adverb from (the feminine) of oudeis; by no means.

DEFINITION: neither, nor, not even, and not.
ORIGIN: From ou and de; not however, i.e. Neither, nor, not even.
USAGE: neither (indeed), never, no (more, nor, not), nor (yet), (also, even, then) not (even, so much as), + nothing, so much as.

DEFINITION: no one, none, nothing.
ORIGIN: Including feminine oudemia (oo-dem-ee'-ah), and neuter ouden (oo-den') from oude and heis; not even one (man, woman or thing), i.e. None, nobody, nothing.
USAGE: any (man), aught, man, neither any (thing), never (man), no (man), none (+ of these things), not (any, at all, -thing), nought.

DEFINITION: never.
ORIGIN: From oude and pote; not even at any time, i.e. Never at all.
USAGE: neither at any time, never, nothing at any time.

DEFINITION: not yet, never before.
ORIGIN: From oude and po; not even yet.
USAGE: as yet not, never before (yet), (not) yet.

DEFINITION: no longer, no more.
ORIGIN: Also (separately) ouk eti (ook et'-ee) from ou and eti; not yet, no longer.
USAGE: after that (not), (not) any more, henceforth (hereafter) not, no longer (more), not as yet (now), now no more (not), yet (not).

DEFINITION: therefore, so then.
ORIGIN: From ou and oun; is it not therefore that, i.e. (affirmatively) hence or so.

DEFINITION: therefore, then, (and) so.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; (adverbially) certainly, or (conjunctionally) accordingly.
USAGE: and (so, truly), but, now (then), so (likewise then), then, therefore, verily, wherefore.

DEFINITION: not yet.
ORIGIN: From ou and po; not yet.
USAGE: hitherto not, (no...) As yet, not yet.

DEFINITION: a tail.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a tail.

DEFINITION: in heaven, belonging to heaven, heavenly, from heaven.
ORIGIN: From ouranos; celestial, i.e. Belonging to or coming from the sky.

DEFINITION: from heaven, from the sky.
ORIGIN: From ouranos and the enclitic of source; from the sky.

DEFINITION: heaven, (a) the visible heavens: the atmosphere, the sky, the starry heavens, (b) the spiritual heavens.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from the same as oros (through the idea of elevation); the sky; by extension, heaven (as the abode of God); by implication, happiness, power, eternity; specially, the Gospel (Christianity).

DEFINITION: Urbanus, a Christian in Rome, fellow-worker of Paul.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; Urbanus (of the city, "urbane"), a Christian.

DEFINITION: Uriah, husband of Bathsheba the mother of Solomon.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin ('Uwriyah); Urias (i.e. Urijah), a Hittite.

DEFINITION: (a) the ear, (b) met: the faculty of perception.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; the ear (physically or mentally).

DEFINITION: property, wealth, substance.
ORIGIN: From the feminine of on; substance, i.e. Property (possessions).

DEFINITION: and not, neither, nor.
ORIGIN: From ou and te; not too, i.e. Neither or nor; by analogy, not even.
USAGE: neither, none, nor (yet), (no, yet) not, nothing.

DEFINITION: this; he, she, it.
ORIGIN: Including nominative masculine plural houtoi (hoo'-toy), nominative feminine singular haute (how'-tay), and nominative feminine plural hautai (how'-tahee) from the article ho and autos; the he (she or it), i.e. This or that (often with article repeated).
USAGE: he (it was that), hereof, it, she, such as, the same, these, they, this (man, same, woman), which, who.

DEFINITION: thus, so, in this manner.
