ORIGIN: Or (before a vowel houtos hoo'-toce adverb from houtos; in this way (referring to what precedes or follows).
USAGE: after that, after (in) this manner, as, even (so), for all that, like(-wise), no more, on this fashion(-wise), so (in like manner), thus, what.

DEFINITION: by no means, not at all.
ORIGIN: Intensive of ou; not indeed.

DEFINITION: (a) a debtor, one who owes, one who is indebted, (b) one who has sinned against another (an Aramaism), a sinner.
ORIGIN: From opheilo; an ower, i.e. Person indebted; figuratively, a delinquent; morally, a transgressor (against God).

DEFINITION: a debt, a duty, what is due.
ORIGIN: From opheilo; indebtedness, i.e. (concretely) a sum owed; figuratively, obligation, i.e. (conjugal) duty.

DEFINITION: that which is owed, a debt.
ORIGIN: From (the alternate of) opheilo; something owed, i.e. (figuratively) a due; morally, a fault.

DEFINITION: to owe, ought.
ORIGIN: Or (in certain tenses), its prolonged form opheileo (of-i-leh'-o) probably from the base of ophelos (through the idea of accruing); to owe (pecuniarily); figuratively, to be under obligation (ought, must, should); morally, to fail in duty.
USAGE: behove, be bound, (be) debt(-or), (be) due(-ty), be guilty (indebted), (must) need(-s), ought, owe, should. See also ophelon.

DEFINITION: O that! I wish! Would that!, followed by indicative.
ORIGIN: First person singular of a past tense of opheilo; I ought (wish), i.e. (interjection) oh that!.

DEFINITION: advantage, gain, profit, help.
ORIGIN: From ophello (to heap up, i.e. Accumulate or benefit); gain.

DEFINITION: eye-service; service rendered only while the master watches.
ORIGIN: From ophthalmos and douleia; sight-labor, i.e. That needs watching (remissness).

DEFINITION: the eye; fig: the mind's eye.
ORIGIN: From optanomai; the eye (literally or figuratively); by implication, vision; figuratively, envy (from the jealous side-glance).

DEFINITION: a serpent, snake; used of the devil or Satan.
ORIGIN: Probably from optanomai (through the idea of sharpness of vision); a snake, figuratively, (as a type of sly cunning) an artful malicious person, especially Satan.

DEFINITION: the brow, a ridge (of a mountain).
ORIGIN: Perhaps from optanomai (through the idea of the shading or proximity to the organ of vision); the eye-"brow" or forehead, i.e. (figuratively) the brink of a precipice.

DEFINITION: to trouble, torment, worry, vex.
ORIGIN: From ochlos; to mob, i.e. (by implication) to harass.

DEFINITION: to gather a crowd, make a riot.
ORIGIN: From ochlos and poieo; to make a crowd, i.e. Raise a public disturbance.

DEFINITION: a crowd, multitude, the common people.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of echo (meaning a vehicle); a throng (as borne along); by implication, the rabble; by extension, a class of people; figuratively, a riot.
USAGE: company, multitude, number (of people), people, press.

DEFINITION: a fortress, strong defense, stronghold.
ORIGIN: From a remote derivative of echo (meaning to fortify, through the idea of holding safely); a castle (figuratively, argument).

DEFINITION: a little fish.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of the base of optos; a relish to other food (as if cooked sauce), i.e. (specially), fish (presumably salted and dried as a condiment).

DEFINITION: late, in the evening.
ORIGIN: From the same as opiso (through the idea of backwardness); (adverbially) late in the day; by extension, after the close of the day.

DEFINITION: the latter rain.
ORIGIN: From opse; later, i.e. Vernal (showering).

DEFINITION: late, evening.
ORIGIN: From opse; late; feminine (as noun) afternoon (early eve) or nightfall (later eve).

DEFINITION: (a) the face, countenance, (b) the features, outward appearance.
ORIGIN: From optanomai; properly, sight (the act), i.e. (by implication) the visage, an external show.

DEFINITION: pay, wages, salary, reward.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of the same as opsarion; rations for a soldier, i.e. (by extension) his stipend or pay.

TRANSLITERATED_LEXICAL_FORM: ho ón kai ho én kai ho erchomenos
DEFINITION: to come.
ORIGIN: Ho erchomenos (ho own kahee) ho ane kahee (ho er-khom'-en-os) a phrase combining ho with the present participle and imperfect of eimi and the present participle of erchomai by means of kai; the one being and the one that was and the one coming, i.e. The Eternal, as a divine epithet of Christ.
USAGE: which art (is, was), and (which) wast (is, was), and art (is) to come (shalt be).

DEFINITION: to ensnare, entrap, entangle.
ORIGIN: From pagis; to ensnare (figuratively).

DEFINITION: a snare, trap (especially for catching birds) hence, met: stratagem, device, wile.
ORIGIN: From pegnumi; a trap (as fastened by a noose or notch); figuratively, a trick or statagem (temptation).

DEFINITION: (a) suffering, affliction, (b) passion, emotion, (c) an undergoing, an enduring.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of pathos; something undergone, i.e. Hardship or pain; subjectively, an emotion or influence.

DEFINITION: one who has suffered or is subject to suffering.
ORIGIN: From the same as pathema; liable (i.e. Doomed) to experience pain.

DEFINITION: that which befalls one, a passion, a suffering.
ORIGIN: From the alternate of pascho; properly, suffering ("pathos"), i.e. (subjectively) a passion (especially concupiscence).

DEFINITION: a boy's guardian or tutor, a slave who had charge of the life and morals of the boys of a family, not strictly a teacher.
ORIGIN: From pais and a reduplicated form of ago; a boy-leader, i.e. A servant whose office it was to take the children to school; (by implication, (figuratively) a tutor ("paedagogue")).

DEFINITION: a little boy, lad.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of pais; a little boy.

DEFINITION: discipline; training and education of children, hence: instruction; chastisement, correction.
ORIGIN: From paideuo; tutorage, i.e. Education or training; by implication, disciplinary correction.

DEFINITION: an instructor, trainer; almost: a chastiser.
ORIGIN: From paideuo; a trainer, i.e. Teacher or (by implication) discipliner.

DEFINITION: (a) to discipline, educate, train, (b) more severely: to chastise.
ORIGIN: From pais; to train up a child, i.e. Educate, or (by implication), discipline (by punishment).

DEFINITION: from childhood, from early boyhood.
ORIGIN: Adverb (of source) from paidion; from infancy.

DEFINITION: a little child, an infant, little one.
ORIGIN: Neuter diminutive of pais; a childling (of either sex), i.e. (properly), an infant, or (by extension) a half-grown boy or girl; figuratively, an immature Christian.

DEFINITION: a female slave, maidservant, maid, young girl.
ORIGIN: Feminine diminutive of pais; a girl, i.e. (specially), a female slave or servant.

DEFINITION: to play, sport (includes singing and dancing), play in the manner of children.
ORIGIN: From pais; to sport (as a boy).

DEFINITION: (a) a male child, boy, (b) a male slave, servant; thus: a servant of God, especially as a title of the Messiah, (c) a female child, girl.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from paio; a boy (as often beaten with impunity), or (by analogy), a girl, and (genitive case) a child; specially, a slave or servant (especially a minister to a king; and by eminence to God).
USAGE: child, maid(-en), (man) servant, son, young man.

DEFINITION: to strike, smite, sting.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to hit (as if by a single blow and less violently than tupto); specially, to sting (as a scorpion).

DEFINITION: Pacatiana.
ORIGIN: Feminine of an adjective of uncertain derivation; Pacatianian, a section of Phrygia.

DEFINITION: of old, long ago, in times past, former.
ORIGIN: Probably another form for palin (through the idea of retrocession); (adverbially) formerly, or (by relatively) sometime since; (elliptically as adjective) ancient.
USAGE: any while, a great while ago, (of) old, in time past.

DEFINITION: old, ancient, not new or recent.
ORIGIN: From palai; antique, i.e. Not recent, worn out.

DEFINITION: oldness, obsoleteness.
ORIGIN: From palaios; antiquatedness.

DEFINITION: to make old, declare obsolete; pass: to grow old, become obsolete.
ORIGIN: From palaios; to make (passively, become) worn out, or declare obsolete.

DEFINITION: wrestling, a wrestling bout; hence: a struggle, fight, conflict, contest.
ORIGIN: From pallo (to vibrate; another form for ballo); wrestling.

DEFINITION: a new birth, regeneration, renewal.
ORIGIN: From palin and genesis; (spiritual) rebirth (the state or the act), i.e. (figuratively) spiritual renovation; specially, Messianic restoration.

DEFINITION: again, back, once more, further, on the other hand.
ORIGIN: Probably from the same as pale (through the idea of oscillatory repetition); (adverbially) anew, i.e. (of place) back, (of time) once more, or (conjunctionally) furthermore or on the other hand.

DEFINITION: all at once, all together.
ORIGIN: Dative case (adverb) of a compound of pas and plethos; in full multitude, i.e. Concertedly or simultaneously.

DEFINITION: very great, very much.
ORIGIN: From pas and polus; full many, i.e. Immense.

DEFINITION: Pamphylia, a Roman province on the south coast of Asia Minor.
ORIGIN: From a compound of pas and pura; every-tribal, i.e. Heterogeneous (chora being implied); Pamphylia, a region of Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: an inn, khan, hotel.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed compound of pas and a derivative of dechomai; all-receptive, i.e. A public lodging-place (caravanserai or khan).

DEFINITION: an innkeeper, landlord, host.
ORIGIN: From the same as pandocheion; an innkeeper (warden of a caravanserai).

DEFINITION: a festival assembly.
ORIGIN: From pas and a derivative of agora; a mass-meeting, i.e. (figuratively) universal companionship.

DEFINITION: with one's whole household or family.
ORIGIN: Adverb from pas and oikos; with the whole family.

DEFINITION: complete armor, panoply.
ORIGIN: From a compound of pas and hoplon; full armor ("panoply").

DEFINITION: shrewdness, skill; hence: cunning, craftiness.
ORIGIN: From panougos; adroitness, i.e. (in a bad sense) trickery or sophistry.

DEFINITION: ready to do anything, crafty, skillful.
ORIGIN: From pas and ergon; all-working, i.e. Adroit (shrewd).

DEFINITION: from all sides, from all parts.
ORIGIN: Adverb (of source) from pantachou; from all directions.

DEFINITION: everywhere, in all places.
ORIGIN: Genitive case (as adverb of place) of a presumed derivative of pas; universally.

DEFINITION: complete, entire, perfect, through all time.
ORIGIN: From pas and telos; full-ended, i.e. Entire (neuter as noun, completion).

DEFINITION: in every way, entirely, everywhere.
ORIGIN: Adverb (of manner) from pas; wholly.

DEFINITION: from all sides, on all sides.
ORIGIN: Adverb (of source) from pas; from (i.e. On) all sides.

DEFINITION: ruler of all, ruler of the universe, the almighty.
ORIGIN: From pas and kratos; the all-ruling, i.e. God (as absolute and universal sovereign).

DEFINITION: always, at all times, ever.
ORIGIN: From pas and hote; every when, i.e. At all times.

DEFINITION: wholly, entirely, in every way, by all means, certainly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from pas; entirely; specially, at all events, (with negative, following) in no event.
USAGE: by all means, altogether, at all, needs, no doubt, in (no) wise, surely.

DEFINITION: gen: from; dat: beside, in the presence of; acc: alongside of.
ORIGIN: A primary preposition; properly, near; i.e. (with genitive case) from beside (literally or figuratively), (with dative case) at (or in) the vicinity of (objectively or subjectively), (with accusative case) to the proximity with (local (especially beyond or opposed to) or causal (on account of).
USAGE: above, against, among, at, before, by, contrary to, X friend, from, + give (such things as they), + that (she) had, X his, in, more than, nigh unto, (out) of, past, save, side...by, in the sight of, than, (there-)fore, with. In compounds it retains the same variety of application.

DEFINITION: to transgress, violate, depart, desert.
ORIGIN: From para and the base of basis; to go contrary to, i.e. Violate a command.

DEFINITION: to compare, arrive, land.
ORIGIN: From para and ballo; to throw alongside, i.e. (reflexively) to reach a place, or (figuratively) to liken.

DEFINITION: a transgression, overstepping, deviation.
ORIGIN: From parabaino; violation.

DEFINITION: a transgressor, law-breaker.
ORIGIN: From parabaino; a violator.

DEFINITION: to urge, press, constrain by entreaties.
ORIGIN: From para and the middle voice of biazo; to force contrary to (nature), i.e. Compel (by entreaty).

DEFINITION: (a) a comparison, (b) a parable, often of those uttered by our Lord, (c) a proverb, an adage.
ORIGIN: From paraballo; a similitude ("parable"), i.e. (symbolic) fictitious narrative (of common life conveying a moral), apothegm or adage.

DEFINITION: to expose myself to danger; to be adventuresome, reckless.
ORIGIN: From para and the middle voice of bouleuo; to misconsult, i.e. Disregard.

DEFINITION: a command, charge, injunction; a precept, rule of living.
ORIGIN: From paraggello; a mandate.

DEFINITION: to notify, command, charge, entreat solemnly.
ORIGIN: From para and the base of aggelos; to transmit a message, i.e. (by implication) to enjoin.

DEFINITION: (a) to come on the scene, appear, come, (b) with words expressing destination: to present myself at, arrive at, reach.
ORIGIN: From para and ginomai; to become near, i.e. Approach (have arrived); by implication, to appear publicly.

DEFINITION: to lead by, to pass by or away.
ORIGIN: From para and ago; to lead near, i.e. (reflexively or intransitively) to go along or away.

DEFINITION: to put to open shame, make a public example of, put to disgrace.
ORIGIN: From para and deigmatizo; to show alongside (the public), i.e. Expose to infamy.
USAGE: make a public example, put to an open shame.

DEFINITION: a park, a garden, a paradise.
ORIGIN: Of Oriental origin (compare pardec); a park, i.e. (specially), an Eden (place of future happiness, "paradise").

DEFINITION: to receive, accept, acknowledge.
ORIGIN: From para and dechomai; to accept near, i.e. Admit or (by implication) delight in.

DEFINITION: wrangling, constant arguing.
ORIGIN: From a compound of para and diatribo; misemployment, i.e. Meddlesomeness.

DEFINITION: to hand over, pledge, hand down, deliver, commit, commend, betray, abandon.
ORIGIN: From para and didomi; to surrender, i.e yield up, intrust, transmit.
USAGE: betray, bring forth, cast, commit, deliver (up), give (over, up), hazard, put in prison, recommend.

DEFINITION: unexpected, strange, wonderful, astonishing.
ORIGIN: From para and doxa (in the sense of seeming); contrary to expectation, i.e. Extraordinary ("paradox").

DEFINITION: a handing down or over, a tradition.
ORIGIN: From paradidomi; transmission, i.e. (concretely) a precept; specially, the Jewish traditionary law.

DEFINITION: to make jealous, provoke to jealously, provoke to anger.
ORIGIN: From para and zeloo; to stimulate alongside, i.e. Excite to rivalry.

DEFINITION: by the sea.
ORIGIN: From para and thalassa; along the sea, i.e. Maritime (lacustrine).

DEFINITION: to look past, overlook, neglect.
ORIGIN: From para and theoreo; to overlook or disregard.

DEFINITION: a deposit, anything committed to one's charge or trust.
ORIGIN: From paratithemi; a deposit, i.e. (figuratively) trust.

DEFINITION: to admonish, advise, exhort.
ORIGIN: From para and aineo; to mispraise, i.e. Recommend or advise (a different course).

DEFINITION: to beg off, make excuse, deprecate, refuse, reject, decline, shun, avoid.
ORIGIN: From para and the middle voice of aiteo; to beg off, i.e. Deprecate, decline, shun.

DEFINITION: to sit down beside, set beside.
ORIGIN: From para and kathizo; to sit down near.

DEFINITION: (a) to send for, summon, invite, (b) to beseech, entreat, beg, (c) to exhort, admonish, (d) to comfort, encourage, console.
ORIGIN: From para and kaleo; to call near, i.e. Invite, invoke (by imploration, hortation or consolation).
USAGE: beseech, call for, (be of good) comfort, desire, (give) exhort(-ation), intreat, pray.

DEFINITION: to cover (by hanging something beside), to hide.
ORIGIN: From para and kalupto; to cover alongside, i.e. Veil (figuratively).

DEFINITION: a trust or deposit.
ORIGIN: From a compound of para and katatithemi; something put down alongside, i.e. A deposit (sacred trust).

DEFINITION: to be at hand, be present with, rest with.
ORIGIN: From para and keimai; to lie near, i.e. Be at hand (figuratively, be prompt or easy).

DEFINITION: a calling for, summons, hence: (a) exhortation, (b) entreaty, (c) encouragement, joy, gladness, (d) consolation, comfort.
ORIGIN: From parakaleo; imploration, hortation, solace.

DEFINITION: (a) an advocate, intercessor, (b) a consoler, comforter, helper, (c) Paraclete.
ORIGIN: An intercessor, consoler.

DEFINITION: a hearing amiss, by implication disobedience.
ORIGIN: From parakouo; inattention, i.e. (by implication) disobedience.

DEFINITION: to accompany, follow closely, characterize, both lit. and met.; to investigate.
ORIGIN: From para and akoloutheo; to follow near, i.e. (figuratively) attend (as a result), trace out, conform to.
USAGE: attain, follow, fully know, have understanding.

DEFINITION: (a) to hear carelessly or incidentally, or to pretend not to hear, (b) to refuse to hear; to disobey, disregard.
ORIGIN: From para and akouo; to mishear, i.e. (by implication) to disobey.

DEFINITION: to stoop, peer in, look down, look intently.
ORIGIN: From para and kupto; to bend beside, i.e. Lean over (so as to peer within).

DEFINITION: to take from, receive from, or: to take to, receive (apparently not used of money), admit, acknowledge; to take with me.
ORIGIN: From para and lambano; to receive near, i.e. Associate with oneself (in any familiar or intimate act or relation); by analogy, to assume an office; figuratively, to learn.

DEFINITION: to sail past or coast along.
ORIGIN: From para and the middle voice of lego (in its original sense); (specially), to lay one's course near, i.e. Sail past.

DEFINITION: adjacent to the sea, on the coast.
ORIGIN: From para and hals; beside the salt (sea), i.e. Maritime.

DEFINITION: a change, variation, mutation.
ORIGIN: From a compound of para and allasso.
USAGE: transmutation (of phase or orbit), i.e. (figuratively) fickleness; variableness.

DEFINITION: to deceive, beguile, reason falsely, mislead.
ORIGIN: From para and logizomai; to misreckon, i.e. Delude.

DEFINITION: afflicted with paralysis.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of paraluo; as if dissolved, i.e. "paralytic".

DEFINITION: to relax, enfeeble, weaken.
ORIGIN: From para and luo; to loosen beside, i.e. Relax (perfect passive participle, paralyzed or enfeebled).
USAGE: feeble, sick of the (taken with) palsy.

DEFINITION: to remain by, abide with; met: to persevere in.
ORIGIN: From para and meno; to stay near, i.e. Remain (literally, tarry; or figuratively, be permanent, persevere).

DEFINITION: to encourage, comfort, console, exhort.
ORIGIN: From para and the middle voice of a derivative of muthos; to relate near, i.e. (by implication) encourage, console.

DEFINITION: encouragement, comfort, consolation, exhortation.
ORIGIN: From paramutheomai; consolation (properly, abstract).

DEFINITION: comfort, consolation, an exhortation, persuasion, encouragement.
ORIGIN: Neuter of paramuthia; consolation (properly, concretely).

DEFINITION: to act contrary to law.
ORIGIN: From a compound of para and nomos; to be opposed to law, i.e. To transgress.

DEFINITION: a transgression, violation of law.
ORIGIN: From the same as paranomeo.

DEFINITION: to embitter, provoke, irritate.
ORIGIN: From para and pikraino; to embitter alongside, i.e. (figuratively) to exasperate.

DEFINITION: a provocation, irritation, rebellion.
ORIGIN: From parapikraino; irritation.

DEFINITION: to fall away, fall back (into the unbelieving and godless ways of the old time).
ORIGIN: From para and pipto; to fall aside, i.e. (figuratively) to apostatize.

DEFINITION: to sail past (without stopping there).
ORIGIN: From para and pleo; to sail near.

DEFINITION: coming near, nearly resembling.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a compound of para and the base of plesion (as adverb); close by, i.e. (figuratively) almost.

DEFINITION: similarly, in like manner, likewise.
ORIGIN: Adverb from the same as paraplesion; in a manner near by, i.e. (figuratively) similarly.

DEFINITION: to go past, pass by, pass along by.
ORIGIN: From para and poreuomai; to travel near.

DEFINITION: a falling away, lapse, slip, false step, trespass, sin.
ORIGIN: From parapipto; a side-slip (lapse or deviation), i.e. (unintentional) error or (wilful) transgression.

DEFINITION: (lit: to flow past, glide past, hence) to be lost, perish, or merely: to drift away (fall away) from duty.
ORIGIN: From para and the alternate of rheo; to flow by, i.e. (figuratively) carelessly pass (miss).

DEFINITION: marked amiss, marked at the side, marked with a sign.
ORIGIN: From para and the base of semaino; side-marked, i.e. Labelled (with a badge (figure-head) of a ship).

DEFINITION: to prepare; mid: to prepare, make preparations.
ORIGIN: From para and a derivative of skeuos; to furnish aside, i.e. Get ready.

DEFINITION: preparation, the day of preparation (for a Sabbath or feast).
ORIGIN: As if from paraskeuazo; readiness.

DEFINITION: to extend, prolong, continue.
ORIGIN: From para and teino (to stretch); to extend along, i.e. Prolong (in point of time).

DEFINITION: to watch closely, to observe scrupulously.
ORIGIN: From para and tereo; to inspect alongside, i.e. Note insidiously or scrupulously.

DEFINITION: observation, careful watching.
ORIGIN: From paratereo; inspection, i.e. Ocular evidence.

DEFINITION: (a) to set (especially a meal) before, serve, (b) act. and mid: to deposit with, entrust to, (c) to bring forward, quote as evidence.
ORIGIN: From para and tithemi; to place alongside, i.e. Present (food, truth); by implication, to deposit (as a trust or for protection).
USAGE: allege, commend, commit (the keeping of), put forth, set before.

DEFINITION: to come by chance, chance to meet.
ORIGIN: From para and tugchano; to chance near, i.e. Fall in with.

DEFINITION: adv. with force of adj: present, immediate, for the moment.
ORIGIN: From para and a derivative of autos; at the very instant, i.e. Momentary.

DEFINITION: to turn aside, carry away, remove, cause to pass away; pass: to be misled, seduced.
ORIGIN: From para and phero (including its alternate forms); to bear along or aside, i.e. Carry off (literally or figuratively); by implication, to avert.

DEFINITION: to be out of senses, be beside myself.
ORIGIN: From para and phroneo; to misthink, i.e. Be insane (silly).

DEFINITION: madness, folly.
ORIGIN: From paraphroneo; insanity, i.e. Foolhardiness.

DEFINITION: to pass the winter.
ORIGIN: From para and cheimazo; to winter near, i.e. Stay with over the rainy season.

DEFINITION: wintering, spending the winter.
ORIGIN: From paracheimazo; a wintering over.

DEFINITION: instantly, immediately, on the spot.
ORIGIN: From para and chrema (in its original sense); at the thing itself, i.e. Instantly.

DEFINITION: a panther, leopard.
ORIGIN: Feminine of pardos (a panther); a leopard.

DEFINITION: to be present, be near; to have come, arrived.
ORIGIN: From para and eimi (including its various forms); to be near, i.e. At hand; neuter present participle (singular) time being, or (plural) property.
USAGE: come, X have, be here, + lack, (be here) present.

DEFINITION: to introduce, to bring in secretly.
ORIGIN: From para and eisago; to lead in aside, i.e. Introduce surreptitiously.

DEFINITION: brought in secretly, surreptitious.
ORIGIN: From pareisago.

DEFINITION: to enter secretly, come in by stealth.
ORIGIN: From para and a compound of eis and duno; to settle in alongside, i.e. Lodge stealthily.

DEFINITION: to enter secretly, come in from the side.
ORIGIN: From para and eiserchomai; to come in alongside, i.e. Supervene additionally or steathily.

DEFINITION: to contribute besides, bring in besides, smuggle in.
ORIGIN: From para and eisphero; to bear in alongside, i.e. Introduce simultaneously.

DEFINITION: (a) adv. used as adj: besides, outside, without, left over, in addition, (b) prep: apart from, except.
ORIGIN: From para and ektos; near outside, i.e. Besides.

DEFINITION: a camp, fort, castle, barracks, army in battle array.
ORIGIN: From a compound of para and emballo; a throwing in beside (juxtaposition), i.e. (specially), battle-array, encampment or barracks (tower Antonia).

DEFINITION: to trouble, cause disturbance to, annoy, harass.
ORIGIN: From para and enochleo; to harass further, i.e. Annoy.

DEFINITION: residing in a strange country; subst: a stranger, sojourner.
ORIGIN: From para and the base of epidemeo; an alien alongside, i.e. A resident foreigner.

DEFINITION: to pass by, pass away, pass out of sight; to be rendered void, become vain, neglect, disregard.
ORIGIN: From para and erchomai; to come near or aside, i.e. To approach (arrive), go by (or away), (figuratively) perish or neglect, (causative) avert.
USAGE: come (forth), go, pass (away, by, over), past, transgress.

DEFINITION: overlooking, suspension, remission of punishment for.
ORIGIN: From ktetor; praetermission, i.e. Toleration.

DEFINITION: act. and mid: to offer, provide, confer, afford, give, bring, show, cause.
ORIGIN: From para and echo; to hold near, i.e. Present, afford, exhibit, furnish occasion.
USAGE: bring, do, give, keep, minister, offer, shew, + trouble.

DEFINITION: solace, consolation, comfort.
ORIGIN: From a compound of para and a derivative of agora (meaning to harangue an assembly); an address alongside, i.e. (specially), consolation.

DEFINITION: virginity.
ORIGIN: From parthenos; maidenhood.

DEFINITION: a maiden, virgin; extended to men who have not known women.
ORIGIN: Of unknown origin; a maiden; by implication, an unmarried daughter.

DEFINITION: a Parthian, an inhabitant of the country beyond the eastern boundary of the Roman Empire between the Caspian Sea and the Persian Gulf.
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin; a Parthian, i.e. Inhabitant of Parthia.

DEFINITION: (a) to let pass, neglect, omit, disregard, (b) to slacken, loosen; pass: to be wearied.
ORIGIN: From para and hiemi (to send); to let by, i.e. Relax.

DEFINITION: to bring, present, prove, come up to and stand by, be present.
ORIGIN: Or prolonged paristano (par-is-tan'-o) from para and histemi; to stand beside, i.e. (transitively) to exhibit, proffer, (specially), recommend, (figuratively) substantiate; or (intransitively) to be at hand (or ready), aid.
USAGE: assist, bring before, command, commend, give presently, present, prove, provide, shew, stand (before, by, here, up, with), yield.

DEFINITION: Parmenas, one of the original seven deacons at Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: Probably by contraction for Parmenides (a derivative of a compound of para and meno); constant; Parmenas, a Christian.

DEFINITION: a passing by or through.
ORIGIN: From para and hodos; a by-road, i.e. (actively) a route.

DEFINITION: to dwell near, reside as a foreigner.
ORIGIN: From para and oikeo; to dwell near, i.e. Reside as a foreigner.

DEFINITION: a sojourning, a dwelling in a strange land.
ORIGIN: From paroikos; foreign residence.

DEFINITION: foreign, alien, subst: a foreigner, sojourner.
ORIGIN: From para and oikos; having a home near, i.e. (as noun) a by-dweller (alien resident).

DEFINITION: a cryptic saying, an allegory; a proverb, figurative discourse.
ORIGIN: From a compound of para and perhaps a derivative of oiomai; apparently a state alongside of supposition, i.e. (concretely) an adage; specially, an enigmatical or fictitious illustration.

DEFINITION: given to wine, drunken, quarrelsome.
ORIGIN: From para and oinos; staying near wine, i.e. Tippling (a toper).

DEFINITION: to have passed by.
ORIGIN: From para and oichomai (to depart); to escape along, i.e. Be gone.

DEFINITION: to resemble, be like.
ORIGIN: From paromoios; to resemble.

DEFINITION: like, similar.
ORIGIN: From para and homoios; alike nearly, i.e. Similar.

DEFINITION: to sharpen, to stimulate, to provoke.
ORIGIN: From para and a derivative of oxus; to sharpen alongside, i.e. (figuratively) to exasperate.

DEFINITION: stimulation, provocation, irritation, angry dispute.
ORIGIN: From paroxuno ("paroxysm"); incitement (to good), or dispute (in anger).

DEFINITION: to provoke to anger, exasperate.
ORIGIN: From para and orgizo; to anger alongside, i.e. Enrage.

DEFINITION: exasperation, wrath, irritation, indignation.
ORIGIN: From parorgizo; rage.

DEFINITION: to stir up, incite, urge on.
ORIGIN: From para and otruno (to spur); to urge along, i.e. Stimulate (to hostility).

DEFINITION: (a) presence, (b) a coming, an arrival, advent, especially of the second coming of Christ.
ORIGIN: From the present participle of pareimi; a being near, i.e. Advent (often, return; specially, of Christ to punish Jerusalem, or finally the wicked); (by implication) physically, aspect.

DEFINITION: prop: a dainty side-dish; meton: a plate, dish, platter.
ORIGIN: From para and the base of opsarion; a side-dish (the receptacle).

DEFINITION: freedom, openness, especially in speech; boldness, confidence.
ORIGIN: From pas and a derivative of rheo; all out-spokenness, i.e. Frankness, bluntness, publicity; by implication, assurance.
USAGE: bold (X -ly, -ness, -ness of speech), confidence, X freely, X openly, X plainly(-ness).

DEFINITION: to speak freely, boldly; to be confident.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from parrhesia; to be frank in utterance, or confident in spirit and demeanor.

DEFINITION: all, the whole, every kind of.
ORIGIN: Including all the forms of declension; apparently a primary word; all, any, every, the whole.
USAGE: all (manner of, means), alway(-s), any (one), X daily, + ever, every (one, way), as many as, + no(-thing), X thoroughly, whatsoever, whole, whosoever.

DEFINITION: the Passover, the Passover supper or lamb.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (compare pecach); the Passover (the meal, the day, the festival or the special sacrifices connected with it).

DEFINITION: to be acted upon in a certain way, either good or bad; to experience ill treatment, suffer.
ORIGIN: Including the forms patho (path'-o), and pentho (pen'-tho), used only in certain tenses for it apparently a primary verb; to experience a sensation or impression (usually painful).

DEFINITION: Patara, a town on the coast of the Roman province Lycia.
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin; Patara, a place in Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: to smite, strike (as with a sword), smite to death, afflict.
ORIGIN: Probably prolongation from paio; to knock (gently or with a weapon or fatally).

DEFINITION: to tread, trample upon.
ORIGIN: From a derivative probably of paio (meaning a "path"); to trample (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: father, (Heavenly) Father, ancestor, elder, senior.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a "father" (literally or figuratively, near or more remote).

DEFINITION: Patmos, a small rocky island in the Aegean sea, south-west of Ephesus.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; Patmus, an islet in the Mediterranean.

DEFINITION: a patricide, a murderer of his father.
ORIGIN: From pater and the same as the latter part of metraloias; a parricide.

DEFINITION: lineage, ancestry; a family, tribe.
ORIGIN: As if feminine of a derivative of pater; paternal descent, i.e. (concretely) a group of families or a whole race (nation).

DEFINITION: a patriarch, head or founder of a family.
ORIGIN: From patria and archo; a progenitor ("patriarch").

DEFINITION: ancestral, paternal, belonging to the fathers (ancestors).
ORIGIN: From pater; paternal, i.e. Ancestral.

DEFINITION: fatherland, one's native place.
ORIGIN: From parasemos; a father-land, i.e. Native town; (figuratively) heavenly home.

DEFINITION: "father's life", Patrobas, a Christian.
ORIGIN: Perhaps a contraction for Patrobios (a compound of pater and bios); father's life; Patrobas, a Christian.

DEFINITION: handed down by (from) one's ancestors, inherited.
ORIGIN: From pater and a derivative of paradidomi (in the sense of handing over or down); traditionary.

DEFINITION: of one's fathers, received from one's fathers.
ORIGIN: From pater; paternal, i.e. Hereditary.

DEFINITION: (Sergius) Paulus (a Roman proconsul), also Paul (an apostle).
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; (little; but remotely from a derivative of pauo, meaning the same); Paulus, the name of a Roman and of an apostle.

DEFINITION: (a) act: to cause to cease, restrain, hinder, (b) mid: to cease, stop, leave off.
ORIGIN: A primary verb ("pause"); to stop (transitively or intransitively), i.e. Restrain, quit, desist, come to an end.

DEFINITION: Paphos, a city at the western end of Cyprus.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; Paphus, a place in Cyprus.

DEFINITION: to fatten, thicken; pass. fig: to become stupid, dull, unfeeling.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of pegnumi (meaning thick); to thicken, i.e. (by implication) to fatten (figuratively, stupefy or render callous).

DEFINITION: a shackle, fetter for the feet.
ORIGIN: Ultimately from pous; a shackle for the feet.

DEFINITION: level, low-lying, flat.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of pous (meaning the ground); level (as easy for the feet).

DEFINITION: to travel on foot or by land.
ORIGIN: From the same as peze; to foot a journey, i.e. Travel by land.

DEFINITION: on foot, by land.
ORIGIN: Dative case feminine of a derivative of pous (as adverb); foot-wise, i.e. By walking.

DEFINITION: to obey one in authority, conform to advice, obey, follow.
ORIGIN: From a compound of peitho and archo; to be persuaded by a ruler, i.e. (genitive case) to submit to authority; by analogy, to conform to advice.

DEFINITION: persuasive, enticing, skilful.
ORIGIN: From peitho; persuasive.

DEFINITION: to persuade, to have confidence.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to convince (by argument, true or false); by analogy, to pacify or conciliate (by other fair means); reflexively or passively, to assent (to evidence or authority), to rely (by inward certainty).
USAGE: agree, assure, believe, have confidence, be (wax) conflent, make friend, obey, persuade, trust, yield.

DEFINITION: to be hungry, needy, desire earnestly.
ORIGIN: From the same as penes (through the idea of pinching toil; "pine"); to famish (absolutely or comparatively); figuratively, to crave.

DEFINITION: a trial, experiment, attempt.
ORIGIN: From the base of peran (through the idea of piercing); a test, i.e. Attempt, experience.

DEFINITION: to make proof of, to attempt, test, tempt.
ORIGIN: From peira; to test (objectively), i.e. Endeavor, scrutinize, entice, discipline.
USAGE: assay, examine, go about, prove, tempt(-er), try.

DEFINITION: (a) trial, probation, testing, being tried, (b) temptation, (c) calamity, affliction.
ORIGIN: From peirazo; a putting to proof (by experiment (of good), experience (of evil), solicitation, discipline or provocation); by implication, adversity.

DEFINITION: mid: to try, attempt, endeavor.
ORIGIN: From peira; to test (subjectively), i.e. (reflexively) to attempt.

DEFINITION: persuasion, conviction, a yielding to persuasion.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of peitho; persuadableness, i.e. Credulity.

DEFINITION: the deep, the deep sea.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; deep or open sea, i.e. The main.

DEFINITION: to cut off with an ax, to behead.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of plesso (meaning an axe); to chop off (the head), i.e. Truncate.

DEFINITION: the fifth.
ORIGIN: From pente; fifth.

DEFINITION: to send, transmit, permit to go, put forth.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to dispatch (from the subjective view or point of departure, whereas hiemi (as a stronger form of eimi) refers rather to the objective point or terminus ad quem, and stello denotes properly, the orderly motion involved), especially on a temporary errand; also to transmit, bestow, or wield.

DEFINITION: one who works for his living; a laborer, poor man.
ORIGIN: From a primary peno (to toil for daily subsistence); starving, i.e. Indigent.

DEFINITION: a mother-in-law.
ORIGIN: Feminine of pentheros; a wife's mother.

DEFINITION: a father-in-law.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a wife's father.

DEFINITION: to mourn, lament, feel guilt.
ORIGIN: From penthos; to grieve (the feeling or the act).

DEFINITION: mourning, sorrow, sadness, grief.
ORIGIN: Strengthened from the alternate of pascho; grief.

DEFINITION: needy, poor.
ORIGIN: Prolongation from the base of penes; necessitous.

DEFINITION: five times.
ORIGIN: Multiplicative adverb from pente; five times.

DEFINITION: five thousand.
ORIGIN: From pentakis and chilioi; five times a thousand.

DEFINITION: five hundred.
ORIGIN: From pente and hekaton; five hundred.

DEFINITION: five.
ORIGIN: A primary number; "five".

DEFINITION: the fifteenth.
ORIGIN: From pente and kai and dekatos; five and tenth.

DEFINITION: fifty.
ORIGIN: Multiplicative of pente; fifty.

DEFINITION: fiftieth, Pentecost, the second of the three great Jewish feasts.
ORIGIN: Feminine of the ordinal of pentekonta; fiftieth (hemera being implied) from Passover, i.e. The festival of "Pentecost".

DEFINITION: confidence, trust, reliance.
ORIGIN: From the perfect of the alternate of pascho; reliance.

DEFINITION: indeed (adds force to the preceding word).
ORIGIN: From the base of peran; an enclitic particle significant of abundance (thoroughness), i.e. Emphasis; much, very or ever.

DEFINITION: over, on the other side, beyond.
ORIGIN: Apparently accusative case of an obsolete derivative of peiro (to "pierce"); through (as adverb or preposition), i.e. Across.

DEFINITION: (a) a boundary, limit, extremity, (b) an end, conclusion.
ORIGIN: From the same as peran; an extremity.

DEFINITION: Pergamum, an important city of the Roman province Asia.
ORIGIN: From purgos; fortified; Pergamus, a place in Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: Perga, a city on the river Cestrus in the Roman province Pamphylia.
ORIGIN: Probably from the same as Pergamos; a tower; Perga, a place in Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: about, concerning, around (denotes place, cause or subject).
ORIGIN: From the base of peran; properly, through (all over), i.e. Around; figuratively with respect to; used in various applications, of place, cause or time (with the genitive case denoting the subject or occasion or superlative point; with the accusative case the locality, circuit, matter, circumstance or general period).
USAGE: (there-)about, above, against, at, on behalf of, X and his company, which concern, (as) concerning, for, X how it will go with, ((there-, where-)) of, on, over, pertaining (to), for sake, X (e-)state, (as) touching, (where-)by (in), with. In comparative, it retains substantially the same meaning of circuit (around), excess (beyond), or completeness (through).

DEFINITION: to lead or carry about (or around), go about, traverse.
ORIGIN: From peri and ago; to take around (as a companion); reflexively, to walk around.

DEFINITION: (a) to strip off, strip from, take away, (b) to cast off, cut adrift, cast loose.
ORIGIN: From peri and haireomai (including its alternate); to remove all around, i.e. Unveil, cast off (anchor); figuratively, to expiate.

DEFINITION: to flash (gleam) around like lightning.
ORIGIN: From peri and astrapto; to flash all around, i.e. Envelop in light.

DEFINITION: to cast around, wrap a garment about, put on; hence mid: to put on to myself, clothe myself, dress; to draw (a line).
ORIGIN: From peri and ballo; to throw all around, i.e. Invest (with a palisade or with clothing).
USAGE: array, cast about, clothe(-d me), put on.

DEFINITION: to look around on, survey.
ORIGIN: From peri and blepo; to look all around.

DEFINITION: a wrapper, mantle, veil, cloak, covering.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of periballo; something thrown around one, i.e. A mantle, veil.

DEFINITION: to bind (tie) around.
ORIGIN: peri and deo; to bind around one, i.e. Enwrap.

DEFINITION: to overdo, be a busybody, waste labor about (a thing).
ORIGIN: From peri and ergazomai; to work all around, i.e. Bustle about (meddle).

DEFINITION: of persons: over-careful; curious, meddling, a busy-body; of things: over-wrought; superfluous; curious, uncanny; subst: curious arts, magic.
ORIGIN: From peri and ergon; working all around, i.e. Officious (meddlesome, neuter plural magic).

DEFINITION: to go around, move about, visit; to make a circuit, tack (as a ship).
ORIGIN: From peri and erchomai (including its alternate); to come all around, i.e. Stroll, vacillate, veer.
USAGE: fetch a compass, vagabond, wandering about.

DEFINITION: (a) to contain (of a book containing subject matter); hence: it stands (has its content) thus, (b) to encompass, surround, get hold of, seize.
ORIGIN: From peri and echo; to hold all around, i.e. Include, clasp (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to gird round; mid: to gird myself, generally for active work or travel.
ORIGIN: From peri and zonnumi; to gird all around, i.e. (middle voice or passive) to fasten on one's belt (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a putting around or on (as of ornaments).
ORIGIN: From peritithemi; a putting all around, i.e. Decorating oneself with.

DEFINITION: in intrans. act. tenses: to stand around; mid: to avoid, shun.
ORIGIN: From peri and histemi; to stand all around, i.e. (near) to be a bystander, or (aloof) to keep away from.

DEFINITION: that which is cleaned off, refuse.
ORIGIN: From a compound of peri and kathairo; something cleaned off all around, i.e. Refuse (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to cover up, cover round about, veil round, blindfold.
ORIGIN: From peri and kalupto; to cover all around, i.e. Entirely (the face, a surface).

DEFINITION: to lie about, surround; to be encompassed, surrounded, or clothed with, be in submission to.
ORIGIN: From peri and keimai; to lie all around, i.e. Inclose, encircle, hamper (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a helmet.
ORIGIN: Feminine of a compound of peri and kephale; encirclement of the head, i.e. A helmet.

DEFINITION: having full power over, mastering, gaining control over.
ORIGIN: From peri and kratos; strong all around, i.e. A master (manager).

DEFINITION: to conceal, hide (by putting something around it).
ORIGIN: From peri and krupto; to conceal all around, i.e. Entirely.

DEFINITION: to encircle, surround, encompass.
ORIGIN: From peri and kukloo; to encircle all around, i.e. Blockade completely.

DEFINITION: to shine around.
ORIGIN: From peri and lampo; to illuminate all around, i.e. Invest with a halo.

DEFINITION: to leave behind; pass: to be left behind, remain, survive.
ORIGIN: From peri and leipo; to leave all around, i.e. (passively) survive.

DEFINITION: very sorrowful, greatly grieved.
ORIGIN: From peri and lupe; grieved all around, i.e. Intensely sad.

DEFINITION: to wait for, await.
ORIGIN: From peri and meno; to stay around, i.e. Await.

DEFINITION: round about, neighboring.
ORIGIN: Adverb from peri; all around, i.e. (as an adjective) circumjacent.

DEFINITION: to dwell around, be neighboring to.
ORIGIN: From peri and oikeo; to reside around, i.e. Be a neighbor.

DEFINITION: dwelling around; subst: a neighbor.
ORIGIN: From peri and oikos; housed around, i.e. Neighboring (used elliptically as a noun).

DEFINITION: costly, treasured, select, specially chosen.
ORIGIN: From the present participle feminine of a compound of peri and eimi; being beyond usual, i.e. Special (one's own).

DEFINITION: circumference, a portion circumscribed.
ORIGIN: From periecho; a being held around, i.e. (concretely) a passage (of Scripture, as circumscribed).

DEFINITION: to walk, hence Hebraistically (in an ethical sense): to conduct life, live.
ORIGIN: From peri and pateo; to tread all around, i.e. Walk at large (especially as proof of ability); figuratively, to live, deport oneself, follow (as a companion or votary).

DEFINITION: to put on a spit; met: to pierce, wound deeply.
ORIGIN: From peri and the base of peran; to penetrate entirely, i.e. Transfix (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to fall into the midst of, be involved in, happen upon a place.
ORIGIN: From peri and pipto; to fall into something that is all around, i.e. Light among or upon, be surrounded with.

DEFINITION: to acquire, earn, purchase, make own, preserve alive.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from peri and poieo; to make around oneself, i.e. Acquire (buy).

DEFINITION: acquiring, obtaining, possessing, possession, ownership.
ORIGIN: From peripoieomai; acquisition (the act or the thing); by extension, preservation.

DEFINITION: to tear off, as of garments.
ORIGIN: From peri and rhegnumi; to tear all around, i.e. Completely away.

DEFINITION: to distract, trouble greatly.
ORIGIN: From peri and spao; to drag all around, i.e. (figuratively) to distract (with care).

DEFINITION: abundance, superfluity.
ORIGIN: From perisseuo; surplusage, i.e. Superabundance.

DEFINITION: abundance, overflow.
ORIGIN: From perisseuo; a surplus, or superabundance.
USAGE: abundance, that was left, over and above.

DEFINITION: (a) intrans: to exceed the ordinary (the necessary), abound, overflow; be left over, (b) trans: to cause to abound.
ORIGIN: From perissos; to superabound (in quantity or quality), be in excess, be superfluous; also (transitively) to cause to superabound or excel.
USAGE: (make, more) abound, (have, have more) abundance (be more) abundant, be the better, enough and to spare, exceed, excel, increase, be left, redound, remain (over and above).

DEFINITION: more, greater, excessive, abundant, exceedingly, vehemently; noun: preeminence, advantage.
ORIGIN: From peri (in the sense of beyond); superabundant (in quantity) or superior (in quality); by implication, excessive; adverbially (with ek) violently; neuter (as noun) preeminence.
USAGE: exceeding abundantly above, more abundantly, advantage, exceedingly, very highly, beyond measure, more, superfluous, vehement(-ly).

DEFINITION: more abundantly, a great deal, far more.
ORIGIN: Neuter of perissoteros (as adverb); in a more superabundant way.
USAGE: more abundantly, a great deal, far more.

DEFINITION: greater, more, even more, more abundantly.
ORIGIN: Comparative of perissos; more superabundant (in number, degree or character).

DEFINITION: more abundantly, much more.
ORIGIN: Adverb from perissoteros (g4055); more superabundantly.
USAGE: more abundant(-ly), X the more earnest, (more) exceedingly, more frequent, much more, the rather.

DEFINITION: greatly, exceedingly, abundantly, vehemently.
ORIGIN: Adverb from perissos; superabundantly.
USAGE: exceedingly, out of measure, the more.

DEFINITION: a dove, pigeon.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a pigeon.

DEFINITION: to cut around, circumcise.
ORIGIN: From peri and the base of tomoteros; to cut around, i.e. (specially) to circumcise.

DEFINITION: to place or put around, clothe; fig: to bestow, confer.
ORIGIN: From peri and tithemi; to place around; by implication, to present.
USAGE: bestow upon, hedge round about, put about (on, upon), set about.

DEFINITION: circumcision.
ORIGIN: From peritemno; circumcision (the rite, the condition or the people, literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to turn round, turn, change.
ORIGIN: From peri and the base of trope; to turn around, i.e. (mentally) to craze.

DEFINITION: to run around.
ORIGIN: From peri and trecho (including its alternate); to run around, i.e. Traverse.

DEFINITION: to carry around; pass: to be driven to and fro.
ORIGIN: From peri and phero; to convey around, i.e. Transport hither and thither.

DEFINITION: to examine on all sides, to despise.
ORIGIN: From peri and phroneo; to think beyond, i.e. Depreciate (contemn).

DEFINITION: neighboring; subst: the neighboring country, neighboring inhabitants.
ORIGIN: From peri and chora; around the region, i.e. Circumjacent (as noun, with ge implied vicinity).
USAGE: country (round) about, region (that lieth) round about.

DEFINITION: scrapings, offscourings, wiped-off filth.
ORIGIN: From a comparative of peri and psao (to rub); something brushed all around, i.e. Off-scrapings (figuratively, scum).

DEFINITION: to boast, vaunt myself.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from perperos (braggart; perhaps by reduplication of the base of peran); to boast.

DEFINITION: Persis, name of a Christian lady in Rome.
ORIGIN: A Persian woman; Persis, a Christian female.

DEFINITION: last year, a year ago.
ORIGIN: Adverb from peras; the by-gone, i.e. (as noun) last year.

DEFINITION: a bird, fowl.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of petomai; a flying animal, i.e. Bird.

DEFINITION: to fly.
ORIGIN: Or prolongation petaomai (pet-ah'-om-ahee), or contracted ptaomai (ptah'-om-ahee) middle voice of a primary verb; to fly.

DEFINITION: a rock, ledge, cliff, cave, stony ground.
ORIGIN: Feminine of the same as Petros; a (mass of) rock (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: "a stone" or "a boulder", Peter, one of the twelve apostles.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a (piece of) rock (larger than lithos); as a name, Petrus, an apostle.

DEFINITION: rocky, stony.
ORIGIN: From petra and eidos; rock-like, i.e. Rocky.

DEFINITION: rue, a plant used for flavoring or garnishing food.
ORIGIN: From pegnumi; rue (from its thick or fleshy leaves).

DEFINITION: a fountain, spring, well, issue, flow.
ORIGIN: Probably from pegnumi (through the idea of gushing plumply); a fount (literally or figuratively), i.e. Source or supply (of water, blood, enjoyment) (not necessarily the original spring).

DEFINITION: to fasten, pitch a tent.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary verb (which in its simpler form occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses); to fix ("peg"), i.e. (specially) to set up (a tent).

DEFINITION: the rudder of a ship.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a (presumed) derivative of pedon (the blade of an oar; from the same as pede); a "pedal", i.e. Helm.

DEFINITION: how large? how great?.
ORIGIN: A quantitative form (the feminine) of the base of pou; how much (as an indefinite), i.e. In size or (figuratively) dignity.

DEFINITION: clay, mud.
ORIGIN: Perhaps a primary word; clay.

DEFINITION: a sack, wallet for carrying provisions.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a wallet or leather pouch for food.

DEFINITION: a cubit, about a foot and a half.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; the fore-arm, i.e. (as a measure) a cubit.

DEFINITION: to lay hold of, apprehend, catch, arrest.
ORIGIN: Probably another form of biazo; to squeeze, i.e. Seize (gently by the hand (press), or officially (arrest), or in hunting (capture)).
USAGE: apprehend, catch, lay hand on, take. Compare piezo.

DEFINITION: to press down, press together, as in a measure.
ORIGIN: Another form for piazo; to pack.

DEFINITION: persuasive speech.
ORIGIN: From a compound of a derivative of peitho and logos; persuasive language.

DEFINITION: to make bitter, embitter; pass: to grow angry or harsh.
ORIGIN: From pikros; to embitter (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: bitterness, harshness, hence met: an embittered (resentful) spirit.
ORIGIN: From pikros; acridity (especially poison), literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: bitter, acrid, malignant.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from pegnumi (through the idea of piercing); sharp (pungent), i.e. Acrid (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: bitterly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from pikros; bitterly, i.e. (figuratively) violently.

DEFINITION: Pilate, a Roman procurator of Judea.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; close-pressed, i.e. Firm; Pilatus, a Roman.

DEFINITION: to swell, be inflamed.
ORIGIN: A reduplicated and prolonged form of a primary preo preh'-o which occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses); to fire, i.e. Burn (figuratively and passively, become inflamed with fever).

DEFINITION: a tablet for writing.
ORIGIN: Diminutive of pinax; a tablet (for writing on).

DEFINITION: a plate, platter, disc, dish.
ORIGIN: Apparently a form of plax; a plate.

DEFINITION: to drink, imbibe.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of pio (pee'-o), which (together with another form) poo (po'-o) occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses; to imbibe (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: fatness, as of the olive; richness.
ORIGIN: From pion (fat; perhaps akin to the alternate of pino through the idea of repletion); plumpness, i.e. (by implication) richness (oiliness).

DEFINITION: to sell; pass: to be a slave to, be devoted to.
ORIGIN: A reduplicated and prolonged form of prao (prah'-o); (which occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses) contracted from perao (to traverse; from the base of peran); to traffic (by travelling), i.e. Dispose of as merchandise or into slavery (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to fall, fall under (as under condemnation), fall prostrate.
ORIGIN: A reduplicated and contracted form of peto (pet'-o); (which occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses); probably akin to petomai through the idea of alighting; to fall (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: Pisidia, a country of Asia Minor, being the south-western part of the Roman province Galatia.
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin; Pisidia, a region of Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: to believe, have faith in, trust in; pass: to be entrusted with.
ORIGIN: From pistis; to have faith (in, upon, or with respect to, a person or thing), i.e. Credit; by implication, to entrust (especially one's spiritual well-being to Christ).
USAGE: believe(-r), commit (to trust), put in trust with.

DEFINITION: genuine, pure (of ointment), trustworthy.
ORIGIN: From pistis; trustworthy, i.e. Genuine (unadulterated).

DEFINITION: faith, belief, trust, confidence; fidelity, faithfulness.
ORIGIN: From peitho; persuasion, i.e. Credence; moral conviction (of religious truth, or the truthfulness of God or a religious teacher), especially reliance upon Christ for salvation; abstractly, constancy in such profession; by extension, the system of religious (Gospel) truth itself.

DEFINITION: trustworthy, faithful, believing.
ORIGIN: From peitho; objectively, trustworthy; subjectively, trustful.

DEFINITION: to convince, establish, give assurance to; pass: to be assured of.
ORIGIN: From pistos; to assure.

DEFINITION: to lead astray, deceive, cause to wander.
ORIGIN: From plane; to (properly, cause to) roam (from safety, truth, or virtue).
USAGE: go astray, deceive, err, seduce, wander, be out of the way.

DEFINITION: a wandering; fig: deceit, delusion, error, sin.
ORIGIN: Feminine of planos (as abstractly); objectively, fraudulence; subjectively, a straying from orthodoxy or piety.

DEFINITION: a wanderer.
ORIGIN: From planos; a rover ("planet"), i.e. (figuratively) an erratic teacher.

DEFINITION: adj: misleading, deceiving, wandering; as subst: a deceiver, imposter.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; roving (as a tramp), i.e. (by implication) an impostor or misleader.

DEFINITION: anything flat and broad, a flat stone.
ORIGIN: From plasso; a moulding-board, i.e. Flat surface ("plate", or tablet, literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a thing formed or fashioned.
ORIGIN: From plasso; something moulded.

DEFINITION: to form, mould, as a potter his clay.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to mould, i.e. Shape or fabricate.

DEFINITION: formed, molded; fig: feigned, made up, counterfeit.
ORIGIN: From plasso; moulded, i.e. (by implication) artificial or (figuratively) fictitious (false).

DEFINITION: a street, public square, broad way.
ORIGIN: Feminine of platus; a wide "plat" or "place", i.e. Open square.

DEFINITION: breadth.
ORIGIN: From platus; width.

DEFINITION: to enlarge, make broad; met: of the growth of tenderness and love.
ORIGIN: From platus; to widen (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: broad, wide; subst: a street.
ORIGIN: From plasso; spread out "flat" ("plot"), i.e. Broad.

DEFINITION: braided hair, anything interwoven.
ORIGIN: From pleko; a plait (of hair).

DEFINITION: the greatest, the most, very great.
ORIGIN: Irregular superlative of polus; the largest number or very large.

DEFINITION: more excellent, very great, many.
ORIGIN: Or neuter pleion (pli'-on), or pleon (pleh'-on) comparative of polus; more in quantity, number, or quality; also (in plural) the major portion.
USAGE: X above, + exceed, more excellent, further, (very) great(-er), long(-er), (very) many, greater (more) part, + yet but.

DEFINITION: to weave together, plait, twist, braid.
ORIGIN: A primary word; to twine or braid.

DEFINITION: to have more than enough; to abound, increase.
ORIGIN: From pleion; to do, make or be more, i.e. Increase (transitively or intransitively); by extension, to superabound.
USAGE: abound, abundant, make to increase, have over.

DEFINITION: to take advantage of, overreach, defraud.
ORIGIN: From pleonektes; to be covetous, i.e. (by implication) to over-reach.
USAGE: get an advantage, defraud, make a gain.

DEFINITION: a covetous or avaricious person; one desirous of having more.
ORIGIN: From pleion and echo; holding (desiring) more, i.e. Eager for gain (avaricious, hence a defrauder).

DEFINITION: covetousness, avarice, aggression, desire for advantage.
ORIGIN: From pleonektes; avarice, i.e. (by implication) fraudulency, extortion.

DEFINITION: the side of the body.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a rib, i.e. (by extension) side.

DEFINITION: to sail, travel by sea, voyage.
ORIGIN: Another form for pleuo (plyoo'-o); which is used as an alternate in certain tenses; probably a form of pluno (through the idea of plunging through the water); to pass in a vessel.

DEFINITION: a blow, stripe, wound; an affliction, plague.
ORIGIN: From plesso; a stroke; by implication, a wound; figuratively, a calamity.

DEFINITION: a multitude, crowd, great number, assemblage.
ORIGIN: From pletho; a fulness, i.e. A large number, throng, populace.

DEFINITION: to increase, to be increased.
ORIGIN: From another form of plethos; to increase (transitively or intransitively).

DEFINITION: furnish, accomplish, fill, supply.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary pleo (pleh'-o) (which appears only as an alternate in certain tenses and in the reduplicated form pimplemi) to "fill" (literally or figuratively (imbue, influence, supply)); specially, to fulfil (time).

DEFINITION: a striker, contentious person, brawler.
ORIGIN: From plesso; a smiter, i.e. Pugnacious (quarrelsome).

DEFINITION: a flood.
ORIGIN: Prolonged from pletho; flood-tide, i.e. (by analogy) a freshet.

DEFINITION: however, nevertheless, but, except that, yet.
ORIGIN: From pleion; moreover (besides), i.e. Albeit, save that, rather, yet.
USAGE: but (rather), except, nevertheless, notwithstanding, save, than.

DEFINITION: full, abounding in, complete, completely occupied with.
ORIGIN: From pletho; replete, or covered over; by analogy, complete.

DEFINITION: (lit: to carry full), (a) to complete, carry out fully, (b) to fully convince, satisfy fully, (c) to fully believe.
ORIGIN: From pleres and phoreo; to carry out fully (in evidence), i.e. Completely assure (or convince), entirely accomplish.
USAGE: most surely believe, fully know (persuade), make full proof of.

DEFINITION: full assurance, conviction, confidence.
ORIGIN: From plerophoreo; entire confidence.

DEFINITION: to fill, fulfill, complete.
ORIGIN: From pleres; to make replete, i.e. (literally) to cram (a net), level up (a hollow), or (figuratively) to furnish (or imbue, diffuse, influence), satisfy, execute (an office), finish (a period or task), verify (or coincide with a prediction), etc..
USAGE: accomplish, X after, (be) complete, end, expire, fill (up), fulfil, (be, make) full (come), fully preach, perfect, supply.

DEFINITION: (a) a fill, fullness; full complement; supply, patch, supplement, (b) fullness, filling, fulfillment, completion.
ORIGIN: From pleroo; repletion or completion, i.e. (subjectively) what fills (as contents, supplement, copiousness, multitude), or (objectively) what is filled (as container, performance, period).
USAGE: which is put in to fill up, piece that filled up, fulfilling, full, fulness.

DEFINITION: near, nearby, a neighbor.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of pelas (near); (adverbially) close by; as noun, a neighbor, i.e. Fellow (as man, countryman, Christian or friend).

DEFINITION: satisfaction, indulgence.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of pletho; a filling up, i.e. (figuratively) gratification.

DEFINITION: to strike, smite.
ORIGIN: Apparently another form of plasso (through the idea of flattening out); to pound, i.e. (figuratively) to inflict with (calamity).

DEFINITION: (a little boat, hence) a boat.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of ploion; a boat.

DEFINITION: a ship, vessel, boat.
ORIGIN: From pleo; a sailer, i.e. Vessel.

DEFINITION: a voyage, sailing.
ORIGIN: From pleo; a sail, i.e. Navigation.

DEFINITION: rich, abounding in, wealthy; subst: a rich man.
ORIGIN: From ploutos; wealthy; figuratively, abounding with.

DEFINITION: richly, abundantly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from plousios; copiously.

DEFINITION: to become rich, be rich, abound in.
ORIGIN: From ploutizo; to be (or become) wealthy (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: be increased with goods, (be made, wax) rich.

DEFINITION: to make rich, cause to abound in, enrich.
ORIGIN: From ploutos; to make wealthy (figuratively).

DEFINITION: riches, wealth, abundance, materially or spiritually.
ORIGIN: From the base of pletho; wealth (as fulness), i.e. (literally) money, possessions, or (figuratively) abundance, richness, (specially), valuable bestowment.

DEFINITION: to wash.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of an obsolete pluo (to "flow"); to "plunge", i.e. Launder clothing.

DEFINITION: wind, breath, spirit.
ORIGIN: From pneo; a current of air, i.e. Breath (blast) or a breeze; by analogy or figuratively, a spirit, i.e. (human) the rational soul, (by implication) vital principle, mental disposition, etc., or (superhuman) an angel, demon, or (divine) God, Christ's spirit, the Holy Spirit.
USAGE: ghost, life, spirit(-ual, -ually), mind. Compare psuche.

DEFINITION: spiritual.
ORIGIN: From pneuma; non-carnal, i.e. (humanly) ethereal (as opposed to gross), or (daemoniacally) a spirit (concretely), or (divinely) supernatural, regenerate, religious.

DEFINITION: spiritually, in a spiritual way; from a spiritual point of view.
ORIGIN: Adverb from pneumatikos; non-physically, i.e. Divinely, figuratively.

DEFINITION: to blow, breathe, as the wind.
ORIGIN: A primary word; to breathe hard, i.e. Breeze.

DEFINITION: to choke, throttle, strangle; hence: to drown.
ORIGIN: Strengthened from pneo; to wheeze, i.e. (causative, by implication) to throttle or strangle (drown).

DEFINITION: strangled (i.e. killed without letting out the blood).
ORIGIN: From pnigo; throttled, i.e. (neuter concretely) an animal choked to death (not bled).

DEFINITION: (a) breath, (b) gust, breeze, wind.
ORIGIN: From pneo; respiration, a breeze.

DEFINITION: reaching to the feet (of a garment).
ORIGIN: From pous and another element of uncertain affinity; a dress (esthes implied) reaching the ankles.

DEFINITION: whence, from what place.
ORIGIN: From the base of posis with enclitic adverb of origin; from which (as interrogative) or what (as relative) place, state, source or cause.

DEFINITION: (a) to make, manufacture, construct, (b) to do, act, cause.
ORIGIN: Apparently a prolonged form of an obsolete primary; to make or do (in a very wide application, more or less direct).
USAGE: abide, + agree, appoint, X avenge, + band together, be, bear, + bewray, bring (forth), cast out, cause, commit, + content, continue, deal, + without any delay, (would) do(-ing), execute, exercise, fulfil, gain, give, have, hold, X journeying, keep, + lay wait, + lighten the ship, make, X mean, + none of these things move me, observe, ordain, perform, provide, + have purged, purpose, put, + raising up, X secure, shew, X shoot out, spend, take, tarry, + transgress the law, work, yield. Compare prasso.

DEFINITION: a thing made, a work, workmanship.
ORIGIN: From poieo; a product, i.e. Fabric (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a doing, making, performance.
ORIGIN: From poieo; action, i.e. Performance (of the law).

DEFINITION: (a) a maker, poet, (b) a doer, carrier out, performer.
ORIGIN: From poieo; a performer; specially, a "poet".

DEFINITION: various, of different colors, diverse, various.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; motley, i.e. Various in character.

DEFINITION: to shepherd, tend, herd; hence: to rule, govern.
ORIGIN: From poimen; to tend as a shepherd of (figuratively, superviser).

DEFINITION: a shepherd; hence met: of the feeder, protector, and ruler of a flock of men.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a shepherd (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a flock (of sheep or goats).
ORIGIN: Contraction from poimaino; a flock (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a little flock.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of poimne; a flock, i.e. (figuratively) group (of believers).

DEFINITION: of what sort?.
ORIGIN: From the base of pou and hoios; individualizing interrogative (of character) what sort of, or (of number) which one.

DEFINITION: to make war, contend, fight, battle.
ORIGIN: From polemos.
USAGE: to be (engaged) in warfare, i.e. To battle (literally or figuratively); fight, (make) war.

DEFINITION: a war, battle, strife.
ORIGIN: From pelomai (to bustle); warfare (literally or figuratively; a single encounter or a series).

DEFINITION: a city, the inhabitants of a city.
ORIGIN: Probably from the same as polemos, or perhaps from polus; a town (properly, with walls, of greater or less size).

DEFINITION: a ruler of a city, city magistrate.
ORIGIN: From polis and archo; a town-officer, i.e. Magistrate.

DEFINITION: (a) commonwealth, polity; citizen body, (b) (the Roman) citizenship, citizen-rights, franchise.
ORIGIN: From polites ("polity"); citizenship; concretely, a community.

DEFINITION: a form of government, citizenship.
ORIGIN: From politeuomai; a community, i.e. (abstractly) citizenship (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to live the life of a citizen, live.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of a derivative of polites; to behave as a citizen (figuratively).

DEFINITION: a citizen, fellow-citizen.
ORIGIN: From polis; a townsman.

DEFINITION: many times, often, frequently.
ORIGIN: Multiplicative adverb from polus; many times, i.e. Frequently.

DEFINITION: many times more, manifold.
ORIGIN: From polus and probably a derivative of pleko; manifold, i.e. (neuter as noun) very much more.

DEFINITION: much-speaking, loquacity.
ORIGIN: From a compound of polus and logos; loquacity, i.e. Prolixity.

DEFINITION: in many parts (one at one time, another at another, and so on).
ORIGIN: Adverb from a compound of polus and meros; in many portions, i.e. Variously as to time and agency (piecemeal).

DEFINITION: much varied, manifold.
ORIGIN: From polus and poikilos; much variegated, i.e. Multifarious.

DEFINITION: much, many; often.
ORIGIN: Including the forms from the alternate pollos; (singular) much (in any respect) or (plural) many; neuter (singular) as adverbial, largely; neuter (plural) as adverb or noun often, mostly, largely.
USAGE: abundant, + altogether, common, + far (passed, spent), (+ be of a) great (age, deal, -ly, while), long, many, much, oft(-en (-times)), plenteous, sore, straitly. Compare pleistos, pleion.

DEFINITION: very compassionate, of great mercy.
ORIGIN: From polus and splagchnon (figuratively); extremely compassionate.

DEFINITION: very costly, very precious, of great value.
ORIGIN: From polus and telos; extremely expensive.
USAGE: costly, very precious, of great price.

DEFINITION: of great value, very costly, very precious.
ORIGIN: From polus and time; extremely valuable.

DEFINITION: in many ways.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a compound of polus and tropos; in many ways, i.e. Variously as to method or form.

DEFINITION: a drink.
ORIGIN: From the alternate of pino; a beverage.

DEFINITION: wickedness, iniquities.
ORIGIN: From poneros; depravity, i.e. (specially), malice; plural (concretely) plots, sins.

DEFINITION: evil, bad, wicked, malicious, slothful.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of ponos; hurtful, i.e. Evil (properly, in effect or influence, and thus differing from kakos, which refers rather to essential character, as well as from sapros, which indicates degeneracy from original virtue); figuratively, calamitous; also (passively) ill, i.e. Diseased; but especially (morally) culpable, i.e. Derelict, vicious, facinorous; neuter (singular) mischief, malice, or (plural) guilt; masculine (singular) the devil, or (plural) sinners.
USAGE: bad, evil, grievous, harm, lewd, malicious, wicked(-ness). See also poneroteros.

DEFINITION: more wicked.
ORIGIN: Comparative of poneros; more evil.

DEFINITION: (a) labor, toil, (b) pain, anguish, distress, suffering.
ORIGIN: From the base of penes; toil, i.e. (by implication) anguish.

DEFINITION: belonging to Pontus.
ORIGIN: From Pontos; a Pontican, i.e. Native of Pontus.

DEFINITION: Pontius (Pilate), a governor of Judea.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; apparently bridged; Pontius, a Roman.

DEFINITION: Pontus, a Roman province in the north of Asia Minor, bordering on the Black Sea, governed along with Bithynia.
ORIGIN: A sea; Pontus, a region of Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: Publius, an inhabitant of Malta.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; apparently "popular"; Poplius (i.e. Publius), a Roman.

DEFINITION: a journey, pursuit, undertaking, progress.
ORIGIN: From poreuomai; travel (by land); figuratively (plural) proceedings, i.e. Career.

DEFINITION: to travel, journey, go, die.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from a derivative of the same as peira; to traverse, i.e. Travel (literally or figuratively; especially to remove (figuratively, die), live, etc.).
USAGE: depart, go (away, forth, one's way, up), (make a, take a) journey, walk.

DEFINITION: to lay waste, destroy, ravage, harass.
ORIGIN: Prolongation from pertho (to sack); to ravage (figuratively).

DEFINITION: a providing, a means of gain.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of poros (a way, i.e. Means); furnishing (procuring), i.e. (by implication) money-getting (acquisition).

DEFINITION: Porcius, the middle (gentile) name of the procurator Festus.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; apparently swinish; Porcius, a Roman.

DEFINITION: fornication, whoredom; met: idolatry.
ORIGIN: From porneuo; harlotry (including adultery and incest); figuratively, idolatry.

DEFINITION: to fornicate; met: to practice idolatry.
ORIGIN: From porne; to act the harlot, i.e. (literally) indulge unlawful lust (of either sex), or (figuratively) practise idolatry.

DEFINITION: a prostitute; met: an idolatrous community.
ORIGIN: Feminine of pornos; a strumpet; figuratively, an idolater.

DEFINITION: a fornicator, man who prostitutes himself.
ORIGIN: From pernemi (to sell; akin to the base of piprasko); a (male) prostitute (as venal), i.e. (by analogy) a debauchee (libertine).

DEFINITION: far, far off, at a distance.
ORIGIN: Adverb from pro; forwards, i.e. At a distance.
USAGE: far, a great way off. See also porrhothen.

DEFINITION: from afar, far off, from a distance.
ORIGIN: From porrho with adverbial enclitic of source; from far, or (by implication) at a distance, i.e. Distantly.

DEFINITION: farther, beyond.
ORIGIN: Adverb comparative of porrho; further, i.e. A greater distance.

DEFINITION: a purple garment, indicating power or wealth.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; the "purple" mussel, i.e. (by implication) the red-blue color itself, and finally a garment dyed with it.

DEFINITION: purple.
ORIGIN: From porphura; purpureal, i.e. Bluish red.

DEFINITION: a female seller of purple cloth.
ORIGIN: Feminine of a compound of porphura and poleo; a female trader in purple cloth.

DEFINITION: how often, how many times.
ORIGIN: Multiplicative from posos; how many times.

DEFINITION: drinking, drink, beverage.
ORIGIN: From the alternate of pino; a drinking (the act), i.e. (concretely) a draught.

DEFINITION: how much, how great, how many.
ORIGIN: From an absolute pos (who, what) and hos; interrogative pronoun (of amount) how much (large, long or (plural) many).

DEFINITION: a river, torrent, stream.
ORIGIN: Probably from a derivative of the alternate of pino (compare potos); a current, brook or freshet (as drinkable), i.e. Running water.

DEFINITION: carried away by a stream.
ORIGIN: From potamos and a derivative of phoreo; river-borne, i.e. Overwhelmed by a stream.

DEFINITION: of what kind, of what manner.
ORIGIN: Apparently from pote and the base of pou; interrogatively, whatever, i.e. Of what possible sort.

DEFINITION: at one time or other, at some time, formerly.
ORIGIN: From the base of pou and te; indefinite adverb, at some time, ever.
USAGE: afore-(any, some-)time(-s), at length (the last), (+ n-)ever, in the old time, in time past, once, when.

DEFINITION: when, at what time.
ORIGIN: From the base of pou and te; interrogative adverb, at what time.

DEFINITION: which of two, whether.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a comparative of the base of pou; interrogative as adverb, which (of two), i.e. Is it this or that.

DEFINITION: a drinking cup, the contents of the cup; fig: the portion which God allots.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of the alternate of pino; a drinking-vessel; by extension, the contents thereof, i.e. A cupful (draught); figuratively, a lot or fate.

DEFINITION: to cause to drink, give to drink; irrigate, water.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of the alternate of pino; to furnish drink, irrigate.

DEFINITION: Puteoli, the great harbor for traffic with Alexandria on the Bay of Naples.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; little wells, i.e. Mineral springs; Potioli (i.e. Puteoli), a place in Italy.

DEFINITION: a drinking, carousing.
ORIGIN: From the alternate of pino; a drinking-bout or carousal.

DEFINITION: where, somewhere, anywhere; with numerals: somewhere about.
ORIGIN: Genitive case of an indefinite pronoun pos (some) otherwise obsolete (compare posos); as adverb of place, somewhere, i.e. Nearly.

DEFINITION: where, in what place.
ORIGIN: Genitive case of an interrogative pronoun pos (what) otherwise obsolete (perhaps the same as pou used with the rising slide of inquiry); as adverb of place; at (by implication, to) what locality.

DEFINITION: Pudens, a Christian man in Rome.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; modest; Pudes (i.e. Pudens), a Christian.

DEFINITION: the foot.
ORIGIN: A primary word; a "foot" (figuratively or literally).

DEFINITION: a thing done, a deed, action; a matter, an affair.
ORIGIN: From prasso; a deed; by implication, an affair; by extension, an object (material).

DEFINITION: a business, an occupation, affair, transaction.
ORIGIN: From pragmateuomai; a transaction, i.e. Negotiation.

DEFINITION: to transact business, trade.
ORIGIN: From pragma; to busy oneself with, i.e. To trade.

DEFINITION: the palace at Jerusalem occupied by the Roman governor, or the quarters of the praetorian guard in Rome.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; the praetorium or governor's courtroom (sometimes including the whole edifice and camp).

DEFINITION: an officer employed to execute judicial sentences.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of prasso; a practiser, i.e. (specially), an official collector.

DEFINITION: (a) a doing, action, mode of action; plur: deeds, acts, (b) function, business.
ORIGIN: From prasso; practice, i.e. (concretely) an act; by extension, a function.

DEFINITION: mild, gentle, meek, kind.
ORIGIN: A form of praus, used in certain parts; gentle, i.e. Humble.

DEFINITION: mildness, gentleness, meekness, kindness.
ORIGIN: From praios; gentleness, by implication, humility.

DEFINITION: a company formed into divisions (like garden-beds).
ORIGIN: Perhaps from prason (a leek, and so an onion-patch); a garden plot, i.e. (by implication, of regular beds) a row (repeated in plural by Hebraism, to indicate an arrangement).

DEFINITION: to do, perform, accomplish; be in any condition, i.e. to fare; to exact, require.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to "practise", i.e. Perform repeatedly or habitually (thus differing from poieo, which properly refers to a single act); by implication, to execute, accomplish, etc.; specially, to collect (dues), fare (personally).
USAGE: commit, deeds, do, exact, keep, require, use arts.

DEFINITION: mild, gentle.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; mild, i.e. (by implication) humble.

DEFINITION: mildness, gentleness.
ORIGIN: From praus; mildness, i.e. (by implication) humility.

DEFINITION: it becomes, is fitting to, is right.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to tower up (be conspicuous), i.e. (by implication) to be suitable or proper (third person singular present indicative, often used impersonally, it is fit or right).

DEFINITION: an embassy, delegation, eldership.
ORIGIN: From presbeuo; seniority (eldership), i.e. (by implication) an embassy (concretely, ambassadors).

DEFINITION: to be the elder, to take precedence.
ORIGIN: From the base of presbuteros; to be a senior, i.e. (by implication) act as a representative (figuratively, preacher).

DEFINITION: an assembly of elders, the Sanhedrin, officers of the church assembly, presbytery.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of presbuteros; the order of elders, i.e. (specially), Israelite Sanhedrin or Christian "presbytery".

DEFINITION: elder, usually used as subst.; an elder, a member of the Sanhedrin, an elder of a Christian assembly.
ORIGIN: Comparative of presbus (elderly); older; as noun, a senior; specially, an Israelite Sanhedrist (also figuratively, member of the celestial council) or Christian "presbyter".

DEFINITION: an old man, an ambassador.
ORIGIN: From the same as presbuteros; an old man.

DEFINITION: an aged woman.
ORIGIN: Feminine of presbutes; an old woman.

DEFINITION: falling headlong, prone.
ORIGIN: From pro; leaning (falling) forward ("prone"), i.e. Head foremost.

DEFINITION: to saw, saw through.
ORIGIN: A strengthened form of a primary prio (to saw); to saw in two.

DEFINITION: formerly, before.
ORIGIN: Adverb from pro; prior, sooner.

DEFINITION: Prisca, Priscilla, the former being the more correct and formal name, the latter a diminutive and more familiar; a Roman lady, probably of good birth, wife of the Jewish Christian Aquila.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; feminine of Priscus, ancient; Priska, a Christian woman.

DEFINITION: Prisca, Priscilla, the former being the more correct and formal name, the latter a diminutive and more familiar; a Roman lady, probably of good birth, wife of the Jewish Christian Aquila.
ORIGIN: Diminutive of Priska; Priscilla (i.e. Little Prisca), a Christian woman.

DEFINITION: (a) of place: before, in front of, (b) of time: before, earlier than.
ORIGIN: A primary preposition; "fore", i.e. In front of, prior (figuratively, superior) to.
USAGE: above, ago, before, or ever. In the comparative, it retains the same significations.

DEFINITION: (a) trans: to lead forth; in the judicial sense, into court, (b) intrans. and trans: to precede, go before, (c) intrans: to go too far.
ORIGIN: From pro and ago; to lead forward (magisterially); intransitively, to precede (in place or time (participle, previous)).

DEFINITION: to propose; mid: to propose to myself, purpose.
ORIGIN: From pro and haireomai; to choose for oneself before another thing (prefer), i.e. (by implication) to propose (intend).

DEFINITION: to make a prior accusation.
ORIGIN: From pro and a derivative of aitia; to accuse already, i.e. Previously charge.

DEFINITION: to hear beforehand.
ORIGIN: From pro and akouo; to hear already,i.e. Anticipate.

DEFINITION: to sin previously.
ORIGIN: From pro and hamartano; to sin previously (to conversion).

DEFINITION: a porch, court before a building, vestibule.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed compound of pro and aule; a forecourt, i.e. Vestibule (alley-way).

DEFINITION: to go forward, advance.
ORIGIN: From pro and the base of basis; to walk forward, i.e. Advance (literally, or in years).
USAGE: + be of a great age, go farther (on), be well stricken.

DEFINITION: to thrust forward, put forth (as of branches), produce.
ORIGIN: From pro and ballo; to throw forward, i.e. Push to the front, germinate.

DEFINITION: pertaining to sheep.
