ORIGIN: From probaton; relating to sheep, i.e. (a gate) through which they were led into Jerusalem.

DEFINITION: a little sheep.
ORIGIN: Probably neuter of a presumed derivative of probaino; something that walks forward (a quadruped), i.e. (specially), a sheep (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to lead forward, lead on; met: to induce, incite, urge.
ORIGIN: From pro and a reduplicated form of biazo; to force forward, i.e. Bring to the front, instigate.

DEFINITION: to provide, foresee.
ORIGIN: From pro and blepo; to look out beforehand, i.e. Furnish in advance.

DEFINITION: to happen (come about) previously.
ORIGIN: From pro and ginomai; to be already, i.e. Have previousy transpired.

DEFINITION: to know beforehand, foreknow.
ORIGIN: From pro and ginosko; to know beforehand, i.e. Foresee.

DEFINITION: foreknowledge, previous determination.
ORIGIN: From proginosko; forethought.

DEFINITION: born before.
ORIGIN: From proginomai; an ancestor, (grand-)parent.

DEFINITION: (a) to write previously (aforetime); to write above (already), (b) to depict or portray openly, (c) to designate beforehand.
ORIGIN: From pro and grapho; to write previously; figuratively, to announce, prescribe.
USAGE: before ordain, evidently set forth, write (afore, aforetime).

DEFINITION: manifest to all, evident, very clear.
ORIGIN: From pro and delos; plain before all men, i.e. Obvious.

DEFINITION: to give before, give forth, betray.
ORIGIN: From pro and didomi; to give before the other party has given.

DEFINITION: a betrayer, traitor.
ORIGIN: From prodidomi (in the sense of giving forward into another's (the enemy's) hands); a surrender.

DEFINITION: a precursor, forerunner, advance guard.
ORIGIN: From the alternate of protrecho; a runner ahead, i.e. Scout (figuratively, precursor).

DEFINITION: to see beforehand, be mindful.
ORIGIN: From pro and eido; foresee.

DEFINITION: to hope before, be the first to hope.
ORIGIN: From pro and elpizo; to hope in advance of other confirmation.

DEFINITION: to say previously, predict, proclaim, foretell.
ORIGIN: From pro and epo; to say already, to predict.
USAGE: forewarn, say (speak, tell) before. Compare proereo.

DEFINITION: to begin before.
ORIGIN: From pro and enarchomai; to commence already.

DEFINITION: to promise beforehand.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from pro and epaggello; to promise of old.

DEFINITION: to say already, predict, foretell.
ORIGIN: From pro and ereo; used as alternate of proepo; to say already, predict.

DEFINITION: to go forward, go on, advance; to go before, precede.
ORIGIN: From pro and erchomai (including its alternate); to go onward, precede (in place or time).
USAGE: go before (farther, forward), outgo, pass on.

DEFINITION: to prepare or appoint beforehand, predestine.
ORIGIN: From pro and hetoimazo; to fit up in advance (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to preach the gospel beforehand, foretell good tidings.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from pro and euaggelizo; to announce glad news in advance.

DEFINITION: trans: to hold before; mid: to excuse myself; intrans: to project, excel, surpass, have preeminence.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from pro and echo; to hold oneself before others, i.e. (figuratively) to excel.

DEFINITION: to lead onward by example, go before, prefer.
ORIGIN: From pro and hegeomai; to lead the way for others, i.e. Show deference.

DEFINITION: a setting forth, the show-bread; predetermination, purpose.
ORIGIN: From protithemai; a setting forth, i.e. (figuratively) proposal (intention); specially, the show-bread (in the Temple) as exposed before God.

DEFINITION: appointed before; a previously-appointed time.
ORIGIN: From pro and a derivative of tithemi; fixed beforehand, i.e. (feminine with hemera implied) a designated day.

DEFINITION: inclination, readiness, eagerness, willingness, promptness.
ORIGIN: From prothumos; predisposition, i.e. Alacrity.
USAGE: forwardness of mind, readiness (of mind), ready (willing) mind.

DEFINITION: eager, ready, willing, prompt.
ORIGIN: From pro and thumos; forward in spirit, i.e. Predisposed; neuter (as noun) alacrity.

DEFINITION: readily, eagerly, with a ready mind, cheerfully.
ORIGIN: Adverb from prothumos; with alacrity.

DEFINITION: to preside, rule over, give attention to, direct, maintain, practice diligently.
ORIGIN: From pro and histemi; to stand before, i.e. (in rank) to preside, or (by implication) to practise.

DEFINITION: to provoke, stimulate, challenge, call out.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from pro and kaleo; to call forth to oneself (challenge), i.e. (by implication) to irritate.

DEFINITION: to announce beforehand, promise, predict.
ORIGIN: From pro and kataggello; to anounce beforehand, i.e. Predict, promise.

DEFINITION: to prepare or complete beforehand.
ORIGIN: From pro and katartizo; to prepare in advance.

DEFINITION: to be set (placed, put) before, be already there.
ORIGIN: From pro and keimai; to lie before the view, i.e. (figuratively) to be present (to the mind), to stand forth (as an example or reward).

DEFINITION: to announce or preach beforehand, announce by herald.
ORIGIN: From pro and kerusso; to herald (i.e. Proclaim) in advance.

DEFINITION: progress, advancement.
ORIGIN: From prokopto; progress, i.e. Advancement (subjectively or objectively).

DEFINITION: (originally of the pioneer cutting his way through brushwood), to advance, progress, make progress.
ORIGIN: From pro and kopto; to drive forward (as if by beating), i.e. (figuratively and intransitively) to advance (in amount, to grow; in time, to be well along).
USAGE: increase, proceed, profit, be far spent, wax.

DEFINITION: a prejudgment, prejudice, partiality, preference.
ORIGIN: From a compound of pro and krino; a prejudgment (prejudice), i.e. Prepossession.

DEFINITION: to establish or ratify before.
ORIGIN: From pro and kuroo; to ratify previously.

DEFINITION: to take before, anticipate; pass: to be caught or overtaken, taken by surprise.
ORIGIN: From pro and lambano; to take in advance, i.e. (literally) eat before others have an opportunity; (figuratively) to anticipate, surprise.

DEFINITION: to tell (say) beforehand, forewarn, declare, tell plainly.
ORIGIN: From pro and lego; to say beforehand, i.e. Predict, forewarn.

DEFINITION: to predict, testify or protest beforehand.
ORIGIN: From pro and marturomai; to be a witness in advance i.e. Predict.

DEFINITION: to meditate beforehand, prepare, get up, premeditate.
ORIGIN: From pro and meletao; to premeditate.

DEFINITION: to be anxious beforehand, ponder beforehand.
ORIGIN: From pro and merimnao; to care (anxiously) in advance.

DEFINITION: to take thought for beforehand, provide for, practice.
ORIGIN: From pro and noieo; to consider in advance, i.e. Look out for beforehand (actively, by way of maintenance for others; middle voice by way of circumspection for oneself).

DEFINITION: forethought, foresight, provision for, providence.
ORIGIN: From pronoeo; forethought, i.e. Provident care or supply.

DEFINITION: to see beforehand, foresee, see previously, be mindful of; mid: to pay regard to, set before me.
ORIGIN: From pro and horao; to behold in advance, i.e. (actively) to notice (another) previously, or (middle voice) to keep in (one's own) view.

DEFINITION: to foreordain, predetermine, mark out beforehand.
ORIGIN: From pro and horizo; to limit in advance, i.e. (figuratively) predetermine.

DEFINITION: to suffer previously.
ORIGIN: From pro and pascho; to undergo hardship previously.

DEFINITION: to send forward, accompany, equip for a journey.
ORIGIN: From pro and pempo; to send forward, i.e. Escort or aid in travel.
USAGE: accompany, bring (forward) on journey (way), conduct forth.

DEFINITION: falling forward, headlong.
ORIGIN: From a compound of pro and pipto; falling forward, i.e. Headlong (figuratively, precipitate).

DEFINITION: to make to go before, to cause to go before.
ORIGIN: From pro and poreuomai; to precede (as guide or herald).

DEFINITION: advantageous for, at (denotes local proximity), toward (denotes motion toward a place).
ORIGIN: A strengthened form of pro; a preposition of direction; forward to, i.e. Toward (with the genitive case, the side of, i.e. Pertaining to; with the dative case, by the side of, i.e. Near to; usually with the accusative case, the place, time, occasion, or respect, which is the destination of the relation, i.e. Whither or for which it is predicated).
USAGE: about, according to, against, among, at, because of, before, between, (where-)by, for, X at thy house, in, for intent, nigh unto, of, which pertain to, that, to (the end that), X together, to (you) -ward, unto, with(-in). In the comparative case, it denotes essentially the same applications, namely, motion towards, accession to, or nearness at.

DEFINITION: the day before the Sabbath.
ORIGIN: From pro and sabbaton; a fore-sabbath, i.e. The Sabbath-eve.
USAGE: day before the sabbath. Compare paraskeue.

DEFINITION: to address by name, designate, accost.
ORIGIN: From pros and a derivative of agora (mean to harangue); to address, i.e. Salute by name.

DEFINITION: to bring to, bring near; to come to or towards, approach.
ORIGIN: From pros and ago; to lead towards, i.e. (transitively) to conduct near (summon, present), or (intransitively) to approach.

DEFINITION: approach, access, admission.
ORIGIN: From prosago (compare agoge); admission.

DEFINITION: to beg, ask earnestly, ask for in addition.
ORIGIN: From pros and aiteo; to ask repeatedly (importune), i.e. Solicit.

DEFINITION: to go up to, come up to, go up further.
ORIGIN: From pros and anabaino; to ascend farther, i.e. Be promoted (take an upper (more honorable) seat).

DEFINITION: to spend in addition.
ORIGIN: From pros and analisko; to expend further.

DEFINITION: to fill up by adding to, supply.
ORIGIN: From pros and anapleroo; to fill up further, i.e. Furnish fully.

DEFINITION: to lay on besides, to undertake besides (mid.).
ORIGIN: From pros and anatithemai; to lay up in addition, i.e. (middle voice and figuratively) to impart or (by implication) to consult.

DEFINITION: to utter additional threats.
ORIGIN: From pros and apeileo; to menace additionally.

DEFINITION: to spend in addition.
ORIGIN: From pros and dapanao; to expend additionally.

DEFINITION: to want more, need in addition.
ORIGIN: From pros and deomai; to require additionally, i.e. Want further.

DEFINITION: (a) to await, expect, (b) to receive, welcome (originally: to house), (c) to accept.
ORIGIN: From pros and dechomai; to admit (to intercourse, hospitality, credence, or (figuratively) endurance); by implication, to await (with confidence or patience).

DEFINITION: to expect, wait for, await, think, anticipate.
ORIGIN: From pros and dokeuo (to watch); to anticipate (in thought, hope or fear); by implication, to await.
USAGE: (be in) expect(-ation), look (for), when looked, tarry, wait for.

DEFINITION: expectation, waiting.
ORIGIN: From prosdokao; apprehension (of evil); by implication, infliction anticipated.

DEFINITION: to permit one to approach, permit further.
ORIGIN: From pros and eao; to permit further progress.

DEFINITION: to approach, come near to.
ORIGIN: From pros and eggizo; to approach near.

DEFINITION: to wait upon, minister to, have charge of.
ORIGIN: From a compound of pros and the base of hedraios; to sit near, i.e. Attend as a servant.

DEFINITION: to work besides, to gain besides.
ORIGIN: From pros and ergazomai; to work additionally, i.e. (by implication) acquire besides.

DEFINITION: to come up to, come to, come near (to), approach, consent (to).
ORIGIN: From pros and erchomai (including its alternate); to approach, i.e. (literally) come near, visit, or (figuratively) worship, assent to.
USAGE: (as soon as he) come (unto), come thereunto, consent, draw near, go (near, to, unto).

DEFINITION: (a) prayer (to God), (b) a place for prayer (used by Jews, perhaps where there was no synagogue).
ORIGIN: From proseuchomai; prayer (worship); by implication, an oratory (chapel).

DEFINITION: to pray, pray for, offer prayer.
ORIGIN: From pros and euchomai; to pray to God, i.e. Supplicate, worship.

DEFINITION: (a) to attend to, pay attention to, (b) to beware, be cautious, (c) to join, devote myself to.
ORIGIN: From pros and echo; (figuratively) to hold the mind (nous implied) towards, i.e. Pay attention to, be cautious about, apply oneself to, adhere to.
USAGE: (give) attend(-ance, -ance at, -ance to, unto), beware, be given to, give (take) heed (to unto); have regard.

DEFINITION: to fasten with nails, nail to.
ORIGIN: From pros and a derivative of helos; to peg to, i.e. Spike fast.

DEFINITION: (lit: that has come to), a proselyte, that is a non-Jew, who has been circumcised and has adopted the Jews' religion.
ORIGIN: From the alternate of proserchomai; an arriver from a foreign region, i.e. (specially), an acceder (convert) to Judaism ("proselyte").

DEFINITION: for a season, temporary.
ORIGIN: From pros and kairos; for the occasion only, i.e. Temporary.
USAGE: dur-(eth) for awhile, endure for a time, for a season, temporal.

DEFINITION: to call to myself, summon.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from pros and kaleo; to call toward oneself, i.e. Summon, invite.

DEFINITION: to persist, persevere in, continue steadfast in; to wait upon.
ORIGIN: From pros and kartereo; to be earnest towards, i.e. (to a thing) to persevere, be constantly diligent, or (in a place) to attend assiduously all the exercises, or (to a person) to adhere closely to (as a servitor).
USAGE: attend (give self) continually (upon), continue (in, instant in, with), wait on (continually).

DEFINITION: steadfastness.
ORIGIN: From proskartereo; persistancy.

DEFINITION: a pillow or cushion.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed compound of pros and kephale; something for the head, i.e. A cushion.

DEFINITION: to assign by lot, allot, associate with, follow as a disciple.
ORIGIN: From pros and kleroo; to give a common lot to, i.e. (figuratively) to associate with.

DEFINITION: partiality, an inclination towards.
ORIGIN: From a compound of pros and klino; a leaning towards, i.e. (figuratively) proclivity (favoritism).

DEFINITION: (lit: to glue one thing to another), to join (unite) closely, cleave (to), follow as an adherent.
ORIGIN: From pros and kollao; to glue to, i.e. (figuratively) to adhere.

DEFINITION: a stumbling-block, an occasion for falling, a moral embarrassment.
ORIGIN: From proskopto; a stub, i.e. (figuratively) occasion of apostasy.

DEFINITION: a cause of stumbling, offense, shock.
ORIGIN: From proskopto; a stumbling, i.e. (figuratively and concretely) occasion of sin.

DEFINITION: to stumble, strike the foot against, beat upon, take offense at.
ORIGIN: From pros and kopto; to strike at, i.e. Surge against (as water); specially, to stub on, i.e. Trip up (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to roll to, roll up against.
ORIGIN: From pros and kulioo; to roll towards, i.e. Block against.

DEFINITION: to go down on knees to, do obeisance to, worship.
ORIGIN: From pros and a probable derivative of kuon (meaning to kiss, like a dog licking his master's hand); to fawn or crouch to, i.e. (literally or figuratively) prostrate oneself in homage (do reverence to, adore).

DEFINITION: a worshipper.
ORIGIN: From proskuneo; an adorer.

DEFINITION: to speak to, converse with.
ORIGIN: From pros and laleo; to talk to, i.e. Converse with.

DEFINITION: (a) to take to myself, (b) to take aside, (c) to welcome.
ORIGIN: From pros and lambano; to take to oneself, i.e. Use (food), lead (aside), admit (to friendship or hospitality).

DEFINITION: a receiving, a taking to one's self, acceptance.
ORIGIN: From proslambano; admission.

DEFINITION: to remain; to abide in, remain in, persist in, adhere to.
ORIGIN: From pros and meno; to stay further, i.e. Remain in a place, with a person; figuratively, to adhere to, persevere in.
USAGE: abide still, be with, cleave unto, continue in (with).

DEFINITION: to bring (a ship) to anchor at.
ORIGIN: From pros and a derivative of the same as horme (meaning to tie (anchor) or lull); to moor to, i.e. (by implication) land at.

DEFINITION: to owe besides (in addition).
ORIGIN: From pros and opheilo; to be indebted additionally.

DEFINITION: to be displeased or offended with.
ORIGIN: From pros and a form of ochtheo (to be vexed with something irksome); to feel indignant at.

DEFINITION: very hungry.
ORIGIN: From pros and the same as peinao; hungering further, i.e. Intensely hungry.

DEFINITION: to fasten to, applied to Christ's being fastened to the cross.
ORIGIN: From pros and pegnumi; to fasten to, i.e. (specially), to impale (on a cross).

DEFINITION: (a) to fall down before, (b) to beat against, rush violently upon.
ORIGIN: From pros and pipto; to fall towards, i.e. (gently) prostrate oneself (in supplication or homage), or (violently) to rush upon (in storm).

DEFINITION: to attach to, take to oneself, to pretend.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from pros and poieo; to do forward for oneself, i.e. Pretend (as if about to do a thing).

DEFINITION: to come to, approach.
ORIGIN: From pros and poreuomai; to journey towards, i.e. Approach (not the same as proporeuomai).

DEFINITION: to dash against, as waves.
ORIGIN: From pros and rhegnumi; to tear towards, i.e. Burst upon (as a tempest or flood).

DEFINITION: (a) to instruct, command, (b) to appoint, assign.
ORIGIN: From pros and tasso; to arrange towards, i.e. (figuratively) enjoin.

DEFINITION: a female guardian, protector, patroness.
ORIGIN: Feminine of a derivative of proistemi; a patroness, i.e. Assistant.

DEFINITION: to place (put) to, add; to do again.
ORIGIN: From pros and tithemi; to place additionally, i.e. Lay beside, annex, repeat.
USAGE: add, again, give more, increase, lay unto, proceed further, speak to any more.

DEFINITION: to run to.
ORIGIN: From pros and trecho (including its alternate); to run towards, i.e. Hasten to meet or join.

DEFINITION: anything eaten with bread, especially fish or meat.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of a compound of pros and phago; something eaten in addition to bread, i.e. A relish (specially, fish; compare opsarion).

DEFINITION: (originally: newly slaughtered, freshly killed), recent, new.
ORIGIN: From pro and a derivative of sphazo; previously (recently) slain (fresh), i.e. (figuratively) lately made.

DEFINITION: recently, lately, newly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from prosphatos; recently.

DEFINITION: (a) to bring to, (b) characteristically: to offer (of gifts, sacrifices, etc).
ORIGIN: From pros and phero (including its alternate); to bear towards, i.e. Lead to, tender (especially to God), treat.
USAGE: bring (to, unto), deal with, do, offer (unto, up), present unto, put to.

DEFINITION: pleasing, acceptable, grateful.
ORIGIN: From a presumed compound of pros and phileo; friendly towards, i.e. Acceptable.

DEFINITION: an offering, sacrifice.
ORIGIN: From prosphero; presentation; concretely, an oblation (bloodless) or sacrifice.

DEFINITION: to call to, summon; to call (out) to, address, give a speech to, harangue.
ORIGIN: From pros and phoneo; to sound towards, i.e. Address, exclaim, summon.

DEFINITION: a pouring upon, an effusion, a sprinkling.
ORIGIN: From a comparative of pros and cheo (to pour); a shedding forth, i.e. Affusion.

DEFINITION: to touch lightly.
ORIGIN: From pros and psauo (to touch); to impinge, i.e. Lay a finger on (in order to relieve).

DEFINITION: to favor specially, show partiality.
ORIGIN: From prosopoleptes; to favor an individual, i.e. Show partiality.

DEFINITION: an accepter of a face, a respecter of persons.
ORIGIN: From prosopon and lambano; an accepter of a face (individual), i.e. (specially), one exhibiting partiality.

DEFINITION: partiality, favoritism.
ORIGIN: From prosopoleptes; partiality, i.e. Favoritism.

DEFINITION: the face, countenance, surface.
ORIGIN: From pros and ops (the visage, from optanomai); the front (as being towards view), i.e. The countenance, aspect, appearance, surface; by implication, presence, person.
USAGE: (outward) appearance, X before, countenance, face, fashion, (men's) person, presence.

DEFINITION: appoint beforehand.
ORIGIN: From pro and tasso; to pre-arrange, i.e. Prescribe.

DEFINITION: to stretch out, tie up (for scourging), extend before.
ORIGIN: From pro and teino (to stretch); to protend, i.e. Tie prostrate (for scourging).

DEFINITION: formerly, before.
ORIGIN: Neuter of proteros as adverb (with or without the article); previously.

DEFINITION: former, before, formerly.
ORIGIN: Comparative of pro; prior or previous.

DEFINITION: to purpose, design beforehand, determine.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from pro and tithemi; to place before, i.e. (for oneself) to exhibit; (to oneself) to propose (determine).

DEFINITION: to encourage, exhort, persuade.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from pro and the base of trope; to turn forward for oneself, i.e. Encourage.

DEFINITION: to run before, outrun, run in advance.
ORIGIN: From pro and trecho (including its alternate); to run forward, i.e. Outstrip, precede.

DEFINITION: to have been already, have been previously.
ORIGIN: From pro and huparcho; to exist before, i.e. (adverbially) to be or do something previously.

DEFINITION: a pretext, an excuse.
ORIGIN: From a compound of pro and phaino; an outward showing, i.e. Pretext.

DEFINITION: to bring forth, produce.
ORIGIN: From pro and phero; to bear forward, i.e. Produce.

DEFINITION: prophecy, prophesying; the gift of communicating and enforcing revealed truth.
ORIGIN: From prophetes ("prophecy"); prediction (scriptural or other).

DEFINITION: to foretell, prophesy; to set forth matter of divine teaching by special faculty.
ORIGIN: From prophetes; to foretell events, divine, speak under inspiration, exercise the prophetic office.

DEFINITION: a prophet (an interpreter or forth-teller of the divine will).
ORIGIN: From a compound of pro and phemi; a foreteller ("prophet"); by analogy, an inspired speaker; by extension, a poet.

DEFINITION: prophetic, uttered by a prophet.
ORIGIN: From prophetes; pertaining to a foreteller ("prophetic").

DEFINITION: a prophetess.
ORIGIN: Feminine of prophetes; a female foreteller or an inspired woman.

DEFINITION: to anticipate, forestall.
ORIGIN: From pro and phthano; to get an earlier start of, i.e. Anticipate.

DEFINITION: to put into the hand, to take into one's hand, to determine.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from pro and a derivative of cheir; to handle for oneself in advance, i.e. (figuratively) to purpose.

DEFINITION: to choose or appoint beforehand.
ORIGIN: From pro and cheirotoneo; to elect in advance.

DEFINITION: Prochorus, one of the seven original deacons at Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: From pro and choros; before the dance; Prochorus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: the stern (of a ship).
ORIGIN: Feminine of prumnus (hindmost); the stern of a ship.

DEFINITION: early in the morning, at dawn.
ORIGIN: Adverb from pro; at dawn; by implication, the day-break watch.

DEFINITION: (early) morning.
ORIGIN: Feminine of a derivative of proi as noun; day-dawn.

DEFINITION: early rain, early crops.
ORIGIN: From proi; dawning, i.e. (by analogy) autumnal (showering, the first of the rainy season).

DEFINITION: belonging to the morning, early.
ORIGIN: From proi; pertaining to the dawn, i.e. Matutinal.

DEFINITION: the prow (of a ship).
ORIGIN: Feminine of a presumed derivative of pro as noun; the prow, i.e. Forward part of a vessel.

DEFINITION: to have preeminence, be chief, be first.
ORIGIN: From protos; to be first (in rank or influence).

DEFINITION: a chief (most honorable) seat.
ORIGIN: From protos and kathedra; a sitting first (in the front row), i.e. Preeminence in council.

DEFINITION: the chief place at a banquet or table.
ORIGIN: From protos and klisia; a reclining first (in the place of honor) at the dinner-bed, i.e. Preeminence at meals.

DEFINITION: first, in the first place, before, formerly.
ORIGIN: Neuter of protos as adverb (with or without ho); firstly (in time, place, order, or importance).
USAGE: before, at the beginning, chiefly (at, at the) first (of all).

DEFINITION: first, before, principal, most important.
ORIGIN: Contracted superlative of pro; foremost (in time, place, order or importance).
USAGE: before, beginning, best, chief(-est), first (of all), former.

DEFINITION: one who stands in the front rank, hence: a leader, ringleader, chief.
ORIGIN: From protos and histemi; one standing first in the ranks, i.e. A captain (champion).

DEFINITION: the birthright, the rights of the first-born.
ORIGIN: From prototokos; primogeniture (as a privilege).

DEFINITION: first-born, eldest.
ORIGIN: From protos and the alternate of tikto; first-born (usually as noun, literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to stumble, fall, sin, err, transgress.
ORIGIN: A form of pipto; to trip, i.e. (figuratively) to err, sin, fail (of salvation).

DEFINITION: the heel.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; the heel (figuratively).

DEFINITION: a little wing, (anything like a wing) a battlement.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of pterux; a winglet, i.e. (figuratively) extremity (top corner).

DEFINITION: a wing, pinion.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of petomai (meaning a feather); a wing.

DEFINITION: winged; subst: a bird, fowl.
ORIGIN: Contraction for peteinon; a bird.

DEFINITION: to terrify, scare, strike with panic.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to the alternate of pipto (through the idea of causing to fall) or to petomai (through that of causing to fly away); to scare.

DEFINITION: a fluttering, excitement, terror.
ORIGIN: From ptoeo; alarm.

DEFINITION: Ptolemais, a coast city of Phoenicia, midway between Tyre and Caesarea.
ORIGIN: From Ptolemaios (Ptolemy, after whom it was named); Ptolemais, a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: a simple wooden pitchfork; a winnowing-shovel or fan.
ORIGIN: From ptuo; a winnowing-fork (as scattering like spittle).

DEFINITION: to frighten, terrify.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of ptuo (and thus akin to ptoeo); to frighten.

DEFINITION: spittle, saliva.
ORIGIN: From ptuo; saliva.

DEFINITION: to fold, roll up (as a scroll).
ORIGIN: Probably akin to petannumi (to spread; and thus apparently allied to petomai through the idea of expansion, and to ptuo through that of flattening; compare pateo); to fold, i.e. Furl a scroll.

DEFINITION: to spit.
ORIGIN: A primary verb (compare ptusso); to spit.

DEFINITION: a fall; a carcass, corpse, dead body.
ORIGIN: From the alternate of pipto; a ruin, i.e. (specially), lifeless body (corpse, carrion).

DEFINITION: a falling, a fall, ruin.
ORIGIN: From the alternate of pipto; a crash, i.e. Downfall (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: beggary, poverty, destitution.
ORIGIN: From ptocheuo; beggary, i.e. Indigence (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to be in poverty, be a beggar.
ORIGIN: From ptochos; to be a beggar, i.e. (by implication) to become indigent (figuratively).

DEFINITION: poor, destitute, spiritually poor, either in a good sense (humble devout persons) or bad.
ORIGIN: From ptosso (to crouch); akin to ptoeo and the alternate of pipto); a beggar (as cringing), i.e. Pauper (strictly denoting absolute or public mendicancy, although also used in a qualified or relative sense; whereas penes properly means only straitened circumstances in private), literally (often as noun) or figuratively (distressed).

DEFINITION: the fist.
ORIGIN: From a primary pux (the fist as a weapon); the clenched hand, i.e. (only in dative case as adverb) with the fist (hard scrubbing).

DEFINITION: a divining spirit, Python, called after the Pythian serpent said to have guarded the oracle at Delphi and been slain by Apollo.
ORIGIN: From Putho (the name of the region where Delphi, the seat of the famous oracle, was located); a Python, i.e. (by analogy, with the supposed diviner there) inspiration (soothsaying).

DEFINITION: frequent, often, much.
ORIGIN: From the same as skenopoios; clasped (thick), i.e. (figuratively) frequent; neuter plural (as adverb) frequently.

DEFINITION: to box, be a boxer.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of the same as pugme; to box (with the fist), i.e. Contend (as a boxer) at the games (figuratively).

DEFINITION: a gate.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a gate, i.e. The leaf or wing of a folding entrance (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a large gate; a gateway, porch, vestibule.
ORIGIN: From pule; a gate-way, door-way of a building or city; by implication, a portal or vestibule.

DEFINITION: to ask, inquire, ascertain by inquiry, understand.
ORIGIN: Middle voice prolonged from a primary putho (which occurs only as an alternate in certain tenses); to question, i.e. Ascertain by inquiry (as a matter of information merely; and thus differing from erotao, which properly means a request as a favor; and from aiteo, which is strictly a demand for something due; as well as from zeteo, which implies a search for something hidden; and from deomai, which involves the idea of urgent need); by implication, to learn (by casual intelligence).

DEFINITION: fire; the heat of the sun, lightning; fig: strife, trials; the eternal fire.
ORIGIN: A primary word; "fire" (literally or figuratively, specially, lightning).

DEFINITION: a fire, pile of burning fuel.
ORIGIN: From pur; a fire (concretely).

DEFINITION: a tower, fortified structure.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word ("burgh"); a tower or castle.

DEFINITION: to be on fire, to be ill of a fever.
ORIGIN: From pura; to be on fire, i.e. (specially), to have a fever.

DEFINITION: a fever, scorching heat.
ORIGIN: From puresso; inflamed, i.e. (by implication) feverish (as noun, fever).

DEFINITION: fiery, glittering.
ORIGIN: From pura; fiery, i.e. (by implication) flaming.

DEFINITION: pass: to burn, be set on fire, be inflamed; glow with heat, be purified by fire.
ORIGIN: From pur; to kindle, i.e. (passively) to be ignited, glow (literally), be refined (by implication), or (figuratively) to be inflamed (with anger, grief, lust).
USAGE: burn, fiery, be on fire, try.

DEFINITION: to be red, fire-colored.
ORIGIN: From purrhos; to redden (intransitively).

DEFINITION: red, fire-colored.
ORIGIN: From pur; fire-like, i.e. (specially), flame- colored.

DEFINITION: a burning, trial, fiery test.
ORIGIN: From puroo; ignition, i.e. (specially), smelting (figuratively, conflagration, calamity as a test).

DEFINITION: yet, even.
ORIGIN: Another form of the base of pos; an enclitic particle of indefiniteness; yet, even; used only in the comparative. See medepo, mepo, oudepo, oupo, popote..
USAGE: yet, even; used only in the comparative. See medepo, mepo, oudepo, oupo, popote.

DEFINITION: to exchange or barter, to sell.
ORIGIN: Probably ultimately from pelomai (to be busy, to trade); to barter (as a pedlar), i.e. To sell.

DEFINITION: a colt, young ass, foal.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a "foal" or "filly", i.e. (specially), a young ass.

DEFINITION: at any time, ever.
ORIGIN: From po and pote; at any time, i.e. (with negative particle) at no time.
USAGE: at any time, + never (...to any man), + yet, never man.

DEFINITION: to harden, render callous, petrify.
ORIGIN: Apparently from poros (a kind of stone); to petrify, i.e. (figuratively) to indurate (render stupid or callous).

DEFINITION: a covering with a callous, blindness.
ORIGIN: From poroo; stupidity or callousness.

DEFINITION: hardly, by any means, perhaps.
ORIGIN: Adverb from the base of pou; an enclitic particle of indefiniteness of manner; somehow or anyhow; used only in composition.
USAGE: haply, by any (some) means, perhaps. See ei pos, mepos. Compare pos.

DEFINITION: how, in what manner, by what means.
ORIGIN: Adverb from the base of pou; an interrogative particle of manner; in what way? (sometimes the question is indirect, how?); also as exclamation, how much!.
USAGE: how, after (by) what manner (means), that. (Occasionally unexpressed in English).

DEFINITION: Rahab, a Canaanitess, who rescued the Hebrew spies at Jericho.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Rachab); Raab (i.e. Rachab), a Canaanitess.

DEFINITION: Rabbi, master, teacher; a title of respect often applied to Christ.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (rab with pronominal suffix); my master, i.e Rabbi, as an official title of honor.

DEFINITION: Rabbi, master, teacher; a title of respect often applied to Christ.
ORIGIN: Or rhabbouni (hrab-boo-nee') of Chaldee origin; corresponding to rhabbi.

DEFINITION: to beat with rods, scourge.
ORIGIN: From rhabdos; to strike with a stick, i.e. Bastinado.

DEFINITION: a rod, staff, staff of authority, scepter.
ORIGIN: From the base of rhapizo; a stick or wand (as a cudgel, a cane or a baton of royalty).

DEFINITION: a rod holder, (a Roman) lictor (one holding the rod of office).
ORIGIN: From rhabdos and echo; a rod- (the Latin fasces) holder, i.e. A Roman lictor (constable or executioner).

DEFINITION: Ragau (or Reu), an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (r'uw); Ragau (i.e. Reu), a patriarch.

DEFINITION: a careless action, an act of villainy.
ORIGIN: From a comparative of rhaidios (easy, i.e. Reckless) and ergon; easy-going behavior, i.e. (by extension) a crime.

DEFINITION: ease in doing, laziness, recklessness, wickedness.
ORIGIN: From the same as rhaidiourgema; recklessness, i.e. (by extension) malignity.

DEFINITION: empty (an expression of contempt).
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (compare reyq); O empty one, i.e. Thou worthless (as a term of utter vilification).

DEFINITION: a piece of cloth, a remnant torn off.
ORIGIN: From rhegnumi; a "rag," i.e. Piece of cloth.

DEFINITION: Rama, a place in Ephraim, two hours north of Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Ramah); Rama (i.e. Ramah), a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: to sprinkle, cleanse ceremonially by sprinkling.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of rhaino (to sprinkle); to render besprinkled, i.e. Asperse (ceremonially or figuratively).

DEFINITION: sprinkling, purification.
ORIGIN: From rhantizo; aspersion (ceremonially or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to strike with a rod, to strike with the palm of the hand.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of a primary rhepo (to let fall, "rap"); to slap.
USAGE: smite (with the palm of the hand). Compare tupto.

DEFINITION: a blow (with a stick or the palm of the hand).
ORIGIN: From rhapizo; a slap.
USAGE: (+ strike with the) palm of the hand, smite with the hand.

DEFINITION: a needle.
ORIGIN: From a primary rhapto (to sew; perhaps rather akin to the base of rhapizo through the idea of puncturing); a needle.

DEFINITION: Rahab, a Canaanitess, who rescued the Hebrew spies at Jericho.
ORIGIN: From the same as Rhaab; Rachab, a Canaanitess.

DEFINITION: Rachel, younger wife of the patriarch Jacob.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Rachel); Rachel, the wife of Jacob.

DEFINITION: Rebecca, wife of the patriarch Isaac.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Ribqah); Rebecca (i.e. Ribkah), the wife of Isaac.

DEFINITION: a chariot.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; a rheda, i.e. Four-wheeled carriage (wagon for riding).

DEFINITION: Rephan, the Saturn of later mythology.
ORIGIN: By incorrect transliteration for a word of Hebrew origin (Kiyuwn); Remphan (i.e. Kijun), an Egyptian idol.

DEFINITION: to flow, overflow with.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; for some tenses of which a prolonged form rheuo (hryoo'-o) is used to flow ("run"; as water).

DEFINITION: command, make, say, speak of.
ORIGIN: For certain tenses of which a prolonged form ereo (er-eh'-o) is used; and both as alternate for epo; perhaps akin (or identical) with rheo (through the idea of pouring forth); to utter, i.e. Speak or say.
USAGE: command, make, say, speak (of). Compare lego.

DEFINITION: Rhegium, a city in the south-west corner of Italy opposite Sicily (modern Reggio).
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; Rhegium, a place in Italy.

DEFINITION: what is broken, a ruin.
ORIGIN: From rhegnumi; something torn, i.e. A fragment (by implication and abstractly, a fall).

DEFINITION: to rend, break asunder; to break forth (into speech); to throw or dash down.
ORIGIN: Or rhesso (hrace'-so) both prolonged forms of rheko (which appears only in certain forms, and is itself probably a strengthened form of agnumi (see in katagnumi)) to "break," "wreck" or "crack", i.e. (especially) to sunder (by separation of the parts; katagnumi being its intensive (with the preposition in composition), and thrauo a shattering to minute fragments; but not a reduction to the constituent particles, like luo) or disrupt, lacerate; by implication, to convulse (with spasms); figuratively, to give vent to joyful emotions.

DEFINITION: a thing spoken, (a) a word or saying of any kind, as command, report, promise, (b) a thing, matter, business.
ORIGIN: From rheo; an utterance (individually, collectively or specially); by implication, a matter or topic (especially of narration, command or dispute); with a negative naught whatever.

DEFINITION: Rhesa, an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Probably of Hebrew origin (apparently for Rphayah); Resa (i.e. Rephajah), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: an orator, public speaker, advocate.
ORIGIN: From rheo; a speaker, i.e. (by implication) a forensic advocate.

DEFINITION: expressly, explicitly, in so many words.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a derivative of rheo; out-spokenly, i.e. Distinctly.

DEFINITION: a root, shoot, source; that which comes from the root, a descendent.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a "root" (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to cause to take root; met: to plant, fix firmly, establish.
ORIGIN: From rhiza; to root (figuratively, become stable).

DEFINITION: a glance, twinkle or flash of the eye; a rush of wind or flame; any rapid movement.
ORIGIN: From rhipto; a jerk (of the eye, i.e. (by analogy) an instant).

DEFINITION: to fan, generally to make a breeze.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of rhipto (meaning a fan or bellows); to breeze up, i.e. (by analogy) to agitate (into waves).

DEFINITION: to throw off or away, cast, hurl.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of rhipto; to toss up.

DEFINITION: to throw, cast, toss, set down; pass: to be dispersed.
ORIGIN: A primary verb (perhaps rather akin to the base of rhapizo, through the idea of sudden motion); to fling (properly, with a quick toss, thus differing from ballo, which denotes a deliberate hurl; and from teino (see in ekteino), which indicates an extended projection); by qualification, to deposit (as if a load); by extension, to disperse.

DEFINITION: Rehoboam, son of Solomon, and King of Israel.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Rchab'am); Roboam (i.e. Rechobam), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Rhoda, a maidservant in the house of John Mark's mother at Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: Probably for rhode (a rose); Rode, a servant girl.

DEFINITION: Rhodes, an island in the Aegean sea, south-west of Asia Minor.
ORIGIN: Probably from rhodon (a rose); Rhodus, an island of the Mediterranean.

DEFINITION: with a great noise, with a rushing sound.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a derivative of rhoizos (a whir); whizzingly, i.e. With a crash.

DEFINITION: a sword, scimitar; fig: war, piercing grief.
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin; a sabre, i.e. A long and broad cutlass (any weapon of the kind, literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: Reuben, eldest son of the patriarch Jacob and founder of a tribe.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (r'uwben); Ruben (i.e. Reuben), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Ruth, a Moabitess and an ancestor of Christ.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Ruwth); Ruth, a Moabitess.

DEFINITION: Rufus, a Christian man in Rome, probably to be identified with the brother of Alexander and son of Simon of Cyrene.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; red; Rufus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: the rush (of a moving body), a (crowded) street.
ORIGIN: Prolongation from rhoumai in its original sense; an alley or avenue (as crowded).

DEFINITION: to rescue, deliver (from danger or destruction).
ORIGIN: Middle voice of an obsolete verb, akin to rheo (through the idea of a current; compare rhusis); to rush or draw (for oneself), i.e. Rescue.

DEFINITION: filth, pollution, defilement.
ORIGIN: From rhuparos; dirtiness (morally).

DEFINITION: filthy, defiled, dirty.
ORIGIN: From rhupos; dirty, i.e. (relatively) cheap or shabby; morally, wicked.

DEFINITION: filth, filthiness, dirt, squalor.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; dirt, i.e. (morally) depravity.

DEFINITION: to be filthy; hence (morally): to be stained with sin.
ORIGIN: From rhupos; to soil, i.e. (intransitively) to become dirty (morally).

DEFINITION: a flowing, an issue.
ORIGIN: From rhoumai in the sense of its congener rheo; a flux (of blood).

DEFINITION: a wrinkle; fig: a spiritual defect, flaw.
ORIGIN: From rhoumai; a fold (as drawing together), i.e. A wrinkle (especially on the face).

DEFINITION: Roman, Latin.
ORIGIN: From Rhomaios; Romaic, i.e. Latin.

DEFINITION: Roman; subst: a Roman citizen.
ORIGIN: From Rhome; Romaean, i.e. Roman (as noun).

DEFINITION: in the Latin language.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a presumed derivative of Rhome; Romaistically, i.e. In the Latin language.

DEFINITION: Rome, the capital of Italy and the Rom. Empire (named after Romulus, the legendary founder).
ORIGIN: From the base of rhonnumi; strength; Roma, the capital of Italy.

DEFINITION: to strengthen, render firm; imperative at the end of letters: farewell.
ORIGIN: Prolongation from rhoomai (to dart; probably akin to rhoumai); to strengthen, i.e. (impersonal passive) have health (as a parting exclamation, good-bye).

DEFINITION: thou hast forsaken me.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee or (shbaq with pronominal suffix); thou hast left me; sabachthani (i.e. Shebakthani), a cry of distress.

DEFINITION: Sabaoth, armies.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (tsaba' in feminine plural); armies; sabaoth (i.e. Tsebaoth), a military epithet of God.

DEFINITION: a keeping of the Sabbath, a Sabbath rest.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of sabbaton; a "sabbatism", i.e. (figuratively) the repose of Christianity (as a type of heaven).

DEFINITION: the Sabbath, the seventh day (of the week).
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (shabbath); the Sabbath (i.e. Shabbath), or day of weekly repose from secular avocations (also the observance or institution itself); by extension, a se'nnight, i.e. The interval between two Sabbaths; likewise the plural in all the above applications.

DEFINITION: a fishing-net.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of satto (to equip) meaning furniture, especially a pack-saddle (which in the East is merely a bag of netted rope); a "seine" for fishing.

DEFINITION: a Sadducee, a member of the aristocratic party among the Jews, from whom the high-priests were almost invariably chosen.
ORIGIN: Probably from Sadok; a Sadducaean (i.e. Tsadokian), or follower of a certain heretical Israelite.

DEFINITION: Zadok, an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Tsadowq); Sadoc (i.e. Tsadok), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: to fawn upon, flatter, beguile; pass: to be perturbed.
ORIGIN: Akin to seio; to wag (as a dog its tail fawningly), i.e. (generally) to shake (figuratively, disturb).

DEFINITION: sack-cloth, a sign of mourning.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (saq); "sack"-cloth, i.e. Mohair (the material or garments made of it, worn as a sign of grief).

DEFINITION: Shelah, an ancestor of Christ, also Salmon, an ancestor of Christ.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Shelach); Sala (i.e. Shelach), a patriarch.

DEFINITION: Salathiel, son of Jechoniah.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Sh'altiy'el); Salathiel (i.e. Shealtiel), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Salamis, a city at the eastern end of Cyprus.
ORIGIN: Probably from salos (from the surge on the shore); Salamis, a place in Cyprus.

DEFINITION: Salim, a place in Palestine.
ORIGIN: Probably from the same as saleuo; Salim, a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: to shake, excite, disturb in mind, stir up, drive away.
ORIGIN: From salos; to waver, i.e. Agitate, rock, topple or (by implication) destroy; figuratively, to disturb, incite.
USAGE: move, shake (together), which can(-not) be shaken, stir up.

DEFINITION: Salem, doubtless identical with Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Shalem); Salem (i.e. Shalem), a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: Salmon, son of Nahshon and father of Boaz.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Salmown); Salmon, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Salmone, a promontory on the east of Crete.
ORIGIN: Perhaps of similar origin to Salamis; Salmone, a place in Crete.

DEFINITION: the tossing of the sea in a tempest; agitation, rolling.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of saino; a vibration, i.e. (specially), billow.

DEFINITION: a trumpet, the sound of a trumpet.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from salos (through the idea of quavering or reverberation); a trumpet.

DEFINITION: to sound a trumpet.
ORIGIN: From salpigx; to trumpet, i.e. Sound a blast (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a trumpeter.
ORIGIN: From salpizo; a trumpeter.

DEFINITION: Salome, wife of Zebedee and mother of James and John, the apostles.
ORIGIN: Probably of Hebrew origin; Salome (i.e. Shelomah), an Israelitess.

DEFINITION: Samaria, a small district of Palestine, bounded by Galilee on the north, and by Judaea on the south, and taking its name from the city of Samaria, the ancient capital of the kingdom of (northern) Israel.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Shomrown); Samaria (i.e. Shomeron), a city and region of Palestine.

DEFINITION: a Samaritan, an inhabitant of the region of Samaria.
ORIGIN: From Samareia; a Samarite, i.e. Inhabitant of Samaria.

DEFINITION: (the region of) Samaria, a Samaritan woman.
ORIGIN: Feminine of Samareites; a Samaritess, i.e. Woman of Samaria.

DEFINITION: "Samos of Thrace", Samothrace, an island in the Aegean.
ORIGIN: From Samos and Thraike (Thrace); Samo-thrace (Samos of Thrace), an island in the Mediterranean.

DEFINITION: Samos, an island in the Aegean sea off the coast of Asia Minor, near Ephesus and Miletus.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; Samus, an island of the Mediterranean.

DEFINITION: Samuel, a prophet and judge in Isr.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Shmuw'el); Samuel (i.e. Shemuel), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: Samson, one of the Judges of Israel.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Shimshown); Sampson (i.e. Shimshon), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: a sandal.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of sandalon (a "sandal"; of uncertain origin); a slipper or sole-pad.

DEFINITION: a plank, board.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a plank.

DEFINITION: Saul, (a) the first king of Israel, (b) the Hebrew name of the Apostle to the Gentiles.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Sha'uwl); Saul (i.e. Shaul), the Jewish name of Paul.

DEFINITION: rotten, useless, corrupt, depraved.
ORIGIN: From sepo; rotten, i.e. Worthless (literally or morally).

DEFINITION: Sapphira, wife of Ananias, an early Christian.
ORIGIN: Feminine of sappheiros; Sapphire, an Israelitess.

DEFINITION: sapphire, perhaps lapis lazuli.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (cappiyr); a "sapphire" or lapis-lazuli gem.

DEFINITION: a basket, generally of twisted cords.
ORIGIN: Apparently of Hebrew origin (sarag); a basket (as interwoven or wicker-work.

DEFINITION: Sardis, an ancient city of Lydia in the province of Asia.
ORIGIN: Plural of uncertain derivation; Sardis, a place in Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: sardine.
ORIGIN: From the same as sardios; sardine (lithos being implied), i.e. A gem, so called.

DEFINITION: carnelian, a precious stone.
ORIGIN: Properly, an adjective from an uncertain base; sardian (lithos being implied), i.e. (as noun) the gem so called.

DEFINITION: sardonyx, a precious stone, white streaked with red.
ORIGIN: From the base of sardios and onux (the nail of a finger; hence the "onyx" stone); a "sardonyx", i.e. The gem so called.

DEFINITION: Zarephath, a town in the district of Sidon in Phoenicia.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Tsarphath); Sarepta (i.e. Tsarephath), a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: pertaining to the flesh, carnal.
ORIGIN: From sarx; pertaining to flesh, i.e. (by extension) bodily, temporal, or (by implication) animal, unregenerate.

DEFINITION: fleshly, consisting of flesh, carnal.
ORIGIN: From sarx; similar to flesh, i.e. (by analogy) soft.

DEFINITION: flesh, body, human nature, materiality; kindred.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of saroo; flesh (as stripped of the skin), i.e. (strictly) the meat of an animal (as food), or (by extension) the body (as opposed to the soul (or spirit), or as the symbol of what is external, or as the means of kindred), or (by implication) human nature (with its frailties (physically or morally) and passions), or (specially), a human being (as such).

DEFINITION: Serug, an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Sruwg); Saruch (i.e. Serug), a patriarch.

DEFINITION: to sweep, cleanse by sweeping.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of sairo (to brush off; akin to suro); meaning a broom; to sweep.

DEFINITION: Sarah, the wife of Abraham.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Sarah); Sarra (i.e. Sarah), the wife of Abraham.

DEFINITION: Sharon, the maritime plain between Carmel and Joppa.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Sharown); Saron (i.e. Sharon), a district of Palestine.

DEFINITION: Satan.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (satan); Satan, i.e. The devil.

DEFINITION: the adversary, Satan, the devil.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin corresponding to ma'bad (with the definite affix); the accuser, i.e. The devil.

DEFINITION: seah, a (Hebrew) measure (equiv. to about one and a half pecks).
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (c'ah); a certain measure for things dry.

DEFINITION: Saul, the Jewish name of the apostle Paul.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin, the same as Saoul; Saulus (i.e. Shaul), the Jewish name of Paul.

DEFINITION: (a) to extinguish, quench, (b) to suppress, thwart.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of an apparently primary verb; to extinguish (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: you.
ORIGIN: Accusative case singular of su; thee.

DEFINITION: of (to, for) yourself.
ORIGIN: Genitive case from se and autos, also dative case of the same, seautoi seh-ow-to', and accusative case seauton seh-ow-ton', likewise contracted sautou (sow-too'), sautoi (sow-to'), and sauton (sow-ton'), respectively of (with, to) thyself.

DEFINITION: to fear, to have reverential awe.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from a derivative of sebomai; to venerate, i.e. Adore.

DEFINITION: an object of worship or veneration.
ORIGIN: From sebazomai; something adored, i.e. An object of worship (god, altar, etc).

DEFINITION: (official Greek equivalent of Augustus), venerated, august, a title of the Roman emperors; hence secondarily: Augustan, imperial.
ORIGIN: From sebazomai; venerable (august), i.e. (as noun) a title of the Roman Emperor, or (as adjective) imperial.

DEFINITION: to reverence, worship, adore.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to revere, i.e. Adore.

DEFINITION: a chain.
ORIGIN: Probably from suro through its congener eiro (to fasten; akin to haireomai); a chain (as binding or drawing).

DEFINITION: a shaking (as an earthquake); a storm.
ORIGIN: From seio; a commotion, i.e. (of the air) a gale, (of the ground) an earthquake.

DEFINITION: to shake; fig: to agitate, stir up.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to rock (vibrate, properly, sideways or to and fro), i.e. (generally) to agitate (in any direction; cause to tremble); figuratively, to throw into a tremor (of fear or concern).

DEFINITION: "second", Secundus, a Christian of Thessalonica.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; "second"; Secundus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: Seleucia, on the Syrian coast, the harbor of Syrian Antioch.
ORIGIN: From Seleukos (Seleucus, a Syrian king); Seleuceia, a place in Syria.

DEFINITION: the moon.
ORIGIN: From selas (brilliancy; probably akin to the alternate of haireomai, through the idea of attractiveness); the moon.

DEFINITION: to be moonstruck, be epileptic (supposedly influenced by the moon).
ORIGIN: Middle voice or passive from a presumed derivative of selene; to be moon-struck, i.e. Crazy.

DEFINITION: Semein, an ancestor of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Shim'iy); Semei (i.e. Shimi), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: the finest wheaten flour.
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin; fine wheaten flour.

DEFINITION: venerable, honorable, grave, serious, dignified.
ORIGIN: From sebomai; venerable, i.e. Honorable.

DEFINITION: dignity, honor, gravity, seriousness.
ORIGIN: From semnos; venerableness, i.e. Probity.

DEFINITION: Sergius, the middle (gentile) name of the proconsul of Cyprus.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; Sergius, a Roman.

DEFINITION: Seth, third son of Adam.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Sheth); Seth (i.e. Sheth), a patriarch.

DEFINITION: Shem, a son of Noah.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Shem); Sem (i.e. Shem), a patriarch.

DEFINITION: to signify, indicate, give a sign, make known.
ORIGIN: From sema (a mark; of uncertain derivation); to indicate.

DEFINITION: a sign, miracle, indication, mark, token.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of the base of semaino; an indication, especially ceremonially or supernaturally.

DEFINITION: to note, mark for myself.
ORIGIN: From semeion; to distinguish, i.e. Mark (for avoidance).

DEFINITION: today, now.
ORIGIN: Neuter (as adverb) of a presumed compound of the article ho (t changed to s) and hemera; on the (i.e. This) day (or night current or just passed); generally, now (i.e. At present, hitherto).

DEFINITION: to make corrupt, pass. become corrupt.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to putrefy, i.e. (figuratively) perish.

DEFINITION: silken, silk.
ORIGIN: From Ser (an Indian tribe from whom silk was procured; hence the name of the silk-worm); Seric, i.e. Silken (neuter as noun, a silky fabric).

DEFINITION: a moth.
ORIGIN: Apparently of Hebrew origin (cac); a moth.

DEFINITION: moth-eaten.
ORIGIN: From ses and a derivative of bibrosko; moth-eaten.

DEFINITION: to strengthen.
ORIGIN: From sthenos (bodily vigor; probably akin to the base of histemi); to strengthen, i.e. (figuratively) confirm (in spiritual knowledge and power).

DEFINITION: a jawbone, by implication cheek.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; the jaw-bone, i.e. (by implication) the cheek or side of the face.

DEFINITION: intrans: to be silent, keep silence; trans: to keep secret; pass: to be kept secret.
ORIGIN: From sige; to keep silent (transitively or intransitively).

DEFINITION: silence.
ORIGIN: Apparently from sizo (to hiss, i.e. Hist or hush); silence.

DEFINITION: made of iron.
ORIGIN: From sideros; made of iron.

DEFINITION: of iron.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; iron.

DEFINITION: Sidon, a great coast city of Phoenicia.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Tsiydown); Sidon (i.e. Tsidon), a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: Sidonian, inhabitant of Sidon.
ORIGIN: From Sidon; a Sidonian, i.e. Inhabitant of Sidon.

DEFINITION: an assassin, murderer, bandit; one of the Sicarii.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; a dagger-man or assassin; a freebooter (Jewish fanatic outlawed by the Romans).

DEFINITION: intoxicating drink.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (shekar); an intoxicant, i.e. Intensely fermented liquor.

DEFINITION: Silas, a pet-form of the name Silvanus; a Roman citizen and a helper of Paul.
ORIGIN: Contraction for Silouanos; Silas, a Christian.

DEFINITION: "sylvan", Silvanus, alt. form of the name Silas.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; "silvan"; Silvanus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: Siloam, a spring within the walls, in the south-east corner of Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Shiloach); Siloam (i.e. Shiloach), a pool of Jerusalem.

DEFINITION: an apron worn by artisans.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; a semicinctium or half-girding, i.e. Narrow covering (apron).

DEFINITION: Simon, the name of several Israelites.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Shim'own); Simon (i.e. Shimon), the name of nine Israelites.

DEFINITION: Sinai, a mountain probably on the Sinai Peninsula.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Ciynay); Sina (i.e. Sinai), a mountain in Arabia.

DEFINITION: mustard (probably the shrub, not the herb).
ORIGIN: Perhaps from sinomai (to hurt, i.e. Sting); mustard (the plant).

DEFINITION: fine linen, a linen cloth.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain (perhaps foreign) origin; byssos, i.e. Bleached linen (the cloth or a garment of it).

DEFINITION: to sift, prove by trials, winnow.
ORIGIN: From sinion (a sieve); to riddle (figuratively).

DEFINITION: a pit (for grain storage).
ORIGIN: From a derivative of sitos; grain-fed, i.e. Fattened.

DEFINITION: fattened; subst: a fatling, cattle.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of sitos; grained, i.e. Fatted.

DEFINITION: a measured portion of grain or food.
ORIGIN: From sitos and metron; a grain-measure, i.e. (by implication) ration (allowance of food).

DEFINITION: wheat, grain.
ORIGIN: Also plural irregular neuter sita (see'-tah) of uncertain derivation; grain, especially wheat.

DEFINITION: Zion, a mountain of Jerusalem or the city of Jer.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Tsiyown); Sion (i.e. Tsijon), a hill of Jerusalem; figuratively, the Church (militant or triumphant).

DEFINITION: to keep silence, be silent, either voluntarily or involuntarily.
ORIGIN: From siope (silence, i.e. A hush; properly, muteness, i.e. Involuntary stillness, or inability to speak; and thus differing from sige, which is rather a voluntary refusal or indisposition to speak, although the terms are often used synonymously); to be dumb (but not deaf also, like kophos properly); figuratively, to be calm (as quiet water).

DEFINITION: to cause to stumble, cause to sin, cause to become indignant, shock, offend.
ORIGIN: From skandalon; to entrap, i.e. Trip up (figuratively, stumble (transitively) or entice to sin, apostasy or displeasure).

DEFINITION: a stick for bait (of a trap), generally a snare, a stumbling block, an offense.
ORIGIN: Scandal; probably from a derivative of kampto; a trap-stick (bent sapling), i.e. Snare (figuratively, cause of displeasure or sin).
USAGE: occasion to fall (of stumbling), offence, thing that offends, stumblingblock.

DEFINITION: to dig, excavate.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to dig.

DEFINITION: anything scooped out, a light boat.
ORIGIN: A "skiff" (as if dug out), or yawl (carried aboard a large vessel for landing).

DEFINITION: the leg (from the hip downwards).
ORIGIN: Apparently from skello (to parch; through the idea of leanness); the leg (as lank).

DEFINITION: clothing, a covering, raiment.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of skepas (a covering; perhaps akin to the base of skopos through the idea of noticeableness); clothing.

DEFINITION: Sceva, an inhabitant of Ephesus.
ORIGIN: Apparently of Latin origin; left-handed; Scevas (i.e. Scoevus), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: tackle, fittings, equipment.
ORIGIN: From skeuos; furniture, i.e. Spare tackle.

DEFINITION: a vessel to contain liquid; a vessel of mercy or wrath; any instrument by which anything is done; a household utensil; of ships: tackle.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a vessel, implement, equipment or apparatus (literally or figuratively (specially, a wife as contributing to the usefulness of the husband)).

DEFINITION: a tent, booth, tabernacle, abode, dwelling, mansion, habitation.
ORIGIN: Apparently akin to skeuos and skia; a tent or cloth hut (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: the feast of tabernacles, the great festival of the Jews, held in October.
ORIGIN: From skenos and pegnumi; the Festival of Tabernacles (so called from the custom of erecting booths for temporary homes).

DEFINITION: making tents.
ORIGIN: From skene and poieo; a manufacturer of tents.

DEFINITION: a tent, tabernacle; fig: of the human body.
ORIGIN: From skene; a hut or temporary residence, i.e. (figuratively) the human body (as the abode of the spirit).

DEFINITION: to dwell as in a tent, encamp, have tabernacle.
ORIGIN: From skenos; to tent or encamp, i.e. (figuratively) to occupy (as a mansion) or (specially), to reside (as God did in the Tabernacle of old, a symbol of protection and communion).

DEFINITION: a tent pitched, a dwelling, tabernacle.
ORIGIN: From skenoo; an encampment, i.e. (figuratively) the Temple (as God's residence), the body (as a tenement for the soul).

DEFINITION: a shadow, shade, thick darkness, an outline.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; "shade" or a shadow (literally or figuratively (darkness of error or an adumbration)).

DEFINITION: to leap (for joy), skip, bound.
ORIGIN: Akin to skairo (to skip); to jump, i.e. Sympathetically move (as the quickening of a fetus).

DEFINITION: hardness of heart, perverseness, obstinacy.
ORIGIN: Feminine of a compound of skleros and kardia; hard-heartedness, i.e. (specially), destitution of (spiritual) perception.

DEFINITION: hard, violent, harsh, stern.
ORIGIN: From the base of skelos; dry, i.e. Hard or tough (figuratively, harsh, severe).

DEFINITION: hardness, hardness of heart, obstinacy, perverseness.
ORIGIN: From skleros; callousness, i.e. (figuratively) stubbornness.

DEFINITION: stiff-necked, stubborn, obstinate.
ORIGIN: From skleros and trachelos; hardnaped, i.e. (figuratively) obstinate.

DEFINITION: to harden, make hard, make stubborn.
ORIGIN: From skleros; to indurate, i.e. (figuratively) render stubborn.

DEFINITION: crooked, perverse, unfair, curved, tortuous.
ORIGIN: From the base of skelos; warped, i.e. Winding; figuratively, perverse.

DEFINITION: a stake or thorn; fig: a sharp affliction.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from the base of skelos and optanomai; withered at the front, i.e. A point or prickle (figuratively, a bodily annoyance or disability).

DEFINITION: to look at, regard attentively, take heed, beware, consider.
ORIGIN: From skopos; to take aim at (spy), i.e. (figuratively) regard.
USAGE: consider, take heed, look at (on), mark. Compare optanomai.

DEFINITION: a watchman, a mark (on which to fix the eye).
ORIGIN: From skeptomai (to peer about ("skeptic"); perhaps akin to skapto through the idea of concealment; compare skepasma); a watch (sentry or scout), i.e. (by implication) a goal.

DEFINITION: to disperse, scatter abroad (as of sheep); to dissipate, waste; to distribute alms.
ORIGIN: Apparently from the same as skorpios (through the idea of penetrating); to dissipate, i.e. (figuratively) put to flight, waste, be liberal.

DEFINITION: a scorpion.
ORIGIN: Probably from an obsolete skerpo (perhaps strengthened from the base of skopos and meaning to pierce); a "scorpion" (from its sting).

DEFINITION: full of darkness, dark.
ORIGIN: From skotos; opaque, i.e. (figuratively) benighted.

DEFINITION: darkness; fig: spiritual darkness.
ORIGIN: From skotos; dimness, obscurity (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to darken.
ORIGIN: From skotos; to obscure (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: darkness, either physical or moral.
ORIGIN: From the base of skia; shadiness, i.e. Obscurity (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: (lit. or met.) to darken.
ORIGIN: From skotos; to obscure or blind (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: refuse, dregs, dung.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of eis and kuon and ballo; what is thrown to the dogs, i.e. Refuse (ordure).

DEFINITION: a Scythian, an inhabitant of Scythia (considered the wildest of barbarians).
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin; a Scythene or Scythian, i.e. (by implication) a savage.

DEFINITION: gloomy, sad-countenanced.
ORIGIN: From skuthros (sullen) and a derivative of optanomai; angry-visaged, i.e. Gloomy or affecting a mournful appearance.

DEFINITION: to flay, trouble, annoy, vex.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to flay, i.e. (figuratively) to harass.

DEFINITION: arms stripped from a foe, spoils.
ORIGIN: Neuter from skullo; something stripped (as a hide), i.e. Booty.

DEFINITION: eaten by worms.
ORIGIN: From skolex and a derivative of bibrosko; worm-eaten, i.e. Diseased with maggots.

DEFINITION: a gnawing worm; gnawing anguish.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a grub, maggot or earth-worm.

DEFINITION: made of emerald, emerald-green.
ORIGIN: From smaragdos; consisting of emerald.

DEFINITION: an emerald.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; the emerald or green gem so called.

DEFINITION: myrrh (used as an ointment and for embalming).
ORIGIN: Apparently strengthened for muron; myrrh.

DEFINITION: Smyrna, a great port of the Roman province Asia.
ORIGIN: The same as smurna; Smyrna, a place in Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: of Smyrna.
ORIGIN: From Smurna; a Smyrnoean.

DEFINITION: to be like myrrh, to mingle with myrrh.
ORIGIN: From Smurna; to tincture with myrrh, i.e. Embitter (as a narcotic).

DEFINITION: Sodom, an unidentified city in the Jordan Valley.
ORIGIN: Plural of Hebrew origin (Cdom); Sodoma (i.e. Sedom), a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: you.
ORIGIN: Dative case of su; to thee.

DEFINITION: Solomon, son of David King of Israel, and Bathsheba.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Shlomoh); Solomon (i.e. Shelomoh), the son of David.

DEFINITION: a cinerary urn, by anal. a coffin.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to the base of soreuo; a funereal receptacle (urn, coffin), i.e. (by analogy) a bier.

DEFINITION: yours, thy, thine.
ORIGIN: From su; thine.

DEFINITION: you.
ORIGIN: Genitive case of su; of thee, thy.
USAGE: X home, thee, thine (own), thou, thy.

DEFINITION: a handkerchief, a head cloth (for the dead).
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; a sudarium (sweat-cloth), i.e. Towel (for wiping the perspiration from the face, or binding the face of a corpse).

DEFINITION: "lily", Susanna, one of the women accompanying Jesus on His journeys.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (shuwshan feminine); lily; Susannah (i.e. Shoshannah), an Israelitess.

DEFINITION: wisdom, insight, skill (human or divine), intelligence.
ORIGIN: From sophos; wisdom (higher or lower, worldly or spiritual).

DEFINITION: to make wise, instruct; pass: to be skillfully devised.
ORIGIN: From sophos; to render wise; in a sinister acceptation, to form "sophisms", i.e. Continue plausible error.

DEFINITION: wise, learned, cultivated, skilled, clever.
ORIGIN: Akin to saphes (clear); wise (in a most general application).

DEFINITION: Spain, roughly co-extensive with the modern country of the name.
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin; Spania, a region of Europe.

DEFINITION: to convulse, throw into spasms.
ORIGIN: Prolongation from spairo (to grasp; apparently strengthened from spao through the idea of spasmodic contraction); to mangle, i.e. Convluse with epilepsy.

DEFINITION: to swathe, wrap in swaddling clothes.
ORIGIN: From sparganon (a strip; from a derivative of the base of sparasso meaning to strap or wrap with strips); to swathe (an infant after the Oriental custom).

DEFINITION: to live extravagantly, luxuriously; to be wanton.
ORIGIN: From spatale (luxury); to be voluptuous.

DEFINITION: to draw (as a sword), pull.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to draw.

DEFINITION: anything wound up or coiled, a body (of soldiers), a cohort.
ORIGIN: Of immediate Latin origin, but ultimately a derivative of haireomai in the sense of its cognate heilisso; a coil (spira, "spire"), i.e. (figuratively) a mass of men (a Roman military cohort; also (by analogy) a squad of Levitical janitors).

DEFINITION: to sow, spread, scatter.
ORIGIN: Probably strengthened from spao (through the idea of extending); to scatter, i.e. Sow (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a body-guardsman; an executioner.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; a speculator, i.e. Military scout (spy or (by extension) life-guardsman).

DEFINITION: to pour out (as a drink offering), to make a libation.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to pour out as a libation, i.e. (figuratively) to devote (one's life or blood, as a sacrifice) ("spend").

DEFINITION: (a) seed, commonly of cereals, (b) offspring, descendents.
ORIGIN: From speiro; something sown, i.e. Seed (including the male "sperm"); by implication, offspring; specially, a remnant (figuratively, as if kept over for planting).

DEFINITION: a babbler, gossiper, one who picks up seeds and trifles as does a bird.
ORIGIN: From sperma and lego; a seed-picker (as the crow), i.e. (figuratively) a sponger, loafer (specially, a gossip or trifler in talk).

DEFINITION: to hasten, urge on, desire earnestly.
ORIGIN: Probably strengthened from pous; to "speed" ("study"), i.e. Urge on (diligently or earnestly); by implication, to await eagerly.

DEFINITION: a cave, den, hideout.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of speos (a grotto); a cavern; by implication, a hiding-place or resort.

DEFINITION: a ledge of rock (over which the sea dashes), a reef.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a ledge or reef of rock in the sea.

DEFINITION: to defile, spot, stain, soil.
ORIGIN: From spilos; to stain or soil (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a spot, fault, stain, blemish.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a stain or blemish, i.e. (figuratively) defect, disgrace.

DEFINITION: to be moved in the inward parts, to feel compassion.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from splagchnon; to have the bowels yearn, i.e. (figuratively) feel sympathy, to pity.

DEFINITION: the inward parts; the heart, affections, seat of the feelings.
ORIGIN: Probably strengthened from splen (the "spleen"); an intestine (plural); figuratively, pity or sympathy.

DEFINITION: a sponge.
ORIGIN: Perhaps of foreign origin; a "sponge".

DEFINITION: ashes.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; ashes.

DEFINITION: a sowing, by implication seed.
ORIGIN: From speiro; a sowing, i.e. (by implication) parentage.

DEFINITION: sown; neut. plur: sown fields.
ORIGIN: From sporos; sown, i.e. (neuter plural) a planted field.

DEFINITION: a sowing, seed (sown).
ORIGIN: From speiro; a scattering (of seed), i.e. (concretely) seed (as sown).

DEFINITION: to make haste, to give diligence.
ORIGIN: From spoude; to use speed, i.e. To make effort, be prompt or earnest.
USAGE: do (give) diligence, be diligent (forward), endeavour, labour, study.

DEFINITION: diligent, earnest, zealous, eager.
ORIGIN: From spoude; prompt, energetic, earnest.

DEFINITION: more diligently, earnestly, eagerly, zealously.
ORIGIN: Neuter of spoudaioteros as adverb; more earnestly than others), i.e. Very promptly.

DEFINITION: more diligent.
ORIGIN: Comparative of spoudaios; more prompt, more earnest.

DEFINITION: more earnestly, diligently, zealously.
ORIGIN: Adverb from spoudaioteros; more speedily, i.e. Sooner than otherwise.

DEFINITION: diligently, earnestly, zealously.
ORIGIN: Adverb from spoudaios; earnestly, promptly.

DEFINITION: (a) speed, haste, (b) diligence, earnestness, enthusiasm.
ORIGIN: From speudo; "speed", i.e. (by implication) despatch, eagerness, earnestness.

DEFINITION: a (large, flexible) basket (for carrying provisions).
ORIGIN: From speiro (as woven); a hamper or lunch-receptacle.

DEFINITION: (a) a stadium, one eighth of a Roman mile, (b) a race-course for public games.
ORIGIN: Or masculine (in plural) stadios (stad'-ee-os) from the base of histemi (as fixed); a stade or certain measure of distance; by implication, a stadium or race-course.

DEFINITION: an earthen jar (for racking off wine).
ORIGIN: From the base of histemi (as stationary); a jar or earthen tank.

DEFINITION: an insurrection, dissension; originally: standing, position, place.
ORIGIN: From the base of histemi; a standing (properly, the act), i.e. (by analogy) position (existence); by implication, a popular uprising; figuratively, controversy.

DEFINITION: an Attic silver coin equal in value to the Jewish shekel.
ORIGIN: From the base of kauchesis; a stander (standard of value), i.e. (specially), a stater or certain coin.

DEFINITION: an upright stake, a cross (the Rom. instrument of crucifixion).
ORIGIN: From the base of histemi; a stake or post (as set upright), i.e. (specially), a pole or cross (as an instrument of capital punishment); figuratively, exposure to death, i.e. Self-denial; by implication, the atonement of Christ.

DEFINITION: to fix to the cross, crucify; fig: to destroy, mortify.
ORIGIN: From stauros; to impale on the cross; figuratively, to extinguish (subdue) passion or selfishness.

DEFINITION: a grape, cluster of grapes.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of stephanos; a cluster of grapes (as if intertwined).

DEFINITION: a head of grain.
ORIGIN: From the base of histemi; a head of grain (as standing out from the stalk).

DEFINITION: Stachys, a Christian man at Rome.
ORIGIN: The same as stachus; Stachys, a Christian.

DEFINITION: a flat roof of a house.
ORIGIN: Strengthened from a primary tegos (a "thatch" or "deck" of a building); a roof.

DEFINITION: to cover closely (so as to keep water out), generally to bear up under.
ORIGIN: From stege; to roof over, i.e. (figuratively) to cover with silence (endure patiently).

DEFINITION: barren.
ORIGIN: A contraction from stereos (as stiff and unnatural); "sterile".

DEFINITION: to set, arrange; mid: to provide for, take care, withdraw from, hold aloof, avoid.
ORIGIN: Probably strengthened from the base of histemi; properly, to set fast ("stall"), i.e. (figuratively) to repress (reflexively, abstain from associating with).

DEFINITION: a garland, wreath, crown.
ORIGIN: From the base of stephanos; a wreath for show.

DEFINITION: a groaning, sighing.
ORIGIN: From stenazo; a sigh.

DEFINITION: to groan, expressing grief, anger, or desire.
ORIGIN: From stenos; to make (intransitively, be) in straits, i.e. (by implication) to sigh, murmur, pray inaudibly.

DEFINITION: narrow, strait.
ORIGIN: Probably from the base of histemi; narrow (from obstacles standing close about).

DEFINITION: (to keep some one in a tight place), to press upon, cramp, restrain.
ORIGIN: From the same as stenochoria; to hem in closely, i.e. (figuratively) cramp.

DEFINITION: a narrow space, great distress, anguish.
ORIGIN: From a compound of stenos and chora; narrowness of room, i.e. (figuratively) calamity.

DEFINITION: solid, firm, steadfast.
ORIGIN: From histemi; stiff, i.e. Solid, stable (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to strengthen, confirm, establish, settle.
ORIGIN: From stereos; to solidify, i.e. Confirm (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a solid body, a support, strength, firmness.
ORIGIN: From stereoo; something established, i.e. (abstractly) confirmation (stability).

DEFINITION: "crowned", Stephanas, a Christian at Corinth.
ORIGIN: Probably contraction for stephanotos (crowned; from stephanoo); Stephanas, a Christian.

DEFINITION: a crown, garland, honor, glory.
ORIGIN: From an apparently primary stepho (to twine or wreathe); a chaplet (as a badge of royalty, a prize in the public games or a symbol of honor generally; but more conspicuous and elaborate than the simple fillet, diadema), literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: Stephen, one of the seven original deacons at Jerusalem, and the first martyr.
ORIGIN: The same as stephanos; Stephanus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: to crown, adorn, decorate.
ORIGIN: From stephanos; to adorn with an honorary wreath (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: the breast, chest.
ORIGIN: From histemi (as standing prominently); the (entire external) bosom, i.e. Chest.

DEFINITION: to stand fast, stand firm, persevere.
ORIGIN: From the perfect tense of histemi; to be stationary, i.e. (figuratively) to persevere.

DEFINITION: a setting firmly, steadfastness.
ORIGIN: From sterizo; stability (figuratively).

DEFINITION: (a) to fix firmly, direct myself towards, (b) generally met: to buttress, prop, support; to strengthen, establish.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of histemi (like stereos); to set fast, i.e. (literally) to turn resolutely in a certain direction, or (figuratively) to confirm.

DEFINITION: a bed of leaves or rushes.
ORIGIN: From a primary stizo (to "stick", i.e. Prick); a mark incised or punched (for recognition of ownership), i.e. (figuratively) scar of service.

DEFINITION: a moment, point of time, an instant.
ORIGIN: Feminine of stigma; a point of time, i.e. An instant.

DEFINITION: to shine, glisten, flash, be radiant.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to gleam, i.e. Flash intensely.

DEFINITION: a colonnade, portico.
ORIGIN: Probably from histemi; a colonnade or interior piazza.

DEFINITION: a bough, branch of a tree.
ORIGIN: From a primary steibo (to "step" or "stamp"); a spread (as if tramped flat) of loose materials for a couch, i.e. (by implication) a bough of a tree so employed.

DEFINITION: (a) plur: the heavenly bodies, (b) a rudiment, an element, a rudimentary principle, an elementary rule.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of the base of stoicheo; something orderly in arrangement, i.e. (by implication) a serial (basal, fundamental, initial) constituent (literally), proposition (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to be in rows, to walk by rule.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of steicho (to range in regular line); to march in (military) rank (keep step), i.e. (figuratively) to conform to virtue and piety.

DEFINITION: a long robe, worn by the upper classes in the East.
ORIGIN: From stello; equipment, i.e. (specially), a "stole" or long-fitting gown (as a mark of dignity).

DEFINITION: the mouth, speech, eloquence in speech, the point of a sword.
ORIGIN: Probably strengthened from a presumed derivative of the base of tomoteros; the mouth (as if a gash in the face); by implication, language (and its relations); figuratively, an opening (in the earth); specially, the front or edge (of a weapon).

DEFINITION: an opening, the stomach.
ORIGIN: From stoma; an orifice (the gullet), i.e. (specially), the "stomach".

DEFINITION: warfare, military service; of Christian warfare.
ORIGIN: From strateuomai; military service, i.e. (figuratively) the apostolic career (as one of hardship and danger).

DEFINITION: an expedition, an army, a company of soldiers.
ORIGIN: From strateuomai; an armament, i.e. (by implication) a body of troops (more or less extensive or systematic).

DEFINITION: to wage war, fight, serve as a soldier; fig: of the warring lusts against the soul.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from the base of stratia; to serve in a military campaign; figuratively, to execute the apostolate (with its arduous duties and functions), to contend with carnal inclinations.

DEFINITION: (a) a general or leader of the army, (b) a magistrate or governor, (c) captain of the temple.
ORIGIN: From the base of stratia and ago or hegeomai; a general, i.e. (by implication or analogy) a (military) governor (praetor), the chief (praefect) of the (Levitical) temple-wardens.

DEFINITION: an army; met: a host of angels, the hosts of heaven (i.e. the stars).
ORIGIN: Feminine of a derivative of stratos (an army; from the base of stronnumi, as encamped); camp-likeness, i.e. An army, i.e. (figuratively) the angels, the celestial luminaries.

DEFINITION: a soldier.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of the same as stratia; a camper-out, i.e. A (common) warrior (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to collect an army, enlist troops.
ORIGIN: From a compound of the base of stratia and lego (in its original sense); to gather (or select) as a warrior, i.e. Enlist in the army.

DEFINITION: commander of the Roman emperor's body-guard.
ORIGIN: From stratopedon and archo; a ruler of an army, i.e. (specially), a Praetorian praefect.

DEFINITION: a military camp, an army.
ORIGIN: From the base of stratia and the same as pedinos; a camping-ground, i.e. (by implication) a body of troops.

DEFINITION: to twist, torture; met: to twist or pervert language.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of strepho; to wrench, i.e. (specially), to torture (by the rack), but only figuratively, to pervert.

DEFINITION: to turn, be converted, change, change direction.
ORIGIN: Strengthened from the base of trope; to twist, i.e. Turn quite around or reverse (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: convert, turn (again, back again, self, self about).

DEFINITION: to live luxuriously, revel, riot.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of strenos; to be luxurious.

DEFINITION: wantonness, luxury.
ORIGIN: Akin to stereos; a "straining", "strenuousness" or "strength", i.e. (figuratively) luxury (voluptuousness).

DEFINITION: a small bird, sparrow.
ORIGIN: Diminutive of strouthos (a sparrow); a little sparrow.

DEFINITION: to spread, make a bed.
ORIGIN: Or simpler stronnuo (strone-noo'-o), prolongation from a still simpler stroo (stro'-o), (used only as an alternate in certain tenses) (probably akin to stereos through the idea of positing); to "strew," i.e. Spread (as a carpet or couch).

DEFINITION: hateful, detestable, disgusting.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of an obsolete apparently primary stugo (to hate); hated, i.e. Odious.
