DEFINITION: to be gloomy, have a somber countenance, be shocked.
ORIGIN: From the same as stugnetos; to render gloomy, i.e. (by implication) glower (be overcast with clouds, or sombreness of speech).

DEFINITION: a pillar, support, column.
ORIGIN: From stuo (to stiffen; properly akin to the base of histemi); a post ("style"), i.e. (figuratively) support.

DEFINITION: a Stoic.
ORIGIN: From stoa; a "Stoic" (as occupying a particular porch in Athens), i.e. Adherent of a certin philosophy.

DEFINITION: you (early mod. Eng. thou).
ORIGIN: The person pronoun of the second person singular; thou.
USAGE: thou. See also se, soi, sou; and for the plural humas, humeis, humin, humon.

DEFINITION: kinship, kinfolk, relatives.
ORIGIN: From suggenes; relationship, i.e. (concretely) relatives.

DEFINITION: akin to, related; subst: fellow countryman, kinsman.
ORIGIN: From sun and genos; a relative (by blood); by extension, a fellow countryman.

DEFINITION: permission, indulgence, concession.
ORIGIN: From a compound of sun and ginosko; fellow knowledge, i.e. Concession.

DEFINITION: to sit together or with.
ORIGIN: From sun and kathemai; to seat oneself in company with.

DEFINITION: to cause to sit down with, sit down together.
ORIGIN: From sun and kathizo; to give (or take) a seat in company with.

DEFINITION: to bear evil treatment along with.
ORIGIN: From sun and kakopatheo; to suffer hardship in company with.

DEFINITION: to endure adversity with (pass.).
ORIGIN: From sun and kakoucheo; to maltreat in company with, i.e. (passively) endure persecution together.

DEFINITION: to call together.
ORIGIN: From sun and kaleo; to convoke.

DEFINITION: to conceal closely, cover up wholly.
ORIGIN: From sun and kalupto; to conceal altogether.

DEFINITION: to oppress, bend together.
ORIGIN: From sun and kampto; to bend together, i.e. (figuratively) to afflict.

DEFINITION: to go down with.
ORIGIN: From sun and katabaino; to descend in company with.

DEFINITION: assent, agreement, concord, alliance.
ORIGIN: From sugkatatithemai; a deposition (of sentiment) in company with, i.e. (figuratively) accord with.

DEFINITION: to deposit together, to agree with.
ORIGIN: Mid from sun and katatithemi; to deposit (one's vote or opinion) in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to accord with.

DEFINITION: to condemn with, to vote (one) a place among.
ORIGIN: From sun and a compound of kata and psephizo; to count down in company with, i.e. Enroll among.

DEFINITION: to mix together, to agree with.
ORIGIN: From sun and kerannumi; to commingle, i.e. (figuratively) to combine or assimilate.

DEFINITION: to move together, stir up, excite.
ORIGIN: From sparasso and kineo; to move together, i.e. (specially), to excite as a mass (to sedition).

DEFINITION: to enclose, shut in, make subject to.
ORIGIN: From sun and kleio; to shut together, i.e. Include or (figuratively) embrace in a common subjection to.

DEFINITION: a joint heir, participant.
ORIGIN: From sun and kleronomos; a co-heir, i.e. (by analogy) participant in common.

DEFINITION: to be a partaker with, have fellowship with, be an accomplice in.
ORIGIN: From sun and koinoneo; to share in company with, i.e. Co-participate in.
USAGE: communicate (have fellowship) with, be partaker of.

DEFINITION: a partaker with, co-partner.
ORIGIN: From sun and koinonos; a co-participant.

DEFINITION: to bear away together with, as in carrying away a corpse.
ORIGIN: From sun and komizo; to convey together, i.e. Collect or bear away in company with others.

DEFINITION: to join together, combine, compare, interpret, explain.
ORIGIN: From sun and krino; to judge of one thing in connection with another, i.e. Combine (spiritual ideas with appropriate expressions) or collate (one person with another by way of contrast or resemblance).

DEFINITION: to be bowed together, bent double.
ORIGIN: From sun and kupto; to stoop altogether, i.e. Be completely overcome by.

DEFINITION: a coincidence, accident, chance.
ORIGIN: From a comparative of sun and kureo (to light or happen; from the base of kurios); concurrence, i.e. Accident.

DEFINITION: to rejoice with, congratulate.
ORIGIN: From sun and chairo; to sympathize in gladness, congratulate.

DEFINITION: to pour together, to confuse, throw into confusion.
ORIGIN: Or sugchuno (soong-khoo'-no) from sun and cheo (to pour) or its alternate; to commingle promiscuously, i.e. (figuratively) to throw (an assembly) into disorder, to perplex (the mind).
USAGE: confound, confuse, stir up, be in an uproar.

DEFINITION: to use together with, to associate with.
ORIGIN: From sun and chraomai; to use jointly, i.e. (by implication) to hold intercourse in common.

DEFINITION: confusion, disturbance.
ORIGIN: From sugcheo; commixture, i.e. (figuratively) riotous disturbance.

DEFINITION: to live together with.
ORIGIN: From sun and zao; to continue to live in common with, i.e. Co-survive (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to yoke together, unite (as man and wife).
ORIGIN: From sun and the base of zeugos; to yoke together, i.e. (figuratively) conjoin (in marriage).

DEFINITION: to seek together, discuss, dispute.
ORIGIN: From sun and zeteo; to investigate jointly, i.e. Discuss, controvert, cavil.

DEFINITION: mutual questioning, disputation.
ORIGIN: From suzeteo; mutual questioning, i.e. Discussion.

DEFINITION: a disputer, as the Greek sophists.
ORIGIN: From suzeteo; a disputant, i.e. Sophist.

DEFINITION: a yoke-fellow, colleague.
ORIGIN: From suzeugnumi; co-yoked, i.e. (figuratively) as noun, a colleague; probably rather as a proper name; Syzygus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: to make alive together with.
ORIGIN: From sun and zoopoieo; to reanimate conjointly with (figuratively).

DEFINITION: a sycamore tree, black mulberry tree.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (shaqam) in imitation of sukomoraia; a sycamore-fig tree.

DEFINITION: a fig tree.
ORIGIN: From sukon; a fig-tree.

DEFINITION: the fig-mulberry tree, sycamore fig.
ORIGIN: From sukon and moron (the mulberry); the "sycamore"-fig tree.

DEFINITION: a (ripe) fig.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a fig.

DEFINITION: to accuse falsely, defraud.
ORIGIN: From a compound of sukon and a derivative of phaino; to be a fig-informer (reporter of the law forbidding the exportation of figs from Greece), "sycophant", i.e. (genitive and by extension) to defraud (exact unlawfully, extort).
USAGE: accuse falsely, take by false accusation.

DEFINITION: to plunder, lead captive; met: to make victim by fraud.
ORIGIN: From the base of sulao and (the reduplicated form of) ago; to lead away as booty, i.e. (figuratively) seduce.

DEFINITION: to rob, plunder, strip.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of sullo (to strip; probably akin to haireomai; compare skulon); to despoil.

DEFINITION: to talk with, discuss.
ORIGIN: From sun and laleo; to talk together, i.e. Converse.

DEFINITION: to collect, to take, by implication to take part with, to conceive.
ORIGIN: From sun and lambano; to clasp, i.e. Seize (arrest, capture); specially, to conceive (literally or figuratively); by implication, to aid.

DEFINITION: to collect, gather.
ORIGIN: From sun and lego in its original sense; to collect.

DEFINITION: to reason, reckon with myself, consider.
ORIGIN: From sun and logizomai; to reckon together (with oneself), i.e. Deliberate.

DEFINITION: to be moved to grief with (pass.).
ORIGIN: From sun and lupeo; to afflict jointly, i.e. (passive) sorrow at (on account of) someone.

DEFINITION: to come together, (of events) to come to pass.
ORIGIN: From sun and the base of basis; to walk (figuratively, transpire) together, i.e. Concur (take place).

DEFINITION: properly: to throw together, hence: to ponder, come up with, encounter, with or without hostile intent; to dispute with; mid: to confer, consult with, contribute.
ORIGIN: From sun and ballo; to combine, i.e. (in speaking) to converse, consult, dispute, (mentally) to consider, (by implication) to aid, (personally) to join, attack.
USAGE: confer, encounter, help, make, meet with, ponder.

DEFINITION: to reign together with.
ORIGIN: From sun and basileuo; to be co-regent (figuratively).

DEFINITION: (a) to unite or knit together, (b) to put together in reasoning, and so: to conclude, prove, (c) to teach, instruct.
ORIGIN: From sun and bibazo (to force; causative (by reduplication) of the base of basis); to drive together, i.e. Unite (in association or affection), (mentally) to infer, show, teach.
USAGE: compact, assuredly gather, intrust, knit together, prove.

DEFINITION: to give advice, exhort; mid: to take counsel together, consult.
ORIGIN: From sun and bouleuo; to give (or take) advice jointly, i.e. Recommend, deliberate or determine.

DEFINITION: (a) a body of advisers (assessors) in a court, a council, (b) abstr: consultation, counsel, advice; resolution, decree.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of sumboulos; advisement; specially, a deliberative body, i.e. The provincial assessors or lay-court.

DEFINITION: an adviser, counselor.
ORIGIN: From sun and boule; a consultor, i.e. Adviser.

DEFINITION: Symeon, Simeon, the name of several Israelites, also a tribe of Isr.
ORIGIN: From the same as Simon; Symeon (i.e. Shimon), the name of five Israelites.

DEFINITION: a fellow disciple.
ORIGIN: From a compound of sun and manthano; a co-learner (of Christianity).

DEFINITION: to testify or bear witness with.
ORIGIN: From sun and martureo; to testify jointly, i.e. Corroborate by (concurrent) evidence.

DEFINITION: to partake with, divide together with, have a share in.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from sun and merizo; to share jointly, i.e. Participate in.

DEFINITION: partaking with, subst. a joint partaker.
ORIGIN: From sun and metochos; a co-participant.

DEFINITION: a fellow imitator.
ORIGIN: From a presumed compound of sun and mimeomai; a co-imitator, i.e. Fellow votary.

DEFINITION: similar, conformed to.
ORIGIN: From sun and morphe; jointly formed, i.e. (figuratively) similar.

DEFINITION: to bring to the same form with, conform.
ORIGIN: From summorphos; to render like, i.e. (figuratively) to assimilate.

DEFINITION: to have a fellow feeling with, sympathize with.
ORIGIN: From sumpathes; to feel "sympathy" with, i.e. (by implication) to commiserate.
USAGE: have compassion, be touched with a feeling of.

DEFINITION: sympathizing, compassionate.
ORIGIN: From sumpascho; having a fellow-feeling ("sympathetic"), i.e. (by implication) mutually commiserative.

DEFINITION: to come together with, stand by one, help.
ORIGIN: From sun and paraginomai; to be present together, i.e. To convene; by implication, to appear in aid.

DEFINITION: to invite, encourage along with others; pass: to share in encouragement with.
ORIGIN: From sun and parakaleo; to console jointly.

DEFINITION: to take along as a companion.
ORIGIN: From sun and paralambano; to take along in company.

DEFINITION: to remain or continue together with.
ORIGIN: From sun and parameno; to remain in company, i.e. Still live.

DEFINITION: to be present together with.
ORIGIN: From sun and pareimi; to be at hand together, i.e. Now present.

DEFINITION: to suffer together with, sympathize.
ORIGIN: From sun and pascho (including its alternate); to experience pain jointly or of the same kind (specially, persecution; to "sympathize").

DEFINITION: to send together with.
ORIGIN: From sun and pempo; to despatch in company.

DEFINITION: to embrace completely.
ORIGIN: From sun and a compound of peri and lambano; to take by enclosing altogether, i.e. Earnestly throw the arms about one.

DEFINITION: to drink together with.
ORIGIN: From sun and pino; to partake a beverage in company.

DEFINITION: to fill completely; pass: to be completed.
ORIGIN: From sun and pleroo; to implenish completely, i.e. (of space) to swamp (a boat), or (of time) to accomplish (passive, be complete).

DEFINITION: to choke utterly, as weeds do plants; to crowd upon.
ORIGIN: From sun and pnigo; to strangle completely, i.e. (literally) to drown, or (figuratively) to crowd.

DEFINITION: a fellow citizen.
ORIGIN: From sun and polites; a native of the same town, i.e. (figuratively) co-religionist (fellow-Christian).

DEFINITION: to journey together with; to come together, assemble.
ORIGIN: From sun and poreuomai; to journey together; by implication, to assemble.

DEFINITION: a drinking party, company (guests at a party).
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of the alternate of sumpino; a drinking-party ("symposium"), i.e. (by extension) a room of guests.

DEFINITION: a fellow elder.
ORIGIN: From sun and presbuteros; a co-presbyter.

DEFINITION: to bring together, collect; to be profitable to.
ORIGIN: From sun and phero (including its alternate); to bear together (contribute), i.e. (literally) to collect, or (figuratively) to conduce; especially (neuter participle as a noun) advantage.
USAGE: be better for, bring together, be expedient (for), be good, (be) profit(-able for).

DEFINITION: to assent to, consent, confess, agree with.
ORIGIN: From sun and phemi; to say jointly, i.e. Assent to.

DEFINITION: one of the same tribe, a fellow country-man.
ORIGIN: From sun and a derivative of phule; a co-tribesman, i.e. Native of the same country.

DEFINITION: grown together, united with.
ORIGIN: From sun and a derivative of phuo; grown along with (connate), i.e. (figuratively) closely united to.

DEFINITION: to grow together (pass.).
ORIGIN: From sun and phuo; passive, to grow jointly.

DEFINITION: to call out with, to be in harmony, generally to agree.
ORIGIN: From sumphonos; to be harmonious, i.e. (figuratively) to accord (be suitable, concur) or stipulate (by compact).

DEFINITION: harmony, agreement, concord.
ORIGIN: From sumphoneo; accordance.

DEFINITION: harmony of instruments, music.
ORIGIN: From sumphonos; unison of sound ("symphony"), i.e. A concert of instruments (harmonious note).

DEFINITION: calling out together, agreeing.
ORIGIN: From sun and phone; sounding together (alike), i.e. (figuratively) accordant (neuter as noun, agreement).

DEFINITION: to compute, reckon up, count together.
ORIGIN: From sun and psephizo; to compute jointly.

DEFINITION: of one accord.
ORIGIN: From sun and psuche; co-spirited, i.e. Similar in sentiment.

DEFINITION: with, together with (expresses association with).
ORIGIN: A primary preposition denoting union; with or together (but much closer than meta or para), i.e. By association, companionship, process, resemblance, possession, instrumentality, addition, etc..
USAGE: beside, with. In composition it has similar applications, including completeness.

DEFINITION: to gather together, collect, assemble, receive with hospitality, entertain.
ORIGIN: From sun and ago; to lead together, i.e. Collect or convene; specially, to entertain (hospitably).
USAGE: + accompany, assemble (selves, together), bestow, come together, gather (selves together, up, together), lead into, resort, take in.

DEFINITION: an assembly, congregation, synagogue, either the place or the people gathered together in the place.
ORIGIN: From (the reduplicated form of) sunago; an assemblage of persons; specially, a Jewish "synagogue" (the meeting or the place); by analogy, a Christian church.

DEFINITION: to struggle in company with, aid.
ORIGIN: From sun and agonizomai; to struggle in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to be a partner (assistant).

DEFINITION: to compete together with others, cooperate vigorously with.
ORIGIN: From sun and athleo; to wrestle in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to seek jointly.

DEFINITION: to gather together, assemble.
ORIGIN: From sun and athroizo (to hoard); to convene.

DEFINITION: to compare (settle) accounts, make a reckoning.
ORIGIN: From sun and airo; to make up together, i.e. (figuratively) to compute (an account).

DEFINITION: a fellow captive or prisoner.
ORIGIN: From sun and aichmalotos; a co-captive.

DEFINITION: to accompany, follow together with.
ORIGIN: From sun and akoloutheo; to accompany.

DEFINITION: to be assembled together with.
ORIGIN: From sun and halizo (to throng); to accumulate, i.e. Convene.

DEFINITION: to go up with.
ORIGIN: From sun and anabaino; to ascend in company with.

DEFINITION: to recline with (at table).
ORIGIN: From sun and anakeimai; to recline in company with (at a meal).
USAGE: sit (down, at the table, together) with (at meat).

DEFINITION: to mingle together with, keep company with.
ORIGIN: From sun and a compound of ana and mignumi; to mix up together, i.e. (figurative) associate with.

DEFINITION: to lie down to rest with, to be refreshed in spirit with.
ORIGIN: Middle from sun and anapano; to recruit oneself in company with.

DEFINITION: to meet, encounter, fall in with.
ORIGIN: From sun and a derivative of anti; to meet with; figuratively, to occur.

DEFINITION: a meeting with.
ORIGIN: From sunantao; a meeting with.

DEFINITION: to lend a hand along with, take interest in (a thing) along with (others), assist jointly to perform some task, cooperate with, take share in, help, aid.
ORIGIN: From sun and antilambanomai; to take hold of opposite together, i.e. Co-operate (assist).

DEFINITION: to lead away with, carry along with (in good or bad sense according to context); mid: to conform myself willingly to.
ORIGIN: From sun and apago; to take off together, i.e. Transport with (seduce, passively, yield).

DEFINITION: to die together with.
ORIGIN: From sun and apothnesko; to decease (literally) in company with, or (figuratively), similarly to.

DEFINITION: to destroy with, mid. to perish together.
ORIGIN: From sun and apollumi; to destroy (middle voice or passively, be slain) in company with.

DEFINITION: to send together with.
ORIGIN: From sun and apostello; to despatch (on an errand) in company with.

DEFINITION: to fit together, compact.
ORIGIN: From sun and a derivative of a compound of harmos and lego (in its original sense of laying); to render close-jointed together, i.e. Organize compactly.

DEFINITION: to seize and carry away.
ORIGIN: From sun and harpazo; to snatch together, i.e. Seize.

DEFINITION: to cause to grow together, pass. to grow together.
ORIGIN: From sun and auzano; to increase (grow up) together.

DEFINITION: that which binds together; a band, bond.
ORIGIN: From sun and desmon; a joint tie, i.e. Ligament, (figuratively) uniting principle, control.

DEFINITION: to bind together; pass: to be bound together with, as of prisoners in chains.
ORIGIN: From sun and deo; to bind with, i.e. (passively) be a fellow-prisoner (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to join in approving, to glorify together.
ORIGIN: From sun and doxazo; to exalt to dignity in company (i.e. Similarly) with.

DEFINITION: a fellow slave, fellow servant; of Christians: a fellow worker, colleague.
ORIGIN: From sun and doulos; a co-slave, i.e. Servitor or ministrant of the same master (human or divine).

DEFINITION: a running together, a concourse (esp. of a riotous gathering).
ORIGIN: From (the alternate of) suntrecho; a running together, i.e. (riotous) concourse.

DEFINITION: to raise along with.
ORIGIN: From sun and egeiro; to rouse (from death) in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to revivify (spirtually) in resemblance to.

DEFINITION: a council, tribunal; the Sanhedrin, the meeting place of the Sanhedrin.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of a compound of sun and the base of hedraios; a joint session, i.e. (specially), the Jewish Sanhedrin; by analogy, a subordinate tribunal.

DEFINITION: the conscience, a persisting notion.
ORIGIN: From a prolonged form of suneido; co-perception, i.e. Moral consciousness.

DEFINITION: to see together, to comprehend.
ORIGIN: From sun and eido; to see completely; used (like its primary) only in two past tenses, respectively meaning to understand or become aware, and to be conscious or (clandestinely) informed of.
USAGE: consider, know, be privy, be ware of.

DEFINITION: to be with, come together with.
ORIGIN: From sun and eimi (including its various inflections); to be in company with, i.e. Present at the time.

DEFINITION: to come together.
ORIGIN: From sun and eimi (to go); to assemble.

DEFINITION: to enter together with, embark with.
ORIGIN: From sun and eiserchomai; to enter in company with.
USAGE: go in with, go with into.

DEFINITION: a fellow traveler.
ORIGIN: From sun and the base of ekdemeo; a co-absentee from home, i.e. Fellow-traveller.

DEFINITION: fellow-elect, fellow-chosen.
ORIGIN: From a compound of sun and eklegomai; chosen in company with, i.e. Co-elect (fellow Christian).

DEFINITION: to compel, urge, force together.
ORIGIN: From sun and elauno; to drive together, i.e. (figuratively) exhort (to reconciliation).

DEFINITION: to testify or bear witness together with.
ORIGIN: From sun and epimartureo; to testify further jointly, i.e. Unite in adding evidence.

DEFINITION: to accompany, follow with.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from sun and a primary hepo (to follow); to attend (travel) in company with.

DEFINITION: to cooperate with, work together.
ORIGIN: From sunergos; to be a fellow-worker, i.e. Co-operate.

DEFINITION: a fellow worker, associate, helper.
ORIGIN: From a presumed compound of sun and the base of ergon; a co-laborer, i.e. Coadjutor.
USAGE: companion in labour, (fellow-)helper(-labourer, -worker), labourer together with, workfellow.

DEFINITION: to come or go with, accompany; to come together, assemble.
ORIGIN: From sun and erchomai; to convene, depart in company with, associate with, or (specially), cohabit (conjugally).
USAGE: accompany, assemble (with), come (together), come (company, go) with, resort.

DEFINITION: to eat with.
ORIGIN: From sun and esthio (including its alternate); to take food in company with.

DEFINITION: a putting together in the mind, hence: understanding, practical discernment, intellect.
ORIGIN: From suniemi; a mental putting together, i.e. Intelligence or (concretely) the intellect.

DEFINITION: intelligent, prudent, wise, understanding, discerning.
ORIGIN: From suniemi; mentally put (or putting) together, i.e. Sagacious.

DEFINITION: to consent, agree, be of one mind with, be willing.
ORIGIN: From sun and eudokeo; to think well of in common, i.e. Assent to, feel gratified with.
USAGE: allow, assent, be pleased, have pleasure.

DEFINITION: to entertain together, pass. feast together.
ORIGIN: From sun and a derivative of a presumed compound of eu and a derivative of echo (meaning to be in good condition, i.e. (by implication) to fare well, or feast); to entertain sumptuously in company with, i.e. (middle voice or passive) to revel together.

DEFINITION: to place over, rise together.
ORIGIN: From sun and ephistemi; to stand up together, i.e. To resist (or assault) jointly.

DEFINITION: (a) to press together, close, (b) to press on every side, confine, (c) to hold fast, (d) to urge, impel, (e) pass: to be afflicted with (sickness).
ORIGIN: From sun and echo; to hold together, i.e. To compress (the ears, with a crowd or siege) or arrest (a prisoner); figuratively, to compel, perplex, afflict, preoccupy.
USAGE: constrain, hold, keep in, press, lie sick of, stop, be in a strait, straiten, be taken with, throng.

DEFINITION: to delight inwardly in, congratulate.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from sun and the base of hedone; to rejoice in with oneself, i.e. Feel satisfaction concerning.

DEFINITION: a custom, habit, practice.
ORIGIN: From a compound of sun and ethos; mutual habituation, i.e. Usage.

DEFINITION: one of the same age.
ORIGIN: From sun and a derivative of helikia; a co-aged person, i.e. Alike in years.

DEFINITION: to bury along with.
ORIGIN: From sun and thapto; to inter in company with, i.e. (figuratively) to assimilate spiritually (to Christ by a sepulture as to sin).

DEFINITION: to break, break in pieces, crush, shatter.
ORIGIN: From sun and thlao (to crush); to dash together, i.e. Shatter.

DEFINITION: to press on all sides, crowd upon.
ORIGIN: From sun and thlibo; to compress, i.e. Crowd on all sides.

DEFINITION: to break in pieces, crush, thoroughly weaken.
ORIGIN: From sun and thrupto (to crumble); to crush together, i.e. (figuratively) to dispirit.

DEFINITION: to consider, understand, perceive.
ORIGIN: From sun and hiemi (to send); to put together, i.e. (mentally) to comprehend; by implication, to act piously.

DEFINITION: to place together, commend, prove, exhibit; instrans: to stand with; to be composed of, cohere.
ORIGIN: Or (strengthened) sunistano (soon-is-tan'-o), or sunistemi (soon-is'-tay-mee) from sun and histemi (including its collateral forms); to set together, i.e. (by implication) to introduce (favorably), or (figuratively) to exhibit; intransitively, to stand near, or (figuratively) to constitute.

DEFINITION: to journey with, accompany.
ORIGIN: From sun and hodeuo; to travel in company with.

DEFINITION: a journey in company, a company (of travelers).
ORIGIN: From a compound of sun and hodos ("synod"); companionship on a journey, i.e. (by implication), a caravan.

DEFINITION: to dwell with, live in wedlock with.
ORIGIN: From sun and oikeo; to reside together (as a family).

DEFINITION: to build together, to build up together.
ORIGIN: From sun and oikodomeo; to construct, i.e. (passively) to compose (in company with other Christians, figuratively).

DEFINITION: to talk with, live with.
ORIGIN: From sun and homileo; to converse mutually.

DEFINITION: to be contiguous with, be next door to.
ORIGIN: From sun and a derivative of a compound of the base of homou and the base of horion; to border together, i.e. Adjoin.

DEFINITION: a holding together, distress.
ORIGIN: From sunecho; restraint, i.e. (figuratively) anxiety.

DEFINITION: to arrange with, direct, appoint, prescribe, ordain.
ORIGIN: From sun and tasso; to arrange jointly, i.e. (figuratively) to direct.

DEFINITION: a joint payment (for public service), joint action, completion.
ORIGIN: From sunteleo; entire completion, i.e. Consummation (of a dispensation).

DEFINITION: to bring to an end, fulfill, accomplish.
ORIGIN: From sun and teleo; to complete entirely; generally, to execute (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to cut short, bring to swift accomplishment, determine, decide.
ORIGIN: From sun and the base of tomoteros; to contract by cutting, i.e. (figuratively) do concisely (speedily).

DEFINITION: to preserve, keep safe, keep in mind, keep close.
ORIGIN: From sun and tereo; to keep closely together, i.e. (by implication) to conserve (from ruin); mentally, to remember (and obey).

DEFINITION: mid. and pass: to make a compact (agreement) with (together), covenant with, agree.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from sun and tithemi; to place jointly, i.e. (figuratively) to consent (bargain, stipulate), concur.

DEFINITION: concisely, briefly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a derivative of suntemno; concisely (briefly).

DEFINITION: to run (rush) together, run with.
ORIGIN: From sun and trecho (including its alternate); to rush together (hastily assemble) or headlong (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to break by crushing, break in pieces, shatter, crush, bruise.
ORIGIN: From sun and the base of tribos; to crush completely, i.e. To shatter (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: break (in pieces), broken to shivers (+ -hearted), bruise.

DEFINITION: crushing, destruction, calamity.
ORIGIN: From suntribo; concussion or utter fracture (properly, concretely), i.e. Complete ruin.

DEFINITION: one brought up with, a foster brother or an intimate friend.
ORIGIN: From sun and trophos (in a passive sense); a fellow-nursling, i.e. Comrade.

DEFINITION: to meet with, come to, fall in with.
ORIGIN: From sun and tugchano; to chance together, i.e. Meet with (reach).

DEFINITION: "happy event", Syntyche, a Christian woman at Philippi.
ORIGIN: From suntugchano; an accident; Syntyche, a Christian female.

DEFINITION: to dissemble with, play a part with.
ORIGIN: From sun and hupokrinomai; to act hypocritically in concert with.

DEFINITION: to help together, join in serving.
ORIGIN: From sun and a derivative of a compound of hupo and the base of ergon; to be a co-auxiliary, i.e. Assist.

DEFINITION: to be in travail together.
ORIGIN: From sun and odino; to have (parturition) pangs in company (concert, simultaneously) with, i.e. (figuratively) to sympathize (in expectation of relief from suffering).

DEFINITION: a swearing together, a conspiracy.
ORIGIN: From a compound of sun and omnuo; a swearing together, i.e. (by implication) a plot.

DEFINITION: Syracuse, a large maritime city of Sicily.
ORIGIN: Plural of uncertain derivation; Syracuse, the capital of Sicily.

DEFINITION: Syria, a great Roman imperial province, united with Cilicia.
ORIGIN: Probably of Hebrew origin (Tsor); Syria (i.e. Tsyria or Tyre), a region of Asia.

DEFINITION: Syrian, belonging to Syria.
ORIGIN: From the same as Suria; a Syran (i.e. Probably Tyrian), a native of Syria.

DEFINITION: Syrophoenician, i.e. Phoenician (of Syria, in contrast to Carthage and its territory in North Africa).
ORIGIN: Feminine of a compound of Suros and the same as Phoinike; a Syro-phoenician woman, i.e. A female native of Phoenicia in Syria.

DEFINITION: "shoal", Syrtis, the name of two large sandbanks on the Lybian coast.
ORIGIN: From suro; a shoal (from the sand drawn thither by the waves), i.e. The Syrtis Major or great bay on the north coast of Africa.

DEFINITION: to draw, drag, force away.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to haireomai; to trail.

DEFINITION: to throw violently on the ground.
ORIGIN: From sun and sparasso; to rend completely, i.e. (by analogy) to convulse violently.

DEFINITION: a signal agreed upon.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a compound of sun and the base of semaino; a sign in common, i.e. Preconcerted signal.

DEFINITION: belonging to the same body; fig: of Jews and Gentiles belonging to the same Church.
ORIGIN: From sun and soma; of a joint body, i.e. (figuratively) a fellow-member of the Christian community.

DEFINITION: a fellow insurgent.
ORIGIN: From a compound of sun and a derivative of stasis; a fellow-insurgent.

DEFINITION: constructive, commendatory.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of sunistao; introductory, i.e. Recommendatory.

DEFINITION: to crucify together with.
ORIGIN: From sun and stauroo; to impale in company with (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to contract, shorten, wrap around, swathe.
ORIGIN: From sun and stello; to send (draw) together, i.e. Enwrap (enshroud a corpse for burial), contract (an interval).

DEFINITION: to groan together.
ORIGIN: From sun and stenazo; to moan jointly, i.e. (figuratively) experience a common calamity.

DEFINITION: to be in the same rank with; to answer to, correspond to.
ORIGIN: From sun and stoicheo; to file together (as soldiers in ranks), i.e. (figuratively) to correspond to.

DEFINITION: a fellow soldier (in the Christian faith).
ORIGIN: From sun and stratiotes; a co-campaigner, i.e. (figuratively) an associate in Christian toil.

DEFINITION: to twist together, to gather together (pass.).
ORIGIN: From sun and strepho; to twist together, i.e. Collect (a bundle, a crowd).

DEFINITION: a gathering together, riotous concourse, conspiracy.
ORIGIN: From sustrepho; a twisting together, i.e. (figuratively) a secret coalition, riotous crowd.

DEFINITION: to conform to.
ORIGIN: From sun and a derivative of schema; to fashion alike, i.e. Conform to the same pattern (figuratively).
USAGE: conform to, fashion self according to.

DEFINITION: Sychar, a city in Samaria.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (shekar); Sychar (i.e. Shekar), a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: Shechem, a city in Samaria.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Shkem); Sychem (i.e. Shekem), the name of a Canaanite and of a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: slaughter, sacrifice.
ORIGIN: From sphazo; butchery (of animals for food or sacrifice, or (figuratively) of men (destruction)).

DEFINITION: a victim (for slaughter).
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of sphage; a victim (in sacrifice).

DEFINITION: to slay, kill by violence, slaughter, wound mortally.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to butcher (especially an animal for food or in sacrifice) or (generally) to slaughter, or (specially), to maim (violently).

DEFINITION: exceedingly, greatly, very much.
ORIGIN: Neuter plural of sphodros (violent; of uncertain derivation) as adverb; vehemently, i.e. In a high degree, much.

DEFINITION: exceedingly, vehemently.
ORIGIN: Adverb from the same as sphodra; very much.

DEFINITION: to seal, set a seal upon.
ORIGIN: From sphragis; to stamp (with a signet or private mark) for security or preservation (literally or figuratively); by implication, to keep secret, to attest.
USAGE: (set a, set to) seal up, stop.

DEFINITION: a seal, signet ring, the impression of a seal, that which the seal attests, the proof.
ORIGIN: Probably strengthened from phrasso; a signet (as fencing in or protecting from misappropriation); by implication, the stamp impressed (as a mark of privacy, or genuineness), literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: the ankle bone.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative probably of the same as sphaira (a ball, "sphere"; compare the feminine sphura, a hammer); the ankle (as globular).

DEFINITION: nearly, almost.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of the alternate of echo as adverb; nigh, i.e. Nearly.

DEFINITION: fashion, habit, form, appearance.
ORIGIN: From the alternate of echo; a figure (as a mode or circumstance), i.e. (by implication) external condition.

DEFINITION: to rend, divide asunder, cleave.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to split or sever (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: break, divide, open, rend, make a rent.

DEFINITION: a rent, as in a garment; a division, dissention.
ORIGIN: From schizo; a split or gap ("schism"), literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: a rope (made of rushes).
ORIGIN: Diminutive of schoinos (a rush or flag-plant; of uncertain derivation); a rushlet, i.e. Grass-withe or tie (generally).

DEFINITION: (a) to have leisure, (b) to stand empty (of a house).
ORIGIN: From schole; to take a holiday, i.e. Be at leisure for (by implication, devote oneself wholly to); figuratively, to be vacant (of a house).

DEFINITION: leisure, disputation (that for which leisure is used), school.
ORIGIN: Probably feminine of a presumed derivative of the alternate of echo; properly, loitering (as a withholding of oneself from work) or leisure, i.e. (by implication) a "school" (as vacation from physical employment).

DEFINITION: to save, heal, preserve, rescue.
ORIGIN: From a primary sos (contraction for obsolete saos, "safe"); to save, i.e. Deliver or protect (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: heal, preserve, save (self), do well, be (make) whole.

DEFINITION: body, flesh; the body of the Church.
ORIGIN: From sozo; the body (as a sound whole), used in a very wide application, literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: bodily, corporeal.
ORIGIN: From soma; corporeal or physical.

DEFINITION: bodily, corporeally, belonging to the body.
ORIGIN: Adverb from somatikos; corporeally or physically.

DEFINITION: "of a safe father", Sopater, a Christian from Berea.
ORIGIN: From the base of sozo and pater; of a safe father; Sopatrus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: to heap up, load.
ORIGIN: From another form of soros; to pile up (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: "of safe strength", Sosthenes, the name of a ruler of a synagogue and of a Christian.
ORIGIN: From the base of sozo and that of sthenoo; of safe strength; Sosthenes, a Christian.

DEFINITION: "of a safe father", Sosipater, a Christian.
ORIGIN: Prolongation for Sopatros; Sosipatrus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: a savior, deliverer, preserver.
ORIGIN: From sozo; a deliverer, i.e. God or Christ.

DEFINITION: welfare, prosperity, deliverance, preservation, salvation, safety.
ORIGIN: Feminine of a derivative of soter as (properly, abstract) noun; rescue or safety (physically or morally).

DEFINITION: saving, bringing salvation; subst: salvation.
ORIGIN: Neuter of the same as soteria as (properly, concretely) noun; defender or (by implication) defence.

DEFINITION: to be of sound mind, be sober-minded, exercise self-control.
ORIGIN: From sophron; to be of sound mind, i.e. Sane, (figuratively) moderate.
USAGE: be in right mind, be sober (minded), soberly.

DEFINITION: to make sober-minded, admonish, control.
ORIGIN: From sophron; to make of sound mind, i.e. (figuratively) to discipline or correct.

DEFINITION: self-control, self-discipline, prudence.
ORIGIN: From sophronizo; discipline, i.e. Self-control.

DEFINITION: soberly, with moderation, prudently.
ORIGIN: Adverb from sophron; with sound mind, i.e. Moderately.

DEFINITION: soundness of mind, sanity; self-control, sobriety.
ORIGIN: From sophron; soundness of mind, i.e. (literally) sanity or (figuratively) self-control.

DEFINITION: of sound mind, self-controlled, temperate, sober-minded, modest, chaste.
ORIGIN: From the base of sozo and that of phren; safe (sound) in mind, i.e. Self-controlled (moderate as to opinion or passion).

DEFINITION: taverns; Three Taverns, the name of a village or town on the Appian Way, about thirty-three miles from Rome.
ORIGIN: Plural of Latin origin; huts or wooden-walled buildings; Tabernoe.

DEFINITION: "gazelle", Tabitha (also called Dorcas), a Christian woman.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (compare tsbiyah); the gazelle; Tabitha (i.e. Tabjetha), a Christian female.

DEFINITION: that which has been arranged in order, a division, rank.
ORIGIN: From tasso; something orderly in arrangement (a troop), i.e. (figuratively) a series or succession.

DEFINITION: appointed, arranged, fixed.
ORIGIN: From tasso; arranged, i.e. Appointed or stated.

DEFINITION: to endure severe hardship, be harassed, complain.
ORIGIN: From talaiporos; to be wretched, i.e. Realize one's own misery.

DEFINITION: hardship, misery, distress, toil.
ORIGIN: From talaiporos; wretchedness, i.e. Calamity.

DEFINITION: wretched, afflicted, miserable.
ORIGIN: From the base of talanton and a derivative of the base of peira; enduring trial, i.e. Miserable.

DEFINITION: worth a talent, of a talent's weight.
ORIGIN: From talanton; talent-like in weight.

DEFINITION: a balance, that which is weighed, a talent (about 3000 shekels in weight).
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of the original form of tlao (to bear; equivalent to phero); a balance (as supporting weights), i.e. (by implication) a certain weight (and thence a coin or rather sum of money) or "talent".

DEFINITION: (Aramaic), girl, little girl.
ORIGIN: Of Chaldee origin (compare taleh); the fresh, i.e. Young girl; talitha (O maiden).

DEFINITION: a store-chamber, secret chamber, closet; a granary, barn.
ORIGIN: Neuter contraction of a presumed derivative of tamias (a dispenser or distributor; akin to temno, to cut); a dispensary or magazine, i.e. A chamber on the ground-floor or interior of an Oriental house (generally used for storage or privacy, a spot for retirement).

DEFINITION: order, (a) regular arrangement, (b) appointed succession, (c) position, rank.
ORIGIN: From tasso; regular arrangement, i.e. (in time) fixed succession (of rank or character), official dignity.

DEFINITION: humble, lowly, in position or spirit (in a good sense).
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; depressed, i.e. (figuratively) humiliated (in circumstances or disposition).
USAGE: base, cast down, humble, of low degree (estate), lowly.

DEFINITION: humility, lowliness of mind, modesty.
ORIGIN: From a compound of tapeinos and the base of phren; humiliation of mind, i.e. Modesty.
USAGE: humbleness of mind, humility (of mind, loneliness (of mind).

DEFINITION: to make or bring low, humble, humiliate; pass: to be humbled.
ORIGIN: From tapeinos; to depress; figuratively, to humiliate (in condition or heart).

DEFINITION: abasement (in spirit), low condition (in circumstances).
ORIGIN: From tapeinoo; depression (in rank or feeling).
USAGE: humiliation, be made low, low estate, vile.

DEFINITION: to disturb, agitate, stir up, trouble.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; to stir or agitate (roil water).

DEFINITION: a disturbance, tumult, sedition, trouble.
ORIGIN: Feminine from tarasso; disturbance, i.e. (of water) roiling, or (of a mob) sedition.

DEFINITION: a disturbance, commotion, trouble.
ORIGIN: Masculine from tarasso; a disturbance, i.e. (popular) tumult.

DEFINITION: belonging to Tarsus, a Tarsian.
ORIGIN: From Tarsos; a Tarsean, i.e. Native of Tarsus.

DEFINITION: Tarsus, the capital of the Roman province Cilicia.
ORIGIN: Perhaps the same as tarsos (a flat basket); Tarsus, a place in Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: to thrust down to Tartarus or Gehenna.
ORIGIN: From Tartaros (the deepest abyss of Hades); to incarcerate in eternal torment.

DEFINITION: (a) to assign, arrange, (b) to determine; mid: to appoint.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary verb (which latter appears only in certain tenses); to arrange in an orderly manner, i.e. Assign or dispose (to a certain position or lot).

DEFINITION: a bull, an ox.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word (compare towr, "steer"); a bullock.

DEFINITION: this; he, she, it.
ORIGIN: Nominative or accusative case neuter plural of houtos; these things.
USAGE: + afterward, follow, + hereafter, X him, the same, so, such, that, then, these, they, this, those, thus.

DEFINITION: even thus, so.
ORIGIN: Neuter plural of ho and autos as adverb; in the same way.

DEFINITION: hence, that, then, these, those.
ORIGIN: And tautas (tow'-tas) dative case and accusative case feminine plural respectively of houtos; (to or with or by, etc.) These.

DEFINITION: her.
ORIGIN: And tauten (tow'-tane), and tautes (tow'-tace) dative case, accusative case and genitive case respectively of the feminine singular of houtos; (towards or of) this.
USAGE: her, + hereof, it, that, + thereby, the (same), this (same).

DEFINITION: a burial, burial place.
ORIGIN: Feminine from thapto; burial (the act).

DEFINITION: a burial-place, sepulcher, tomb, grave.
ORIGIN: Masculine from thapto; a grave (the place of interment).

DEFINITION: quickly, presently, perhaps.
ORIGIN: As if neuter plural of tachus (adverbially); shortly, i.e. (figuratively) possibly.

DEFINITION: soon, quickly, hastily.
ORIGIN: Adverb from tachus; briefly, i.e. (in time) speedily, or (in manner) rapidly.

DEFINITION: swift, quick, impending.
ORIGIN: From tachos; curt, i.e. Impending.

DEFINITION: more swiftly, more quickly.
ORIGIN: Neuter singular of the comparative of tachus (as adverb); more swiftly, i.e. (in manner) more rapidly, or (in time) more speedily.

DEFINITION: most swiftly, most quickly, as quickly as possible.
ORIGIN: Neuter plural of the superlative of tachus (as adverb); most quickly, i.e. (with hos prefixed) as soon as possible.

DEFINITION: quickness, speed; hastily, immediately.
ORIGIN: From the same as tachus; a brief space (of time), i.e. (with en prefixed) in haste.

DEFINITION: quickly, speedily.
ORIGIN: Neuter singular of tachus (as adverb); shortly, i.e. Without delay, soon, or (by surprise) suddenly, or (by implication, of ease) readily.

DEFINITION: quick, swift, speedy, ready, prompt.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; fleet, i.e. (figuratively) prompt or ready.

DEFINITION: and (denotes addition or connection).
ORIGIN: A primary particle (enclitic) of connection or addition; both or also (properly, as correlation of kai).
USAGE: also, and, both, even, then, whether. Often used in composition, usually as the latter participle.

DEFINITION: a wall, especially of a city.
ORIGIN: Akin to the base of tikto; a wall (as formative of a house).

DEFINITION: a sign, certain proof.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of tekmar (a goal or fixed limit); a token (as defining a fact), i.e. Criterion of certainty.

DEFINITION: a little child.
ORIGIN: Diminutive of teknon; an infant, i.e. (plural figuratively) darlings (Christian converts).

DEFINITION: to bear children, beget, rear a family.
ORIGIN: From a compound of teknon and the base of ginomai; to be a child-bearer, i.e. Parent (mother).

DEFINITION: child bearing, the rearing of a family.
ORIGIN: From the same as teknogoneo; childbirth (parentage), i.e. (by implication) maternity (the performance of maternal duties).

DEFINITION: a child, descendent, inhabitant.
ORIGIN: From the base of timoria; a child (as produced).

DEFINITION: to bring up children, rear young.
ORIGIN: From a compound of teknon and trepho; to be a childrearer, i.e. Fulfil the duties of a female parent.

DEFINITION: a craftsman, a carpenter.
ORIGIN: From the base of timoria; an artificer (as producer of fabrics), i.e. (specially), a craftsman in wood.

DEFINITION: perfect, (a) complete in all its parts, (b) full grown, of full age, (c) specially of the completeness of Christian character.
ORIGIN: From telos; complete (in various applications of labor, growth, mental and moral character, etc.); neuter (as noun, with ho) completeness.

DEFINITION: perfectness, perfection, maturity.
ORIGIN: From teleios; (the state) completeness (mentally or morally).

DEFINITION: (a) as a course, a race, or the like: to complete, finish (b) as of time or prediction: to accomplish, (c) to make perfect; pass: to be perfected.
ORIGIN: From teleios; to complete, i.e. (literally) accomplish, or (figuratively) consummate (in character).

DEFINITION: perfectly, completely, without wavering.
ORIGIN: Adverb from teleios; completely, i.e. (of hope) without wavering.

DEFINITION: completion, fulfillment, perfection.
ORIGIN: From phusioo; (the act) completion, i.e. (of prophecy) verification, or (of expiation) absolution.

DEFINITION: a perfecter, completer, finisher.
ORIGIN: From teleioo; a completer, i.e. Consummater.

DEFINITION: to bring fruit to perfection, to bear perfect offspring.
ORIGIN: From a compound of telos and phero; to be a bearer to completion (maturity), i.e. To ripen fruit (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to complete, to come to an end, to die.
ORIGIN: From a presumed derivative of teleo; to finish life (by implication, of bios), i.e. Expire (demise).

DEFINITION: a finishing, end, death.
ORIGIN: From teleutao; decease.

DEFINITION: (a) to end, finish, (b) to fulfill, accomplish, (c) to pay.
ORIGIN: From telos; to end, i.e. Complete, execute, conclude, discharge (a debt).
USAGE: accomplish, make an end, expire, fill up, finish, go over, pay, perform.

DEFINITION: (a) an end, (b) event or issue, (c) the principal end, aim, purpose, (d) a tax.
ORIGIN: From a primary tello (to set out for a definite point or goal); properly, the point aimed at as a limit, i.e. (by implication) the conclusion of an act or state (termination (literally, figuratively or indefinitely), result (immediate, ultimate or prophetic), purpose); specially, an impost or levy (as paid).
USAGE: + continual, custom, end(-ing), finally, uttermost. Compare phoros.

DEFINITION: a publican, collector of taxes.
ORIGIN: From telos and oneomai; a tax-farmer, i.e. Collector of public revenue.

DEFINITION: a tax-collector's office, toll-house.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of telones; a tax-gatherer's place of business.

DEFINITION: a wonder, portent, marvel.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a prodigy or omen.

DEFINITION: Tertius, who wrote the Epistle to the Romans at Paul's dictation.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; third; Tertius, a Christian.

DEFINITION: Tertullus, a barrister acting as professional prosecutor of Paul at Caesarea.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; Tertullus, a Roman.

DEFINITION: forty.
ORIGIN: The decade of tessares; forty.

DEFINITION: forty years of age.
ORIGIN: From tessarakonta and etos; of forty years of age.

DEFINITION: four.
ORIGIN: Or neuter tessara (tes'-sar-ah) a plural number; four.

DEFINITION: fourteenth.
ORIGIN: From tessares and kai and dekatos; fourteenth.

DEFINITION: of the fourth day, four days since.
ORIGIN: From tessares; pertaining to the fourth day.

DEFINITION: fourth.
ORIGIN: Ordinal from tessares; fourth.

DEFINITION: a tetrarch (the governor of a fourth part of a region).
ORIGIN: From tessares and gonia; four-cornered, i.e. Square.

DEFINITION: a group of four, a quaternion (a guard of four soldiers).
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of tetras (a tetrad; from tessares); a quaternion or squad (picket) of four Roman soldiers.

DEFINITION: four thousand.
ORIGIN: From the multiplicative adverb of tessares and chilioi; four times a thousand.

DEFINITION: four hundred.
ORIGIN: Plural from tessares and hekaton.

DEFINITION: of four months, a period of four months.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a compound of tessares and men; a four months' space.

DEFINITION: four-fold, four times as much.
ORIGIN: From tessares and a derivative of the base of pleistos; quadruple.

DEFINITION: four-footed.
ORIGIN: From tessares and pous; a quadruped.

DEFINITION: to rule over as a tetrarch.
ORIGIN: From tetrarches; to be a tetrarch.

DEFINITION: a tetrarch, ruler over a fourth part of a region.
ORIGIN: From tessares and archo; the ruler of a fourth part of a country ("tetrarch").

DEFINITION: to reduce to ashes, consume, destroy.
ORIGIN: From tephra (ashes); to incinerate, i.e. Consume.

DEFINITION: art, skill, trade, craft.
ORIGIN: From the base of tikto; art (as productive), i.e. (specially), a trade, or (generally) skill.

DEFINITION: a craftsman, artisan, architect, builder.
ORIGIN: From techne; an artisan; figuratively, a founder (Creator).

DEFINITION: to make liquid; pass: to melt (away).
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to liquefy.

DEFINITION: clearly, distinctly, plainly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a compound of a derivative of telos and auge; in a far-shining manner, i.e. Plainly.

DEFINITION: such as this, of persons so old, of things so great.
ORIGIN: Or feminine telikaute (tay-lik-ow'-tay) from a compound of ho with helikos and houtos; such as this, i.e. (in (figurative) magnitude) so vast.

DEFINITION: to keep, guard, observe, watch over.
ORIGIN: From teros (a watch; perhaps akin to theoreo); to guard (from loss or injury, properly, by keeping the eye upon; and thus differing from phulasso, which is properly to prevent escaping; and from koustodia, which implies a fortress or full military lines of apparatus), i.e. To note (a prophecy; figuratively, to fulfil a command); by implication, to detain (in custody; figuratively, to maintain); by extension, to withhold (for personal ends; figuratively, to keep unmarried); by extension, to withhold (for personal ends; figuratively, to keep unmarried).
USAGE: hold fast, keep(- er), (pre-, re-)serve, watch.

DEFINITION: a prison; observance (as of precepts).
ORIGIN: From tereo; a watching, i.e. (figuratively) observance, or (concretely) a prison.

DEFINITION: Tiberias, a town in Galilee on the western border of the sea called after it.
ORIGIN: From Tiberios; Tiberias, the name of a town and a lake in Palestine.

DEFINITION: Tiberius, the second Roman emperor (died A.D. 37).
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; probably pertaining to the river Tiberis or Tiber; Tiberius, a Roman emperor.

DEFINITION: to put, place, lay, set, fix, establish.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form of a primary theo (theh'-o) (which is used only as alternate in certain tenses) to place (in the widest application, literally and figuratively; properly, in a passive or horizontal posture, and thus different from histemi, which properly denotes an upright and active position, while keimai is properly reflexive and utterly prostrate).
USAGE: + advise, appoint, bow, commit, conceive, give, X kneel down, lay (aside, down, up), make, ordain, purpose, put, set (forth), settle, sink down.

DEFINITION: to bear, bring forth, produce, beget, yield.
ORIGIN: A strengthened form of a primary teko tek'-o (which is used only as alternate in certain tenses); to produce (from seed, as a mother, a plant, the earth, etc.), literally or figuratively.
USAGE: bear, be born, bring forth, be delivered, be in travail.

DEFINITION: to pluck, to pluck off.
ORIGIN: Perhaps akin to the alternate of haireomai, and thus to suro; to pull off.

DEFINITION: Timaeus, father of the blind beggar Bartimaeus.
ORIGIN: Probably of Chaldee origin (compare tame'); Timoeus (i.e. Timay), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: (a) to value at a price, estimate, (b) to honor, reverence.
ORIGIN: From timios; to prize, i.e. Fix a valuation upon; by implication, to revere.

DEFINITION: a valuing, a price.
ORIGIN: From tino; a value, i.e. Money paid, or (concretely and collectively) valuables; by analogy, esteem (especially of the highest degree), or the dignity itself.

DEFINITION: of great price, precious, honored.
ORIGIN: Including the comparative timioteros (tim-ee-o'-ter-os), and the superlative timiotatos (tim-ee-o'-tat-os) from time; valuable, i.e. (objectively) costly, or (subjectively) honored, esteemed, or (figuratively) beloved.
USAGE: dear, honourable, (more, most) precious, had in reputation.

DEFINITION: preciousness, costliness, worth.
ORIGIN: From timios; expensiveness, i.e. (by implication) magnificence.

DEFINITION: Timothy, a Christian of Lystra, helper of Paul.
ORIGIN: From time and theos; dear to God; Timotheus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: Timon, one of the seven original deacons at Jerusalem.
ORIGIN: From time; valuable; Timon, a Christian.

DEFINITION: to punish, avenge myself on.
ORIGIN: From a comparative of time and ouros (a guard); properly, to protect one's honor, i.e. To avenge (inflict a penalty).

DEFINITION: punishment, vengeance.
ORIGIN: From timoreo; vindication, i.e. (by implication) a penalty.

DEFINITION: to pay, to pay a penalty.
ORIGIN: Strengthened for a primary tio (tee'-o) (which is only used as an alternate in certain tenses) to pay a price, i.e. As a penalty.

DEFINITION: any one, some one, a certain one or thing.
ORIGIN: An enclitic indefinite pronoun; some or any person or object.
USAGE: a (kind of), any (man, thing, thing at all), certain (thing), divers, he (every) man, one (X thing), ought, + partly, some (man, -body, - thing, -what), (+ that no-)thing, what(-soever), X wherewith, whom(-soever), whose(-soever).

DEFINITION: who, which, what, why.
ORIGIN: Probably emphatic of tis; an interrogative pronoun, who, which or what (in direct or indirect questions).
USAGE: every man, how (much), + no(-ne, thing), what (manner, thing), where (-by, -fore, -of, -unto, - with, -withal), whether, which, who(-m, -se), why.

DEFINITION: Titius (surnamed Justus), a Christian.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; a titulus or "title" (placard).

DEFINITION: Titus, a Greek Christian, helper of Paul, perhaps also brother of Luke.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin but uncertain significance; Titus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: an enclitic particle of asseveration used as a prefix or suff. in the N.T.
ORIGIN: Probably for the dative case of ho; an enclitic particle of asseveration by way of contrast; in sooth.
USAGE: (used only with other particles in the comparative, as kaitoige, mentoi, toigaroun, toinun, etc.)

DEFINITION: consequently, therefore, well then, so then.
ORIGIN: From toi and gar and oun; truly for then, i.e. Consequently.

DEFINITION: indeed now, therefore, accordingly, well then.
ORIGIN: From toi and nun; truly now, i.e. Accordingly.

DEFINITION: of this kind, such, such as follows.
ORIGIN: (including the other inflections); from a derivative of toi and de; such-like then, i.e. So great.

DEFINITION: of such a kind, such.
ORIGIN: (including the other inflections); from toi and houtos; truly this, i.e. Of this sort (to denote character or individuality).

DEFINITION: a wall.
ORIGIN: Another form of teichos; a wall.

DEFINITION: a bringing forth, birth, interest, usury.
ORIGIN: From the base of tikto; interest on money loaned (as a produce).

DEFINITION: to dare, endure, be bold, have courage, make up the mind.
ORIGIN: From tolma (boldness; probably itself from the base of telos through the idea of extreme conduct); to venture (objectively or in act; while tharrheo is rather subjective or in feeling); by implication, to be courageous.

DEFINITION: more boldly, more freely, with more confidence.
ORIGIN: Neuter of the compound of a derivative of the base of tolmao (as adverb); more daringly, i.e. With greater confidence than otherwise.

DEFINITION: a bold, daring man.
ORIGIN: From tolmao; a daring (audacious) man.

DEFINITION: sharper, keener.
ORIGIN: Comparative of a derivative of the primary temno (to cut; more comprehensive or decisive than kopto, as if by a single stroke; whereas that implies repeated blows, like hacking); more keen.

DEFINITION: a bow.
ORIGIN: From the base of tikto; a bow (apparently as the simplest fabric).

DEFINITION: a topaz.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative (alternately) of topazos (a "topaz"; of uncertain origin); a gem, probably the chrysolite.

DEFINITION: a place, region, seat; an opportunity.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a spot (general in space, but limited by occupancy; whereas chora is a large but participle locality), i.e. Location (as a position, home, tract, etc.); figuratively, condition, opportunity; specially, a scabbard.
USAGE: coast, licence, place, X plain, quarter, + rock, room, where.

DEFINITION: so great, so large, so long, so many.
ORIGIN: From tosos (so much; apparently from ho and hos) and houtos (including its variations); so vast as this, i.e. Such (in quantity, amount, number of space).
USAGE: as large, so great (long, many, much), these many.

DEFINITION: then, at that time.
ORIGIN: From (the neuter of) ho and hote; the when, i.e. At the time that (of the past or future, also in consecution).

DEFINITION: his.
ORIGIN: Properly, the genitive case of ho; sometimes used for toutou; of this person.

DEFINITION: on the contrary, on the other hand.
ORIGIN: Contraction for the neuter of ho and enantion; on the contrary.

DEFINITION: by name.
ORIGIN: Contraction for the neuter of ho and onoma; the name (is).

DEFINITION: that is to say.
ORIGIN: Contraction for touto and esti; that is.

DEFINITION: this; he, she, it.
ORIGIN: Neuter singular nominative or accusative case of houtos; that thing.
USAGE: here (-unto), it, partly, self(-same), so, that (intent), the same, there(-fore, -unto), this, thus, where(-fore).

DEFINITION: this; he, she, it.
ORIGIN: Dative case plural masculine or neuter of houtos; to (for, in, with or by) these (persons or things).
USAGE: such, them, there(-in, -with), these, this, those.

DEFINITION: this; he, she, it.
ORIGIN: Accusative case singular masculine of houtos; this (person, as objective of verb or preposition).

DEFINITION: this; he, she, it.
ORIGIN: Genitive case singular masculine or neuter of houtos; of (from or concerning) this (person or thing).
USAGE: here(-by), him, it, + such manner of, that, thence(-forth), thereabout, this, thus.

DEFINITION: this; he, she, it.
ORIGIN: Accusative case plural masculine of houtos; these (persons, as objective of verb or preposition).

DEFINITION: this; he, she, it.
ORIGIN: Dative case singular masculine or neuter of houtos; to (in, with or by) this (person or thing).
USAGE: here(-by, -in), him, one, the same, there(-in), this.

DEFINITION: this; he, she, it.
ORIGIN: Genitive case plural masculine or neuter of houtos; of (from or concerning) these (persons or things).
USAGE: such, their, these (things), they, this sort, those.

DEFINITION: a male goat.
ORIGIN: From the base of trogo; a he-goat (as a gnawer).

DEFINITION: a table, (a) for food or banqueting, (b) for money-changing or business.
ORIGIN: Probably contracted from tessares and peze; a table or stool (as being four-legged), usually for food (figuratively, a meal); also a counter for money (figuratively, a broker's office for loans at interest).

DEFINITION: a money-changer, banker.
ORIGIN: From trapeza; a money-broker or banker.

DEFINITION: a wound.
ORIGIN: From the base of titrosko (to wound; akin to the base of thrauo, tribos, trizo, etc.); a wound.

DEFINITION: to wound.
ORIGIN: From trauma; to inflict a wound.

DEFINITION: to take by the throat, to overthrow.
ORIGIN: From trachelos; to seize by the throat or neck, i.e. To expose the gullet of a victim for killing (generally, to lay bare).

DEFINITION: the neck.
ORIGIN: Probably from trecho (through the idea of mobility); the throat (neck), i.e. (figuratively) life.

DEFINITION: rough, rugged, uneven.
ORIGIN: Perhaps strengthened from the base of rhegnumi (as if jagged by rents); uneven, rocky (reefy).

DEFINITION: Trachonitis, the north-east of the territory beyond Jordan.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of trachus; rough district; Trachonitis, a region of Syria.

DEFINITION: three.
ORIGIN: Or neuter tria (tree'-ah) a primary (plural) number; "three".

DEFINITION: to tremble (esp. with fear).
ORIGIN: Strengthened from a primary treo (to "dread", "terrify"); to "tremble" or fear.

DEFINITION: to feed, nourish; to bring up, rear, provide for.
ORIGIN: A primary verb (properly, threpho; but perhaps strengthened from the base of trope through the idea of convolution); properly, to stiffen, i.e. Fatten (by implication, to cherish (with food, etc.), pamper, rear).

DEFINITION: to run, exercise myself, make progress.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb (properly, threcho; compare thrix); which uses dremo drem'-o (the base of dromos) as alternate in certain tenses; to run or walk hastily (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a hole.
ORIGIN: The decade of treis; thirty.

DEFINITION: three hundred.
ORIGIN: Plural from treis and hekaton; three hundred.

DEFINITION: a thistle.
ORIGIN: From treis and belos; properly, a crow-foot (three-pronged obstruction in war), i.e. (by analogy) a thorny plant (caltrop).

DEFINITION: a worn path, beaten way, road, highway.
ORIGIN: From tribo (to "rub"; akin to teiro, truo, and the base of tragos, trauma); a rut or worn track.

DEFINITION: a period of three years.
ORIGIN: From a compound of treis and etos; a three years' period (triennium).

DEFINITION: to cry, chirp, to grind the teeth.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to creak (squeak), i.e. (by analogy) to grate the teeth (in frenzy).

DEFINITION: lasting three months.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a compound of treis and men as noun; a three months' space.

DEFINITION: three times.
ORIGIN: Adverb from treis; three times.

DEFINITION: having three stories; subst: the third story.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a compound of treis and stege as noun; a third roof (story).

DEFINITION: three thousand.
ORIGIN: From tris and chilioi; three times a thousand.

DEFINITION: third.
ORIGIN: Ordinal from treis; third; neuter (as noun) a third part, or (as adverb) a (or the) third time, thirdly.

DEFINITION: made of hair.
ORIGIN: From thrix; hairy, i.e. Made of hair (mohair).

DEFINITION: a trembling, quaking, fear.
ORIGIN: From tremo; a "trembling", i.e. Quaking with fear.

DEFINITION: a turning, change, mutation.
ORIGIN: From an apparently primary trepo to turn; a turn ("trope"), i.e. Revolution (figuratively, variation).

DEFINITION: (a) way, manner, (b) manner of life, character.
ORIGIN: From the same as trope; a turn, i.e. (by implication) mode or style (especially with preposition or relative prefix as adverb, like); figuratively, deportment or character.
USAGE: (even) as, conversation, (+ like) manner, (+ by any) means, way.

DEFINITION: to endure the ways of, put up with.
ORIGIN: From tropos and phoreo; to endure one's habits.

DEFINITION: food, nourishment, maintenance.
ORIGIN: From trepho; nourishment (literally or figuratively); by implication, rations (wages).

DEFINITION: Trophimus, a Christian of Ephesus in Asia.
ORIGIN: From trophe; nutritive; Trophimus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: a nurse.
ORIGIN: From trepho; a nourisher, i.e. Nurse.

DEFINITION: the track of a wheel, a track, path.
ORIGIN: From trochos; a track (as a wheel-rut), i.e. (figuratively) a course of conduct.

DEFINITION: a wheel, course.
ORIGIN: From trecho; a wheel (as a runner), i.e. (figuratively) a circuit of physical effects.

DEFINITION: a deep dish, platter, bowl.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of uncertain affinity; a bowl.

DEFINITION: to gather (as of grapes), harvest.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of trugo (to dry) meaning ripe fruit (as if dry); to collect the vintage.

DEFINITION: a turtle-dove.
ORIGIN: From truzo (to murmur; akin to trizo, but denoting a duller sound); a turtle-dove (as cooing).

DEFINITION: a hole, eye (of a needle).
ORIGIN: From a derivative of truo (to wear away; akin to the base of trauma, tribos and trogo); an orifice, i.e. Needle's eye.

DEFINITION: a hole; the eye of a needle.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of the base of trumalia; an aperture, i.e. A needle's eye.

DEFINITION: Tryphaena, a Christian woman in Rome.
ORIGIN: From truphe; luxurious; Tryphoena, a Christian woman.

DEFINITION: to live a luxurious life, live self-indulgently.
ORIGIN: From truphe; to indulge in luxury.

DEFINITION: effeminate luxury, softness, indulgent living.
ORIGIN: From thrupto (to break up or (figuratively) enfeeble, especially the mind and body by indulgence); effeminacy, i.e. Luxury or debauchery.

DEFINITION: Tryphosa, a Christian woman in Rome, perhaps a sister of Tryphaena.
ORIGIN: From truphe; luxuriating; Tryphosa, a Christian female.

DEFINITION: Troas, a city near the Hellespont (i.e. Dardanelles).
ORIGIN: From Tros (a Trojan); the Troad (or plain of Troy), i.e. Troas, a place in Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: Trogyllium, a promontory somewhat to the south of Ephesus.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; Trogyllium, a place in Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: to eat, partake of a meal.
ORIGIN: Probably strengthened from a collateral form of the base of trauma and tribos through the idea of corrosion or wear; or perhaps rather of a base of trugon and trizo through the idea of a craunching sound; to gnaw or chew, i.e. (generally) to eat.

DEFINITION: (a) gen: to obtain, (b) absol: to chance, happen; ordinary, everyday, it may chance, perhaps.
ORIGIN: Probably for an obsolete tucho (for which the middle voice of another alternate teucho (to make ready or bring to pass) is used in certain tenses; akin to the base of tikto through the idea of effecting; properly, to affect; or (specially), to hit or light upon (as a mark to be reached), i.e. (transitively) to attain or secure an object or end, or (intransitively) to happen (as if meeting with); but in the latter application only impersonal (with ei), i.e. Perchance; or (present participle) as adjective, usual (as if commonly met with, with ou, extraordinary), neuter (as adverb) perhaps; or (with another verb) as adverb, by accident (as it were).
USAGE: be, chance, enjoy, little, obtain, X refresh...self, + special. Compare tupto.

DEFINITION: to torture, break on the wheel, beat to death.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of tupto (meaning a drum, "tympanum"); to stretch on an instrument of torture resembling a drum, and thus beat to death.

DEFINITION: (originally: the mark of a blow, then a stamp struck by a die), (a) a figure; a copy, image, (b) a pattern, model, (c) a type, prefiguring something or somebody.
ORIGIN: From tupto; a die (as struck), i.e. (by implication) a stamp or scar; by analogy, a shape, i.e. A statue, (figuratively) style or resemblance; specially, a sampler ("type"), i.e. A model (for imitation) or instance (for warning).
USAGE: en-(ex-)ample, fashion, figure, form, manner, pattern, print.

DEFINITION: to beat, strike, wound, inflict punishment.
ORIGIN: A primary verb (in a strengthened form); to "thump", i.e. Cudgel or pummel (properly, with a stick or bastinado), but in any case by repeated blows; thus differing from paio and patasso, which denote a (usually single) blow with the hand or any instrument, or plesso with the fist (or a hammer), or rhapizo with the palm; as well as from tugchano, an accidental collision); by implication, to punish; figuratively, to offend (the conscience).

DEFINITION: Tyrannus, an inhabitant of Ephesus, probably a rhetorician.
ORIGIN: A provincial form of the derivative of the base of kurios; a "tyrant"; Tyrannus, an Ephesian.

DEFINITION: to agitate or disturb in mind, trouble.
ORIGIN: From turbe (Latin turba, a crowd; akin to thorubos); to make "turbid", i.e. Disturb.

DEFINITION: a Tyrian, an inhabitant of Tyre.
ORIGIN: From Turos; a Tyrian, i.e. Inhabitant of Tyrus.

DEFINITION: Tyre, an ancient city, the capital of Phoenicia.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Tsor): Tyrus (i.e. Tsor), a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: blind, physically or mentally.
ORIGIN: From, tuphoo; opaque (as if smoky), i.e. (by analogy) blind (physically or mentally).

DEFINITION: to make blind, physically or mentally.
ORIGIN: From tuphlos; to make blind, i.e. (figuratively) to obscure.

DEFINITION: to puff up, make haughty; pass: to be puffed up, be haughty.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of tupho; to envelop with smoke, i.e. (figuratively) to inflate with self-conceit.
USAGE: high-minded, be lifted up with pride, be proud.

DEFINITION: to raise smoke, smolder.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to make a smoke, i.e. Slowly consume without flame.

DEFINITION: violent, tempestuous, stormy.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of tupho; stormy (as if smoky).

DEFINITION: Tychicus, a Christian of the Roman province Asia.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of tugchano; fortuitous, i.e. Fortunate; Tychicus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: dark purple or blue, of the color of hyacinth.
ORIGIN: From huakinthos; "hyacinthine" or "jacinthine", i.e. Deep blue.

DEFINITION: jacinth, a precious stone of the color of hyacinth.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; the "hyacinth" or "jacinth", i.e. Some gem of a deep blue color, probably the zirkon.

DEFINITION: glassy, made of glass, transparent.
ORIGIN: From hualos; glassy, i.e. Transparent.

DEFINITION: glass, crystal, clear transparent stone.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from the same as huetos (as being transparent like rain); glass.

DEFINITION: to run riot, to outrage, insult.
ORIGIN: From hubris; to exercise violence, i.e. Abuse.

DEFINITION: wantonness, insolence, an act of wanton violence.
ORIGIN: From huper; insolence (as over-bearing), i.e. Insult, injury.

DEFINITION: an insolent, insulting, or violent man.
ORIGIN: From hubrizo; an insulter, i.e. Maltreater.

DEFINITION: to be well, be in good health; to be right, reasonable, sound, pure, uncorrupted.
ORIGIN: From hugies; to have sound health, i.e. Be well (in body); figuratively, to be uncorrupt (true in doctrine).
USAGE: be in health, (be safe and) sound, (be) whole(-some).

DEFINITION: (a) sound, healthy, pure, whole, (b) wholesome.
ORIGIN: From the base of auzano; healthy, i.e. Well (in body); figuratively, true (in doctrine).

DEFINITION: wet, moist, of wood sappy.
ORIGIN: From the base of huetos; wet (as if with rain), i.e. (by implication) sappy (fresh).

DEFINITION: a water pot, a pot or jar.
ORIGIN: From hudor; a water-jar, i.e. Receptacle for family supply.

DEFINITION: to be only a water drinker.
ORIGIN: From a compound of hudor and a derivative of pino; to be a water-drinker, i.e. To abstain from vinous beverages.

DEFINITION: afflicted with dropsy.
ORIGIN: From a compound of hudor and a derivative of optanomai (as if looking watery); to be "dropsical".

DEFINITION: water.
ORIGIN: And genitive case, hudatos (hoo'-dat-os), etc. From the base of huetos; water (as if rainy) literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: rain.
ORIGIN: From a primary huo (to rain); rain, especially a shower.

DEFINITION: adoption, as a son into the divine family.
ORIGIN: From a presumed compound of huios and a derivative of tithemi; the placing as a son, i.e. Adoption (figuratively, Christian sonship in respect to God).

DEFINITION: a son, descendent.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a "son" (sometimes of animals), used very widely of immediate, remote or figuratively, kinship.

DEFINITION: wood, timber, forest.
ORIGIN: Perhaps akin to xulon; a forest, i.e. (by implication) fuel.

DEFINITION: you.
ORIGIN: Accusative case of humeis; you (as the objective of a verb or preposition).

DEFINITION: you.
ORIGIN: Irregular plural of su; you (as subjective of verb).

DEFINITION: Hymenaeus, a heretical teacher at Ephesus.
ORIGIN: From Humen (the god of weddings); "hymeneal"; Hymeneus, an opponent of Christianity.

DEFINITION: your, yours.
ORIGIN: From humeis; yours, i.e. Pertaining to you.

DEFINITION: you.
ORIGIN: Irregular dative case of humeis; to (with or by) you.

DEFINITION: to sing, sing hymns to, praise.
ORIGIN: From humnos; to hymn, i.e. Sing a religious ode; by implication, to celebrate (God) in song.

DEFINITION: a hymn, sacred song, song of praise to God.
ORIGIN: Apparently from a simpler (obsolete) form of hudeo (to celebrate; probably akin to aido; compare abowt); a "hymn" or religious ode (one of the Psalms).

DEFINITION: you.
ORIGIN: Genitive case of humeis; of (from or concerning) you.

DEFINITION: to lead or bring under, to lead on slowly, to depart.
ORIGIN: From hupo and ago; to lead (oneself) under, i.e. Withdraw or retire (as if sinking out of sight), literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: obedience, submissiveness, compliance.
ORIGIN: From hupakouo; attentive hearkening, i.e. (by implication) compliance or submission.

DEFINITION: to listen, hearken to, obey, answer.
ORIGIN: From hupo and akouo; to hear under (as a subordinate), i.e. To listen attentively; by implication, to heed or conform to a command or authority.

DEFINITION: under the power of or subject to a man.
ORIGIN: From hupo and aner; in subjection under a man, i.e. A married woman.

DEFINITION: to go to meet, to meet.
ORIGIN: From hupo and a derivative of anti; to go opposite (meet) under (quietly), i.e. To encounter, fall in with.

DEFINITION: a going to meet.
ORIGIN: From hupantao; an encounter or concurrence (with eis for infinitive, in order to fall in with).

DEFINITION: goods, substance, property, possessions.
ORIGIN: From huparcho; existency or proprietorship, i.e. (concretely) property, wealth.

DEFINITION: goods, that which one has, things which one possesseth, substance, that hast.
ORIGIN: Neuter plural of present participle active of huparcho as noun; things extant or in hand, i.e. Property or possessions.
USAGE: goods, that which one has, things which (one) possesseth, substance, that hast.

DEFINITION: to begin, to be ready or at hand, to be.
ORIGIN: From hupo and archomai; to begin under (quietly), i.e. Come into existence (be present or at hand); expletively, to exist (as copula or subordinate to an adjective, participle, adverb or preposition, or as an auxiliary to a principal (verb).

DEFINITION: to yield, submit to authority.
ORIGIN: From hupo and eiko (to yield, be "weak"); to surrender.

DEFINITION: opposite to, adverse; subst: an adversary.
ORIGIN: From hupo and enantios; under (covertly) contrary to, i.e. Opposed or (as noun) an opponent.

DEFINITION: over, beyond, on behalf of, for the sake of, concerning.
ORIGIN: A primary preposition; "over", i.e. (with the genitive case) of place, above, beyond, across, or causal, for the sake of, instead, regarding; with the accusative case superior to, more than.
USAGE: (+ exceeding, abundantly) above, in (on) behalf of, beyond, by, + very chiefest, concerning, exceeding (above, -ly), for, + very highly, more (than), of, over, on the part of, for sake of, in stead, than, to(-ward), very. In the comparative, it retains many of the above applications.

DEFINITION: lit: to raise beyond, uplift; mid: to lift myself up, exalt myself, be arrogant.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from huper and airo; to raise oneself over, i.e. (figuratively) to become haughty.
USAGE: exalt self, be exalted above measure.

DEFINITION: past the bloom of youth, of full age.
ORIGIN: From huper and the base of akmen; beyond the "acme", i.e. Figuratively (of a daughter) past the bloom (prime) of youth.

DEFINITION: (high) above.
ORIGIN: From huper and ano; above upward, i.e. Greatly higher (in place or rank).

DEFINITION: to increase exceedingly or beyond measure.
ORIGIN: From huper and auzano; to increase above ordinary degree.

DEFINITION: to transgress; to go beyond, overreach, defraud.
ORIGIN: From huper and the base of basis; to transcend, i.e. (figuratively) to overreach.

DEFINITION: beyond measure.
ORIGIN: Adverb from present participle active of huperballo; excessively.

DEFINITION: to throw over or beyond, to run beyond.
ORIGIN: From huper and ballo; to throw beyod the usual mark, i.e. (figuratively) to surpass (only active participle supereminent).

DEFINITION: excess, surpassing excellence, preeminence; adv: exceedingly.
ORIGIN: From huperballo; a throwing beyond others, i.e. (figuratively) supereminence; adverbially (with eis or kata) pre- eminently.
USAGE: abundance, (far more) exceeding, excellency, more excellent, beyond (out of) measure.

DEFINITION: to overlook, take no notice of, disregard.
ORIGIN: From huper and eido; to overlook, i.e. Not punish.

DEFINITION: beyond.
ORIGIN: From huper and the neuter plural of ekeinos; above those parts, i.e. Still farther.

DEFINITION: to over-stretch, stretch out beyond the measure assigned to me.
ORIGIN: From huper and ekteino; to extend inordinately.

DEFINITION: to pour out so that it overflows.
ORIGIN: From huper and the alternate form of ekcheo; to pour out over, i.e. (passively) to overflow.

DEFINITION: to intercede for, make petition for.
ORIGIN: From huper and entugchano; to intercede in behalf of.

DEFINITION: to hold above, to rise above, to be superior.
ORIGIN: From huper and echo; to hold oneself above, i.e. (figuratively) to excel; participle (as adjective, or neuter as noun) superior, superiority.

DEFINITION: pride, arrogance, disdain.
ORIGIN: From huperephanos; haughtiness.

DEFINITION: showing oneself above others.
ORIGIN: From huper and phaino; appearing above others (conspicuous), i.e. (figuratively) haughty.

DEFINITION: to be more than conqueror, prevail mightily.
ORIGIN: From huper and nikao; to vanquish beyond, i.e. Gain a decisive victory.

DEFINITION: immoderate, boastful, excessive, pompous.
ORIGIN: From huper and ogkos; bulging over, i.e. (figuratively) insolent.

DEFINITION: superiority, excellence, preeminence, authority.
ORIGIN: From huperecho; prominence, i.e. (figuratively) superiority (in rank or character).

DEFINITION: (a) intrans: to abound exceedingly, (b) dep: to overflow.
ORIGIN: From huper and perisseuo; to super-abound.

DEFINITION: superabundantly, beyond measure.
ORIGIN: From huper and perissos; superabundantly, i.e. Exceedingly.

DEFINITION: to abound exceedingly, be exceedingly abundant.
ORIGIN: From huper and pleonazo; to superabound.

DEFINITION: to exalt beyond measure.
ORIGIN: From huper and hupsoo; to elevate above others, i.e. Raise to the highest position.

DEFINITION: to be overly proud, to have high thoughts.
ORIGIN: From huper and phroneo; to esteem oneself overmuch, i.e. Be vain or arrogant.

DEFINITION: an upper room, the upper part of a house.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of huper; a higher part of the house, i.e. Apartment in the third story.

DEFINITION: to hold or put under, to undergo.
ORIGIN: From hupo and echo; to hold oneself under, i.e. Endure with patience.

DEFINITION: listening to, obedient, submissive.
ORIGIN: From hupakouo; attentively listening, i.e. (by implication) submissive.

DEFINITION: to serve as a rower, to minister to, serve.
ORIGIN: From huperetes; to be a subordinate, i.e. (by implication) subserve.

DEFINITION: a servant, an attendant, (a) an officer, lictor, (b) an attendant in a synagogue, (c) a minister of the gospel.
ORIGIN: From hupo and a derivative of eresso (to row); an under-oarsman, i.e. (generally) subordinate (assistant, sexton, constable).

DEFINITION: sleep; fig: spiritual sleep.
ORIGIN: From an obsolete primary (perhaps akin to hupo through the idea of subsilience); sleep, i.e. (figuratively) spiritual torpor.

DEFINITION: by, under, about.
ORIGIN: A primary preposition; under, i.e. (with the genitive case) of place (beneath), or with verbs (the agency or means, through); (with the accusative case) of place (whither (underneath) or where (below) or time (when (at)).
USAGE: among, by, from, in, of, under, with. In the comparative, it retains the same general applications, especially of inferior position or condition, and specially, covertly or moderately.
