DEFINITION: to throw or put under; met: to subject, submit, suggest, whisper, prompt, suborn, instigate.
ORIGIN: From hupo and ballo; to throw in stealthily, i.e. Introduce by collusion.

DEFINITION: a writing-copy, an example, pattern.
ORIGIN: From a compound of hupo and grapho; an underwriting, i.e. Copy for imitation (figuratively).

DEFINITION: (a) a figure, copy, (b) an example, model.
ORIGIN: From hupodeiknumi; an exhibit for imitation or warning (figuratively, specimen, adumbration).

DEFINITION: to show secretly, to show by tracing out, to teach, make known.
ORIGIN: From hupo and deiknuo; to exhibit under the eyes, i.e. (figuratively) to exemplify (instruct, admonish).

DEFINITION: to receive as a guest, entertain hospitably, welcome.
ORIGIN: From hupo and dechomai; to admit under one's roof, i.e. Entertain hospitably.

DEFINITION: (lit: to bind under), mid: to put on feet, pass: to be shod.
ORIGIN: From hupo and deo; to bind under one's feet, i.e. Put on shoes or sandals.

DEFINITION: a sole bound under (the foot), a sandal.
ORIGIN: From hupodeo; something bound under the feet, i.e. A shoe or sandal.

DEFINITION: answerable to, liable to (brought under) the judgment of.
ORIGIN: From hupo and dike; under sentence, i.e. (by implication) condemned.

DEFINITION: a beast of burden, an ass or mule.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a compound of hupo and zugos; an animal under the yoke (draught-beast), i.e. (specially), a donkey.

DEFINITION: to under-gird, as to strengthen a ship against the waves.
ORIGIN: From hupo and zonnumi; to gird under, i.e. Frap (a vessel with cables across the keel, sides and deck).

DEFINITION: underneath, below, under.
ORIGIN: From hupo and kato; down under, i.e. Beneath.

DEFINITION: to answer, reply, to answer on a stage, to pretend.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from hupo and krino; to decide (speak or act) under a false part, i.e. (figuratively) dissemble (pretend).

DEFINITION: (lit: stage-playing), a response, answer, hypocrisy, dissembling.
ORIGIN: From hupokrinomai; acting under a feigned part, i.e. (figuratively) deceit ("hypocrisy").

DEFINITION: (lit: a stage-player), a hypocrite, dissembler, pretender.
ORIGIN: From hupokrinomai; an actor under an assumed character (stage-player), i.e. (figuratively) a dissembler ("hypocrite".

DEFINITION: (a) to take up, (b) to welcome, entertain, (c) to answer, (d) to suppose, imagine.
ORIGIN: From hupo and lambano; to take from below, i.e. Carry upward; figuratively, to take up, i.e. Continue a discourse or topic; mentally, to assume (presume).

DEFINITION: to leave behind; pass: to be left surviving.
ORIGIN: From hupotrecho and leipo; to leave under (behind), i.e. (passively) to remain (survive).

DEFINITION: a vessel or trough beneath a winepress (to receive the juice).
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed compound of hupo and lenos; vessel or receptacle under the press, i.e. Lower wine-vat.

DEFINITION: to leave behind.
ORIGIN: A prolonged form for hupoleipo; to leave behind, i.e. Bequeath.

DEFINITION: (a) to remain behind, (b) to stand ground, show endurance, (c) to endure, bear up against, persevere.
ORIGIN: From hupo and meno; to stay under (behind), i.e. Remain; figuratively, to undergo, i.e. Bear (trials), have fortitude, persevere.
USAGE: abide, endure, (take) patient(-ly), suffer, tarry behind.

DEFINITION: to remind; pass: to remember, call to mind.
ORIGIN: From hupo and mimnesko; to remind quietly, i.e. Suggest to the (middle voice, one's own) memory.
USAGE: put in mind, remember, bring to (put in) remembrance.

DEFINITION: remembrance, recollection, putting in mind; a reminder.
ORIGIN: From hupomimnesko; a reminding or (reflexively) recollection.

DEFINITION: endurance, steadfastness, patient waiting for.
ORIGIN: From hupomeno; cheerful (or hopeful) endurance, constancy.

DEFINITION: to conjecture, suppose, suspect, deem.
ORIGIN: From hupo and noieo; to think under (privately), i.e. To surmise or conjecture.

DEFINITION: a supposition, suspicion.
ORIGIN: From huponoeo; suspicion.

DEFINITION: to sail under (i.e. under the lee of).
ORIGIN: From hupo and pleo; to sail under the lee of.

DEFINITION: to blow underneath.
ORIGIN: From hupo and pneo; to breathe gently, i.e. Breeze.

DEFINITION: a footstool.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a compound of hupo and pous; something under the feet, i.e. A foot-rest (figuratively).

DEFINITION: (lit: an underlying), (a) confidence, assurance, (b) a giving substance (or reality) to, or a guaranteeing, (c) substance, reality.
ORIGIN: From a compound of hupo and histemi; a setting under (support), i.e. (figuratively) concretely, essence, or abstractly, assurance (objectively or subjectively).

DEFINITION: to withdraw, draw back, keep back, shun, conceal.
ORIGIN: From hupo and stello; to withhold under (out of sight), i.e. (reflexively) to cower or shrink, (figuratively) to conceal (reserve).

DEFINITION: a letting down, a shrinking back.
ORIGIN: From hupostello; shrinkage (timidity), i.e. (by implication) apostasy.

DEFINITION: to turn back, return.
ORIGIN: From hupo and strepho; to turn under (behind), i.e. To return (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: come again, return (again, back again), turn back (again).

DEFINITION: to spread under, strew under.
ORIGIN: From hupo and stronnumi; to strew underneath (the feet as a carpet).

DEFINITION: subjection, submission, obedience.
ORIGIN: From hupotasso; subordination.

DEFINITION: to place under, subject to; mid, pass: to submit, put myself into subjection.
ORIGIN: From hupo and tasso; to subordinate; reflexively, to obey.
USAGE: be under obedience (obedient), put under, subdue unto, (be, make) subject (to, unto), be (put) in subjection (to, under), submit self unto.

DEFINITION: to put under, lay down, suggest to, put in mind.
ORIGIN: From hupo and tithemi; to place underneath, i.e. (figuratively) to hazard, (reflexively) to suggest.

DEFINITION: to run under shelter of.
ORIGIN: From hupo and trecho (including its alternate); to run under, i.e. (specially), to sail past.

DEFINITION: a pattern, example; a form, sample.
ORIGIN: From a compound of hupo and a derivative of tupos; typification under (after), i.e. (concretely) a sketch (figuratively) for imitation.

DEFINITION: to bear by being under, to endure.
ORIGIN: From hupo and phero; to bear from underneath, i.e. (figuratively) to undergo hardship.

DEFINITION: to withdraw, retire, go back, retreat.
ORIGIN: From hupo and choreo; to vacate down, i.e. Retire quietly.

DEFINITION: to strike under the eye, hence: to bruise, treat severely, discipline by hardship, molest, annoy, harass, worry, exhaust.
ORIGIN: From a compound of hupo and a derivative of optanomai; to hit under the eye (buffet or disable an antagonist as a pugilist), i.e. (figuratively) to tease or annoy (into compliance), subdue (one's passions).

DEFINITION: a hog, boar, or sow.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a hog ("swine").

DEFINITION: hyssop, a stalk or stem of hyssop.
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin ('ezowb); "hyssop".

DEFINITION: to fall behind, be lacking, fall short, suffer need, be inferior to.
ORIGIN: From husteros; to be later, i.e. (by implication) to be inferior; generally, to fall short (be deficient).
USAGE: come behind (short), be destitute, fail, lack, suffer need, (be in) want, be the worse.

DEFINITION: (a) of things or persons: that which is lacking, a defect or shortcoming, (b) want, poverty.
ORIGIN: From hustereo; a deficit; specially, poverty.
USAGE: that which is behind, (that which was) lack(-ing), penury, want.

DEFINITION: poverty, want, need.
ORIGIN: A falling short, i.e. (specially), penury.

DEFINITION: lastly, afterward, later.
ORIGIN: Neuter of husteros as adverb; more lately, i.e. Eventually.

DEFINITION: later, latter, last.
ORIGIN: Comparative from hupo (in the sense of behind); later.

DEFINITION: woven.
ORIGIN: From huphaino to weave; woven, i.e. (perhaps) knitted.

DEFINITION: high, lofty.
ORIGIN: From hupsos; lofty (in place or character).

DEFINITION: to be high-minded, proud.
ORIGIN: From a compound of hupselos and phren; to be lofty in mind, i.e. Arrogant.

DEFINITION: highest, most high, the heights.
ORIGIN: Superlative from the base of hupsos; highest, i.e. (masculine singular) the Supreme (God), or (neuter plural) the heavens.

DEFINITION: height, heaven; dignity, eminence.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of huper; elevation, i.e. (abstractly) altitude, (specially), the sky, or (figuratively) dignity.

DEFINITION: (a) to raise on high, lift up, (b) to exalt, set on high.
ORIGIN: From hupsos; to elevate (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: height, barrier, bulwark; presumption.
ORIGIN: From hupsoo; an elevated place or thing, i.e. (abstractly) altitude, or (by implication) a barrier (figuratively).

DEFINITION: a glutton.
ORIGIN: From phago; a glutton.

DEFINITION: to eat, partake of food; met: to devour, consume (e.g. as rust does); used only in fut. and 2nd aor. tenses.
ORIGIN: A primary verb (used as an alternate of esthio in certain tenses); to eat (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: (a) act: to shine, shed light, (b) pass: to shine, become visible, appear, (c) to become clear, appear, seem, show myself as.
ORIGIN: Prolongation for the base of phos; to lighten (shine), i.e. Show (transitive or intransitive, literal or figurative).
USAGE: appear, seem, be seen, shine, X think.

DEFINITION: Peleg, son of Eber, and one of the ancestors of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Peleg); Phalek (i.e. Peleg), a patriarch.

DEFINITION: apparent, clear, visible, manifest; adv: clearly.
ORIGIN: From phaino; shining, i.e. Apparent (literally or figuratively); neuter (as adverb) publicly, externally.
USAGE: abroad, + appear, known, manifest, open (+ -ly), outward (+ -ly).

DEFINITION: to make clear (visible, manifest), make known.
ORIGIN: From phaneros; to render apparent (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: clearly, openly, manifestly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from phaneros; plainly, i.e. Clearly or publicly.

DEFINITION: a manifestation, disclosure.
ORIGIN: From phaneroo; exhibition, i.e. (figuratively) expression, (by extension) a bestowment.

DEFINITION: a torch, lantern, light.
ORIGIN: From phaino; a lightener, i.e. Light; lantern.

DEFINITION: Phanuel, father of Anna the prophetess.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Pnuw'el); Phanuel (i.e. Penuel), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: to make visible, to become visible.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of phaino; to make apparent, i.e. (passively) to appear (neuter participle as noun, a spectacle).

DEFINITION: show, display, pomp, imagination.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of phantazo; (properly abstract) a (vain) show ("fantasy").

DEFINITION: an apparition, ghost, spirit, phantom.
ORIGIN: From phantazo; (properly concrete) a (mere) show ("phantasm"), i.e. Spectre.

DEFINITION: a valley, ravine, chasm, cleft.
ORIGIN: Properly, strengthened from the base of peran or rather of rhegnumi; a gap or chasm, i.e. Ravine (winter-torrent).

DEFINITION: Pharaoh, the title of ancient Egyptian kings.
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin (Par'oh); Pharao (i.e. Pharoh), an Egyptian king.

DEFINITION: Perez, son of Judah and one of the ancestors of Jesus.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Perets); Phares (i.e. Perets), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: a Pharisee, member of a Jewish religious sect.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (compare parash); a separatist, i.e. Exclusively religious; a Pharisean, i.e. Jewish sectary.

DEFINITION: the use of medicine, drugs or spells.
ORIGIN: From pharmakeus; medication ("pharmacy"), i.e. (by extension) magic (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: sorcerer.
ORIGIN: From pharmakon (a drug, i.e. Spell-giving potion); a druggist ("pharmacist") or poisoner, i.e. (by extension) a magician.

DEFINITION: a poisoner, sorcerer, magician.
ORIGIN: The same as pharmakeus.

DEFINITION: report, tidings, information.
ORIGIN: From phemi (not the same as "phase", which is from phaino); a saying, i.e. Report.

DEFINITION: to assert, affirm, profess.
ORIGIN: Prolongation from the same as phemi; to assert.

DEFINITION: a manger, feeding-trough, stall.
ORIGIN: From pateomai (to eat); a crib (for fodder).

DEFINITION: worthless, wicked, base.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; "foul" or "flawy", i.e. (figuratively) wicked.

DEFINITION: brightness, light, splendor, radiance.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to the base of phos (compare phtheggomai); brilliancy.

DEFINITION: to spare, abstain, forbear.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; to be chary of, i.e. (subjectively) to abstain or (objectively) to treat leniently.

DEFINITION: sparingly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from participle of pheidomai; abstemiously, i.e. Stingily.

DEFINITION: a mantle, cloak.
ORIGIN: By transposition for a derivative probably of phaino (as showing outside the other garments); a mantle (surtout).

DEFINITION: to carry, bear, bring; to conduct, lead; perhaps: to make publicly known.
ORIGIN: A primary verb.
USAGE: for which other, and apparently not cognate ones are used in certain tenses only; namely, oio (oy'-o); and enegko (en-eng'-ko) to "bear" or carry (in a very wide application, literally and figuratively, as follows)

DEFINITION: to flee, escape, shun.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to run away (literally or figuratively); by implication, to shun; by analogy, to vanish.

DEFINITION: Felix, third name of (Marcus) Antonius Felix, procurator of the Roman province Judea from an uncertain date (before A.D. 52 ?) till A.D. 59.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; happy; Phelix (i.e. Felix), a Roman.

DEFINITION: a report, fame, saying.
ORIGIN: From phemi; a saying, i.e. Rumor ("fame").

DEFINITION: to declare, say.
ORIGIN: Properly, the same as the base of phos and phaino; to show or make known one's thoughts, i.e. Speak or say.

DEFINITION: Festus, a governor of Judea.
ORIGIN: Of Latin derivation; festal; Phestus (i.e. Festus), a Roman.

DEFINITION: (a) to anticipate, precede, (b) to come, arrive.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to be beforehand, i.e. Anticipate or precede; by extension, to have arrived at.

DEFINITION: perishable, corruptible.
ORIGIN: From phtheiro; decayed, i.e. (by implication) perishable.

DEFINITION: to speak aloud, utter.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to pheggos and thus to phemi; to utter a clear sound, i.e. (generally) to proclaim.

DEFINITION: to corrupt, spoil, destroy, ruin.
ORIGIN: Probably strengthened from phthio (to pine or waste); properly, to shrivel or wither, i.e. To spoil (by any process) or (generally) to ruin (especially figuratively, by moral influences, to deprave).

DEFINITION: autumnal, in autumn, when fruit is expected.
ORIGIN: From derivative of phthino (to wane; akin to the base of phtheiro) and opora (meaning late autumn); autumnal (as stripped of leaves).

DEFINITION: a sound.
ORIGIN: From phtheggomai; utterance, i.e. A musical note (vocal or instrumental).

DEFINITION: to envy.
ORIGIN: From phthonos; to be jealous of.

DEFINITION: envy, a grudge, spite.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to the base of phtheiro; ill-will (as detraction), i.e. Jealousy (spite).

DEFINITION: corruption, destruction, decay, rottenness, decomposition.
ORIGIN: From phtheiro; decay, i.e. Ruin (spontaneous or inflicted, literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: a shallow and flat bowl.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain affinity; a broad shallow cup ("phial").

DEFINITION: loving that which is good.
ORIGIN: From philos and agathos; fond to good, i.e. A promoter of virtue.

DEFINITION: Philadelphia, a city of the Roman province Asia.
ORIGIN: From Philadelphos (the same as philadelphos), a king of Pergamos; Philadelphia, a place in Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: brotherly love, love of Christian brethren.
ORIGIN: From philadelphos; fraternal affection.
USAGE: brotherly love (kindness), love of the brethren.

DEFINITION: loving like a brother, loving one's brethren.
ORIGIN: From philos and adephos; fond of brethren, i.e. Fraternal.

DEFINITION: loving men, (of a wife) loving her husband.
ORIGIN: From philos and aner; fond of man, i.e. Affectionate as a wife.

DEFINITION: love of mankind, benevolence.
ORIGIN: From the same as philanthropos; fondness of mankind, i.e. Benevolence ("philanthropy").

DEFINITION: humanely, kindly.
ORIGIN: Adverb from a compound of philos and anthropos; fondly to man ("philanthropically"), i.e. Humanely.

DEFINITION: love of money, avarice, covetousness.
ORIGIN: From philarguros; avarice.

DEFINITION: money-loving, avaricious, covetous.
ORIGIN: From philos and arguros; fond of silver (money), i.e. Avaricious.

DEFINITION: self-loving, selfish.
ORIGIN: From philos and autos; fond of self, i.e. Selfish.

DEFINITION: to love (of friendship), regard with affection, cherish; to kiss.
ORIGIN: From philos; to be a friend to (fond of (an individual or an object)), i.e. Have affection for (denoting personal attachment, as a matter of sentiment or feeling; while agapao is wider, embracing especially the judgment and the deliberate assent of the will as a matter of principle, duty and propriety: the two thus stand related very much as ethelo and boulomai, or as thumos and nous respectively; the former being chiefly of the heart and the latter of the head); specially, to kiss (as a mark of tenderness).

DEFINITION: loving pleasure.
ORIGIN: From philos and hedone; fond of pleasure, i.e. Voluptuous.

DEFINITION: a kiss.
ORIGIN: From phileo; a kiss.

DEFINITION: Philemon, a Christian man of Colossae.
ORIGIN: From phileo; friendly; Philemon, a Christian.

DEFINITION: "worthy of love", Philetus, an erring Christian at Ephesus.
ORIGIN: From phileo; amiable; Philetus, an opposer of Christianity.

DEFINITION: friendship, affection, fondness, love.
ORIGIN: From philos; fondness.

DEFINITION: a Philippian, an inhabitant of Philippi.
ORIGIN: From Philippoi; a Philippesian (Philippian), i.e. Native of Philippi.

DEFINITION: Philippi, a great city of the Roman province Macedonia.
ORIGIN: Plural of Philippos; Philippi, a place in Macedonia.

DEFINITION: Philip, (a) one of the twelve apostles of Jesus, (b) tetrarch of the Ituraean and Trachonitic region, half-brother of Herod Antipas, tetrarch of Galilee, (c) one of the seven original deacons at Jerusalem and a missionary.
ORIGIN: From philos and hippos; fond of horses; Philippus, the name of four Israelites.

DEFINITION: loving God.
ORIGIN: From philos and theos; fond of God, i.e. Pious.

DEFINITION: "student, scholar", Philologus, a Christian.
ORIGIN: From philos and logos; fond of words, i.e. Talkative (argumentative, learned, "philological"); Philologus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: love of dispute, contention.
ORIGIN: From philoneikos; quarrelsomeness, i.e. A dispute.

DEFINITION: strife-loving, contentious.
ORIGIN: From philos and neikos (a quarrel; probably akin to nikos); fond of strife, i.e. Disputatious.

DEFINITION: love to strangers, hospitality.
ORIGIN: From philoxenos; hospitableness.

DEFINITION: hospitable, loving strangers.
ORIGIN: From philos and xenos; fond of guests, i.e. Hospitable.

DEFINITION: to love the chief place, desire preeminence.
ORIGIN: From a compound of philos and protos; to be fond of being first, i.e. Ambitious of distinction.

DEFINITION: friendly; subst: a friend, an associate.
ORIGIN: Properly, dear, i.e. A friend; actively, fond, i.e. Friendly (still as a noun, an associate, neighbor, etc.).

DEFINITION: love of wisdom, philosophy, in the NT of traditional Jewish theology.
ORIGIN: From philosophos; "philosophy", i.e. (specially), Jewish sophistry.

DEFINITION: a philosopher.
ORIGIN: From philos and sophos; fond of wise things, i.e. A "philosopher".

DEFINITION: tenderly loving, kindly affectionate to.
ORIGIN: From philos and storge (cherishing one's kindred, especially parents or children); fond of natural relatives, i.e. Fraternal towards fellow Christian.

DEFINITION: loving one's children.
ORIGIN: From philos and teknon; fond of one's children, i.e. Maternal.

DEFINITION: to be zealous, strive eagerly, desire very strongly.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from a compound of philos and time; to be fond of honor, i.e. Emulous (eager or earnest to do something).

DEFINITION: kindly, in a friendly manner.
ORIGIN: Adverb from philophron; with friendliness of mind, i.e. Kindly.

DEFINITION: friendly, kindly, courteous.
ORIGIN: From philos and phren; friendly of mind, i.e. Kind.

DEFINITION: to muzzle, to put to silence.
ORIGIN: From phimos (a muzzle); to muzzle.

DEFINITION: Phlegon, a Roman Christian man.
ORIGIN: Active participle of the base of phlox; blazing; Phlegon, a Christian.

DEFINITION: to inflame, fire with passion, set on fire, burn up.
ORIGIN: From phlox (g5395); to cause a blaze, i.e. Ignite (figuratively, to inflame with passion).

DEFINITION: a flame.
ORIGIN: From a primary phlego (to "flash" or "flame"); a blaze.

DEFINITION: to gossip against, talk idly, make empty charges against, talk nonsense.
ORIGIN: From phluaros; to be a babbler or trifler, i.e. (by implication) to berate idly or mischievously.

DEFINITION: prating, talking foolishly, babbling.
ORIGIN: From phluo (to bubble); a garrulous person, i.e. Prater.

DEFINITION: fearful, dreadful, terrible.
ORIGIN: From phobos; frightful, i.e. (objectively) formidable.

DEFINITION: to fear, dread, reverence, be afraid, terrified.
ORIGIN: From phobos; to frighten, i.e. (passively) to be alarmed; by analogy, to be in awe of, i.e. Revere.

DEFINITION: a terrible sight, cause of terror, an object of fear.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of phobeo; a frightening thing, i.e. Terrific portent.

DEFINITION: (a) fear, terror, alarm, (b) the object or cause of fear, (c) reverence, respect.
ORIGIN: From a primary phebomai (to be put in fear); alarm or fright.

DEFINITION: Phoebe, a Christian woman in the church at Cenchreae.
ORIGIN: Feminine of phoibos (bright; probably akin to the base of phos); Phoebe, a Christian woman.

DEFINITION: Phoenicia, a northern coast strip of the Roman province Syria.
ORIGIN: From phoinix; palm-country; Phoenice (or Phoenicia), a region of Palestine.

DEFINITION: a palm tree, the date-palm.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a palm-tree.

DEFINITION: a Phoenician (an inhabitant of Phoenicia), Phoenix (a city of Crete).
ORIGIN: Probably the same as phoinix; Phoenix, a place in Crete.

DEFINITION: a murderer.
ORIGIN: From phonos; a murderer (always of criminal (or at least intentional) homicide; which anthropoktonos does not necessarily imply; while sikarios is a special term for a public bandit).

DEFINITION: to kill, murder.
ORIGIN: From phoneus; to be a murderer (of).

DEFINITION: murder, slaughter, killing.
ORIGIN: From an obsolete primary pheno (to slay); murder.

DEFINITION: to carry, wear, bear constantly.
ORIGIN: From phoros; to have a burden, i.e. (by analogy) to wear as clothing or a constant accompaniment.

DEFINITION: (of Latin origin), Forum, Market, Market-Town.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; a forum or market-place; only in comparative with Appios; a station on the Appian road.

DEFINITION: a tax, tribute, especially on persons.
ORIGIN: From phero; a load (as borne), i.e. (figuratively) a tax (properly, an individual assessment on persons or property; whereas telos is usually a general toll on goods or travel).

DEFINITION: to load, burden; pass: to be laden.
ORIGIN: From phortos; to load up (properly, as a vessel or animal), i.e. (figuratively) to overburden with ceremony (or spiritual anxiety).

DEFINITION: a burden; the freight of a ship.
ORIGIN: Diminutive of phortos; an invoice (as part of freight), i.e. (figuratively) a task or service.

DEFINITION: cargo.
ORIGIN: From phero; something carried, i.e. The cargo of a ship.

DEFINITION: "prosperous, lucky", Fortunatus, a Christian.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; "fortunate"; Fortunatus, a Christian.

DEFINITION: a scourge, lash, whip.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative from the base of phragelloo; a whip, i.e. Roman lash as a public punishment.

DEFINITION: to flagellate, scourge.
ORIGIN: From a presumed equivalent of the Latin flagellum; to whip, i.e. Lash as a public punishment.

DEFINITION: a hedge, fence, partition.
ORIGIN: From phrasso; a fence, or inclosing barrier (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to declare, explain, interpret.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to phrasso through the idea of defining; to indicate (by word or act), i.e. (specially), to expound.

DEFINITION: to stop, close up, obstruct.
ORIGIN: Apparently a strengthening form of the base of phren; to fence or inclose, i.e. (specially), to block up (figuratively, to silence).

DEFINITION: a pit, well, cistern.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a hole in the ground (dug for obtaining or holding water or other purposes), i.e. A cistern or well; figuratively, an abyss (as a prison).

DEFINITION: to deceive the mind, impose upon.
ORIGIN: From phrenapates; to be a mind-misleader, i.e. Delude.

DEFINITION: a deceiver, seducer.
ORIGIN: From phren and apate; a mind-misleader, i.e. Seducer.

DEFINITION: the mind, intellect, thought, understanding.
ORIGIN: Probably from an obsolete phrao (to rein in or curb; compare phrasso); the midrif (as a partition of the body), i.e. (figuratively and by implication, of sympathy) the feelings (or sensitive nature; by extension (also in the plural) the mind or cognitive faculties).

DEFINITION: to be rough, to shiver, shudder.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary verb; to "bristle" or chill, i.e. Shudder (fear).

DEFINITION: (a) to think, (b) to think, judge, (c) to direct the mind to, seek for, (d) to observe, (e) to care for.
ORIGIN: From phren; to exercise the mind, i.e. Entertain or have a sentiment or opinion; by implication, to be (mentally) disposed (more or less earnestly in a certain direction); intensively, to interest oneself in (with concern or obedience).
USAGE: set the affection on, (be) care(-ful), (be like-, + be of one, + be of the same, + let this) mind(-ed), regard, savour, think.

DEFINITION: the thought (that which is in the mind).
ORIGIN: From phroneo; (mental) inclination or purpose.

DEFINITION: understanding (which leads to right action), practical wisdom, prudence.
ORIGIN: From phroneo; mental action or activity, i.e. Intellectual or moral insight.

DEFINITION: intelligent, prudent, sensible, wise.
ORIGIN: From phren; thoughtful, i.e. Sagacious or discreet (implying a cautious character; while sophos denotes practical skill or acumen; and sunetos indicates rather intelligence or mental acquirement); in a bad sense conceited (also in the comparative).

DEFINITION: wisely, sensibly, prudently.
ORIGIN: Adverb from phronimos; prudently.

DEFINITION: to be thoughtful, careful, give heed.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of phren; to exercise thought, i.e. Be anxious.

DEFINITION: to guard, keep, as by a military guard.
ORIGIN: From a compound of pro and horao; to be a watcher in advance, i.e. To mount guard as a sentinel (post spies at gates); figuratively, to hem in, protect.

DEFINITION: to be wanton, insolent; to roar, rage.
ORIGIN: Akin to bruo, brucho; to snort (as a spirited horse), i.e. (figuratively) to make a tumult.

DEFINITION: a dry stick for burning.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a presumed derivative of phrugo (to roast or parch; akin to the base of phlox); something desiccated, i.e. A dry twig.

DEFINITION: Phrygia, an ethnic district in Asia Minor, the north-western part of which was in the Roman province Asia and the south-eastern part in the Roman province Galatia.
ORIGIN: Probably of foreign origin; Phrygia, a region of Asia Minor.

DEFINITION: Phygelus, a Christian of the Roman province Asia who deserted Paul.
ORIGIN: Probably from pheugo; fugitive; Phygellus, an apostate Christian.

DEFINITION: flight, fleeing.
ORIGIN: From pheugo; a fleeing, i.e. Escape.

DEFINITION: a watching, keeping guard; a guard, prison; imprisonment.
ORIGIN: From phulasso; a guarding or (concretely, guard), the act, the person; figuratively, the place, the condition, or (specially), the time (as a division of day or night), literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: to imprison, deliver into custody.
ORIGIN: From phulax; to incarcerate.

DEFINITION: a phylactery, an amulet, a parchment capsule containing little parchment rolls with the Hebrew texts, affixed to the left upper arm or the forehead of men at morning prayer, and regarded as a protection (hence the name) against evil spirits.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a derivative of phulasso; a guard-case, i.e. "phylactery" for wearing slips of Scripture texts.

DEFINITION: a guard, keeper, sentinel.
ORIGIN: From phulasso; a watcher or sentry.

DEFINITION: (a) to guard, protect; mid: to be on guard, (b) act. and mid. of customs and regulations: to keep, observe.
ORIGIN: Probably from phule through the idea of isolation; to watch, i.e. Be on guard (literally of figuratively); by implication, to preserve, obey, avoid.
USAGE: beward, keep (self), observe, save. Compare tereo.

DEFINITION: a tribe or race of people.
ORIGIN: From phuo (compare phullon); an offshoot, i.e. Race or clan.

DEFINITION: a leaf.
ORIGIN: From the same as phule; a sprout, i.e. Leaf.

DEFINITION: a mass or lump, as of bread dough.
ORIGIN: From a prolonged form of phuro (to mix a liquid with a solid; perhaps akin to phuo through the idea of swelling in bulk), mean to knead; a mass of dough.

DEFINITION: natural, (a) according to nature, (b) merely animal.
ORIGIN: From phusis; "physical", i.e. (by implication) instinctive.

DEFINITION: naturally, by nature.
ORIGIN: Adverb from phusikos; "physically", i.e. (by implication) instinctively.

DEFINITION: to inflate, puff up; pass: to be puffed up, arrogant, proud.
ORIGIN: From phusis in the primary sense of blowing; to inflate, i.e. (figuratively) make proud (haughty).

DEFINITION: nature, inherent nature, origin, birth.
ORIGIN: From phuo; growth (by germination or expansion), i.e. (by implication) natural production (lineal descent); by extension, a genus or sort; figuratively, native disposition, constitution or usage.

DEFINITION: a puffing up, pride, swelling.
ORIGIN: From phusioo; inflation, i.e. (figuratively) haughtiness.

DEFINITION: a plant, that which is planted.
ORIGIN: From phuteuo; trans-planting, i.e. (concretely) a shrub or vegetable.

DEFINITION: to plant, set.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of phuo; to set out in the earth, i.e. Implant; figuratively, to instil doctrine.

DEFINITION: to grow, grow up, spring up.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; probably originally, to "puff" or blow, i.e. To swell up; but only used in the implied sense, to germinate or grow (sprout, produce), literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: a burrow, hole, den, lair.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivative; a burrow or lurking-place.

DEFINITION: to give forth a sound, hence: (a) of a cock: to crow, (b) of men: to shout, (c) trans: to call (to myself), summon; to invite, address.
ORIGIN: From phone; to emit a sound (animal, human or instrumental); by implication, to address in words or by name, also in imitation.

DEFINITION: a sound, noise, voice, language, dialect.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to phaino through the idea of disclosure; a tone (articulate, bestial or artificial); by implication, an address (for any purpose), saying or language.

DEFINITION: light, a source of light, radiance.
ORIGIN: From an obsolete phao (to shine or make manifest, especially by rays; compare phaino, phemi); luminousness (in the widest application, natural or artificial, abstract or concrete, literal or figurative).

DEFINITION: a light, an illuminator, perhaps the sun; a star; brilliancy.
ORIGIN: From phos; an illuminator, i.e. (concretely) a luminary, or (abstractly) brilliancy.

DEFINITION: (lit: light-bearing), radiant, the morning-star.
ORIGIN: From phos and phero; light-bearing ("phosphorus"), i.e. (specially), the morning-star (figuratively).

DEFINITION: bright, luminous, full of light.
ORIGIN: From phos; lustrous, i.e. Transparent or well-illuminated (figuratively).

DEFINITION: (a) to light up, illumine, (b) to bring to light, make evident, reveal.
ORIGIN: From phos; to shed rays, i.e. To shine or (transitively) to brighten up (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: enlighten, illuminate, (bring to, give) light, make to see.

DEFINITION: light, luster, illumination, enlightenment.
ORIGIN: From photizo; illumination (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to rejoice, be glad; also a salutation: Hail.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to be "cheer"ful, i.e. Calmly happy or well-off; impersonally, especially as salutation (on meeting or parting), be well.
USAGE: farewell, be glad, God speed, greeting, hall, joy(- fully), rejoice.

DEFINITION: hailstone.
ORIGIN: Probably from chalao; hail.

DEFINITION: to let down, lower, slacken, loosen.
ORIGIN: From the base of chasma; to lower (as into a void).

DEFINITION: a Chaldean, an inhabitant of Chaldea.
ORIGIN: Probably of Hebrew or (Kasdiy); a Chaldoean (i.e. Kasdi), or native or the region of the lower Euphrates.

DEFINITION: (a) hard, troublesome, (b) harsh, fierce.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from chalao through the idea of reducing the strength; difficult, i.e. Dangerous, or (by implication) furious.

DEFINITION: to bridle, curb, restrain, sway.
ORIGIN: From a compound of chalinos and the reduplicated form of ago; to be a bit-leader, i.e. To curb (figuratively).

DEFINITION: a bridle, bit.
ORIGIN: From chalao; a curb or head-stall (as curbing the spirit).

DEFINITION: brazen (i.e. of copper, bronze, brass).
ORIGIN: From chalkos; coppery.

DEFINITION: a worker in brass or copper; a smith.
ORIGIN: From chalkos; a copper-worker or brazier.

DEFINITION: chalcedony, a small stone of various colors.
ORIGIN: From chalkos and perhaps eidos; copper-like, i.e. "chalcedony".

DEFINITION: a brazen (i.e. of copper, bronze, brass) vessel.
ORIGIN: Diminutive from chalkos; a copper dish.

DEFINITION: orichalcum, a fine metal, or frankincense of a yellow color.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a compound of chalkos and libanos (in the implied mean of whiteness or brilliancy); burnished copper, an alloy of copper (or gold) and silver having a brilliant lustre.

DEFINITION: copper, brass, money; a brazen musical instrument.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from chalao through the idea of hollowing out as a vessel (this metal being chiefly used for that purpose); copper (the substance, or some implement or coin made of it).

DEFINITION: on or to the ground.
ORIGIN: Adverb perhaps from the base of chasma through the idea of a fissure in the soil; earthward, i.e. Prostrate.

DEFINITION: Canaan, the whole of Palestine or Palestine west of the river Jordan.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Kna'an); Chanaan (i.e. Kenaan), the early name of Palestine.

DEFINITION: Canaanite, a Biblical and archaic name for Phoenician.
ORIGIN: From Chanaan; a Chanaanoean (i.e. Kenaanite), or native of gentile Palestine.

DEFINITION: joy, gladness, a source of joy.
ORIGIN: From chairo; cheerfulness, i.e. Calm delight.
USAGE: gladness, X greatly, (X be exceeding) joy(-ful, -fully, -fulness, -ous).

DEFINITION: sculpture; engraving, a stamp, sign.
ORIGIN: From the same as charax; a scratch or etching, i.e. Stamp (as a badge of servitude), or scupltured figure (statue).

DEFINITION: an impression, representation, exact reproduction; a graving-tool.
ORIGIN: From the same as charax; a graver (the tool or the person), i.e. (by implication) engraving (("character"), the figure stamped, i.e. An exact copy or (figuratively) representation).

DEFINITION: a palisade, mound for besieging.
ORIGIN: From charasso (to sharpen to a point; akin to grapho through the idea of scratching); a stake, i.e. (by implication) a palisade or rampart (military mound for circumvallation in a siege).

DEFINITION: (a) to show favor to, (b) to pardon, forgive, (c) to show kindness.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from charis; to grant as a favor, i.e. Gratuitously, in kindness, pardon or rescue.

DEFINITION: for the sake of, by reason of, on account of.
ORIGIN: Accusative case of charis as preposition; through favor of, i.e. On account of.
USAGE: be-(for) cause of, for sake of, +...fore, X reproachfully.

DEFINITION: (a) grace, as a gift or blessing brought to man by Jesus Christ, (b) favor, (c) gratitude, thanks, (d) a favor, kindness.
ORIGIN: From chairo; graciousness (as gratifying), of manner or act (abstract or concrete; literal, figurative or spiritual; especially the divine influence upon the heart, and its reflection in the life; including gratitude).
USAGE: acceptable, benefit, favour, gift, grace(- ious), joy, liberality, pleasure, thank(-s, -worthy).

DEFINITION: a gift of grace, an undeserved favor.
ORIGIN: From charizomai; a (divine) gratuity, i.e. Deliverance (from danger or passion); (specially), a (spiritual) endowment, i.e. (subjectively) religious qualification, or (objectively) miraculous faculty.

DEFINITION: to make graceful, endow with grace.
ORIGIN: From charis; to grace, i.e. Indue with special honor.

DEFINITION: Haran, a city in northwest Mesopotamia.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Charan); Charrhan (i.e. Charan), a place in Mesopotamia.

DEFINITION: a sheet of paper (made of papyrus strips).
ORIGIN: From the same as charax; a sheet ("chart") of writing-material (as to be scribbled over).

DEFINITION: a chasm, wide space.
ORIGIN: From a form of an obsolete primary chao (to "gape" or "yawn"); a "chasm" or vacancy (impassable interval).

DEFINITION: a lip, mouth, shore, edge, brink; meton: language, dialect.
ORIGIN: From a form of the same as chasma; a lip (as a pouring place); figuratively, a margin (of water).

DEFINITION: to expose to winter cold, to drive with storm.
ORIGIN: From the same as cheimon; to storm, i.e. (passively) to labor under a gale.

DEFINITION: a storm-brook, a winter torrent.
ORIGIN: From the base of cheimon and rheo; a storm-runlet, i.e. Winter-torrent.

DEFINITION: a storm, tempest; winter, the rainy season.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of cheo (to pour; akin to the base of chasma through the idea of a channel), meaning a storm (as pouring rain); by implication, the rainy season, i.e. Winter.

DEFINITION: the hand.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from the base of cheimon in the sense of its congener the base of chasma (through the idea of hollowness for grasping); the hand (literally or figuratively (power); especially (by Hebraism) a means or instrument).

DEFINITION: to lead by the hand.
ORIGIN: From cheiragogos; to be a hand-leader, i.e. To guide (a blind person).

DEFINITION: one who leads a helpless person by the hand.
ORIGIN: From cheir and a reduplicated form of ago; a hand-leader, i.e. Personal conductor (of a blind person).
USAGE: some to lead by the hand.

DEFINITION: a (handwritten) document, legal note, bond.
ORIGIN: Neuter of a compound of cheir and grapho; something hand-written ("chirograph"), i.e. A manuscript (specially, a legal document or bond (figuratively)).

DEFINITION: done or made with hands, artificial.
ORIGIN: From cheir and a derivative of poieo; manufactured, i.e. Of human construction.

DEFINITION: to elect by show of hands, choose by vote, appoint.
ORIGIN: From a comparative of cheir and teino (to stretch); to be a hand-reacher or voter (by raising the hand), i.e. (generally) to select or appoint.

DEFINITION: worse, more severe.
ORIGIN: Irregular comparative of kakos; from an obsolete equivalent cheres (of uncertain derivation); more evil or aggravated (physically, mentally or morally).

DEFINITION: Cherubim, heavenly beings who serve God.
ORIGIN: Plural of Hebrew origin (kruwb); "cherubim" (i.e. Cherubs or kerubim).

DEFINITION: a widow.
ORIGIN: Feminine of a presumed derivative apparently from the base of chasma through the idea of deficiency; a widow (as lacking a husband), literally or figuratively.

DEFINITION: yesterday.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; "yesterday"; by extension, in time past or hitherto.

DEFINITION: a thousand, the number one thousand.
ORIGIN: From chilioi; one thousand ("chiliad").

DEFINITION: a commander of a thousand men, a military tribune.
ORIGIN: From chilioi and archo; the commander of a thousand soldiers ("chiliarch"; i.e. Colonel.

DEFINITION: a thousand.
ORIGIN: Plural of uncertain affinity; a thousand.

DEFINITION: Chios (modern Scio), an important island in the Aegean Sea, off the west central coast of Asia Minor.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; Chios, an island in the Mediterranean.

DEFINITION: a tunic, garment, undergarment.
ORIGIN: Of foreign origin (kthoneth); a tunic or shirt.

DEFINITION: snow.
ORIGIN: Perhaps akin to the base of chasma (chalao) or cheimon (as descending or empty); snow.

DEFINITION: a short cloak, worn by military officers and soldiers.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a military cloak.

DEFINITION: to mock, scoff, jest, jeer.
ORIGIN: From a derivative probably of cheilos; to throw out the lip, i.e. Jeer at.

DEFINITION: warm, tepid; of persons: lukewarm.
ORIGIN: From chlio (to warm); tepid.

DEFINITION: Chloe, probably with business connections either in Corinth or in Ephesus or in both.
ORIGIN: Feminine of apparently a primary word; "green"; Chloe, a Christian female.

DEFINITION: green, pale green.
ORIGIN: From the same as Chloe; greenish, i.e. Verdant, dun-colored.

DEFINITION: abbreviation for six hundred sixty-six.
ORIGIN: The 22nd, 14th and an obsolete letter (stigma as a cross) of the Greek alphabet (intermediate between the 5th and 6th), used as numbers; denoting respectively 600, 60, and 6; 666 as a numeral.

DEFINITION: earthy, made of earth.
ORIGIN: From choos; dusty or dirty (soil-like), i.e. (by implication) terrene.

DEFINITION: a choenix (a dry measure of less than a quart).
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a choenix or certain dry measure.

DEFINITION: a swine, hog, sow.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a hog.

DEFINITION: to be melancholy, mad, angry.
ORIGIN: From chole; to be bilious, i.e. (by implication) irritable (enraged, "choleric").

DEFINITION: gall (a bitter herb).
ORIGIN: Feminine of an equivalent perhaps akin to the same as Chloe (from the greenish hue); "gall" or bile, i.e. (by analogy) poison or an anodyne (wormwood, poppy, etc.).

DEFINITION: earth, soil, dust.
ORIGIN: From the base of cheimon; a heap (as poured out), i.e. Rubbish; loose dirt.

DEFINITION: Chorazin, a city of Galilee.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; Chorazin, a place in Palestine.

DEFINITION: to lead a chorus (i.e. a group of performers), to defray the cost of a chorus.
ORIGIN: From a compound of choros and ago; to be a dance-leader, i.e. (generally) to furnish.

DEFINITION: a dance, dancing.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a ring, i.e. Round dance ("choir".

DEFINITION: to feed, fatten, fill, satisfy.
ORIGIN: From chortos; to fodder, i.e. (generally) to gorge (supply food in abundance).

DEFINITION: food, sustenance, provision.
ORIGIN: From chortazo; forage, i.e. Food.

DEFINITION: grass, herbage, growing grain, hay.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; a "court" or "garden", i.e. (by implication, of pasture) herbage or vegetation.

DEFINITION: Chuza, a steward of Herod Antipas.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain origin; Chuzas, an officer of Herod.

DEFINITION: to use, make use of, deal with, take advantage of.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of a primary verb (perhaps rather from cheir, to handle); to furnish what is needed; (give an oracle, "graze" (touch slightly), light upon, etc.), i.e. (by implication) to employ or (by extension) to act towards one in a given manner.

DEFINITION: to lend.
ORIGIN: Probably the same as the base of chraomai; to loan.

DEFINITION: need, necessity, business.
ORIGIN: From the base of chraomai or chre; employment, i.e. An affair; also (by implication) occasion, demand, requirement or destitution.
USAGE: business, lack, necessary(-ity), need(-ful), use, want.

DEFINITION: a debtor.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of chrao and opheiletes; a loan-ower, i.e. Indebted person.

DEFINITION: it is necessary, proper, fitting.
ORIGIN: Third person singular of the same as chraomai or chrao used impersonally; it needs (must or should) be.

DEFINITION: to need, have need of, want, desire.
ORIGIN: From chreia; to make (i.e. Have) necessity, i.e. Be in want of.

DEFINITION: a thing that one uses or needs.
ORIGIN: Something useful or needed, i.e. Wealth, price.

DEFINITION: (originally: to transact business), (a) act. of God: to warn; pass: to be warned by God (probably in response to an inquiry as to one's duty), (b) (to take a name from public business, hence) to receive a name, be publicly called.
ORIGIN: From chrema; to utter an oracle (compare the original sense of chraomai), i.e. Divinely intimate; by implication, (compare the secular sense of chreia) to constitute a firm for business, i.e. (generally) bear as a title.
USAGE: be called, be admonished (warned) of God, reveal, speak.

DEFINITION: a divine response, an oracle.
ORIGIN: From chrematizo; a divine response or revelation.

DEFINITION: useful, profitable.
ORIGIN: From chresis; serviceable.

DEFINITION: use (as in a sexual sense).
ORIGIN: From chraomai; employment, i.e. (specially), sexual intercourse (as an occupation of the body).

DEFINITION: to be kind (full of service to others), gentle.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from chrestos; to show oneself useful, i.e. Act benevolently.

DEFINITION: a kind address; in a bad sense: plausible speaking.
ORIGIN: From a compound of chrestos and lego; fair speech, i.e. Plausibility.

DEFINITION: useful, gentle, pleasant, kind.
ORIGIN: From chraomai; employed, i.e. (by implication) useful (in manner or morals).

DEFINITION: goodness, uprightness, kindness, gentleness.
ORIGIN: From chrestos; usefulness, i.e. Morally, excellence (in character or demeanor).

DEFINITION: an anointing, unction.
ORIGIN: From chrio; an unguent or smearing, i.e. (figuratively) the special endowment ("chrism") of the Holy Spirit.

DEFINITION: a Christian.
ORIGIN: From Christos; a Christian, i.e. Follower of Christ.

DEFINITION: Anointed One; the Messiah, the Christ.
ORIGIN: From chrio; Anointed One, i.e. The Messiah, an epithet of Jesus.

DEFINITION: to anoint, consecrate by anointing.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to chraomai through the idea of contact; to smear or rub with oil, i.e. (by implication) to consecrate to an office or religious service.

DEFINITION: to delay, tarry, linger, spend time.
ORIGIN: From chronos; to take time, i.e. Linger.

DEFINITION: time, a particular time, season.
ORIGIN: Of uncertain derivation; a space of time (in general, and thus properly distinguished from kairos, which designates a fixed or special occasion; and from aion, which denotes a particular period) or interval; by extension, an individual opportunity; by implication, delay.
USAGE: + years old, season, space, (X often-)time(-s), (a) while.

DEFINITION: to waste time, spend time, delay.
ORIGIN: From a presumed compound of chronos and the base of tribos; to be a time-wearer, i.e. To procrastinate (linger).

DEFINITION: golden, made of gold, adorned with gold.
ORIGIN: From chrusos; made of gold.

DEFINITION: a piece of gold, golden ornament.
ORIGIN: Diminutive of chrusos; a golden article, i.e. Gold plating, ornament, or coin.

DEFINITION: adorned with a gold ring.
ORIGIN: From chrusos and daktulios; gold-ringed, i.e. Wearing a golden finger-ring or similar jewelry.

DEFINITION: a topaz, a gem with a bright yellow color.
ORIGIN: From chrusos and lithos; gold-stone, i.e. A yellow gem ("chrysolite").

DEFINITION: a chrysoprase, gem of a golden-greenish color.
ORIGIN: From chrusos and prason (a leek); a greenish-yellow gem ("chrysoprase").

DEFINITION: gold, anything made of gold, a gold coin.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from the base of chraomai (through the idea of the utility of the metal); gold; by extension, a golden article, as an ornament or coin.

DEFINITION: to gild, to cover with gold.
ORIGIN: From chrusos; to gild, i.e. Bespangle with golden ornaments.

DEFINITION: the surface of the body, skin.
ORIGIN: Probably akin to the base of chraomai through the idea of handling; the body (properly, its surface or skin).

DEFINITION: lame, deprived of a foot, limping.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; "halt", i.e. Limping.

DEFINITION: (a) a country or region, (b) the land, as opposed to the sea, (c) the country, distinct from town, (d) plur: fields.
ORIGIN: Feminine of a derivative of the base of chasma through the idea of empty expanse; room, i.e. A space of territory (more or less extensive; often including its inhabitants).
USAGE: coast, county, fields, ground, land, region. Compare topos.

DEFINITION: (lit: to make room, hence) (a) to have room for, receive, contain, (b) to make room for by departing, go, make progress, turn myself.
ORIGIN: From chora; to be in (give) space, i.e. (intransitively) to pass, enter, or (transitively) to hold, admit (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: come, contain, go, have place, (can, be room to) receive.

DEFINITION: (a) to separate, put apart, (b) mid. or pass: to separate myself, depart, withdraw.
ORIGIN: From chora; to place room between, i.e. Part; reflexively, to go away.

DEFINITION: a place, piece of land, field, property, estate.
ORIGIN: Diminutive of chora; a spot or plot of ground.
USAGE: field, land, parcel of ground, place, possession.

DEFINITION: apart from, separately from; without.
ORIGIN: Adverb from chora; at a space, i.e. Separately or apart from (often as preposition).

DEFINITION: the north-west wind, and the quarter of the sky from which it comes.
ORIGIN: Of Latin origin; the north-west wind.

DEFINITION: to sing, sing psalms; earlier: to play on a stringed instrument.
ORIGIN: Probably strengthened from psao (to rub or touch the surface; compare psocho); to twitch or twang, i.e. To play on a stringed instrument (celebrate the divine worship with music and accompanying odes).

DEFINITION: a psalm, song of praise, the Hebrew book of Psalms.
ORIGIN: From psallo; a set piece of music, i.e. A sacred ode (accompanied with the voice, harp or other instrument; a "psalm"); collectively, the book of the Psalms.

DEFINITION: a false brother, pretend Christian.
ORIGIN: From pseudes and adephos; a spurious brother, i.e. Pretended associate.

DEFINITION: a false or pretended apostle.
ORIGIN: From pseudes and apostolos; a spurious apostle, i.e. Pretended pracher.

DEFINITION: false, deceitful, lying, untrue.
ORIGIN: From pseudomai; untrue, i.e. Erroneous, deceitful, wicked.

DEFINITION: a false teacher, teacher of false things.
ORIGIN: From pseudes and didaskalos; a spurious teacher, i.e. Propagator of erroneous Christian doctrine.

DEFINITION: false-speaking, speaking lies.
ORIGIN: From pseudes and lego; mendacious, i.e. Promulgating erroneous Christian doctrine.

DEFINITION: to deceive, lie, speak falsely.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to utter an untruth or attempt to deceive by falsehood.

DEFINITION: a false witness.
ORIGIN: From pseudes and a kindred form of martus; a spurious witness, i.e. Bearer of untrue testimony.

DEFINITION: to bear false witness, give false testimony.
ORIGIN: From pseudomartur; to be an untrue testifier, i.e. Offer falsehood in evidence.

DEFINITION: false witness, false testimony.
ORIGIN: From pseudomartur; untrue testimony.

DEFINITION: a false prophet; one who in God's name teaches what is false.
ORIGIN: From pseudes and prophetes; a spurious prophet, i.e. Pretended foreteller or religious impostor.

DEFINITION: a lie, falsehood, untruth; false religion.
ORIGIN: From pseudomai; a falsehood.

DEFINITION: a false Christ, pretended Messiah.
ORIGIN: From pseudes and Christos; a spurious Messiah.

DEFINITION: under a false name, falsely called.
ORIGIN: From pseudes and onoma; untruly named.

DEFINITION: a falsehood, lie, untruthfulness.
ORIGIN: From pseudomai; a fabrication, i.e. Falsehood.

DEFINITION: a liar, deceiver.
ORIGIN: From pseudomai (g5574); a falsifier.

DEFINITION: to feel, touch, handle; to feel after, grope for.
ORIGIN: From the base of psallo (compare psephos); to manipulate, i.e. Verify by contact; figuratively, to search for.

DEFINITION: to reckon, compute, calculate.
ORIGIN: From psephos; to use pebbles in enumeration, i.e. (generally) to compute.

DEFINITION: (a) a pebble, small stone, (b) hence, from their use in voting: a vote.
ORIGIN: From the same as pselaphao; a pebble (as worn smooth by handling), i.e. (by implication, of use as a counter or ballot) a verdict (of acquittal) or ticket (of admission); a vote.

DEFINITION: a whispering, secret slandering.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of psithos (a whisper; by implication, a slander; probably akin to pseudomai); whispering, i.e. Secret detraction.

DEFINITION: a whisperer, secret slanderer.
ORIGIN: From the same as psithurismos; a secret calumniator.

DEFINITION: a crumb (of bread).
ORIGIN: Diminutive from a derivative of the base of psallo (meaning a crumb); a little bit or morsel.

DEFINITION: (a) the vital breath, breath of life, (b) the human soul, (c) the soul as the seat of affections and will, (d) the self, (e) a human person, an individual.
ORIGIN: From psucho; breath, i.e. (by implication) spirit, abstractly or concretely (the animal sentient principle only; thus distinguished on the one hand from pneuma, which is the rational and immortal soul; and on the other from zoe, which is mere vitality, even of plants: these terms thus exactly correspond respectively to the Hebrew nephesh, ruwach and chay).
USAGE: heart (+ -ily), life, mind, soul, + us, + you.

DEFINITION: natural, of the soul or mind.
ORIGIN: From psuche; sensitive, i.e. Animate (in distinction on the one hand from pneumatikos, which is the higher or renovated nature; and on the other from phusikos, which is the lower or bestial nature).

DEFINITION: cold.
ORIGIN: From psucho; coolness.

DEFINITION: cool, cold; fig: cold-hearted.
ORIGIN: From psuchos; chilly (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: to breathe, blow, to make cool.
ORIGIN: A primary verb; to breathe (voluntarily but gently, thus differing on the one hand from pneo, which denotes properly a forcible respiration; and on the other from the base of aer, which refers properly to an inanimate breeze), i.e. (by implication, of reduction of temperature by evaporation) to chill (figuratively).

DEFINITION: to feed with morsels.
ORIGIN: From the base of psomion; to supply with bits, i.e. (generally) to nourish.

DEFINITION: a fragment, morsel.
ORIGIN: Diminutive from a derivative of the base of psocho; a crumb or morsel (as if rubbed off), i.e. A mouthful.

DEFINITION: to rub, rub to pieces.
ORIGIN: Prolongation from the same base as psallo; to triturate, i.e. (by analogy) to rub out (kernels from husks with the fingers or hand).

DEFINITION: omega, the last letter of the Greek alphabet.
ORIGIN: The last letter of the Greek alphabet, i.e. (figuratively) the finality.

DEFINITION: O, an exclamation, used in addressing someone.
ORIGIN: A primary interjection; as a sign of the vocative case, O; as a note of exclamation, oh.

DEFINITION: may, might.
ORIGIN: Including the oblique forms, as well as es (ace); e (ay); etc. The subjunctive of eimi; (may, might, can, could, would, should, must, etc.; also with ei and its comparative, as well as with other particles) be.
USAGE: + appear, are, (may, might, should) be, X have, is, + pass the flower of her age, should stand, were.

DEFINITION: Obed.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Owbed); Obed, an Israelite.

DEFINITION: here, the things here, what is here, what is going on here, the state of affairs here.
ORIGIN: From an adverb form of hode; in this same spot, i.e. Here or hither.

DEFINITION: an ode, song, hymn.
ORIGIN: From aido; a chant or "ode" (the general term for any words sung; while humnos denotes especially a religious metrical composition, and psalmos still more specially, a Hebrew cantillation).

DEFINITION: the pain of childbirth, acute pain, severe agony, a snare.
ORIGIN: Akin to odune; a pang or throe, especially of childbirth.

DEFINITION: to be in travail, suffer birth-pangs.
ORIGIN: From odin; to experience the pains of parturition (literally or figuratively).

DEFINITION: the shoulder.
ORIGIN: Perhaps from the alternate of phero; the shoulder (as that on which burdens are borne).

DEFINITION: be, come, have.
ORIGIN: Including the feminine ousa (oo'-sah); and the neuter on (on) present participle of eimi; being.

DEFINITION: to buy, purchase.
ORIGIN: Middle voice from an apparently primary onos (a sum or price); to purchase (synonymous with the earlier pimpremi).

DEFINITION: an egg.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; an "egg".

DEFINITION: (a) a definite space of time, a season, (b) an hour, (c) the particular time for anything.
ORIGIN: Apparently a primary word; an "hour" (literally or figuratively).
USAGE: day, hour, instant, season, X short, (even-)tide, (high) time.

DEFINITION: fair, beautiful, blooming.
ORIGIN: From hora; belonging to the right hour or season (timely), i.e. (by implication) flourishing (beauteous (figuratively)).

DEFINITION: to roar, howl, as a beast.
ORIGIN: Middle voice of an apparently primary verb; to "roar".

DEFINITION: as, like as, about, as it were, according as, how, when, while, as soon as, so that.
ORIGIN: Probably adverb of comparative from hos; which how, i.e. In that manner (very variously used, as follows).
USAGE: about, after (that), (according) as (it had been, it were), as soon (as), even as (like), for, how (greatly), like (as, unto), since, so (that), that, to wit, unto, when(-soever), while, X with all speed.

DEFINITION: (Aramaic and Hebrew, originally a cry for help), hosanna!, a cry of happiness.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (yasha' and na'); oh save!; hosanna (i.e. Hoshia-na), an exclamation of adoration.

DEFINITION: in like manner, likewise, just so.
ORIGIN: From hos and an adverb from autos; as thus, i.e. In the same way.
USAGE: even so, likewise, after the same (in like) manner.

DEFINITION: as if, as it were, like; with numbers: about.
ORIGIN: From hos and ei; as if.
USAGE: about, as (it had been, it were), like (as).

DEFINITION: Hosea, an Israelite prophet.
ORIGIN: Of Hebrew origin (Howshea'); Hosee (i.e. Hoshea), an Israelite.

DEFINITION: just as, as, even as.
ORIGIN: From hos and per; just as, i.e. Exactly like.

DEFINITION: just as if, as it were.
ORIGIN: From hosper and ei; just as if, i.e. As it were.

DEFINITION: so that, therefore, so then, so as to.
ORIGIN: From hos and te; so too, i.e. Thus therefore (in various relations of consecution, as follow).
USAGE: (insomuch) as, so that (then), (insomuch) that, therefore, to, wherefore.

DEFINITION: an ear.
ORIGIN: Diminutive of ous; an earlet, i.e. One of the ears, or perhaps the lobe of the ear.

DEFINITION: usefulness, profit, advantage, benefit, gain.
ORIGIN: From a derivative of the base of ophelimos; usefulness, i.e. Benefit.

DEFINITION: to help, benefit, do good, be useful (to), profit.
ORIGIN: From the same as opheleia; to be useful, i.e. To benefit.

DEFINITION: profitable, beneficial, useful.
ORIGIN: From a form of ophelos; helpful or serviceable, i.e. Advantageous.
